[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/nsspObqZ/gcoVh6lh"]
[FEN "4rrk1/6pp/p4q2/1ppp3b/5n2/2P3QP/PPBN2P1/R1B3NK w - - 0 22"]
[SetUp "1"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ As we have seen, Botvinnik went wrong on the previous move by moving the c-pawn forward. How should White continue now to exploit this mistake? }
22. Nb3 { It was probably better not to place the knight on f3 and avoid all ideas of Bxf3. } (22. Ndf3 { This logical move, moving the knight away from the path of the bishop, attacking f4 and also keeping it closer to the king was played in the game, but it transpired not to be the best because at hthe correct moment - Black could have taken on f3. } { [%csl Gf3][%cal Rc1f4,Rg3f4] }) 22... Ne2 23. Nxe2 Rxe2 24. Bd3 { A good move, attacking the rook and forcing it away. If White is allowed to consolidate, he will be winning due to the material advantage. Black doesn't have anything better than to go for the queen exchange. } 24... Qe5 { This aims to get to the endgame similar to the one seen in the previous exercise, but here White has opened the bishop on c1 so it makes a major difference. } 25. Kh2 { Allows White to retain some initiative in the
endgame after } { This allows White to retain some initiative in the endgame. } (25. Qxe5 { Is probably less precise as the rook comes to e1 with check and White loses a tempo. Nevertheless after } 25... Rxe5 { the evaluation of the endgame is different as after } 26. Nxc5 Re1+ 27. Kh2 { We have managed to get a pawn and get our pieces out and can play Nb3-a4 next
trying to get the rook in the game. The engine insists this is still equal,
but I feel only White can now play for the win. } { We have managed to get a pawn and get our pieces out and can play Nb3-a4 next trying to get the rook in the game. The engine insists this is still equal, but I feel only White can now play for the win. } { [%cal Ga2a4,Gc5b3] }) 25... Qxg3+ 26. Kxg3 Re1 27. Nxc5 { This endgame is highly attractive for White due to the material advantage. He will play Nb3 next to defend the rook and then move the c1 bishop, or even then play a4 to open the rook up. Black is really hurt by the fact they lost the pawn on c5. } { [%cal Gc5b3,Ga2a4] } 1-0


