[FEN "r2r1k2/pp2nppQ/4pbnp/1q2N3/3P4/P5N1/1P3PPP/R1B1R1K1 w - - 0 22"]
[SetUp "1"]
[ChapterMode "gamebook"]

{ As mentioned in the previous exercise, in the game, Ribli allowed the White queen to go to h7 and destabilize the king under favorable circumstances. By move 22, Smyslov increased the pressure and provoked a decisive mistake on his opponent's part. Ribli has just retreated the knight from d5 to e7, allowing a decisive combination. Can you find it? }
22. Bxh6!! { Boom. Now Black's position collapses at once due to the
weaknesses of the g7, f7 and the king, in general. } { [%csl Rf7,Rf8,Rg7,Rh6][%cal Rh7f7] } 22... Nxe5 (22... gxh6 23. Qxf7#) (22... Bxe5 23. Rxe5 Nxe5 24. Qxg7+ { is not an improvement for Black. }) 23. Nh5 { The pressure against the g7 point is at its peak! } { [%cal Rh5g7,Rh6g7,Rh7g7] } (23. dxe5 { Is also good enough, as after } 23... Bxe5 24. Nh5 Nf5 25. Bg5 { Black has to give up some material or get mated! } 25... f6 26. g4 $18) 23... Nf3+ { A possible defence, trying to eliminate the option of advancing the g-pawn, but it doesn't change much. } (23... Nf5 24. dxe5 Bxe5 25. Bg5 { Transposes to the line
analyzed earlier. }) 24. gxf3 Nf5 25. Nxf6 Nxh6 26. d5 { A wonderful move, creating pressure against the e6 pawn and also creating various tactical ideas associated with the capture on e6 and with the d6 discoveries. We will see the end of the game in the very next exercise. } { [%cal Re1e8] } (26. Qh8+?? { Would be horrible as after } 26... Ke7 27. Qxg7 { And suddenly White is the one losing after } 27... Rg8 28. Nxg8+ Rxg8 { it is never too late to lose a game of chess, I guess! } { [%cal Rg8g1] }) 1-0


[Event "Exercise #3"]
[Site "London ENG"]
[Date "1983.11.30"]
