1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 { With this bishop move, White
initiates a very popular variation of the French Defence that, surprisingly
enough, doesn't have a proper name (at least not at this point). The idea is
simple - White is violating the principle of developing the knights before the
bishops in order to put the pressure on the knight on f6 and - consequently -
the central pan on d5. -- According to my database, this is the most popular
move in this position and is definitely one that any 3...Nf6 French Defence
player has to prepare for. } { [%cal Rg5d8] } 4... dxe4 { This exchanging maneuver in the center,
reminscent of the so-called Rubinstein variation, might actually be the best
way to handle this position. At first glance, this seems like a concession as
Black is surrendering the center, but they are trying to make an argument that
the knight will be drawn to e4 and then somewhat exposed - especially since
the bishop is already on g5. --- Even though traditionally, 4...Be7 has been
the more popular move, if I were to recommend a weapon against 4.Bg5, I would
definitely recommend this one - I have even played it once myself in a serious
tournament game. } 5. Nxe4 Be7 { The point of
Black's play. Now the knight on e4 is under the attack and the bishop on g5 is
also prone to exchanging. Black is trying to make an argument that the piece
exchanges will favour them as they have less space (and traditionally,
exchanges favour the player with less space in the majority of cases). } { [%csl Re4,Rg5][%cal Re7g5,Rf6e4] } (5... Nbd7 { Black can also try reinforcing the knight with Nbd7, but here we
transpose to a variation of the Rubinstein defence that will be examined in
the video/file dedicated to that variation (3...dxe4). }) 6. Bxf6 { In my opinion, this is the most ambitious move in the position,
exchanging only one pair of minor pieces and keeping the knight on e4 on the
board. It is true that White is giving up the bishop pair, but in return, we
either game some time or ruin Black's pawn structure, depending how Black
recaptures. Furthermore, the knight on e4 also controls the important c5
square, preventing Black's liberating c5 push (at least for now). } { [%csl Ge4][%cal Ge4c5] } (6. Nxf6+ { White can also take on f6 here, but it feels less ambitious as it leads to
quite a few exchanges - which should nominally benefit Black as they have less
space here. } 6... Bxf6 7. Bxf6 { Nothing else makes much sense. } 7... Qxf6 8. Nf3 { White continues developing normally, but Black essentially has a reasonable
version of the Rubinstein variation. It is very difficult to prevent them from
playing the liberating c5 push. There are plenty of games with Grischuk with
Black from this position. } 8... O-O 9. Bd3 { By far the main move here. White has
some other options, but I feel Black should be very happy with the outcome of
the opening after playing c5 on the next move anyway. } 9... c5 { And
due to the hanging b2 pawn the c5 pawn can't be taken so Black should be
reasonably happy here. Rd8, Nc6 are all coming, etc. There are no problems
with development and no weaknesses, which is the reason why 6. Nxf6 is not as
popular as 6. Bxf6. } { [%cal Rf6b2] }) 6... gxf6 { The most ambitious and fighting approach in this position, as it
leads to a very imbalanced position. Black voluntarily doubles the pawns, but
claims that the open g-file, the bishop pair and the potential to kick the
knight from e4 with f5 next all provide compensation for the ruined pawn
structure. Furthermore, Black keeps the bishop on e7 where it helps prepare
the central c5 pawn advance. } { [%csl Gc5,Gf6,Gf7][%cal Ge7c5,Gc7c5,Gh8g8,Gf6f5] } 7. Nf3 { The starting point of the variation. Now
Black has the first decision to make - do they want to include f5 immediately,
or do they want to wait a bit before doing so. } 7... a6 { Apart
from the move 7...f5, forcing the knight away from e4, the text move,
preparing to fianchetto the bishop with b5-Bb7 next, is the second big option
and main move in the position. Black doesn't want to chase the knight to c3
and think about d5 resources all the time. On the other hand, the downside of
keeping the knight on e4 is the fact that it can access the c5 square - which
becomes especially relevant once Black plays b5. So there is definitely pro
and contra when it comes to including f5 and both approaches have the right to
exist. } { [%cal Ga6b5,Gb7b5] } 8. g3 { Just like in variations with f5 included, this is the main
reply to Black's idea of fianchettoing the bishop - and the nature of the play
is fairly similar (not to mention that Black can include f5 and transpose at
any moment). } 8... b5 { At this point, it is probably better to include f5 and chase
the knight away from e4 as in this positional line, the added option of having
it on e4 becomes surprisingly relevant - especially once White moves the queen
away from d1 and introduces the idea of playing Rd1. } 9. Bg2 Bb7 { Developing the bishop to the long diagonal and attacking the knight on e4.
Alas, now White can switch plans and maintain the knight on e4. } { [%cal Rb7g2] } (9... f5 { Now is probably the last chance to include f5 and chase the
knight away as jumping to c5 is not as good with the queen on d1. } { [%cal Rf5e4] } 10. Nc5 Bxc5 11. dxc5 Qxd1+ 12. Rxd1 Bb7 { With the queens exchanged, this
position is perfectly acceptable for Black. The king will be perfectly safe on
e7. } { [%cal Ge8e7] }) 10. Qe2 { White brings the queen to e2 and
vacates the d1 square. More importantly - now the knight has the option of
jumping to c5 as Black no longer has the option of exchanging the queens in
case they take on c5. } { [%csl Gd1][%cal Ge2e4,Ga1d1] } 10... Nd7 { The main move in the position, but I am really a
bit sceptical about Black's setup (even though some very strong players such
as Vitiugov, Short and Morozevich played this with Black). As mentioned
earlier - the issue is that now Nc5 will be a strong resource in many cases. } (10... f5 11. Nc5 { Might be an option for Black, though. The point is that the
knight hasn't been developed to d7 so it has the option to go to c6, e.g. } 11... Bxc5 12. dxc5 Be4 13. O-O Nc6 { Although A) This is very computerish and B) White
nevertheless retains the edge in this position, despite the fact that the pawn
on c5 can be potentially weak. }) 11. O-O f5 { And now White has the option of
going back to the 7...f5 lines or play more energetically by jumping to c5. } 12. Nc5 { The point is that the pawn can't be captured due to the critical Qe5
double attack, e.g. } 12... Bxc5 (12... Nxc5 13. dxc5 Bf6 { Is probably better, but
then after } 14. Rad1 Qe7 15. b4 { White obtains a very
reasonable position with hopes of exploiting the defects in Black's pawn
structure. Note that White will eliminate the bishop pair with ease after Ne5/
Nd4 due to the staredown contest between the two light-squared bishops. } { [%cal Rg2b7,Rb7g2,Gf3d4] }) 13. dxc5 Nxc5 14. Qe5 { [%cal Re5c5,Re5h8] } *


[Event "4.Bg5 dxe4"]
[Date "2022.11.02"]
[White "French Defence"]
[Black "Burn Variation"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "mistr"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C11"]
[Opening "French Defense: Classical Variation, Burn Variation, Morozevich Line"]
[StudyName "Burn Variation Of The French Defence"]
[ChapterName "Burn Variation - Detailed Analysis"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/cPClFn0l/QZAI5VDt"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 { With this bishop move, White
initiates a very popular variation of the French Defence that, surprisingly
enough, doesn't have a proper name (at least not at this point). The idea is
simple - White is violating the principle of developing the knights before the
bishops in order to put the pressure on the knight on f6 and - consequently -
the central pan on d5. -- According to my database, this is the most popular
move in this position and is definitely one that any 3...Nf6 French Defence
player has to prepare for. } { [%cal Rg5d8] } 4... dxe4 { This exchanging maneuver in the center,
reminscent of the so-called Rubinstein variation, might actually be the best
way to handle this position. At first glance, this seems like a concession as
Black is surrendering the center, but they are trying to make an argument that
the knight will be drawn to e4 and then somewhat exposed - especially since
the bishop is already on g5. --- Even though traditionally, 4...Be7 has been
the more popular move, if I were to recommend a weapon against 4.Bg5, I would
definitely recommend this one - I have even played it once myself in a serious
tournament game. } 5. Nxe4 Be7 { The point of
Black's play. Now the knight on e4 is under the attack and the bishop on g5 is
also prone to exchanging. Black is trying to make an argument that the piece
exchanges will favour them as they have less space (and traditionally,
exchanges favour the player with less space in the majority of cases). } { [%csl Re4,Rg5][%cal Re7g5,Rf6e4] } (5... Nbd7 { Black can also try reinforcing the knight with Nbd7, but here we
transpose to a variation of the Rubinstein defence that will be examined in
the video/file dedicated to that variation (3...dxe4). }) 6. Bxf6 { In my opinion, this is the most ambitious move in the position,
exchanging only one pair of minor pieces and keeping the knight on e4 on the
board. It is true that White is giving up the bishop pair, but in return, we
either game some time or ruin Black's pawn structure, depending how Black
recaptures. Furthermore, the knight on e4 also controls the important c5
square, preventing Black's liberating c5 push (at least for now). } { [%csl Ge4][%cal Ge4c5] } (6. Nxf6+ { White can also take on f6 here, but it feels less ambitious as it leads to
quite a few exchanges - which should nominally benefit Black as they have less
space here. } 6... Bxf6 7. Bxf6 { Nothing else makes much sense. } 7... Qxf6 8. Nf3 { White continues developing normally, but Black essentially has a reasonable
version of the Rubinstein variation. It is very difficult to prevent them from
playing the liberating c5 push. There are plenty of games with Grischuk with
Black from this position. } 8... O-O 9. Bd3 { By far the main move here. White has
some other options, but I feel Black should be very happy with the outcome of
the opening after playing c5 on the next move anyway. } 9... c5 { And
due to the hanging b2 pawn the c5 pawn can't be taken so Black should be
reasonably happy here. Rd8, Nc6 are all coming, etc. There are no problems
with development and no weaknesses, which is the reason why 6. Nxf6 is not as
popular as 6. Bxf6. } { [%cal Rf6b2] }) 6... gxf6 { The most ambitious and fighting approach in this position, as it
leads to a very imbalanced position. Black voluntarily doubles the pawns, but
claims that the open g-file, the bishop pair and the potential to kick the
knight from e4 with f5 next all provide compensation for the ruined pawn
structure. Furthermore, Black keeps the bishop on e7 where it helps prepare
the central c5 pawn advance. } { [%csl Gc5,Gf6,Gf7][%cal Ge7c5,Gc7c5,Gh8g8,Gf6f5] } (6... Bxf6 { With that
being said, recapturing with the bishop is also possible. It has been played
by some very strong players, such as Matthias Bluebaum or Evgeny Bareev. Black
keeps the structure intact, but White's argument is that the knight on e4
makes it much more difficult for Black to execute the liberating c5 pawn break. } { [%csl Gc5][%cal Ge4c5] } 7. Nf3 O-O 8. Qd2 Nd7 { We can see that here White's good
control over the c5 square makes it difficult to execute the c5 pawn push, so
Black has to develop more modestly (with the knight on d7). It is true that
Black has the two bishops which are a long-term asset, but White can always
consider taking on f6 to eliminate that advantage. } { [%cal Gc7c5,Ge4c5] } 9. O-O-O b6 10. Bd3 { The most natural move in this position, although not the only one.
Still, it allows us to illustrate the main idea of this variation - kingside
attack! } { [%cal Gd3h7] } (10. Bc4 { and }) (10. Qf4 { have both been played, with reasonable
results, as well, but I feel placing the bishop on d3 is most natural and the
only move worth considering in this opening survey. }) 10... Bb7 11. h4 { The most popular move in the
position and a typical one for this variation. White wants to create some
threats on the kingside and advancing the h-pawn is a good start as it anchors
the g5 square while still keeping some flexibility. In some cases White would
like to push g4-g5 (especially if Black plays h6 to control the g5 square),
sometimes Qf4-Ne5 is an idea, while this move doesn't yet rule out switching
to more positional plans such as Qe2-Ba6 (as gaining space on the kingside can
be useful in endgames as well). --- Once again, there are other ways to handle
the position, but this one is not only the most popular, but also very
thematic! } { [%cal Gd2e2,Ge2a6,Gf3g5,Ge4g5,Rd3h7,Gd2f4,Gf3e5] } 11... Be7 { This move is logical. Black removes the bishop
from the attack and covers the d6 square in preparation for c5. However, Black
spends more time moving the bishop and not striking in the center, giving
White another tempo to improve the pieces. } { [%cal Ge7a3] } (11... c5 { It is important to
mention that striking in the center with c5 is not as attracitve in this
particular position because it weakens the d6 square. You might wonder how
that is relevant, but White has a nice sequence. } 12. Nfg5 { Threatening Nxh7 and/or Nd6. } { [%cal Rd3h7,Ge4d6] } 12... h6 13. Nd6 { And this
intermediate move works very well for White as now we are threatening the
bishop on b7 and also Bh7 and Nxf7 - and Black can't take the knight on g5. } { [%cal Rd6b7,Gd3h7] } 13... hxg5 14. Nxb7 Qc7 15. hxg5 { White is completely winning here, e.g. } 15... Be7 16. Rh3 { Not even rushing with the preliminary check on h7.
Something bad will happen to the king on g8 due to the open h-file. } { [%cal Gh3h8,Gd3h7,Gh7e4] }) 12. Qe2 { The most popular move in this position, moving the queen
closer to the important squares on the kingside and opening up the rook on d1
- which is now saying hello to the queen on d8 and making the liberating c5
push even less attractive. White has ideas of jumping with the knight to g5
and has a better version of similar position we have seen in the pure
Rubinstein variation. } { [%cal Rd1d8,Ge2h5] }) 7. Nf3 { The starting point of the variation. Now Black
has the first decision to make - do they want to include f5 immediately, or do
they want to wait a bit before doing so. } 7... f5 { This is the most
natural and historically - most common move played in this position. Black
kicks the knight from e4 away from the center and opens up the diagonal for
the be bishop. The downside is that Black spends a tempo to kick the knight to
a square where it can potentially help with the thematic d5 pawn break - which
is why recently delaying f5 has been becoming more and more popular. } { [%cal Rf5e4] } (7... b6 { In order to understand why a6-b5 is the main idea in this position, let's see
what happens if Black tries to play with b6-Bb7 instead. As will be also
mentioned in the mainline with 7...f5, this is not ideal as Black is not
contesting the pieces on the queenside - most specifically - the bishop that
will appear on c4. } 8. Bc4 { A very active square for the
bishop, where it helps with the thematic d5 pawn break in the future. } { [%cal Gc4d5,Gd4d5] } 8... Bb7 9. Qe2 { Also a very nice move, vacating the d-file and
preparing to bring the rook to d1 that will keep an eye on the queen on d8. } { [%cal Ge1c1,Rd1d8] } 9... Nd7 10. O-O-O { And now d6 is already a very unpleasant threat so Black has to
go for the passive prevention of that plan. } 10... c6 11. Rhe1 { White has a very convincing plus score from this position as Black is
very passive and all White's pieces are participating in the game. At some
point, White can even consider playing Ba6 to exchange the bishops and put
pressure on the light-squares on the queenside. Meanwhile, it is tricky for
Black to find the save heaven for the king on e8. } { [%csl Re8][%cal Ge2a6] }) (7... a6 { Apart from the move 7...f5, forcing the knight away from e4, the text
move, preparing to fianchetto the bishop with b5-Bb7 next, is the second big
option and main move in the position. Black doesn't want to chase the knight
to c3 and think about d5 resources all the time. On the other hand, the
downside of keeping the knight on e4 is the fact that it can access the c5
square - which becomes especially relevant once Black plays b5. So there is
definitely pro and contra when it comes to including f5 and both approaches
have the right to exist. } { [%cal Ga6b5] } 8. g3 { Just like in variations with f5 included,
this is the main reply to Black's idea of fianchettoing the bishop - and the
nature of the play is fairly similar (not to mention that Black can include f5
and transpose at any moment). } (8. a4 f5 { Transposes to the variation that
will be examined via the 7...f5 move order. }) (8. c4 { Preventing b5 with the
help of the advance of the c-pawn also looks sensible, but it is actually
beneficial for Black as the pawn on c4 can also be used as a "hook" to open
the queenside with the help of b5 in the future - if the center gets closed
and White castles long. } 8... f5 { Now there is no reason to keep
denying this move. } { [%cal Ge7b4] } 9. Nc3 { Here this is the only move that makes any sense as
otherwise Bb4 would come. } 9... Bf6 { Preparing c5 and intending
to double the c-pawns by capturing on c3. } { [%cal Gc7c5,Rf6c3] } 10. Qd2 c5 11. d5 O-O 12. O-O-O e5 { And now we see the point of Black's play. With the c-pawn on c2, it would have
been more difficult to open up the queenside, but here the c4 pawn can serve
as a wedge for the future b5. } (12... Bg7 { Has also been played here, with the
idea of capturing on d5 next, say after } 13. h4 exd5 14. Nxd5 Nc6 { And here also, the fact that White played c4 is relevant as their
control over the d4 square has been weakened, providing Black with some active
ideas and nice counterplay. The position is already balanced and this whole
variation shouldn't be too attractive for White from the "obtaining the
opening advantage" viewpoint. } { [%csl Rd4][%cal Gc6d4] })) (8. Bc4 { Developing the bishop to c4 is very
bad (in contrast to the lines with the pawn on b6) as now the queenside
expansion comes with the gain of tempo. } 8... b5 9. Bb3 { The bishop
tries to stay on the diagonal where it helps with the d5 breakthrough, but it
is merely in the way of the queenside pawns. } { [%csl Rb3] } 9... f5 10. Ng3 (10. Nc3 c5 { Is even worse for White. There aren't any d5 breaks with the
bishop being in trouble. } { [%csl Rb3][%cal Gc5c4] }) 10... c5 { And Black already takes over
the initiative because White has no time to play d5 due to the threat of c4,
capturing the bishop. } { [%cal Gc5c4] }) (8. Qd2 { Going for the queenside castling is not the
best idea against this whole a6-b5 plan - as we will soon see in the lines
where 7...f5 8. Nc3 is included. The reason is that Black makes progress on
the side of the board where White is castled and controls some very important
squares. } 8... b5 9. O-O-O Bb7 { This version where the knight is on c5 is
particularly good for Black as there aren't any d5 ideas in the air, so Black
can aim for very harmonious development. } 10. Qe3 { Sidestepping the d-file and threatening Nc5. } { [%cal Gd1d8,Ge4c5] } 10... Nd7 { Adding some control to the crucial c5 square. Black is perfectly fine here and
can consider playing f5-Bf6 next, among other things. Note that the jump to c5
is bad now as after } { [%csl Rc5][%cal Rd7c5] } 11. Nc5 (11. Be2 { Seems to be the most common move in the
database, when Black can consider playing the same idea. } 11... Bd5 12. Kb1 c6 { Black will keep the king in the center and try to create chances on the
queenside. The position is complicated, but objectively balanced and Black
should be reasonably happy with the outcome of the opening. }) 11... Bd5 { Black has everything covered. c6 is coming next and
Black is very solid - with attacking chances on the queenside. } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Re6a2] }) (8. Bd3 { Moving the bishop to d3 is possible, but it is meek because it blocks the
d-file and makes it much more difficult to push d5 in the future. } 8... f5 { Now that Black has avoided any Bc4-Nc3 ideas they kick the
knight away. } { [%csl Re4][%cal Rf5e4] } 9. Ned2 { One way in which White can try to justify the
positioning of the bishop on d3, but it does not impress. } (9. Ng3 c5 { Is
immediately fine for Black. True, they don't manage to exchange queens here,
but they achieve this central counterstrike under good circumstances. }) (9. Nc3 { Going to c5 also doesn't make much sense in this position as it leads to
inferior positions of the 7...f5 8. Nc3 system where the bishop is inferior on
d3 - it would much rather be on g2, neutralizing Black's light-squared bishop. } 9... b5 10. Qe2 c5 { And once again Black is instantly fine after executing this
thematic pawn break under favourable circumstances. }) 9... c5 { Striking
immediately in the center basically solves Black's problems. There are other
moves, but this is virtually the only move that has been tried here - and
Black's practical results are fairly reasonable. } 10. dxc5 Qa5 { Intending to regain the pawn with the queen and keeping the
bishop on e7, as it keeps the option to go to f6 in the future. } { [%cal Ra5e1,Ra5d5] } 11. Qe2 Rg8 { Why not include this useful tempo-gaining move
now that the g2 pawn is undefended. Note that the queen on a5 also makes it
highly annoying for White to castle long. } { [%csl Ra2][%cal Ra5a2,Rg8g2] } 12. g3 Nc6 13. a3 Qxc5 14. O-O-O Bd7 { Black will castle long and shouldn't have any
objective problems with the two bishops, despite the slightly damaged pawn
structure. The pieces are developed and fairly active and the bishop pair is a
long-term asset. } { [%csl Gd7,Ge7][%cal Ge8c8] }) 8... b5 { At this point, it is probably better to include f5
and chase the knight away from e4 as in this positional line, the added option
of having it on e4 becomes surprisingly relevant - especially once White moves
the queen away from d1 and introduces the idea of playing Rd1. } 9. Bg2 Bb7 { Developing the bishop to the long diagonal and attacking the
knight on e4. Alas, now White can switch plans and maintain the knight on e4. } { [%cal Rb7g2] } (9... f5 { Now is probably the last chance to include f5 and chase
the knight away as jumping to c5 is not as good with the queen on d1. } { [%cal Rf5e4] } 10. Nc5 Bxc5 11. dxc5 Qxd1+ 12. Rxd1 Bb7 { With the queens exchanged, this
position is perfectly acceptable for Black. The king will be perfectly safe on
e7. } { [%cal Ge8e7] }) 10. Qe2 { White brings the queen to e2 and
vacates the d1 square. More importantly - now the knight has the option of
jumping to c5 as Black no longer has the option of exchanging the queens in
case they take on c5. } { [%csl Gd1][%cal Ge2e4,Ga1d1] } 10... Nd7 { The main move in the position, but I am really a
bit sceptical about Black's setup (even though some very strong players such
as Vitiugov, Short and Morozevich played this with Black). As mentioned
earlier - the issue is that now Nc5 will be a strong resource in many cases. } (10... f5 11. Nc5 { Might be an option for Black, though. The point is that the
knight hasn't been developed to d7 so it has the option to go to c6, e.g. } 11... Bxc5 12. dxc5 Be4 13. O-O Nc6 { Although A) This is very computerish and B) White
nevertheless retains the edge in this position, despite the fact that the pawn
on c5 can be potentially weak. }) 11. O-O f5 { And now White has the option of
going back to the 7...f5 lines or play more energetically by jumping to c5. } 12. Nc5 { The point is that the pawn can't be captured due to the critical Qe5
double attack, e.g. } 12... Bxc5 (12... Nxc5 13. dxc5 Bf6 { Is probably better, but
then after } 14. Rad1 Qe7 15. b4 { White obtains a very
reasonable position with hopes of exploiting the defects in Black's pawn
structure. Note that White will eliminate the bishop pair with ease after Ne5/
Nd4 due to the staredown contest between the two light-squared bishops. } { [%cal Rg2b7,Rb7g2,Gf3d4] }) 13. dxc5 Nxc5 14. Qe5 { [%cal Re5c5,Re5h8] }) 8. Nc3 { Probably
the best retreat, albeit a bit counterintuitive. White takes the d5 square
under control, in order to be able to meet the advance of the c5 pawn with d5.
However, the knight is blocking the c-pawn here - and can also be in the way
of the a6-b5 idea. } { [%cal Gd4d5,Gc3d5] } (8. Ng3 { Retreating the knight to g3 makes some sense as
in some cases, White can try to create the pin along the e-file and then
threaten some Nxf5 ideas. However, the downside of this move is that it
doesn't really account for the possibility of Black striking with c5 at once. } 8... c5 { This liberating push of the c-pawn frees Black's
position completely. If the knight were on c3, White would be able to push the
d-pawn forward, but here it is not the case. } { [%csl Gc5][%cal Rc5d4] } 9. Bb5+ { The main move in the
position. The idea is to force Black to block the d-file and then either
sacrifice a pawn under favourable circumstances, or play d5. } (9. dxc5 { First of all - White can't really take the pawn on c5 as it gives Black a
pretty easy game. } 9... Qxd1+ 10. Rxd1 Bxc5 { Two bishops in an open
position more than compensate for the doubled f-pawns. Black is already
slightly preferable. } { [%csl Gc5,Gc8] }) (9. c3 { Second of all - White can't really reinforce
the pawn center as it also allows Black to liberate the position and go for
very fluent development. } 9... cxd4 10. Nxd4 Bd7 { The knight
is coming to c6 next and Black has no problems. They will very probably castle
long and once again enjoy with the bishop pair. } { [%csl Gc6][%cal Gb8c6] }) 9... Bd7 { The most natural move, blocking the check. When you analyze this
position with the engine, it suggests an even stronger - and very surprising
alternative in the form of side-stepping the check. } { [%csl Gb5][%cal Gd7b5] } (9... Kf8 { The idea behind this move is simply keeping control
over the d5 square and also claiming that the bishop on b5 is now hanging in
the air (as Qa5 is being threatened). Definitely an option worth exploring
further that has already been tried in a few games. } { [%csl Rb5,Rd4][%cal Gd8a5,Gd8d4,Rc5d4] }) 10. Bxd7+ { The point
behind White's play. The argument is that both of Black's recaptures now have
drawbacks. } 10... Qxd7 { This is possibly the
more natural recapture. Black keeps control over the d5 square and potentially
keeps the c6 square for the knight. Now White's solely chance of obtaining any
opening advantage lies in the surprising pawn sacrifice. } { [%csl Gc6,Gd5][%cal Gb8c6,Gd7d5,Rc5d4] } (10... Nxd7 { Taking
with the knight is also possible, though. White's point is that now Black's
communication with d5 has been prevented, which enables the thematic pawn push. } 11. d5 { However, an argument is to be made whether this is the end of the
world for Black due to the following queen maneuver. } 11... Qa5+ 12. c3 Qa6 { Black reinforces the e6 pawn, prepares long castling and also
prevents White from castling short. The position should be relatively balanced
and it is definitely a more solid - albeit a less ambitious way of handling
this variation. } { [%cal Ga6e6,Ge8c8] }) 11. d5 { A very thematic, although not the
most obvious move - especially not at the club level. White willingly
sacrifices a pawn in order to open the e-file, isolate the doubled f-pawns,
prevent Black from taking on d4 and also tries to justify the knight on g3. } { [%csl Gd5,Gg3] } 11... exd5 12. O-O { And due to the open e-file and the
doubled f-pawns, White definitely has the compensation for the pawn - although
Black also has a relatively easy development with Nc6 and O-O-O, while the
g-file is also open. Definitely a playable option, but in general, the entire
Ng3 idea is not something that should worry Black too much. } { [%csl Rf5,Rf7][%cal Ge1e8] }) 8... a6 { A very thematic move for this variation, which we have already seen in
the scenario where Black pushed f5. Here, the situation is different - White's
knight has been kicked away from e4 (so some Nc5 jumps are not something that
should worry us). But on the other hand, the knight helps control the d5
square and makes this central advance a constant idea Black needs to keep in
mind. } { [%cal Gd4d5] } (8... c5 { In contrast to the variation with the knight on g3, this is
not good as White can justify the position of the knight on c3 with the
thematic pawn advance. } 9. d5 { This is very uncomfortable for
Black as now it is a bit difficult to develop the pieces as the e6 pawn can
easily come under pressure and it is best to avoid this altogether. } { [%csl Rc5,Gd5] }) (8... Bf6 { This move can also be tried - the idea is to play c5 and then meet d5 with e5.
However, it turns out that this idea is not as good for Black as it sounds on
paper. } 9. Qd2 c5 10. d5 { And now the desired advance of the e-pawn is not
that good. } 10... e5 11. O-O-O { And it is hard for Black to develop the queenside
and castling kingside is quite risky. } 11... O-O 12. h4 { Black's king is much less
secure than White's king - especially with the center locked and White has
dangerous play in the center and on the kingside. At some point d6 advance can
come - then moves such as Bc4-Nd5 become viable, etc. Black's practical
results are not too impressive, either and it is not surprising that different
ways of handling the position as Black are more popular. }) (8... b6 { Developing with b6-Bb7 seems sensible, but it transpires it is much inferior
to the similar idea a6-b5 as the b-pawn is not disturbing White's pieces on
the c-file. Also, this move doesn't take the b5 square under control. } 9. Bc4 Bb7 10. d5 { This is already extremely strong for White as the e6 pawn is in
trouble and Black really doesn't want to take on d5 and isolate the doubled
f-pawns. Not to be recommended as Black. }) 9. g3 { The most
popular - and arguably the best way of handling this position. White
anticipated that Black will fianchetto the bishop on b7 and gives up on any
aggressive ideas associated with the queenside castling. Instead, White
fianchettoes the bishop to g2 and opposes it to the one on b7 and intends to
castle short and play in a rather more positional manner. } { [%cal Gf1g2,Ge1g1] } (9. d5 { Playing d5
here is not too impressive as nothing is threatened. Black has several good
ways of dealing with it, but the easiest seems to be the modest advance of the
c-pawn. } 9... c6 { Black exploits the fact that the knight is
on b8. } { [%csl Gb8][%cal Gb8c6] } (9... b5 { or }) (9... Bf6 { are alternatives. }) 10. dxe6 Qxd1+ 11. Rxd1 Bxe6 { And this endgame is fine for Black despite the doubled isolated f-pawns
as the development is fluent and the bishop pair is pretty strong. Once again
- not the only way to handle the early advance of the d-pawn. }) (9. Qd2 { One thing that I personally find most attractive against Black's setup with
a6-b5 in these variations is that it works very well against White's most
ambitious plan that involves trying to castle long as it allows Black to gain
space on the queenside and quickly control some important squares in front of
the king. } 9... b5 10. O-O-O { Castling long is the most logical way of playing. Now
Black indeed needs to watch out for some d5 ideas and there are several ways
in which Black can deal with them. } (10. d5 { This is still premature due to
the advanced b.-pawn: } 10... b4 { Black takes on d5 next and White probably has
insufficient compensation. }) 10... Qd6 { This is the main move in the position. Black anticipates that White will play
d5 and prepares to meet it with the counteradvance e5. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gd4d5,Ge6e5,Gd6e5] } (10... Bb7 { Is bad,
although it is hard to understand why exactly at first glance. The point is
that now the advance of the d-pawn is very strong. } 11. d5 { And now all
typical replies have their shortcomings. } 11... c6 { This seems quite sensible as
Black tries to undermine the center and get the knight to c6, but due to the
fact that the bishop has been developed to b7, White actually has a strong
sequence available. } (11... b4 { Is fraught with danger due to the amazing
piece sacrifice!! } 12. Bc4 bxc3 13. Qxc3 { Threatening dxe6
as well as Qxh8. } { [%cal Rc3h8,Rd5e6] } 13... e5 { Virtually the only move, giving up the pawn but removing
the possibility of White playing dxe6. } 14. Nxe5 { And White has two pawns for
the piece and an ongoing initiative and is, therefore, clearly better (even
though a lot of chess remains to be played). }) 12. dxe6 Qxd2+ 13. Rxd2 fxe6 14. Re2 { [%csl Re6][%cal Re2e6] } 14... Kf7 15. g4 { Incredibly strong. White prepares Bg2 and attacks the
Black's pawn chain, while also Ne5 is on the agenda. No matter what Black does,
they are in significant trouble! } { [%csl Re6,Rf5,Rf7,Gg4][%cal Gf1g2,Gf3e5,Ge5g4] }) (10... Nd7 { This seems very
solid. The idea is to meet d5 with e5 - while Black is at the same time
developing a piece and preparing Bb7. } { [%cal Gc8b7] } 11. Qe3 (11. d5) 11... Bb7 12. d5 Bc5) 11. Qe3 { Another idea available to White in this position.
The queen is moved away from the rook's line of fire and adds some additional
control over the e5 square, so d5 is now threatened again. } { [%cal Gd1d8,Ge3e5] } (11. d5 e5 { Actually works in Black's favour, as the center is
now closed and Black has easy development with Nd7-Bb7, timely e4 next, etc. } { [%cal Gb8d7,Gc8b7,Ge5e4] }) 11... Nd7 { Covering the e5 square again. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gd7e5] } 12. d5 { Nevertheless! The point of White's play is this breakthrough. It seems to come
at a very inconvenient moment as the queen and the e6 pawn are exposed, but
Black actually has a nice reply here. } 12... Nb6 (12... e5 { This move is not as
desirable here due to another very shocking tactic. } 13. Bxb5 axb5 14. Nxb5 { Black is just losing in this position. } { [%cal Rb5d6,Rb5c7] }) 13. dxe6 Qxe6 { And the position is absolutely fine for Black, with the only
downside being that White has a repetition available. } { [%cal Re6e3] } 14. Qf4 { Now Black has
to keep harassing the queen as the position is very open and very dangerous. } 14... Bd6 15. Qh4 Be7 16. Qf4 Bd6) (9. a4 { White can also try to prevent Black
from playing b5 at all, but this is also not ideal. Now Black can switch to
the alternative plan of playing for c5 and White's dangerous ideas involving
the d5 advance and castling long are more risky now as with the inclusion of
the moves a6 and a4, Black is quicker when it comes to creating play on the
queenside. } 9... Bf6 { Placing the bishop on a nice
diagonal and preparing c5 (as the bishop is eyeing the knight on c3,
potentially). Black intends to castle short, but delays it for the moment to
conceal the intensions and make a useful move (as the bishop can later come to
g7 to cover the king, if necessary). } { [%cal Rf6d4,Gf6e5,Gc7c5] } (9... O-O { Is maybe a bit early as there
is some wild } 10. Rg1 { Although in practice, the position should probably come
to the same thing. }) 10. Qd2 { In order to illustrate
what can happen if White pursues the plan of castling long, let's take a look
at a sample variation. With this move Black defends the knight on c3 and
avoids some trouble associated with Bxc3. } { [%csl Gc3][%cal Gd2c3] } (10. g3 { Note that plans involving
the fianchetto of the bishop to g3 are also not too good here as Black can
already strike with c5. } 10... c5 11. d5 Bxc3+ { And Black wins a pawn. }) 10... c5 { A thematic move! } { [%csl Rd4][%cal Rc5d4] } 11. d5 O-O { It
is also possible to advance the e-pawn - but Black doesn't need to hurry with
it yet as with the bishop on c8, there aren't any real threats to the e6 pawn. } { [%csl Ge6][%cal Gc8e6] } 12. O-O-O { This is thematic in positions where a6 and a4 haven't been played,
but here it is a bit risky as Black can advance the b-pawn. } 12... b5 { Opening up the files on the queenside - even at the
cost of the pawn. The position is very double-edged and dangerous for both
sides. Black's attack shouldn't be overestimated, but the price of every move
is very high and this is probably not what White wants in a variation like
this one. } { [%cal Ga8a1,Gd8f6,Rh8a1,Gb5b4] }) 9... b5 { The point of the previous move - preparing
to fianchetto the bishop to b7. } { [%cal Gc8b7] } 10. Bg2 Bb7 11. O-O O-O (11... c5 12. d5 b4 13. dxe6 { Piece sacrifice line. } 13... bxc3 14. exf7+ Kf8 15. Qe2 { Very sharp and
unclear, can easily go all ways. }) 12. Ne5 { A very logical and natural move,
trying to activate the knight and exchange the light-squared bishops -
although not the only way to handle this position. } (12. Qe2 { Vacating the d1 square for the rook, is also very interesting. Black has
several options, but probably the most thematic now is the advance of the
c-pawn as White can no longer reply d5 in return. } { [%cal Gf1d1] } 12... c5 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Rad1 Qf6 (14... Qe7 { Also seems reasonable. }) 15. Ne5 { Once again White has a small
advantage due to the better pawn structure, although Black's position is quite
solid. In the game (44) Perunovic,M (2631)-Sedlak,N (2568) Subotica 2014,
Black actually went on to win, although this does not bring a conclusive
verdict to this variation as the sample size is too small. }) 12... Bxg2 13. Kxg2 { And the position is probably balanced. White does
have a better structure, but Black's dark-squared bishop is potentially the
best minor piece on the board and Black doesn't have a clear weakness. c5 will
come at some point. Lazily said - a position with mutual chances that is not
completely dead yet and where the better player is very likely to win. } { [%csl Ge7][%cal Gc7c5] } *


[Event "French Defence - Classical Variation - Intro: French Defence: Classical Variation with 4. Bg5!? - Intro"]
[Date "2022.11.02"]
[White "French Defence"]
[Black "3.Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5!? Intro"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "mistr"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C11"]
[Opening "French Defense: Classical Variation"]
[StudyName "French Defence - Classical Variation - Intro"]
[ChapterName "French Defence: Classical Variation with 4. Bg5!? - Intro"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/VAHbHWrq/GJB5IzIA"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 { With this bishop move, White initiates a
very popular variation of the French Defence that, surprisingly enough,
doesn't have a proper name (at least not at this point). The idea is simple -
White is violating the principle of developing the knights before the bishops
in order to put the pressure on the knight on f6 and - consequently - the
central pan on d5. -- According to my database, this is the most popular move
in this position and is definitely one that any 3...Nf6 French Defence player
has to prepare for. } 4... h6 { In order to understand the point of White's idea,
let's first ask ourselves - what if Black simply chases the bishop away and
pretends the development of the bishop was not particularly good? } 5. Bxf6 { Of course, White captures the knight very happily as it was the sole point of
moving the bishop to f6, claiming that any recapture has serious drawbacks. } 5... Qxf6 { Taking with the queen is better than taking with the pawn, but it does
involve the pawn sacrifice. This whole line waw playedd by some very strong
players - most notably Nodirbek Abdusattorov and Matthias Bluebaum. } (5... gxf6 { Taking with the g-pawn avoids the loss of a pawn but ruins Black's pawn
structure. } 6. exd5 exd5 7. Qf3 { And Black's ugly doubled isolated pawns and
three set of pawn islands already mean they are significantly worse. }) 6. exd5 { Of course, White should take the pawn that is being offered. } 6... Bb4 { This is
the point of Black's play. Black deliberately sacrifices a pawn, hoping to
obtain a massive lead in development that should, in theory, together with the
bishop pair, guarantee a nice advantage. } 7. Bc4 { White refuses to budge and
defends the pawn on d5 while developing a piece. } (7. dxe6 { Taking on e6 is
also possible, but it accelerated Black's development as it allows them to
recapture with the bishop at once. } 7... Bxe6 { Even here White should be able to
fight for the advantage, but matters are not at all so simple. }) 7... O-O { Black insists on the idea of going for rapid development. } 8. Ne2 { While
White continues with the plan of developing the pieces and waiting for Black
to recapture on d5. } 8... exd5 { The only sensible move. Black tries to lure the
bishop to d5 and then create some threats against it and the d4 pawn. } 9. Bxd5 Rd8 { At first glance, it seems as if Black will be able to regain the pawn and
obtain superior play, but there is no need for White to panic. } 10. O-O { Calmly castling and waiting to see what Black will exactly do. } 10... Bxc3 { The only
move that was seen in practice in this position. Black tries to divert the
knight on e2 from defending the d4 pawn hoping that they will then regain it
and reach an equal, symmetrical position. } 11. Nxc3 Nc6 { This is the only move
that makes sense here, attacking the d4 pawn and initiating the following
forcing sequence of moves. } (11... c6 { Trying to chase the bishop from d5 and
then taking on d4 doesn't quite work as after } 12. Bb3 Rxd4 13. Qe2 { White has
a massive lead in development and threatens to infiltrate along the back rank.
Ne4 and Rad1 are all coming and Black is in trouble due to the massive
difference in the activity of the pieces. }) 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Ne4 { Hitting the
queen with a gain of tempo and forcing a queen exchange. } 13... Qxd4 14. c3 { Another
very nice move, exploiting the fact that the queen can't take the knight due
to the hanging rook on d8 and forcing Black to exchange on our own terms. } 14... Qxd1 15. Rfxd1 { All this was seen in a very high profile game between Levon Aronian
and Nodirbek Abdusattorov, played in Riga in 2021. White has a stable
advantage in this endgame due to Black's weakened pawn structure. Levon went
on to convert his advantage into a win. } *


[Event "\"Study of the Millenium\" - Mitrofanov's Immortal Study: The Mitrofanov Study"]
