[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/tEawK0Kh/qKC56Iz8"]
[FEN "8/k7/P2b2P1/KP1Pn2P/4R3/8/6np/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This is probably one of the most famous chess studies ever. Due to its beauty and brilliancy, it is also known as the “Study of the Millenium”. I think studying this one is a must for any self-respectable chess player. }
1. b6+ { White has to prevent the blockade of the pawns by Bc7+. } 1... Ka8 { It is better to go to a8 as now Black has a defensive resource Bb8 dealing with the potential mating threat of g7-g8Q. } (1... Kb8 2. g7 { is threatening g8 mate and there is
not much Black can do about it. }) 2. Re1!! { This seems pointless, because White can't stop the black h-pawn, but this rook sacrifice has a point! } { [%cal Ge1h1] } 2... Nxe1 { Now the 1st rank is blocked. It is hard to see how that is relevant, but we will soon see an ultra-brilliant hidden point! } { [%cal Rh1a1] } 3. g7! h1=Q (3... Nc4+ { but it doesn't really help, as after } 4. Kb5 h1=Q (4... Na3+ 5. Kc6 { also doesn't help. }) 5. g8=Q+ Bb8 6. a7 { And Black doesn't have a check, since the knight on e1 is blocking the path and there is not even Nc6 resource we will see in the mainline. }) 4. g8=Q+ Bb8 5. a7 { Since the knight on e1 is blocking the queen's path, it seems that Black is quite dead. But he has one final resource. } 5... Nc6+! { Everything else also loses, and faster as well. You can trust me on that one. } 6. dxc6 { White has to take this knight as otherwise Black will gladly
sacrifice it for the pawn on a7 or give a check with the queen. } 6... Qxh5+ { Now the 5th rank is opened and Black is able to give this horizontal check. The climax of the study has been reached. Black starts checking and wherever White moves his king, he can't avoid further checks. But White is not forced to move his king. } { [%cal Rh5a5] } 7. Qg5!! { The most beautiful, most paradoxical, and most amazing move I have ever seen. White simply leaves his queen to be taken, and with check to, only to disrupt the Black's queen position. } (7. Ka6 Qe2+) 7... Qxg5+ 8. Ka6 { An amazing position. White threatens b7 mate and Black
simply doesn't have an useful check. His only defence is giving up the bishop. } 8... Bxa7 { And now it seems that White has overplayed himself. But now follows another stupendous move. } 9. c7!! { I don't know how on earth the author arrived at this position, but I think that this ultimate triumph od mind over matter proves that chess compositions deserve to be proclaimed as an art. White is threatening both c8Q and b7 mate, and there is no defence against both threats. The best Black can do is give up his queen. } 9... Qa5+ 10. Kxa5 { But now Black has no way to prevent the promotion of at least one pawn. } 10... Bxb6+ (10... Kb7 11. bxa7 { And one of the pawns will promote. } { [%cal Rc7c8,Ra7a8] }) 11. Kxb6 { And due to the knight on e1, there is no stalemate and White mates on the next move. What else to say, but - simply sensational? } *


