1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7 5. e5 Nfd7 6. h4 a6 { In the previous variation, we have seen how pushing c5 immediately can lead to some trouble due to the weakness of the b5 square. Therefore, a logical question is - can Black afford to take a moment to control the square on b5 before pushing c5? } 7. Qg4 { Well, it turns out that Black's approach on the last move is just a tad too slow as it gives White a free hand to include the queen to the queenside as the center is not under pressure. This variation scores very well for White in practice, although there are some nuances that require knowledge - see Detailed Analysis chapter. } *


