1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7 5. e5 Nfd7 6. h4 h6 { Last but not least, Black can try to avoid the gambit by forcing the bishop to move immediately. This seems to be a very solid option available to Black as it forces the issues and it also doesn't involve the weakening of the queenside (such as the move 6...h6). } 7. Bxe7 { White now has two options. The first one is, obviously, this capture on e7, executing one of the main ideas of this variation - exchange of the dark-squared bishops. } (7. Be3 { It is also possible to retreat the bishop, though and pretend that h6 is now a weakening of the kingside. Check the detailed analysis chapter for more details on this variation. } { [%csl Rh6] }) 7... Qxe7 { And here White has several options at their disposal. } 8. f4 { I personally think this is the most natural and best move. White stabilizes the center and braces for the incoming counterattack with c5. } (8. Qg4 { This standard French queen move is also possible! }) (8. Nb5 { While this knight move doesn't just have the same effect now that the d6 square has not been weakened. Here } 8... Nb6 { is possible, defending the c7 pawn indirectly. Still, this was played by some very strong players as after } 9. c3 { White gets a tempo to reinforce the central pawn structure. I don't think this is a particularly ambitious or critical test of Black's setup, though. But it is playable. }) *


