[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/pc4x0yT2/haNCDD90"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 { With this bishop move, White
initiates a very popular variation of the French Defence that, surprisingly
enough, doesn't have a proper name (at least not at this point). The idea is
simple - White is violating the principle of developing the knights before the
bishops in order to put the pressure on the knight on f6 and - consequently -
the central pan on d5. -- According to my database, this is the most popular
move in this position and is definitely one that any 3...Nf6 French Defence
player has to prepare for. } { [%cal Rg5d8] } 4... Be7 { Apart from the move 4...Bb4, leading to the
sharp McCutcheon variation, Black can also place the bishop on e7, dealing
with the pin in a very direct fashion. The drawback of this move is that it
allows the very sharp option - the so-called Alekhine Chatard attack! } 5. e5 { The drawback of the previous move - White now gains time to
play the typical French move e5 and claims that the fact that the bishops has
been moved to g5 and e7 is to White's benefit compared to the regular lines
where e5 is played immediately. } { [%cal Re5f6,Rg5d8] } 5... Nfd7 { The only move that has remotely any
sense! } (5... Ne4 { Jumping to e4 in the style of McCutcheon makes no sense
here as White can simply exchange everything and obtain a favourable position. } 6. Bxe7 Qxe7 7. Nxe4 dxe4 8. Qe2 { The pawn on e2
is extremely weak and very likely to fall. White is also ready to castle long
and can be very happy with the outcome in the opening, even if some very high
profile games, such as the one between Judit Polgar and Viktor Korchnoi -
played in 1993 - reached this exact position. } { [%csl Re4][%cal Re2e4,Ge1c1] }) 6. h4 { There you have it! This sharp move leads to the so-called Alekhine Chatard
variation. White is ready to sacrifice a pawn to open the h-file and drag the
queen out in the open, so that it can be harassed! } { [%csl Gh4][%cal Gh4g5] } (6. Bxe7 { Taking on e7 is
also possible, though, and was played in some very high-profile games. } 6... Qxe7 7. f4 { Reinforcing the center and covering the e5
point in anticipation of the c5 counterplay. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gf4e5,Gd4e5] } 7... a6 { Preventing the knight from coming to d6 before playing the standard c5
break. } { [%csl Gb5,Rd6][%cal Gc3b5] } 8. Nf3 c5 9. Ne2 { And White wants to play c3
next and hold on to the center as much as possible. Black, in turns, will
probably have to undermine it with f6 at some point. A complex strategic
battle typical of the French defence is ahead of us. White's chances for an
advantage in this type of position are definitely there and this whole line
shouldn't be ignored if you intend to play this variation as Black. } { [%cal Ge2d4,Gf3d4,Gc2c3] }) 6... Bxg5 { Accepting the sacrifice is the most principled continuation, although it is
the one fraught with considerable danger. } (6... c5 { First of all, let us try
to understand what happens if Black just ignores the bishop on g5 and
continues with the queenside counterplay. The text move is typical French
strike in the center - but in this position with the bishop tension it is not
the best at this moment. } 7. Bxe7 { Very strong. We are eliminating
the defender of the d6 square and intending to plant the knight there. } { [%csl Re7] } 7... Kxe7 { This provocative way of playing was seen in some high profile games. Black
anticipates the transfer of the knight to d6 and avoids it coming with check.
Obviously, the downside is that they have to lose time by moving the king! } (7... Qxe7 { Taking with the queen can't be recommended, though. After } 8. Nb5 { Black has to probaly move the king to d8 again - or give up
the rook on a8 for the moment - neither of which seem particularly attractive. } { [%cal Gb5c7,Gb5d6] }) 8. f4 { Since jumping with the knight to b5 has no
particular point now, White advances the f-pawn to reinforce the e5 pawn in
anticipation of Black capturing on d4 and destroying the center a bit. This is
not the only possible move here, but it is by far the most common. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gf4e5] } 8... cxd4 { Exchanging on d4 immediately and trying to force an endgame seems like the
most reasonable strategy for Black. } (8... Qb6 { Trying to create additional
pressure on the b2 and d4 pawns doesn't work due to the standard maneuver } 9. Na4 { Hitting the queen, covering b2 and also attacking the
c5 pawn. } { [%cal Ra4b6,Ga4b2] } 9... Qa5+ 10. c3 { White's center is quite
secure. a3-b4 can be played at some point, taking on c5 is also the idea and
Black's position is unenviable. } { [%csl Ga4][%cal Gd1a4,Gc3d4] }) 9. Qxd4 Qb6 { Black has to go for this if
they want to have any chances here. } (9... Nc6 10. Qd2 { Leads to a
standard French position where the king is stuck on e7 - which obviously works
in White's favour! } { [%csl Re7] }) 10. Qxb6 Nxb6 11. h5 { And in this position, White should
have a pleasant edge due to the fact White has the space advantage and also
due to the fact Black's light-squared bishop is a very bad pieces. Still,
matters are not 100% clear as Black has some active ideas such as the f6
undermining break. A high-profile game between John Nunn and Yasser Seirawan
played in 1992 ended in a draw after } 11... h6 12. Nb5 Nc6 13. Nf3 Bd7 14. b3 a6 15. Nbd4 Nxd4 16. Nxd4 Nc8 17. Kd2 Na7 18. c3 { ½-½ (18) Nunn,J (2615)-Seirawan,Y
(2600) Cannes 1992, although in the resulting position, White should still
retain better chances - not to mention his play could have been improved
somewhat along the way. All in all - this is not too impressive variation for
Black. }) (6... a6 { Instead of the immediate c5 - which we have just seen as
somewhat dubious, Black can try to prepare it by first taking the b5 square
under control. However, this is not an improved version due to the very strong
move available at White's disposal. } 7. Qg4 { This typical French
maneuver is quite strong here. The queen not only reinforces the bishop on g5,
but also creates the threat of taking on g7. } { [%cal Rg4g7] } 7... Bxg5 { Possibly the best option,
although White is now spoilt for choice. } (7... Kf8 { Defending the g7 pawn was
tried in some games, but now White gains a very pleasant position after } 8. Nf3 c5 9. dxc5 Nc6 10. Qf4 { The fact that the queen is very active on the
queenside and that we have forced Black to play Kf8 works in our favour and we
have a favourable version of standard French positions! }) 8. hxg5 { The most logical move. White opens the h-file and also creates ideas of
g6 in many positions. } { [%cal Rh1h8] } (8. Qxg5 { Is even possible here, although White surely
doesn't want to exchange queens in such a position. }) 8... c5 { Black tries to strike in the center immediately! } { [%cal Rc5d4] } 9. dxc5 { The best move,
although it is not too obvious to give up the pawn on e5 in this particular
instance. } (9. g6 { Seems very attractive, but here Black has an unexpected
defensive resource } 9... f5 { And things aren't too clear after this surprising move.
It was even played in more t han 200 games in my database, so it is definitely
not a move that is impossible to find. } (9... fxg6 10. Qxe6+)) 9... Nxe5 10. Qg3 { [%cal Rg3b8] } 10... Nbc6 11. O-O-O { And this
position is surprisingly good for White - mainly due to the fact it is
impossible for Black to castle due to the open h-file. Next, we want to play
some f4 - then potentially even f5 and the fact we have given up our center
and that our c5 pawn is somewhat weak is not very relevant here! } { [%csl Rc5][%cal Gf2f4,Gf4f5] }) (6... h6 { Out of all options that decline the sacrifice of the pawn, this modest move of
the h-pawn might be the best. Black forces White to make a decision in regard
to what they want to do with the bishop at the cost of a tempo. It was played
by some very strong players and is definitely a move both sides that play this
line should be aware of. } 7. Bxe7 { This is very logical, as exchanging the
dark-squared bishops was possible even without the inclusion of h4 and h6 -
and here White is trying to make an argument that this inclusion works to our
advantage as we want to play on the kingside anyway, so moving our pawn should
help us more than moving the Black pawn should help our opponent. } (7. Be3 { Retreating the bishop is also possible here - and not that pointless. White
makes an argument that the fact we have avoided the most dangerous lines with
Bb4 and also moved the bishop to e3 with a gain of time works to our advantage
compared to normal lines. The downside is that Black can now strike in the
center at once as we no longer have ideas of Nb5-Nd6 with the bishop firmly
standing on e7. } 7... c5 { The best move, striking in the center
immediately. } { [%cal Rc5d4] } (7... Bxh4?? { loses immediately to } 8. Qg4 { [%cal Rg4h4,Rg4g7] }) 8. Qg4 { The point of White's play - this typical
queen maneuver, attacking the kingside. } { [%cal Rg4g7] } 8... g6 { A standard way of dealing with
the pressure to the g-pwan. } (8... Kf8 { Is also possible, leading to very
similar lines, but since this is a very rare variation, for the sake of
simplicity, let's just cover one of the possible ways of defending the g-pawn. }) 9. dxc5 { Possibly the most ambitious try here, trying to justify the
existence of the bishop on e3. } (9. Nf3 { Has been played in some games, but
after } 9... cxd4 { We can't recapture on d4 with the knight (which is positionally
desirable), as our e5 pawn is exposed. And if we take with the bishop than
after } 10. Bxd4 Nc6 { We have far-from ideal scenario where
Black might exchange our strong dark-squared bishop while keeping their own
dark-squared bishop. It is still potentially playable, but definitely not the
best! } { [%cal Rc6d4,Rd7e5] }) 9... Nxe5 { The most consistent follow-up, eliminating the
important central e-pawn. } { [%cal Re5g4] } (9... Bxc5 10. Bxc5 Nxc5 11. h5 { Black's position is very suspect, with numerous weaknesses. The e5 pawn
will never be in trouble and it secures us our space advantage. Castling long
and f4 are coming next. } { [%csl Rg6][%cal Ge1c1] }) (9... Nxc5 { Taking the c5 pawn with the knight leads
to something very similar after } 10. h5 { [%csl Rg6][%cal Rh5g6,Ge1c1] }) 10. Qg3 { Hitting the knight on e5. } { [%csl Re5][%cal Rg3e5] } 10... Nbc6 11. O-O-O { And white
has a very attractive position with good dark-square control. It is true that
our center has crumbled and c5 can be weak, but White can play f4 to add some
more security to the dark-squares in the center and Black's kingside is
permanently weak. Of course, a long fight is ahead of us, but overall, this
variation shouldn't be too attractive for Black - there are simply much better
options available. }) 7... Qxe7 8. f4 { Reinforcing the
center in anticipation of the future e5 is very logical way of handling the
position. The general plan is to use the fact that the center is closed to
push the kingside pawns and create threats on that side of the board. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gf4e5] } (8. Qg4 { Moving the queen to g4 first is possible, but White should play f4 anyway as
c5 is definitely coming. } 8... O-O 9. f4 { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gf4e5] }) (8. Nf3 { Trying
to play without f4 is possible, but not the most critical as then our center
is somewhat vulnerable to the well-timed c5, as in this position we can't
really take on c5, e.g. } 8... O-O 9. Qd2 c5 10. dxc5 Qxc5 { And now our
e5 pawn is somewhat soft, e.g. } { [%csl Re5] } 11. O-O-O Nc6 { And
now we have to make a passive move to defend the pawn, Black has ideas of
further playing f6 and this is simply not a good position for White - which is
why 8. Nf3 is not really a popular move here. } { [%cal Rc6e5,Rd7e5,Gf7f6] }) (8. Nb5 { Now doesn't quite work as after } 8... Nb6 { c7 is defended and d6 is not that weak. }) 8... a6 { Trying to take the b5 square under control before striking with c5. } { [%csl Gb5][%cal Ga6b5] } (8... O-O { With the f-pawn marching down the board, Black is not in hurry to
castle as White already has very aggressive ideas in mind, such as the
immediate advance of the g-pawn: } 9. g4 c5 10. dxc5 Qxc5 11. g5 { Now we can
see the difference compared to the lines where White has played the meek Nf3 -
here e5 is very secure and White is able to create immedaite play on the
kingside. This position is very dangerous for Black and they already have to
be extremely careful. }) 9. Nf3 { Only now do
we develop the knight, harmoniously and behind the pawn chain. } { [%csl Gd4,Ge5][%cal Gf3e5,Gf3d4] } 9... c5 { This thematic strike has to be played sooner or later. } { [%cal Rc5d4] } 10. Qd2 { An instructive moment. Here we have a sort of a waiting game - neither side
wants to commit their king and allow the other side to start attacking. This
move seemingly prepares castling long, but it is primarily a move that gets
the queen into the play and kinda waits to see what exactly will Black do. } 10... Nc6 { Black continues to develop and puts some additional pressure on
the d4 pawn. Once again, it is probably best to maintain the tension rather
than to commit to a certain plan. } { [%cal Rc6d4] } (10... O-O 11. g4 { White gets a very dangerous attack on
the kingside. }) (10... cxd4 { Releasing the tension is also not the best as it
removes the possibility of ever playing c4, closing the center and playing on
the queenside. } 11. Nxd4 Nc6 { And now White will gladly castle queenside
indeed: } 12. O-O-O { as now Black doesn't have any
options of going c4 and trying to attack on the queenside. White here has a
good version of this French structure, as we have made some progress on the
kingside, secured the dark-squares and our center is also very stable. Note
how useful it is to have the e5 defended by the pawn on f4. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gf4e5] }) 11. Ne2 { A very interesting moment! White has a
choice of plans in this exact position and I personally really like this
positional idea, reinforcing the d4 pawn with the knight and preparing
potentially to push the c-pawn to c3, if required. The knight has also moved
out of the way of the b-pawn, so the future b4 advance will not come with
tempo. } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Ge2d4,Gf3d4,Rb7b5,Rb5b4] } (11. O-O-O { I know most of you might be wondering - but okay, what if
White simply castles long? Isn't that more logical? Well, it is indeed
playable and it is the most popular move in the position, but then we have to
be ready to deal with Black's counterattacking options on the queenside, say
after } 11... c4 { This idea of closing down the structure on the queenside
in order to push the pawns on the queenside and to create the attack against
the king on b1 is very thematic in similar positions. Here it doesn't quite
work out as White has made more progress on the kingside, but it still leads
to very sharp play, say, after } { [%csl Rc4] } (11... b5) 12. g4 b5 13. f5 b4 14. Na4 { Black should be in difficulties here as White's
initiative is more developed, but the character of the play is nevertheless
sharp and double-edged! }) 11... b5 { This thematic
queenside expansion is very typical in all kinds of variations seen in the 3...
Nf6 system. Black gains more space on the queenside and also prepares to move
the bishop to b7. } { [%csl Gb5][%cal Gc8b7] } 12. g4 { This very aggressive move, expanding further on the
kingside, is also not at all as silly as it looks - mainly because the center
is very secure. It was played twice by my compatriot Ivan Šarić. The
position remains complex, but I feel White has very reasonable chances due to
the stability of the center and the kingside space advantage. It is very
dangerous for Black to castle here. }) 7. hxg5 Qxg5 8. Nh3 { This strange knight move, attacking the queen and
gaining a tempo for development, is the point of White's play. The argument is
that the lead in the development and open lines on the kingside will provide
us with more than sufficient compensation for the pawn. --- If you are asking
yourself - why put the knight on h3 and not on f3 - the answer is: on f3, the
knight does not block the queen from going to g4. } { [%csl Rg5][%cal Rh3g5,Gh3f4,Yh1h8,Gd1g4] } 8... Qe7 { The most natural and
traditional move in this position. Black retreats the queen and asks White to
demonstrate the compensation for the pawn. } (8... Qh4 { In the modern times - under the influence of computer engines - all
sorts of traditional lines have been challenged or fundamentally changed very
early in the game. The Alekhine-Chatard seems to be one such line, as even my
relatively weaker engine suggests this strange move - which was tested in 34
games in my database - as its first choice. --- What is the point of moving
the queen to h4? Well, for the moment Black is pinning the knight on h3 and
preventing the queen from going to g4. It seems as if we can simply kick the
queen away by playing g3 - but Black is trying to make an argument that this
will be a concession on White's part - due to a very specific variation where
this move will turn out to be crucial. --- Typical concrete stuff. } { [%csl Gg4][%cal Rh4h1] } 9. g3 { This seems very logical, kicking the Black queen away -
but it is not the only way of playing the position. } { [%csl Rh4][%cal Rg3h4] } (9. Nb5 { [%cal Rb5c7] } 9... Kd8 { Another point of this variation is this crazy king move, defending the c7 pawn
and preparing to play the good old a6 and c5 combo next. } { [%csl Gc7][%cal Gd8c7,Ga7a6,Gc7c5] } (9... Na6 { You might
be wondering - isn't it better to defend the pawn with the knight on a6 and
keep the castling rights? Well, the answer is - not really - as this move
allows White to keep the knight on b5 and prevents Black from ever playing c5
due to the weakness of the d6 square. --- Besides, with the h-file opened, it
would be suicidal to castle kingside, so Black is trying to make an argument
that their king is fairly secure in the center on d8, behind the two pawn
central pawn masses. }) 10. Qd2 a6 11. Nc3 c5 { The computer insists this variation is completely fine for Black. Given
it has only been seen in a single game in my database, it definitely requires
some further testing - but this whole 8...Qh4 idea seems to me to have a lot
of potential and surprise value! } { [%csl Rd4][%cal Rc5d4,Gd8c7] }) 9... Qe7 10. Qg4 { A
logical move, creating the pressure on the kingside that will also be seen in
the mainline. } { [%csl Rg7][%cal Rg4g7] } 10... g6 { The best way of dealing with the pressure on the g7 pawn. } (10... Kf8 11. Ng5 { There
are some problems along the h-file, e.g. } { [%cal Rg5h7,Rh1h7] } 11... h6 12. f4 { Something similar will be
seen in the line where the pawn is on g2 and this kind of position is
extremely dangerous for Black - keeping the king closer to the kingside is not
particularly desirable. }) 11. Ng5 { A typical move in this
variation, trying to create some pressure on the kingside, first by pressuring
the h7 pawn. } { [%cal Rg5f7,Rh1h7] } 11... h6 { Dealing with the threat and
hitting the knight, although for the moment there aren't any threats that
would involve capturing it due to the pin on the h-file. } { [%csl Rg5][%cal Rh6g5,Rh1h8] } 12. Bd3 { Bringing the bishop into action is very thematic, as now there are some
potential sacrifices on f7 in the air. } { [%cal Rd3g6] } 12... Nc6 { In this variation with the pawn,
Black can actually develop the knight and pressure d4 as sacrficices on f7
don't really work. } 13. O-O-O { In this line, White has to give up dreams of
immediate sacrifice on f7. } (13. Nxf7 { Now doesn't work with the g3 square
being taken away from the queen. } 13... h5 14. Qg5 { In the
variation without the pawn on g3, the queen would go there as if nothing
happened, but here White is forced to go to g4 and offer the exchange of
queens as the queen has to keep an eye on the g6 pawn. This is obviously, very
undesirable for White and it demonstrates the entire justification for the Qh4
inclusion for Black early on move 8. } { [%cal Rg5g6,Gg5e7] } 14... Rg8 { Removing the
attacked rook. } { [%csl Gg6][%cal Gg8g6] } 15. Qxe7+ { White doesn't have anything better. } 15... Kxe7 16. Ng5 { And now Black can collect the d4 pawn. } 16... Nxd4 { Black is definitely not worse in
this queenless middlegame as the only weakness on g6 is easily covered and
White's pieces on d3 and c3 are somewhat in the way of Black's pawns on c5 and
d5. Black's structure is very compact, as well and the king is well-positioned
in the center. }) 13... Nf8 { Black is securing
the kingside and intends to play Bd7 and O-O-O next. } { [%cal Gf8g6,Gf8e6,Gc8d7,Ge8c8] } 14. Nf3 { Now, it transpires that there is not much for the knight on f3 to do on
g5 any longer, so retreating it is quite sensible, as some additional
protection is added to the d4 pawn. White can be happy because Black was at
least dissuaded from going for the c5 undermining plan. } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gf3d4] } 14... Bd7 15. Qf4 { Attacking the pawn on h6. } { [%cal Rf4h6,Rh1h6] } 15... O-O-O { And Black
finally gives up the pawn back to complete development and place the king into
safety. This is one of the reasons why it is better not to play Kf8 earlier
but to move g6 instead. The position is complex and requires some additional
practical testing, but it is not 100% clear if White has any objective
advantage in this variation. } { [%cal Gg6g5,Gf8g6] }) 9. Qg4 { White includes the queen
into the game and targets the kingside in typical French manner. Now Black is
at a big crossroad - how to deal with the threat to the g7 pawn? } { [%cal Rg4g7] } (9. Nf4 { Moving the knight to f4 is actually even more popular move in the position,
but it is seemingly not critical as it allows Black more time to develop/
create threats. } 9... c5 { This seems to be a less wild solution, immediately
challenging the center and allowing the jump of the knight to b5, but things
are not so clear cut. } (9... Nc6 10. Qg4 { [%cal Rg4g7] } (10. Qd2 { Might be
better, but here White is playing for the long-term compensation for the pawn. } 10... Nf8 { Defending h7. } { [%csl Gh7][%cal Gf8h7] } 11. Nh5 Rg8 { And then also g7.
White definitely has compensation for the pawn, but not more. }) 10... g6 { And now it seems White simply has an inferior version of the main lines as I
feel it is much better to try and get the knight to g5 in these positions. } (10... Nxd4 { is possible, going for some crazy
complications after } 11. O-O-O Nf5 12. Nfxd5 exd5 13. Nxd5 Qxe5 14. Bb5 { But I feel this is a bit unpleasant to play as Black in a practical game as
you need to know more details - so not sure why you would want to do so if
there are easier solutions available. })) 10. Nb5 Kd8 { The idea we have seen previously - placing the king to d8 to deal with the
threat on c7. } { [%csl Gc7][%cal Gd8c7] } 11. dxc5 Nc6 { Both the pawns on c5 and e5
are exposed and the position is very complicated, but very hard to play for
both sides! } { [%cal Rc6e5,Rd7c5] }) 9... g6 { The most common and natural way of dealing with the
threat to the g7 pawn - but now we can see why it is not optimal in the
situation where Black hasn't provoked White into playing g3 earlier. } (9... Kf8 { Defending with the king is rarely a good idea in these positions with the
h-pawn gone and the dark-squared bishops exchanged - the life of the monarch
on the kingside is way too perilous. } 10. f4 c5 { Black probably shouldn't go
for this counterplay - but if they don't, what else should they do? In order
to illustrate the point, let's see what happens here: } 11. Ng5 { A standard maneuver we have also seen in the position with the pawn on
g3, creating pressure against the h7 pawn. } { [%cal Rg5h7] } 11... h6 12. Nb5 { The
knight is coming to d6, the f7 will be under attack and Black is in deep
trouble. There are better moves available on move 10, of course, but then we
get something similar to lines examined via the 8...Qh4 move order, when White
has the advantage as the king on f8 is not ideally placed (we have seen that
Black more commonly wants to castle it on the queenside in these positions). } { [%cal Gb5d6,Gb5c7] }) (9... f5 { On the other hand, this typical French move,
defending the g7 pawn with the queen is possible here as the queen is on e7.
However, this move does make the structure on the kingside somewhat less
flexible and weakens the dark-square complex further,, allowing White to
switch on the more protracted, maneuvering play. } { [%cal Ge7g7,Rf5g4] } 10. Qg3 { The
queen is ideally placed on g3 here, exerting influence on the g-file and
eyeing the g5 and g7 squares. } { [%cal Rg3g8] } 10... Nc6 { A logical move - trying to develop and
maybe aim for long castling? Here the plan with c5 or a6-c5 is simply too slow
and is met with the same maneuver of the knight to f4. } 11. Nf4 { A very nice move, creating the threat of Ng6 -
another consequence of moving the f-pawn and weakening the g6 square. } { [%csl Gf4,Rg6][%cal Gf4g6,Rg6h8,Rg6e7] } 11... Nf8 { Desperately trying to defend the g6 square and maybe
prepare Bd7-O-O-O ideas. } { [%cal Gf8g6,Gc8d7] } 12. O-O-O { Alas, it transpires White has further
tactical ideas in position which prevent Black from going for the natural
development. } 12... Bd7? { This move actually loses on the spot - but it is not
easy to see why. } (12... Qf7 { Is probably necessary here, but then White
finishes up the development with } 13. Be2 { Now creating some Bh5 ideas. White also has the option of going Nb5, or even
Na4-Nc5 if Black moves the a-pawn and Black is in deep trouble, as it is very
hard to move the pieces here. White has more than sufficient compensation for
the pawn. } { [%cal Ge2h5,Gc3a4,Gc3b5,Ga4c5,Gc2c4] }) 13. Nfxd5 { Boom! This move is
possible because the bishop is blocking the queen's defence of the c7 square
and now her majesty is impossible to defend both c7 and g7 squares. } { [%csl Rc7,Rd5,Rg7][%cal Rg3g7,Ye7c7] } 13... exd5 14. Nxd5 Qd8 15. Qxg7 { And Black's position is done. } { [%csl Rh8][%cal Rg7h8,Gd5f6] }) 10. Ng5 { A very standard move, creating a threat to the h7
pawn. } { [%cal Rg5h7,Rh1h7] } 10... h5 { Possibly a more reliable option for Black here, although
this forces the queen on the good square on f4, makes the structure less
flexible and also ensures that the knight will sit forever on g5. } { [%csl Gg5] } (10... h6 { This move worked well when the pawn was on g3, but here it is not great due to
the following tactical possibility. } 11. Bd3 { Introducing the
threat of Nxf7. } { [%cal Rg5f7] } 11... Nc6 { There is virtually nothing better - Black has to allow
White to execute the sacrificial idea. } 12. Nxf7 h5 { This is a necessary move,
trying to dislodge the queen from the square where it is attacking e6. } (12... Kxf7 { Accepting the sacrifice immediately is even worse as after } 13. Bxg6+ Kg8 (13... Kg7 { This defense seems more tricky as now Black has some ideas of
playing Qg5, but here we can play the very accurate move } 14. Rh5 { Preventing the queen from coming to g5 and
threatening some nasty discoveries. Note that we don't necessarily need to win
immediately here - Black's king is in permanent peril and we can even make
some slow moves such as O-O-O, Nb5, Rh3, etc. } { [%cal Gh5g5,Ge1c1,Gh5h3,Gc3b5] }) 14. Bh5+ { The
queen is nicely placed, eyeing the e6 square. White has a winning attack here. } { [%cal Rg4e6] }) 13. Qg3 { This wouldn't have been possible if the pawn was on g3 - and this
makes a big difference when it comes to the evaluation of this position. } 13... Kxf7 14. Bxg6+ Kg8 { Already the only move here. } (14... Kf8 { Loses to } 15. Rh4 { [%cal Gh4f4] }) (14... Kg7 { Loses to } 15. Bxh5+ Kf8 16. Qf4+ Kg7 17. O-O-O { The king will not survive here. }) 15. Bxh5+ { And White collects the second
pawn and has an ongoing attack. Black already has to bail out to an inferior
endgame with } 15... Qg7 16. Qf4 Ndxe5 17. dxe5 Qxe5+ 18. Qxe5 Nxe5 { But now the
material equality is restored and we still have a lead in development and
better placed pieces. Besides, Black needs to find a series of only moves to
even get here, which is not an easy task. Besides, why would Black want to
willingly play such a variation just to end up in an inferior endgame if there
are better alternatives along the way. }) 11. Qf4 { The queen and the knight sit very nicely on f4 and g5. Black's main issue is
the weakness of the dark-squares on the kingside. Furthermore, White can now
play g4, undermining the structure on the kingside virtually at any moment.
White will castle long and then play g4 at some point and Black is very much
struggling in this position - which is why the move 8...Qh4 seems to be a much
better line in this variation. } { [%csl Gf4,Rf6,Gg5,Rg7,Rh6] } *


