[Black "Introduction #1"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "Nemec, Vjekoslav"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C00"]
[Opening "French Defense"]
[StudyName "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations"]
[ChapterName "French Defence - Introduction #1"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/hUFnodoF/dQnRF3FM"]

1. e4 e6 { Hello dear students and chess friends, and welcome to this study in which we are going to take a very close look at a very popular and somewhat controversial defence available to Black against 1.e4 that has been giving proper headache to club players, as well as world-class players, for almost 200 hundred years - the French Defence, arising after the initial moves 1.e4 e6.
French Defence is one of those openings with whom people either love deeply (as many Black players love to play it religiously) or hate deeply (most commonly White players who have trouble dealing with it, but also some Black players who encounter regular difficulties due to which they start considering it dubious).
In this study/.pgn, we will be taking an introductory look at the French defence. We are going to start by examining its origins and general philosophy, then we will move to the basic overview of concrete variations. However, we will not be diving too deeply into the varaitions due to the following:
A) It makes no sense to dive deep into the theory in the Introductory .pgn/study devoted to a specific opening and it is not the purpose of this material
B) I feel many people overly focus on concrete variations when they start learning a new opening instead of focusing on understanding the concepts behind the moves in these concrete variations (and behind the opening as a whole). This is why after the overview of the most common variations, we will shift our focus to key themes and middlegame ideas. I firmly believe that understanding a couple of key ideas (e.g. which pawn breaks are thematic, which pieces should be exchanged, which typical plans are available to both sides) should be the very first step whenever we start studying a new opening (even when we are talking about the French defence which has an abundance of typical motifs for both sides).
Finally, we will conclude matters by mentioning model players - players who used to employ French Defence throughout their careers with reasonable success. I firmly believe that studying model games by model players in an opening you play is a very underrated method of studying that helps you to develop the "feel" and understanding as opposed to pure memorization.
My hope is that you will have at least a basic idea about French Defence after going through the material presented in this file (and watching the accompanying video). } *


[Event "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations: French Defence - Introduction #2"]
[Date "2020.03.20"]
[White "French Defence"]
[Black "Introduction #2"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "Nemec, Vjekoslav"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C00"]
[Opening "French Defense"]
[StudyName "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations"]
[ChapterName "French Defence - Introduction #2"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/hUFnodoF/EvUbJE20"]

1. e4 e6 { [%csl Re4][%cal Gd7d5,Gd2d4] } 2. d4 d5 { So, what kind of opening is the French defence and for what kind of players it is suitable? Well, it is always a little bit tricky to put any opening in a generic category - especially in the modern day where the richness of possibilities and types of positions one obtains has exponentially increased in all openings. But if I had to describe French Defence in one word, I would definitely describe it as a counter-attacking opening.
The main reason for my description is the fact that Black doesn't fight for the center from the get-go, but rather intentionally invites White to gain some space, create a long pawn chain and then play against that very chain later down the road. To an extent, this is a very hypermodern idea, that can also be seen in some other openings, such as Pirc, Modern and so on.
But in the French Defence, the surrender of central control is not as radical as we do fight for it already on move 2.
Of course, it has to be said that such counterattacking style is not for everybody. Very often, Black has to be prepared to allow White to gain space and then handle a little bit cramped position. Also, White very often tries to create an attack on the kingside, so Black often does have to show some nerves and show some defensive skills in order to survive and take over in a later stage of the game.
Last but not least, the French Defence features a lot of very closed positions involving protracted maneuvering behind long pawn chains, which requires a very developed sense of positional understanding. Due to everything mentioned above (and many other factors), the French Defence is very complicated and difficult to play and is, in general, not to be recommended to people newer to chess/those on lower rating levels. Even on higher rating levels, people usually either love it or completely hate it, probably even more than any other opening.
On the other hand - almost as any other opening, there are many different ways in which one can try to
handle the French for both colours. And this richness in possibilities, types of positions and different structures is what has always attracted a fair share of followers and aficionados and it will probably continue to do so until chess gets overshadowed by Chess960.
So, if you are wondering whether French is for you, I would urge you to go through the material presented in this .pgn/study and then try it out for yourself - there is no better way of realizing whether you want to play a certain opening rather than trying it out in practice and seeing whether it fits you or not! } *


[Event "French Defence Stem Game"]
[Site "London ENG - Paris FRA"]
[Date "1834.??.??"]
[White "London Chess Club"]
[Black "Paris Chess Club"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Annotator "Nemec, Vjekoslav"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C01"]
[Opening "French Defense: Exchange Variation"]
[StudyName "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations"]
[ChapterName "London Chess Club - Paris Chess Club"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/hUFnodoF/Q515zB4g"]

{ In order to track down the history of the French Defence, we have to go back all the way to the year 1834, when the opening was employed in the correspondence game between the London Chess Club and Paris Chess Club. It wasn't necessarily the first recorded game in chess history where this move was employed, but due to the relatively high profile of the game and the fact that the Paris Chess Club won, the name of the opening stuck ever since. I will be providing this historic encounter - with some brief notes - in this study as well, as I feel the Introduction of the opening wouldn't be complete without it. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 { How very fitting! In the very game after which the opening has been named, White employs the notorious Exchange variation - which is regarded as very unambitious and boring and that is virtually every French Defence player's worst nightmare as it leads to a very symmetrical position. There is some poetic justice in the fact that Black went on to win this historic game. } 3... exd5 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bd3 c5 { An attempt to spice things up a little bit and to go for a position with the isolated pawn, if required. } 6. Qe2+ Be7 7. dxc5 { Temporarily winning a pawn, but modern theory showcases that White can't realistically hope to hold on to that pawn for very long and that the whole excursion of the queen to e2 is arguably not the most precise or ambitious. } 7... O-O 8. Be3 Re8 { Threatening Bxc5 due to the pin on the queen on e2. } { [%cal Re8e2] } 9. Bb5 { Moving the same piece twice in the opening and helping Black develop further. } 9... Nc6 10. Nd4 { Again violating the principle of moving the same piece twice - such was the level at a time - even in correspondence games. } 10... Bxc5 { Very nice. Black realizes they don't have to fear the attack on the c6 square as they have a massive lead in development due to the fact White has been losing a lot of time by moving the same pieces twice. } 11. Bxc6 { I guess White realized around here that they can't really take on c6 with the knight and try to win an exchange due to the massive lag in development. } (11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bxc6 { seems problematic for Black as they seemingly lose na exchange, but it turns out Black can more or less ignore this due to the idea of d4, winning the bishop on e3, e.g. } { [%csl Ra8,Re8][%cal Rc6e8,Rc6a8] } 12... Bd7 13. Bxa8 d4 { And Black will collect both the bishop on a8 and the bishop on e3 and keep a decisive advantage. } { [%csl Ra8,Re3] }) 11... bxc6 12. c3 { Trying desperately to hold on to the strong knight on d4,
but the annoying pin along the e-file is too strong. } 12... Bxd4 13. cxd4 c5 { Very powerful, threatening to either take on d4, or move the d5 pawn to d4 if White takes, in both cases winning the bishop on e3 due to the pin along the e-file. } { [%cal Gc5d4,Gd5d4,Re8e1] } 14. Qd3 { Getting out of the pin, but once again moving the same piece twice, further falling behind in development. } 14... Qb6 { A strong position for the queen, threatening the b2 pawn,
as well as Ba6. } { [%cal Rb6b2,Gc8a6] } 15. O-O { Deciding to give up an exchange just to get the king
to safety and deal with the annoying pin on the e-file. } 15... Ba6 { This wins an exchange due the skewer on the queen and the rook on d3 and f1. } { [%csl Rd3,Rf1][%cal Ra6f1] } 16. Qb3 { I am not sure if it was worth exchanging queens when White is also losing the material, but in any case, the position remains lost as White will simply be down material. } 16... Qxb3 17. axb3 Bxf1 18. Kxf1 Ng4 { A good practical solution - attacking the bishop on e3 and intending to simplify the position. It is always good to KISS (Keep It Simple Stupid) when you have the material advantage. } { [%cal Rg4e3,Rg4h2] } 19. dxc5 Nxe3+ 20. fxe3 Rxe3 { White doesn't even have a pawn for the exchange + White's pawns are very weak, so the outcome of the game is not in very much doubt. } 21. Nd2 Rae8 22. b4 Rd3 23. Rxa7 { This doesn't help - the pawns on the queenside are way too far away to be a real danger. } 23... Rxd2 24. b5 { The idea was to try and push these pawns, but this is simply too slow. } { [%csl Gb5,Gc5] } 24... Rxb2 25. b6 d4 26. b7 d3 27. Ra8 Kf8 { Simply dealing with the threat of promoting the pawn as the rook on b2 is x-raying the b8 square, so here London decided to call it a day and resign the game. Very good marketing for the French Defence and not the best ever model game for all lovers of the Exchange French with White. But an interesting historical game nonetheless! } 0-1


[Event "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations: The French Defence - Sidelines"]
[Date "2020.03.20"]
[White "The French Defence"]
[Black "Sidelines"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "Nemec, Vjekoslav"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C00"]
[Opening "French Defense: Horwitz Attack, Papa-Ticulat Gambit"]
[StudyName "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations"]
[ChapterName "The French Defence - Sidelines"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/hUFnodoF/E0X9xNij"]

1. e4 e6 { Now that we have gained some context about the history and the basic philosophy behind the French Defence, let's start exploring the opening a little bit more deeply and diving into the brief overview of theoretical lines available to both sides.
Even though I have previously emphasized not focusing too much on concrete theory and rather focusing on the key ideas and themes, I thought it made a lot of sense to first introduce the variations and then to talk about the resulting pawn structures and middlegame themes that can arise from these variations. } 2. b3 { First of all, this silly-looking flank move, preparing to fianchetto the bishop to b2, leads to an enterprising sideline that has every right to exist. White intends to essentially gambit a pawn in return for quick development. } (2. d4 { In virtually 90% of the games - especially at the lower rated levels, White players will almost automatically place the second pawn in the center. It is very logical to follow the opening principle of occupying the center and it is also objectively the most promising move.
With that being said, White doesn't necessarily have to do so and there are a lot of sidelines available to the first player as early as move 2. In this chapter of the study/.pgn, we will take a brief look at some common early deviations and the most common ideas associated with them. } { [%csl Gd4,Ge4] }) (2. Nf3 d5 3. e5 { As we will see later down the road, the pawn on d4 often becomes a target of the attack for Black in the French defence, so by playing in this manner White tries to avoid the opponent with the target. Furthermore, there are some ideas to divert the pawn on c5 with the help of the flank sacrifice. The downside of such an approach is that White does have significantly less central control as no pawns have been placed in the center. } 3... c5 { The most common and natural move, advancing the c-pawn and gaining some space in the center and the queenside. } { [%csl Gc5,Gd5] } 4. b4 { White has other options, but the most common move in this exact position is this lunge of the b-pawn, leading to the so-called Wing Gambit. The idea is to distract the pawn from c5 in order to play d4 under the better circumstances - and also to try to exchange the dark-squared bishops and weaken Black's control of the dark-squares. } 4... cxb4 5. a3 { And now if Black takes the pawn on a3 White will recapture with the bishop and happily exchange the defender of the weakened dark-squares - which is why Black most commonly refuses the second pawn. White will also place the d-pawn in the center and Black will not be able to attack it with the c-pawn. This is definitely a playable option, although objectively it is probably not fully correct. } { [%cal Gc1a3,Ra3f8] }) (2. f4 { Intending to place the pawn on e5 in situation where it will be protected by the pawn on f4. This is a move very frequently played by Hikaru Nakamura in blitz games, so it definitely has some practical value. } { [%cal Ge4e5] } 2... d5 3. e5 c5 { And here White will try to play slowly by placing the pawns on d3 and c3, restraining Black's activity in the center and on the queenside and then use the space advantage on the kingside to their benefit. Black will almost certainly play on the queenside. Not a critical variation by any means, but one that has a definite right to exist. } { [%csl Gc5,Gd5][%cal Gc2c3,Gg1f3] }) (2. d3 { This leads to a schematic/universal setup that is known as the King's Indian Attack. White players who play like this often try to employ this scheme against multiple openings, although the move is very typical against the French defence as Black has already moved the pawn to e6. } 2... d5 3. Nd2 { The point of White's play. White tries to protect the e-pawn while avoiding the queen exchange and intends to follow a standard developing scheme involving g3-Bg2-Nf3-O-O-h4-Re1-Nf1-Nfh2-Ng4-h5-h6 and so on. If the knight appears on f6, White will push the pawn forward. It is not at all naive to play against this setup and it scores very well in practice, even though there are different ways in which Black can try to handle it. Most commonly - focusing on the queenside play will be the name of the game for Black. } { [%cal Gd2e4,Gd3e4] }) (2. Qe2 { Last but not least, let's conclude our conversation about the strange 2nd moves by White by mentioning this weird-looking queen move, that violates almost every basic opening principle (don't move your queen too early, don't block your pieces from developing). However, the move has a very simple idea - it is aimed against Black playing d5 as now Black would be unable to recapture on d5 with the pawn due to the pin. } { [%cal Ge2e8] } 2... d5 { This is probably not a good idea when the queen has been moved to e2, actually, but it allows me to illustrate the point behind White's play. } (2... Be7 { Black should probably move the bishop to e7, blocking
the e-file, and then play d5 next. } { [%csl Ge7][%cal Gd7d5] }) (2... c5 { transposing to some sort of Sicilian (just like in 2.b3 lines) is also a possibility. }) 3. exd5 { And now we see the point. Black is unable to execute a desirable capture with the pawn (remember - this was the reason why 1...e6 was played to begin with!). } 3... Qxd5 4. Nc3 { And White gains a free tempo on the queen in the style of the Scandinavian defence, although it is also possible to develop the other knight. In any case, this line is justification for White's early queen move and Black should be aware of this! }) 2... d5 { The most natural move for the French Defence players, although not a must by Black. } (2... c5 { For example, Black can also move the c-pawn and transpose to a variation of the 2...e6 Sicilian. However, White can try to make an argument this is in their favour as French Defence players usually don't play the
Sicilian. Still, you need to be aware of this option and probably should include this variation in your repertoire if you want to play this as White. }) 3. Bb2 { White's point is this move, sacrificing the pawn on e4. It looks very risky and dubious, but it is not at all so bad as it looks. } 3... dxe4 { The most principled reply, although Black is by no means forced to capture the pawn on e4. As a matter of fact, refusing the offer might actually be a better idea - especially in a practical game - but for the sake of this overview let's take a look at this - the most common reply. } 4. Nc3 { Developing a piece with a gain of tempo and attacking the pawn on e4. } { [%csl Re4][%cal Rc3e4] } 4... Nf6 { Probably the best idea - simply developing and not intending to keep the pawn necessarily. } (4... f5 { Moving the f-pawn is very risky as then White plays } 5. f3 { And seeks to include the knight from g1 into the game under very favourable circumstances. This is actually quite dangerous for Black and White's practical results are very good. }) 5. Qe2 { And White will probably regain the pawn on e4 while Black will catch up in development and we have a game of chess in front of ourselves. White is probably happy because the game doesn't resemble the usual French defence, which is exactly the point of playing all these sidelines. } { [%cal Re2e4,Rc3e4] } *


[Event "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations: French Defence - Exchange Variation"]
[Date "2020.03.20"]
[White "French Defence"]
[Black "Exchange Variation"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "Nemec, Vjekoslav"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C01"]
[Opening "French Defense: Exchange Variation"]
[StudyName "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations"]
[ChapterName "French Defence - Exchange Variation"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/hUFnodoF/DbU609HA"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 { As mentioned earlier, this is by far the most common move that White plays against the French defence. It is very logical to occupy the center and place the 2nd pawn there and it is not surprising that it is the main theoretical continuation. } 2... d5 { Again, not a very surprising move, as the sole point of playing 1...e6 was to push the d-pawn on the next move and fight for the share in the center with a small delay. Black is also trying to make an argument that they are forcing White to react to the threat of taking on e4 - and it is precisely on move 3 where White will have a major theoretical choice of variation. } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Rd5e4] } 3. exd5 { The first move we are going to mention is this capture on d5, leading to the dreaded French Exchange variation. Due to its symmetrical pawn structure, it is considered to be as very harmless and has a reputation of being utterly boring.
It is often quoted by Black players as the biggest drawback of the French Defence - as it is very difficult (albeit, not completely impossible) to create a real winning chances (for both sides). } 3... exd5 { The most common recapture, leading to the aforementioned symmetrical pawn structure can also arise via some other openings (e.g. Berlin, Petroff). White's problem is also that Black's minor pieces haven't yet been moved, so they retain maximum flexibility, so Black can react pretty well to any arrangement of the pieces that White chooses. Objectively, White shouldn't have a theoretical advantage, but there is a lot of chess to be played and it can be used very effectively as a psychological weapon. } { [%csl Ga2,Ra7,Gb2,Rb7,Gc2,Rc7,Gd4,Rd5] } (3... Qxd5 { Sometimes, out of desperation, Black players do recapture the queen instead of the pawn, but this allows White to kick the queen away with the gain of tempo with either } 4. Nc3 (4. c4 { In both cases, Black will have some sort of bad Scandinavian as the pawn on e6 is restricting the bishop on e6. } { [%cal Rc8g4] })) *


[Event "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations: French Defence - The Advance Variation"]
[Date "2020.03.20"]
[White "French Defence"]
[Black "The Advance Variation"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "Nemec, Vjekoslav"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C02"]
[Opening "French Defense: Advance Variation"]
[StudyName "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations"]
[ChapterName "French Defence - The Advance Variation"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/hUFnodoF/PZKWKfof"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 { As we have previously seen, capturing on d5 on move 3 is possible, but not necessarily the most ambitious. The other move of the e-pawn, though, is also possible and leads to the so-called Advance variation. It is one of the oldest ways of meeting the French Defence that is still very relevant and played on all levels - so any French Defence player needs to study it properly.
So what is the idea behind the advance of the pawn? Well, White is trying to exploit the fact that Black didn't fight for the central squares from the beginning and grab some space in the center of the board. Black, on the other hand, will try to make an argument that it will be difficult for White to maintain this pawn chain and that they should be able to attack it or undermine it.
This theme is seen in numerous other variations of the French Defence, but here it is exhibited in its purest form. } { [%csl Gd4,Ge5] } 3... c5 { The most principled move, attacking the base of the pawn chain - the pawn on d4. Black would love to take on d4 next and isolate the e5 pawn somewhat. This play against the center is the central theme of not only this particular variation but the entire French Defence and playing c5 as a response to e5 is often made quite automatically. } { [%cal Rc5d4] } 4. c3 { This is the starting point of the French Defence Advance variation and a very standard pawn structure for this opening. Black wants to create play against the pawn chain - either by attacking the d4 pawn with the help of the moves such as Nc6 and Qb6 - or by undermining the front pawn on e5 with the help of a timely f6 break. White, on the other hand, want to utilize the space in the center and on the kingside to go for the attack (as they say - you should play on the side of the board where your pawn chain is pointing to). Alternatively, White sometimes has ideas of reducing the pressure with the help of the moves a3 and then b4. In some variations, White even sacrifices the d4 pawn in order to develop quickly and play against the king on e8. A typical French struggle is ahead of us. } { [%csl Rd4][%cal Gb8c6,Gd8b6,Rb6d4,Gf7f6,Gg1f3,Ga2a3,Gb2b4] } *


[Event "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations: French Defence - Lines with Bd3"]
[Date "2022.11.23"]
[White "French Defence"]
[Black "Lines with Bd3"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "Nemec, Vjekoslav"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C00"]
[Opening "French Defense: Schlechter Variation"]
[StudyName "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations"]
[ChapterName "French Defence - Lines with Bd3"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/hUFnodoF/bpp9tQXX"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Bd3 { Apart from moving the e-pawn, White also has the option of defending it with a piece. In most cases, White
will embark to do so with the knight on the 3rd move, by either playing 3.Nd2 or 3.Nc3. However, it is also possible to defend it with the bishop! This looks a little bit strange as it violates one of the basic opening rules (knights before bishops), but the idea is to get the bishop to f3 (of all places) and then to claim it is exerting some pressure against the Black queenside. It is not objectively the most dangerous or critical continuation, but it is a sideline that can throw Black off a little bit. } { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gd3e4] } (3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bd3 { Here White is trying to make an argument that this leads to a better version as the bishop has been drawn to b4, but on the other hand, Black does get the option of playing Bxc3 and doubling the c-pawns at some moment and will strike with the same c5 push at some point, so it is not 100% clear whether White benefits from the inclusion of 3.Nc3 Bb4 all that much. In any case, it is good to be aware that these Bd3 ideas exist in different variations - especially if you want to play the French with the Black pieces. } { [%csl Rc3] }) 3... dxe4 { Not the only move, but a very principled one. Black takes on e4 and draws the bishop on e4, intending to attack it with the knight next. } 4. Bxe4 Nf6 5. Bf3 { The point of White's opening. White tries to make an argument that the bishop is a little bit pesky on f3 as it is pressuring Black's queenside. But on the other hand, White did lose some time to get it there (Bd3-Be4-Bf3), so Black should probably be fine after they execute a timely advance of the c-pawn. As a matter of fact, an immediate strike is already possible. } { [%cal Rf3a8,Gg1e2] } 5... c5 { And here the theory continues, but I think the main point of the variation has been demonstrated. I have personally played the line with 3.Nc3 Bb4 4. Bd3 a lot, but with mixed success. These variations can be quite effective for White as a surprise, but objectively speaking, they are simply not the best options available to the first player. } *


[Event "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations: The French Defence - 3.Nd2"]
[Date "2020.03.20"]
[White "The French Defence"]
[Black "3.Nd2"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "Nemec, Vjekoslav"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C05"]
[Opening "French Defense: Tarrasch Variation, Closed Variation"]
[StudyName "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations"]
[ChapterName "The French Defence - 3.Nd2"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/hUFnodoF/8MFRpjOH"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 { As we have just seen, White has several "offbeat" ways of dealing with the tension between the d- and e-pawns on move 3. However, by far the most common third move involves defending the pawn on e4 with the knight - either from d2 or from c3. There is actually quite a significant difference between the two - and both moves are almost equally good and popular, so the choice is mostly a matter of taste. } 3. Nd2 { Let's start by examining this move first, which leads to the so-called Tarrasch variation of the French Defence. At first glance, this looks a little bit ridiculous - why would White develop the knight on such a square where it is blocking the bishop instead of the more active c3 square? Well, this move does have a few
benefits:
A) First of all White doesn't allow the annoying ping with Bb4 which does happen in situations where the knight ends up on c3
B) White keeps the c-pawn free, intending to meet c5 by Black with c3
C) White intends to move this knight to f3 in the future, bolstering the center and keeping things as harmonious as possible. Of course, this is a little bit modest as the knight is less active here (say, it doesn't increase the pressure on the d5 square).
In general, Tarrasch is regarded as somewhat less ambitious and as a safer option against the French, although these generalizations about opening lines always have to be taken with a grain of salt.
In any case, Black now has a choice and usually chooses between three main moves. } { [%cal Gd2e4] } 3... Nf6 { This is a very natural move in the French Defence and we will also see it against 3.Nc3. Black attacks the e4 pawn and forces it to advance, transposing to the same structure we have seen in the advance variation. } (3... dxe4 { Apart from the two moves mentioned above, Black can also immediately capture on e4, leading to the so-called Rubinstein variation of the French Defence - a line that is considered somewhat passive, but also very solid. Black concedes the center, but the claim is that they will manage to exchange some pieces and then achieve the liberating c5 break later down the road. One additional advantage of this move order is that it can be employed against both 3.Nd2 and 3.Nc3. } 4. Nxe4 Nd7 { The main move in the position. Black prepares to place the knight to f6 and then to recapture with the knight if White captures it. } (4... Nf6 5. Nxf6+ { Now neither of Black's recaptures are fully satisfactory, to be honest. } 5... Qxf6 { Now the queen is somewhat exposed on f6 as after } (5... gxf6 { Has been played in practice, but I feel it is a bit too early to open up the g-file and make a concession in terms of the pawn structure in hope of some attack in the future? }) 6. Nf3 { There is already the idea to go Bg5 and Black probably has to spend another tempo to prevent that move. Black's practical results are really bad here and I wouldn't really recommend you to go for this if you do want to circumvent the mainlines and play the Rubinstein! } { [%csl Gg5][%cal Gc1g5] }) (4... Bd7 { Apart from the Nd7 move, one also needs to be aware of this move, leading to the so-called Fort-Knox variation of the Rubinstein defence. Black intends to move the bishop to c6 and then develop the knight to d7. } 5. Nf3 Bc6 { The idea is quite often to give up the bishop for the knight on f3 (as Black has less space, they do want to
exchange pieces) and then play that positions. It is probably not the most ambitious or critical variation, but it has been played by quite a few strong players, so it is probably not that bad. White definitely needs to know some stuff to navigate the resulting positions. } { [%cal Rc6f3] }) 5. Nf3 Ngf6 { The point of Black's play. Now the knight on e4 is somewhat exposed and if the bishop defends it, the other knight will come to f6 to harass that bishop. } 6. Nxf6+ { Once again the best and the most popular move as White doesn't really want to move the knight to another passive square. } 6... Nxf6 { The difference allows me to illustrate the main idea! Black recaptures with the knight and claims that all
piece exchanges are in their favour due to their lack of space. Furthermore, Black can usually undermine the center with the timely c5 without any issues - sometimes even on the very next move, say, after } 7. Bd3 c5 { Of course, this is not necessary, but in order to illustrate the main idea, let's include this move here. Remember this typical idea for this variation as it often happens under different circumstances. }) (3... Be7) (3... Nc6) (3... a6) (3... h6 { I definitely wouldn't expect to meet them at the beginning of your chess/French Defence journey as they are very subtle and require some deeper understanding of the nuances (I am also not 100% sure I can explain them fully, to be honest). But they are mentioned in books as possibilities and the former (3...Be7) was given as the main move in, say, Chessable course on the French defence by Yuriy Krykun, so I just want to mention them here so that both White and Black are aware they are a possibility. I would expect these moves to become more relevant closer you get to 2000+ level. }) (3... c5 { Nowadays, I believe striking in the center is the main option. Black tries to exploit the lack of pressure on d5 and strike immediately, intending to recapture on d5 with the queen, most commonly. Note that such play wouldn't really work with the knight on c3 - see notes to the 3.Nc3 system. }) 4. e5 Nfd7 5. Bd3 { White develops the bishop first here in order to get the knight to e2 without locking the bishop. There are other possibilities but for the purpose of this intro, I will just demonstrate the mainline. } { [%cal Gg1e2] } 5... c5 { A thematic central counterstrike in the French Defence. } { [%csl Rd4][%cal Rc5d4] } 6. c3 Nc6 { Increasing the pressure on the d4 pawn. } { [%cal Rc6d4,Rc5d4] } 7. Ne2 { This is the point! Instead of developing the knight to the natural square on f3, White moves it to e2 in order to keep f3 open for the other knight. This will allow White to stabilize the situation in the center and defend all the potential weaknesses, say after } { [%cal Gd2f3] } 7... Qb6 { Trying to increase the pressure on d4, but this move is not
really good as the whole attack on the center is easily rebuffed. } (7... cxd4 8. cxd4 f6 { Is instead played, giving up on the idea of the attack on the d4 point and trying to open up the position and profit from the fact that the knight on d2 is blocking the bishop on c1 and somewhat disturbing White's coordination. Even here White's results are reasonably well in practice. }) 8. Nf3 { And now White will castle next and then at a later stage start playing on the kingside (either by pushing the pawns, lifting the rooks or jumping with the knights). Black does have some counter chances
connected with f6, but if that is the plan then why waste time to bring the queen to b6 and force White to make a move they want to make anyway (Nf3). } { [%csl Gc3,Gd4,Ge5] } *


[Event "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations: French Defence - 3. Nc3"]
[Date "2020.03.20"]
[White "French Defence"]
[Black "3. Nc3"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "Nemec, Vjekoslav"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C18"]
[Opening "French Defense: Winawer Variation, Advance Variation"]
[StudyName "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations"]
[ChapterName "French Defence - 3. Nc3"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/hUFnodoF/tqpD0UZz"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 { Finally, we have arrived to the most popular move, developing the knight on a square where it exerts maximum influence. It is very helpful in a number of variations - for example, in many cases Black can't just go for some strange-looking 3rd moves as was the case in the Tarrasch variation - mainly because with the knight pressuring d5, it is impossible to recapture the pawn on d5 with the queen. The downside of this move is that it makes the knight vulnerable to the 3... Bb4 - which is actually one of the main variations in this entire system.
The debate revolving around 3. Nc3 and 3. Nd2 (whether one move is better or another) has been raging forever among those trying to beat the French and the general verdict is that 3. Nc3 is more critical, but also more double-edged.
Now Black commonly chooses between two big options. } { [%csl Gc3,Rd5][%cal Gc3e4,Rc3d5] } (3. Nd2 Be7 4. Bd3 { We will see in the main variation that this reply to Be7 ideas with the knight on c3 is really good for White. The reason is that the knight is much more active on c3 than on d2 when it comes to the opening of the center with the help of the delayed c5 push. } 4... c5 5. dxc5 Nf6 6. exd5 { And here Black can simply recapture with the queen. } 6... Qxd5 7. Ngf3 Qxc5 { In this position, the fact that White has a knight on d2 actually works against them, as it is placed much worse compared to the c3 square and is also blocking the bishop on c1. This is a perfect example of how one can go about understanding the nuances behind the opening moves - sometimes there is no other way but to dig a
bit deeply and compare an analogous position arising from two very similar lines to fully comprehend the difference! }) 3... Bb4 { This bishop move, pinning the knight on c3 and renewing the threat to the pawn on e4, leads to the fascinating, mind-boggling and razor-sharp Winawer variation of the French Defence, in which Black quite often takes the knight on c3 and then tries to play against the weak and doubled pawns on the c-file (after the
inevitable opening of the position with c5). However, even if it is the most common, it is definitely not the only way of handling the position! } { [%cal Rb4e1,Gc7c5] } (3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 { And now once again we have transposed to the Rubinstein variation of the French Defence, that was examined a moment ago. }) (3... Be7 { Secondly, Black has tried playing some semi-waiting move just like against the 3.Nd2 lines in practice, but with the knight on c3 these semi-waiting lines don't work that well as the knight is influencing the center and controlling the d5 square. The difference is most vividly examined in the case of the quiet bishop development to d3. } 4. Bd3 c5 { This is usually the prescription in situations when the knight is on d2 (trying to make an argument that pushing the bishop to d3 in front of the queen has made the d4 pawn more vulnerable), but here this isn't as powerful as the knight is on c3. } 5. dxc5 { Now this capture is quite decent - note that White would love to take on d5 next, if allowed. } { [%csl Rd5][%cal Rc3d5,Re4d5] } 5... Nf6 6. exd5 { The difference! In the position with the knight on d2, Black was able to recapture with the queen here and obtain a reasonable position, but here they are forced to take with the pawn or the knight (in practice, only the former was seen). In any case, not a variation to be recommended to Black, even if some strong players have employed it here and there. } { [%cal Ge6d5,Gf6d5] }) (3... Nf6 { Apart from the move Bb4, leading to the fascinating Winawer variation, Black can also play this knight move and go for the so-called Steinitz variation. Black increases the pressure on the pawn on e4 and invites White to advance it, claiming that with the knight on c3, it will be easier to undermine the structure later down the road with a thematic c5. } { [%csl Re4][%cal Rf6e4] } 4. e5 { And indeed - White does take the opportunity to advance the pawn to e5 and hit the knight with a gain of tempo. This is one of the two main ways of handling this position for White. } (4. Bg5 { The second main move in this position is this pinning move, indirectly defending the e4 pawn and creating the threat of e5 next. It leads to some very interesting and fascinating variations and Black has many possibilities at their disposal. It is beyond the scope of this study to go into too many details, but let me simply quote a couple of main moves. } { [%cal Rg5d8] } 4... Be7 { Removing the pin is the most natural, when Black has to be ready for the very dangerous } (4... Bb4 { The sharp McCutcheon variation is also a possibility for Black here. The point is that White can't really win a piece with the obvious e5: } 5. e5 h6 { And the practice has shown that capturing on f6 and g7 is not the most critical and that White more commonly retreats the bishop to any of the squares c1, d2, and e3. Of course, there is a lot of theory here and the struggle is very complicated, but overall, it seems that White has quite reasonable chances of obtaining the initiative. } { [%cal Re5f6] }) (4... dxe4 { Finally, taking the pawn on e4 at the moment when the bishop is on g5 leads to the so-called Burn variation, which might be the best way to meet this sharp Bg5 move. The point is that after } 5. Nxe4 Be7 { The knight on e4 is attacked so White is more or less forced to give up the bishop } { [%csl Re4] } 6. Bxf6 (6. Nxf6+ { Taking with the knight is too tame as it allows too many exchanges in a position where Black is lacking space. Following } 6... Bxf6 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 { We have some sort of position similar to the Rubinstein French, with the difference that the queen can't really be harassed on f6. }) 6... gxf6 { The point of Black's play! This leads to a very sharp and unbalanced variation where the weakness of the structure is compensated in the form of the bishop pair. Potentially, open g-file can become relevant although for the moment it is more problematic for Black as the second player can't castle kingside so easily any more. } { [%csl Rf6,Rf7] }) 5. e5 Nfd7 6. h4 { The so-called Alekhine Chatard attack where White sacrifices a pawn to obtain a massive initiative. }) 4... Nfd7 5. f4 { Reinforcing the e5 pawn in anticipation of what follows. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gf4e5] } (5. Nce2 { A possible variation involves removing the knight from c3, so after } 5... c5 6. c3 { White keeps everything quite compact, although it did cost some time (moving the same piece twice - and most likely the third time). Practice shows Black shouldn't necessarily be worse, but it is a fresh position compared to the more tested mainlines. } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gc3d4] }) 5... c5 { And once again we see this typical French move, undermining the pawn on c3 at the moment when White is unable to reinforce it with the c-pawn. This is a start of a major theoretical position that is very flexible and rich with possibilities for both sides. } { [%csl Rd4][%cal Rc5d4] }) 4. e5 { This sharp move, advancing the pawn in the center leads to one of the sharpest and craziest positions in the entire French complex - if not in chess at all. White grabs the central space but exposes his flank a little bit and allows Black to double the c-pawns and go for the immediate counterplay. } (4. exd5 exd5 5. Bd3 { This is not as dry and boring as the pure French Exchange as the bishop has been already committed to b4. Still, it is much more solid and tame than the crazy mainline. } { [%csl Rb4] }) 4... c5 { The main move in the position! Black strikes in the center immediately and undermines the pawn on d4. The position is very rich in possibilities and numerous transpositions are possible, so I will refrain from doing an overall survey and only demonstrate the main line! } { [%cal Rc5d4] } 5. a3 { Needless to say, White also has many other options at their disposal. } 5... Bxc3+ { The most common move. Not only is taking on c3 one of the main ideas of the whole line, it also turns out
retreating to a5 is a little bit risky. } (5... Ba5 { Leads to a very fascinating line starting with } 6. b4 cxb4 7. Nb5 { When White is trying to exploit the weakening of the dark squares and sacrifice a pawn in the style of the wing gambit. However, this is actually an improved version as Black spent a few tempi to get the bishop to a5 while the knight is allowed on b5 already. Some strong players do venture into this variation, but it is definitely a very provocative choice! } { [%cal Gb5d6] }) 6. bxc3 { This is the
starting point of the main variation of the Winawer French. You can notice we
have a familiar pawn chain from c3 to e5 - however this time, the c-pawns are
doubled and potentially exposed to attacks along the semi-open c-file, which
is definitely in Black's favour. --- However, they did give up their
dark-squared bishop, which makes their kingside more vulnerable compared to,
say, the Advance variation. There are many ways to handle the position for
both sides from this point and I don't think it is worth barely scratching the
surface in this Overview file. This is why I will stop here and refer you to a
subsequent file/video devoted exclusively to this fascinating tabiya. } { This is the starting point of the main variation of the Winawer French. You can notice we have a familiar pawn chain from c3 to e5 - however this time, the c-pawns are doubled and potentially exposed to attacks along the semi-open c-file, which is definitely in Black's favour.
However, they did give up their dark-squared bishop, which makes their kingside more vulnerable compared to, say, the Advance variation. There are many ways to handle the position for both sides from this point and I don't think it is worth barely scratching the surface in this Overview file. This is why I will stop here and refer you to a subsequent file/video devoted exclusively to this fascinating tabiya. } { [%cal Gd1g4] } *


