{ As mentioned earlier, even though having a general idea about different variations and possibilities for both sides is definitely beneficial, it is very debatable whether overly focusing on the memorization of the theory
should be at the top of the priority list when we first start looking at a certain opening (or even up to a certain level). I have personally always been a big advocate of the understanding-based approach to opening study (even if I don't always adhere to it myself, FYI).
What does that understanding-based approach consist of? Well, primarily of understanding key pawn structures, pawn breaks, good and bad pieces, standard maneuvers, and other key themes associated with this opening. Almost every chess opening has a number of these themes present across different variations, so learning these "rules of the opening" and analyzing Model games should help you navigate your own games - even when you forget the concrete theory.
When you think of such an approach and compare it to, say, education, it makes a lot of sense. Throughout our school life, we slowly go from general to very specific. I feel it is also a good principle to withhold when it comes to chess openings. Let's first establish some "dogmas" and general principles and then, with time and experience, learn how to apply them in specific positions and games.
That is why after the overview of variations, I would like to also take a moment to talk about some very typical French Defence pawn structures, as well as key middlegame themes, before wrapping things up with a list of good French Defence players whose model games can serve as an inspiration/instructive
material.
One disclaimer: The material presented on Pawn Structures and Key Middlegame Themes and Ideas here should be taken primarily as an overview/ motivation/brain teaser. By no means do I claim that I have come nowhere close to exhausting all the possibilities or diving into the deepest nuances of the French Defence. The primary purpose is to provide the reader with some basic rules of thumb and also to try and illustrate the understanding-based, pawn-structure oriented approach to studying chess openings. }
 *


[Event "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations: Pawn Structures #1 - The \"French\" structure"]
[Date "2022.11.25"]
[White "Pawn Structures #1"]
[Black "The \"French\" structure"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "Nemec, Vjekoslav"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations"]
[ChapterName "Pawn Structures #1 - The \"French\" structure"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/hUFnodoF/6BOrCcvT"]
[FEN "4k3/pp3ppp/4p3/2ppP3/3P4/2P5/PP3PPP/4K3 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Let's start by examining the most typical, pure, structure that arises out of the French Defence - the structure where White has the long pawn chain from c3 to e5 while Black has the pawns on e6 and d5. White typically plays on the kingside as the e5 pawn secures the space advantage and often pushes the kingside pawns or attacks with the pieces. Black, on the other hand, seeks to undermine the pawn chain by either attacking the base (the d4 pawn) with c5, or the front (the e5 pawn) with f6. If the center should collapse, Black can get an upper hand.
This structure can arise from different variations of the French Defence and it was precisely this type of structure that motivated Aaron Nimzowitsch to write about pawn chains in his - somewhat outdated - chess book, My System.
Note also that the structure is somewhat fluid - Black can decide to play c4 and close down the queenside at any moment (and sometimes it is the right approach, as we will soon see). } { [%csl Gc3,Rc5,Gd4,Ge5,Rf6][%cal Rc5d4,Gf7f6,Rf6e5] }
 *


[Event "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations: Pawn Structures #2 - Black Closes The Structure"]
[Date "2020.03.20"]
[White "Pawn Structures #2"]
[Black "Black Closes The Structure"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "Nemec, Vjekoslav"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations"]
[ChapterName "Pawn Structures #2 - Black Closes The Structure"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/hUFnodoF/5Nrbl6JT"]
[FEN "4k3/pp3ppp/4p3/3pP3/2pP4/P1P5/1P3PPP/4K3 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ As mentioned previously, sometimes Black decides to release the tension in the center and close down the queenside to block the position completely. This is typically followed by castling the king long and then trying to open up the kingside to their advantage. White, on the other hand, also tries to play on the kingside (as almost always in the French Defence with the pawn on e5), although sometimes there is the option of undermining the Black's pawn chain via the move b3. } { [%csl Rc4,Re6][%cal Gf2f4,Gf4f5,Gb2b3,Gh2h4,Gh4h5] }
 *


[Event "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations: Pawn Structures #3 - The \"Steinitz\" Structure"]
[Date "2020.03.20"]
[White "Pawn Structures #3"]
[Black "The \"Steinitz\" Structure"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "Nemec, Vjekoslav"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations"]
[ChapterName "Pawn Structures #3 - The \"Steinitz\" Structure"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/hUFnodoF/QMbhfcoH"]
[FEN "6k1/pp3ppp/4p3/3pP3/5P2/2P5/PP4PP/1K6 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Another very typical structure that most commonly arises from the Steinitz variation (3.Nc3 Nf6 4.e4) is the following pawn structure with the d- and c-pawns exchanged and missing from the board - but with the White pawn still being on c3 (or even c2). This structure usually arises when White captures on c5 voluntarily in order to deal with the pressure on d4 - or to get precisely this structure.
One of the main features of this structure is White's control over the d4 square - a knight will sit really nicely here, due to which many endgames are quite favourable for the first player. Some other plans for White include kingside play, with the help of the thematic f5-f6 pawn push.
Black, on the other hand, almost always plays for the kingside pawn push with a5-b5-b4, and so on - almost irrespective if White castled kingside (when the target of the attack are the pawns), or if White castled queenside (when the target of the attack is the king). } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gf4f5,Gf5f6,Gb7b5,Gb5b4,Ga7a5,Ga5a4,Ga4a3,Gb4b3,Gb4c3] }
 *


[Event "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations: Pawn Structures #4 - The open Caro-Kann structure"]
[Date "2020.03.20"]
[White "Pawn Structures #4"]
[Black "The open Caro-Kann structure"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "Nemec, Vjekoslav"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations"]
[ChapterName "Pawn Structures #4 - The open Caro-Kann structure"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/hUFnodoF/jwj3IkTo"]
[FEN "6k1/pp3ppp/2p1p3/8/2PP4/8/PP3PPP/6K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ A somewhat less "French-Defence" like, but no less typical pawn structure that can arise from the French Defence - most notably via the Rubinstein variation (3.Nd2/3.Nc3 - dxe4) is what I call the Caro-Kann structure, characterized by the d4 pawn facing the pawns on e6 and c6.
This structure is fairly thematic as it can arise from many other openings such as the Caro-Kann (duh), Scandinavian, Slav, Alekhine Defence, etc. The main characteristic of this structure is that White has more space as his pawn on d4 is on the 4th rank. Yet, Black is very solid and has no weaknesses in the pawn structure. If they manage to exchange the right amount of the pieces/the right pieces, they might even get some chances (especially if the c-pawn has been advanced to c4, as then d4 might be very weak).
White typically tries to orchestrate the thematic d5 pawn break, play for the kingside attack (with pieces, mainly) or go for some sort of queenside expansion with b4-a4-b5 and so on. Black, on the other hand, has to stay compact and solid, seek piece exchanges, and hope to get one of the two pawn breaks with c5 and e5 at the right moment. } { [%csl Rg8][%cal Gd4d5,Gb2b4,Gb4b5,Gc6c5,Ge6e5,Ga2a4] }
 *


