[Date "2020.03.20"]
[White "Pawn Structures #5"]
[Black "Symmetrical Structure"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "Nemec, Vjekoslav"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations"]
[ChapterName "Pawn Structures #5 - Symmetrical Structure"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/hUFnodoF/qso7pBy6"]
[FEN "6k1/pp3ppp/2p5/3p4/3P4/8/PPP2PPP/6K1 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Last but not the least, we can't conclude the section about the pawn structures without mentioning the dreaded Symmetrical pawn structure, that most commonly arises via the French exchange variation. If that is not a convincing enough reason for you to be repulsed by it, let me also mention that this same structure can also arise via the two most bulletproof "anti 1.e4" openings on the market - The Berlin Defence and the
Petroff Defence.
The reason why this structure is considered so dry is, as its name suggests, its inherent symmetry. In contrast to previously examined, imbalanced structures, here neither side has any particularly appealing pawn pushes (maybe sometimes White can go for the c4 push/Black can go for the c5 push, but it has to be timed well as then the d-pawn becomes isolated and potentially weak). Furthermore, there is only one open file on the board which is relatively easy to contest - so many games in this structure lead to mass exchanges and relatively colorless draws - especially at the higher levels.
The most common way to try and pose problems involves playing on the kingside, gaining some space and trying to slowly push the opponent's pieces to inferior squares.
In contrast to other structures mentioned here, it is far less common as many White players can simply avoid it. However, Black players have no other choice but to face it whenever their opponent plays the Exchange variation. } { [%cal Gc2c4,Re8e1,Re1e8] }
 *


[Event "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations: Key Middlegame Themes #1 - Qg4 Maneuver"]
[Date "2020.03.20"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes #1"]
[Black "Qg4 Maneuver"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "Nemec, Vjekoslav"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations"]
[ChapterName "Key Middlegame Themes #1 - Qg4 Maneuver"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/hUFnodoF/G60OWa5j"]
[FEN "r1b1k1nr/1pq2ppp/p1n1p3/2ppP3/3P4/2PB4/P1P2PPP/R1BQK1NR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Okay, now that we have gotten acquainted with at least some of the basic structures that can arise from the French Defence, let's add some more pieces on the board and check some typical ideas and maneuvers present in these structures. I have prepared a total of 10 Key Middlegame Themes and 5 Key Tactical Themes for you to observe, although - needless to say - the total amount of key ideas in the French Defence (or any opening, for that matter) is significantly greater than that.
In any case, let's take a look at observing a typical scenario that arises in the Winawer variation. Black
managed to double the c-pawns but has exchanged the dark-squared bishop in the process. This typically allows White to execute the following thematic queen maneuver. }
1. Qg4 { This move is very typical in numerous variations of the French Defence. White brings the queen to the kingside, pressures the g7 pawn at once and prepares to develop the knight to f3 BEHIND the queen (!). Also, the queen covers the vulnerable d4 pawn. Black now has several ways of dealing with the threat to the g7 pawn. } { [%cal Rg4g7,Gg4d4] } 1... g6 { This is the first one, but the drawback is that this further weakens the dark-squares on the kingside. } (1... Kf8 { Covering with the king is possible, but also often not optimal as Black loses the castling rights and places the
king on the side of the board where the opponent wants to play anyway. } { [%cal Gf8g7] }) (1... f5 { Moving the f-pawn with the queen on c7 is also sometimes played, but the drawback is that it makes the entire structure static and Black loses the possibility to undermine the structure with f6 next. }) (1... Nge7 { Last but not least - in many variations of the French Defence Black just sacrifices the g7 and h7 pawns on the kingside and then searches for compensation in the resulting complications. It depends on the actual positioning on the pieces, but this idea is present in, say, one of the main lines of the Winawer, sooo. }) *


