[FEN "rnb1k1nr/pp3ppp/4p3/2ppP3/q2P4/P1P5/2PB1PPP/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 0 8"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ As mentioned previously - very often in the French defence, White tries to play on the kingside due to the space advantage secured by having a pawn on e5. We have seen previously the idea of Qg4, pressuring the g7 pawn. Here, I would like to mention another important concept seen in a theoretical line of the Winawer variation, that can often be utilized in various French positions. }
8. h4 { Even before neural networks such as Alpha Zero which revolutionized our relationship with the flank pawns, it was recognized that pushing the h-pawn is very much playable. The pawn secures even more space, intends to go all the way to h6 to open some files or diagonals, and also frees up some space for the rook to come into play. It is very thematic in blocked positions with the pawn on c4 instead, but it is also playable here! I will not continue the concrete variations as they become a bit messy - but remember this idea from the conceptual viewpoint! } { [%cal Gh4h5,Gh5h6,Gh1h3,Gh3h4] } *


[Event "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations: Key Middlegame Themes #3 - Bad French Bishop"]
[Date "2022.11.23"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes #3"]
[Black "Bad French Bishop"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "Nemec, Vjekoslav"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C02"]
[Opening "French Defense: Advance Variation"]
[StudyName "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations"]
[ChapterName "Key Middlegame Themes #3 - Bad French Bishop"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/hUFnodoF/f3yUv2qi"]

1. e4 e6 (1... c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 { When we are talking about the light-squared bishop in these types of structures, it is useful to compare this with the variation that can arise via the Caro-Kann where Black first plays Bf5 and then locks the bishop with e6. In this case, we say that the bishop is "outside of the pawn chain" and in general has more potential, although there are some drawbacks - most notably with the potential weakness of the b7 pawn that is surprisingly relevant in a number of Caro positions. } { [%csl Rb7,Gf5][%cal Gh7b1] }) 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 { Now, one thing that definitely has to be pointed out in the French Defence is Black's light-squared bishop. Since Black played e6 and d5 on the first two moves, placing the pawns on the light squares, the bishop on c8 is quite restricted and is often regarded as the problem piece. Black's sole strategic goal is sometimes to try to find a way to either activate or to exchange the piece under good circumstances. White would mostly like to avoid the exchange of these bishops, although not if they can get something concrete and direct in return - as we will see in the next example. } { [%csl Rc8][%cal Rc8e6] } *


[Event "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations: Key Middlegame Themes #4 - Exchanging the Bad Bishop?"]
[Date "2022.11.23"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes #4"]
[Black "Exchanging the Bad Bishop?"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "Nemec, Vjekoslav"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations"]
[ChapterName "Key Middlegame Themes #4 - Exchanging the Bad Bishop?"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/hUFnodoF/CwFYjH1Q"]
[FEN "rnb1kbnr/pp3ppp/1q2p3/2ppP3/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ As mentioned previously, Black would very much like to exchange the light-squared bishops in the French Defence from a strategic viewpoint. However, very often, they need to be careful how to go about executing this idea as going for it too rigidly might change one type of the problem for another.
A typical scenario from a theoretical line of the Advance variation can be seen in the diagram. Here one possible move is the development of the bishop before the knight. }
5... Bd7 { The idea is to play Bb5 next and exchange the light-squared bishops. From the positional standpoint, this is very desirable, however, there are concrete reasons why it doesn't quite work here. } { [%cal Gd7b5] } 6. Be2 Bb5 7. c4! { A very strong
tactical solution that allows White to hope for some advantage. } 7... Bxc4 { Very
principled, trying to insist on the bishop exchange. } (7... dxc4 8. Nc3 { Is another possible continuation, but here White manages to avoid the exchange
completely. }) 8. Bxc4 dxc4 9. d5 { The point! Due to the fact Black took some time to get the bishop out and exchange it, White can play very concretely and try to open up the position. It turns out that the c4 pawn is potentially weak and that Black might be - somewhat ironically - vulnerable on the light squares. Don't forget about tactics and concrete features of the position when executing strategic plans! } { [%csl Rc4,Gd5] } *


[Event "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations: Key Middlegame Themes #5 - Good Knight vs. Bad Bishop"]
[Date "2020.03.20"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes #5"]
[Black "Good Knight vs. Bad Bishop"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "Nemec, Vjekoslav"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations"]
[ChapterName "Key Middlegame Themes #5 - Good Knight vs. Bad Bishop"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/hUFnodoF/u9Jsjev0"]
[FEN "r1b4r/1p2kppp/pn2p3/1N1pP3/5P2/8/PPP3PP/2KR1B1R w - - 0 15"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The weakness of the bad bishop is especially pronounced in situations where White manages to establish the f4-e5 bind and obtain the so-called "good knight" on d4 - especially if the bishop and the knight are the only pair of minor pieces on the board.
In the diagram position, we have a theoretical position that can arise from the Steinitz variation. We can see that the bishop on c8 is quite passive and that White will establish a strong knight on d4, which leads to a very unpleasant endgame. }
15. Nd4 { Due to the very good knight on d4 (and the fact enemy bishop is somewhat passive), White has some advantage in this endgame, which he managed to convert in many games. It has to be said that the fact that Black has the knight works in their favour. Also, there are some ideas associated with the undermining f6 pawn push to obtain some counterplay. But nevertheless, the evaluation of the position remains in White's favour. } { [%cal Ge5f6] } *


[Event "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations: Key Middlegame Themes #6 - a4-Ba3 maneuver"]
[Date "2022.11.25"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes #6"]
[Black "a4-Ba3 maneuver"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "Nemec, Vjekoslav"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations"]
[ChapterName "Key Middlegame Themes #6 - a4-Ba3 maneuver"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/hUFnodoF/uaVUz7Hz"]
[FEN "1r2k2r/pp1bqpp1/4p1n1/3pP3/2pP2B1/P1P3P1/2PQ2P1/1RB2RK1 w k - 0 19"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In the majority of cases in the French Defence, White plays on the kingside. However, in chess, it is always worth having your eye across the entire board. There are some positions where White combines the play on the kingside and the queenside. One very famous example from the game between the legendary (and somewhat forgotten) Soviet Grandmaster Leonid Stein and the World Champion Tigran Petrosian can be seen on the board.
White has obtained a great attacking position against the Winawer and now Stein decided to include the final piece into play with the help of the standard queenside pawn sacrifice. }
19. a4 { In the Winawer where the b2 pawn is gone, White often has to keep an eye on this option, activating the bishop along the long a3-f8 diagonal. Here it is extremely strong as Ra1-Ba3 is unavoidable. } { [%cal Gc1a3,Gb1a1] } 19... Bxa4 { White doesn't care at all that he sacrificed a pawn - it is all about the initiative and open lines and diagonals here. } 20. Ra1 { [%cal Ra1a4] } 20... b5 21. Ba3 { And White went on to win in a sacrificial attack very shortly. Remember this idea as it is fairly typical. } { [%cal Ra3f8] } *


[Event "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations: Key Middlegame Themes #7 - Blockade of the queenside"]
[Date "2020.03.20"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes #7"]
[Black "Blockade of the queenside"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "Nemec, Vjekoslav"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations"]
[ChapterName "Key Middlegame Themes #7 - Blockade of the queenside"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/hUFnodoF/KGULUUZv"]
[FEN "rnb1k1nr/pp3ppp/4p3/q1ppP3/3P4/P1P5/2PB1PPP/R2QKBNR b KQkq - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ So, as we have seen, White often has the option of playing a4-Ba3 in the Winawer. That is why Black very commonly aims to prevent it by the means of a blockade - and very often her majesty the queen leads the charge very early in the opening. }
7... Qa4 { This is a very thematic continuation in the Winawer. This move is all about preventing White from playing a4 and opening up the c1-a3 diagonal for later. You should always keep an eye on the a4 square in these Winawer structures. } { [%csl Ga4] } *


[Event "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations: Key Middlegame Themes #8 - White queenside expansion"]
[Date "2022.11.23"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes #8"]
[Black "White queenside expansion"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "Nemec, Vjekoslav"]
[Variant "From Position"]
