[StudyName "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations"]
[ChapterName "Key Middlegame Themes #8 - White queenside expansion"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/hUFnodoF/C9gXCPYV"]
[FEN "r1b1kbnr/pp3ppp/1qn1p3/2ppP3/3P4/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Moving away from the Winawer variation - let's go back to the more standard French structure and positions that arise from the Advance variation in order to illustrate a couple of further plans/ideas in these types of position. In this specific position, it is very common for White to try and go for the queenside expansion involving the moves a3 and b4. }
6. a3 { This is a very useful move that takes the b4 square under control (thus
preparing to develop the bishop to d3 without being disturbed with the
subsequent Nb4), but White also hints at the queenside expansion, say after
some routine developing move. } { [%cal Ga3b4,Gb2b4] } 6... Nge7 7. b4 { This is not yet strictly necessary, but with the help of this move, White immediately asks Black to clarify the structure (as c5 is hanging) and also removes the b2 pawn from the attack. White does have to be a bit careful since the queenside is now somewhat exposed, but remember - here it is more about the general ideas rather than concrete positions. } { [%csl Ga3,Gb4,Gc3,Gd4] } *


[Event "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations: Key Middlegame Themes #9 - Black prevents the expansion"]
[Date "2022.11.23"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes #9"]
[Black "Black prevents the expansion"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "Nemec, Vjekoslav"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations"]
[ChapterName "Key Middlegame Themes #9 - Black prevents the expansion"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/hUFnodoF/UdH57H50"]
[FEN "r1b1kbnr/pp3ppp/1qn1p3/2ppP3/3P4/P1P2N2/1P3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ As we have seen - White quite often introduces the idea of playing b4 quite early in the opening. That is why one of the main moves in this position involves moving the c-pawn forward. }
6... c4 { With this Black voluntarily blocks the position on the queenside and removes the tension in the center. The idea is to change the pace of the game and go for some sort of long maneuvering behind the pawn chain. Black will almost certainly castle long and then try to counter White's activity on the kingside. Definitely a plan/pawn structure to be aware of! } { [%csl Gc4,Gd5,Ge6][%cal Gc4b3] } *


[Event "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations: Key Middlegame Themes #10 - Blockade of the queenside"]
[Site "Moscow URS"]
[Date "1961.01.19"]
[Round "6"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes #10"]
[Black "Blockade of the queenside"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "USER"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations"]
[ChapterName "Key Middlegame Themes #10 - Blockade of the queenside"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/hUFnodoF/5Sv0qjwV"]
[FEN "r2qkb1r/pp1b1ppp/2n1p3/3pPn2/1P1P4/P4N2/1B3PPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 0 9"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Another very common theme in the Advance variation involves a tactical way of exploiting White's queenside expansion in a very specific theoretical position. }
9... b5 { A very strong move worth remembering. It seems as if Black is blundering a pawn, but the purpose of this move is to keep the b4 pawn where it is and to play a5 next, blasting open the queenside. The fact that there is a small tactical shot in the position justifies this strategic goal. } { [%csl Rb4,Gb5][%cal Ga7a5] } 10. Nc3 (10. Bxb5 { Black-s idea is justified because White can't really take on b5 due to the standard tactical shot: } 10... Nxe5 11. Bxd7+ Nxd7 { In a scenario like this, Black has exchanged a central pawn that was limiting the pieces and securing White's space for a wing pawn, which should be extremely favourable for Black. }) 10... a5 { The point! Black attacks the b4 pawn and open up the pieces on the queenside, breaking the semi-blockade. This is not yet sufficient for an objective advantage, but it leads to a very pleasant play and is the first step toward outplaying your opponent. } { [%cal Rc6b4,Rf8b4,Ra5b4] } *


[Event "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations: Key Middlegame Themes #11 - No Fear of the Doubled Pawns"]
[Date "2022.11.25"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes #11"]
[Black "No Fear of the Doubled Pawns"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "USER"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations"]
[ChapterName "Key Middlegame Themes #11 - No Fear of the Doubled Pawns"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/hUFnodoF/IdzZt3I3"]
[FEN "r2qkbnr/pp1b1ppp/2n1p3/2ppP3/3P4/P1P2N2/1P3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Another very important thing to mention in regard to the Advance variation/ pawn structure is the following - since Black is lacking space on the kingside, it is a bit clumsy to develop the pieces, which is why very often, Black has to be ready to accept some concessions and not fear the doubled pawns - especially if it involves White giving up their strong bishops. }
6... Nh6 { The first point. The knight can often go to f5 via h6. At first glance it looks as if it allows White to capture on h6 under favourable circumstances, but it turns out that taking on h6 is not that desirable. } 7. Bd3 (7. Bxh6 gxh6 { And even though Black's structure looks ugly (isolated and doubled h-pawns), it transpires it is not super easy to attack the dark squares without the dark-squared bishop. Meanwhile, Black's g-file can come in handy later in the game. } { [%cal Gh8g8] }) 7... Nf5 { The second point - Black can often place the knight to f5 to pressure the pawn on d4 - even if the bishop is on d3. It is important to understand that the capture on f5 is not particularly bothersome. } 8. Bxf5 exf5 { Black will play Be6, securing the pawn on d5, and then take it from there. It is true that the bishop is somewhat passive on this square, but it holds the position like glue and Black does have the bishop pair and no problems on the light-squares in the foreseeable future, so it is definitely not something to be afraid of. } { [%csl Gf5][%cal Gd7e6,Ge6d5] } *


[Event "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations: Key Middlegame Themes #12 - Defending the b2 pawn"]
[Date "2022.11.25"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes #12"]
[Black "Defending the b2 pawn"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "Nemec, Vjekoslav"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations"]
[ChapterName "Key Middlegame Themes #12 - Defending the b2 pawn"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/hUFnodoF/mMbh9qNW"]
[FEN "r1b1kb1r/pp1n1ppp/1qn1p3/2ppP3/3P1P2/2N1BN2/PPP3PP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 8"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In a number of variations of the French defence (and many other openings, for that matter), Black develops the queen to b6 to pressure the d4 pawn, but also the b2 pawn on the queenside, which is vulnerable once the bishop moves from c1. We have a very typical scenario here, which arose from the Steinitz variation. How should White deal with the pressure to the b2 pawn? }
8. a3 { This little pawn move is very useful in all sorts of openings and is worth remembering. White simply covers the b4 square and also prevents the queen from escaping via a3, which means that the b2 pawn is now taboo because of the threat of capturing the queen. } { [%csl Ga3,Gb4][%cal Ga3b4] } (8. Na4 { Another very typical, French way of defending the b2 pawn involves this maneuver. The knight attacks the queen on b6 and also covers the b2 pawn. It seems as if White will get punished with the check on a5, but all
is in order. } 8... Qa5+ { [%cal Ra5e1,Ra5a4] } 9. c3 { And now the queen defends the knight on a4 - and it is also looking to capture on c5, if applicable. It is true that in this particular case there is a sharp variation involving the knight sacrifice with } { [%csl Gc3][%cal Gd1a4] } 9... cxd4 10. b4 Nxb4 11. cxb4 Bxb4+ 12. Bd2 { But
A) this variation is objectively dubious for Black and
B) this is now beside the point as we are talking about a specific pattern to remember. }) 8... cxd4 (8... Qxb2 { Note that taking on b2 is now a horrible blunder as after } 9. Na4 { The queen is immediately lost. } { [%csl Rb2][%cal Ra4b2] }) 9. Nxd4 Bc5 { Now it seems as if the pressure on d4 has reached its climax and that White has to lose some material, but here the afore-mentioned knight jump comes to the rescue. } { [%cal Rb6e3,Rc6d4] } 10. Na4 Qa5+ 11. c3 { And White covers everything and play continues further. Remember these ideas as they are actually quite frequent in all sorts of openings, not only the French defence! } { [%csl Ga4,Gc3][%cal Gc3d4,Gd1a4] } *


[Event "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations: Key Middlegame Themes #13 - Attacking On Opposite Flanks"]
[Date "2022.11.25"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes #13"]
[Black "Attacking On Opposite Flanks"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "Nemec, Vjekoslav"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations"]
[ChapterName "Key Middlegame Themes #13 - Attacking On Opposite Flanks"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/hUFnodoF/aiNbzAOX"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/pp1nbppp/2n1p3/2ppP3/3P1P2/2N1BN2/PPPQ2PP/2KR1B1R b - - 0 9"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Another scenario that most commonly arises in the variation of the Steinitz variation (but also quite frequently in the Rubinstein variation) involves positions with opposite side-castling. In these situations, both sides intend to push their pawns (pawn storms!) as far as possible, in order to open up the enemy king and create an attack.
One such scenario can be seen in the diagram. At first glance, White's attack looks quite deadly as g4-f5-f6 is coming, but it transpires that Black's queenside counterplay is actually much faster. In reality, I specifically
picked this position as it contains an important opening trap that many White players fall into, aside from the fact that it is a nice illustrative position with castling on opposite sides. }
9... c4 { A move that White shouldn't allow in this particular position - and a move that can be very thematic in the French. Black closes down the queenside in order to continue with b5-b4 next, using the fact that the knight on c3 (and the queen on d2) are somewhat in the way of the potential pawn storm. It looks as if this move gives White the necessary stability in the center to push with f5, but it is not really the case. } { [%csl Gc4] } 10. f5 b5 { And both theory and practice show that White's position is very dangerous - maybe even objectively lost, irrespective if they push f6 or take the pawn on b5. Of course, there are other instances where the situation is much more murky and unclear, but I just wanted to emphasize there are positions in the French defence where opposite-side castling and trying to attack the enemy king are the name of the game. } *


[Event "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations: Key Middlegame Themes #14 - Rxf3 sacrifice"]
[Date "2022.11.25"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes #14"]
[Black "Rxf3 sacrifice"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "Nemec, Vjekoslav"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations"]
[ChapterName "Key Middlegame Themes #14 - Rxf3 sacrifice"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/hUFnodoF/OOuK2JOC"]
[FEN "r4rk1/1p1b2qp/p1nbp1p1/3p3n/N2P3B/P4N2/1P3PPP/R2QRBK1 b - - 0 18"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Another very important tactical idea that is very commonly seen in some variations of the Tarrasch variation (but not necessarily only the Tarrasch variation) involves Black sacrificing the exchange in order to ruin White's kingside structure and eliminate the defender of the pawn on d4. }
18... Rxf3 { Not only thematic, but in the given position - also incredibly strong! Black eliminates the important defender,
ensures the win on the d4 pawn next and also exploits the poor positioning of the opponent's pieces to weaken the enemy king. } 19. gxf3 { Usually, if White is forced to recapture the pawn, that means that the sacrifice is pretty much correct. However, sometimes Black can embark on this idea even if White is able to recapture with another piece. Here, however, this is forced as otherwise, White would also lose another piece. } (19. Qxf3 { is met with } 19... Qxd4 { Attacking two pieces on the edge of the board at once, and winning one of them. } { [%cal Rd4a4,Rd4h4] }) 19... Nxd4 { Black has won an important central pawn for an exchange, the pieces are extremely active and the opponent's king is permanently weak. This not only provides the second player with sufficient compensation but ensures that they are completely winning in this particular scenario! } { [%csl Rf3] } *


[Event "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations: Key Middlegame Themes #15 - Pseudo sacrifice on e5"]
[Date "2022.11.25"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes #15"]
[Black "Pseudo sacrifice on e5"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Annotator "Nemec, Vjekoslav"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "French Defence Explained - Introduction, Ideas, Common Variations"]
[ChapterName "Key Middlegame Themes #15 - Pseudo sacrifice on e5"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/hUFnodoF/yjhrJWuE"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/1p1nbppp/1qn1p3/2ppP3/p2P1P2/2P2NPB/PP2N2P/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 0 12"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Last but not least, in some positions, Black is able to destroy White's center with the help of a (pseudo) sacrifice of the knight on e5. }
12. f5? { In the diagram position, White has a very nice position with very interesting prospects on the kingside. However, here White ignores the opponent's ideas and advances the f-pawn prematurely, missing a simple tactic. } (12. Kh1 { simply moving the king away and preparing to push f5. }) 12... cxd4 13. cxd4 Ndxe5 { A very typical - and quite simple - tactic, utilizing the pin on the d4 pawn to win a pawn. However, it is a tactic that is often overlooked and that can sometimes happen even if Black actually does give up a piece - as getting two pawns in return can sometimes be sufficient, especially when combined with other factors, such as the weakness of the enemy king. In any case, a pattern worth keeping somewhere in your mind! } { [%cal Rb6g1] } 0-1


