1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 { As I mentioned earlier - one of the best things you can do when learning a new opening is to not only study the variations, but also the Model Games by strong players played in the given opening (or even the opening
line). Such an approach has multiple benefits - not only can you see how certain players have handled some lines (and potentially discover some new and unique ideas), but you can also see how a typical game in the given opening might look like - much better than when clicking through an opening variation with the Stockfish. Studying Master Games is, in general, a good method for improving your game which I would definitely recommend.
Now, even though studying any game played by a very strong player is very beneficial, for didactic purposes I do think that games played by older masters are, on average, somewhat more instructive. Since chess wasn't as influenced by the engines and since the level of defence was not as high as it is today, older
masters were often allowed to execute their ideas very consistently and with a lot of clarity and win games in a very simple and logical fashion. This is especially true in the context of the openings, since the opening theory has advanced tremendously in the last 10, 20, 30 years.
Thus, in the context of the French Defence, I would definitely recommend studying the games of some
of the older masters of this opening, such as:
A) Alexander Alekhine
B) Mikhail Botvinnik
C) Tigran Petrosian
D) Viktor Korchnoi
E) Wolfgang Uhlmann
As for the more modern grandmasters, I think that the English Grandmaster Nigel Short was one of the French Defence's biggest advocates, and in even more recent times, both Alexander Morozevich and Nikita Vitiugov had played the French a lot.
Although many other names are worthy of including on this list (for example, Ian Nepomniachtchi employed it in the notorious 2019-2020 Candidates tournament) so feel free to investigate on your own. } *


