(2255) Maikop 2004 }) 17. Be4 { [%emt 1:22:00] Kinda admission of failure - as
it was clearly not my intention to move the bishop again. // Still, this is
not such a bad move, tbh. } (17. Rd3 Rd8 { I didn't think was too good for me. } 18. Rxd8 (18. Kb2 { The computer thinks White has some edge here, tho, e.g. } 18... Ne6 19. Be4 { A key move. The idea is to try and provoke b6 so that the a-pawn is
weak, e.g. } 19... b6 20. Rxd8 Nxd8 21. b4 { And now Ra1 comes and how does Black
defend the pawn? } 21... Ne6 22. Ra1 a5 23. bxa5 bxa5 24. Rxa5 { White should be
winning here, although the technique is not easy. Damn. }) 18... Kxd8 19. Rd1+ Kc7 20. Kb2 h5) (17. Rd5 { but I thought Black is in
time with } 17... Rd8 18. Ra5 a6 { And here I thought I don't have anything, which
is wrong because - yes - f4 plan! } 19. f4 $16) 17... Rc8 { [%emt 0:30:00] This
also surprised me a little bit and took me by surprise. We have now reached
arguably the last critical moment of the game. } (17... Rb8 { I don't recall
what I was planning here - probably simply doubling. } 18. Rd2 (18. Rd5 { IS a bit more resolute as the rook is a bit more active on d5, although the
core idea is viable - STockfish. }) 18... Ne6 { A bit too cooperative according
to Stockfish. } (18... b6 { With the rook still on the queenside, this is not a
catastrophe as after } 19. Kb2 Rc8 { The rook will go to c7 to defend - although
White is sill better. Damn, how deep this seemingly simple position is. }) 19. Rhd1 { And now it is kinda hard for Black to challenge on the d-file due to the
weak h-pawn, e.g. } 19... Rhd8 20. Rxd8 Nxd8 (20... Rxd8 21. Bxb7) 21. Bxh7 $18 { // This evaluation is true, but this is a bit too cooperative - the knight
should stay on f8 to cover d7. - Stockfish. }) 18. Rd3 { [%emt 1:17:00] After
thinking for 5 minutes - again this tendency to play it too safe. // To be
fair, here there is not much to calculate after Bxb7 - it is more a matter of
decision making/nerves/evaluation. Now that I look at the position with the
engine, it seems insane not to take a queenside pawn for the doubled pawn -
but I started imagining some horrors with my dark-squares being weak and the
knight coming to d4. Again, my tendency to keep control too much and a bit
lazy too calculate. } (18. Bxb7 Rxc3 { I should have gone for this - last chance
to do something. } 19. Kb2 Rc7 20. Be4 Ne6 { Thought it is hard for me to push
the queenside pawns - but still probably better than what I did. Seems again I
wanted to go without calculating + keep things too much under control. // The
engine indeed thinks this was the best as there is also the open a-file, my
bishop is covering c2 and White is still playing for two results. While f4
plan might have been beyond my capabilities, this sequence definitely wasn't
and I could have/should have spent more time and calculated a bit deeper. Oh
well. } 21. Ra1 $16) 18... Rc7 { [%emt 0:31:00] Now actually Black kinda
consolidated and for some reason I started fearing I might be even worse due
to some pressure along the g-file - although this is a very questionable
verdict as like - why should White exactly be worse? // It is indeed true that
White is not worse - but Black is now quite harmonious and comfortable somehow,
with the moves Ne6-h5 being played on autopilot. } 19. Rhd1 { [%emt 1:16:00] } 19... Ne6 { [%emt 0:27:00] Now I - somewhat surprisingly - felt that I don't really have
an advantage as Rd8 is coming after the h-pawn moves. I started fearing some
Ng5-Nf4 jumps, too and somewhat seeing ghosts - despite having more than an
hour on the clock. But I felt my concentration was not there and that I am
faltering, soo. } 20. Bf5 { [%emt 1:20:00] Probably could have done without this
move, but wanted to avoid Ng4. } (20. g3 Ng5 { This is not an idea tho, because
I can always put the bishop to d5 and then revert "back" to the f4 plan (I am
really starting to sound like a broken record). }) 20... h5 { [%emt 0:23:00] A
very thematic idea in these endgames, gaining space, trying to fix the
structure and target the f2 pawn. } 21. g3 { [%emt 1:10:00] Here I was somewhat
reconciled with a draw - and probably too little upset with it because I did
manage to catch my opponent and get a good position out of the opening. } (21. h4 { WAs the alternative I considered, but after } 21... Rg8 22. g4 Rh8 { I thought was
just dead equal - not a good version of Zirk's g4-h4 stuff. // Stockfish
indeed confirms that arguably only Black can talk about being better. }) (21. Kb2 h4 { When the g-pawn is
kinda target (although I guess I can move it). // Engine agrees with this
assessment. }) 21... h4 { [%emt 0:24:00] } 22. g4 { [%emt 1:04:00] I really didn't
want to open up the h-file and allow the rook in. } (22. Kb2 hxg3 23. hxg3 Rh2 { I also thought was kinda equal, but somewhat annoying with the rook on the 2nd
rank. // For the engine it probably doesn't matter, but as a human I really
don't want ot allow the rampaging rook. }) 22... Rd8 { [%emt 0:24:00] Finally
this exchanging mechanism. Here I was worried my kingside might become weak
due to Ng5-Nf4 ideas, so I decided to simplify stuff. } 23. Bxe6 { [%emt 1:02:00] } (23. Rxd8 Nxd8 { Felt like I am playing with fire as the knight goes back to
g5 at some point and Black has nice dark-square control on the kingside. //
Tbh, here I overestimated the danger a bit - this is just an equal endgame, e.
g. } 24. Kb2 Ne6 25. c4 Ng5 26. Be4 { And this Ng5 didn't achieve much - we
don't fear the exchange on e4 somehow. Stockfish. }) 23... Rxd3 { [%emt 0:24:00] } 24. cxd3 { [%emt 1:02:00] This was the small point of my "petite combinasion"
as now the c3 pawn is immune. So I managed to improve my structure and
undouble the pawns in preparation for the rook endgame. } 24... Kxe6 { [%emt 0:16:00] } (24... fxe6 { Although
even in the game there are f5 pushes soo } 25. Kd2 { I guess the verdict is
close to being equal. } 25... a5 { But this is an important move, to prevent some play
along the a-file. } (25... Kf7 26. b4 { Is also fine tho - how am I getting to
the queenside after a6? But I guess gaining space is better. } 26... a6)) (24... Rxc3+ 25. Kd2 { Ofc loses for Black. }) 25. Kd2 { [%emt 1:02:00] Here I agreed to a
draw as I was tired, unsure if I have anything and worried I might even lose a
position like this. Initially I wrote it was the correct decision, as at the
moment I did this the team was doing very well, but ultimately we went on to
draw this highly important match. I think it would have been very beneficial
for me to try and play this endgame, although with tiredness and lack of
concentration who knows what would have happened. Although my older opponent
also must have been not at the best. // To be completely fair, if anyone is on
the better side of things it is White, although I thought after the f-pawn
pushes there is nothing bad for Black apparent. It might indeed be so, e.g. } 25... f5 (25... a5 { Is also more than fine for equality, tho. }) 26. b4 fxg4 27. fxg4 f5 { There are easier ways, according to Stocfkish, but I thought this direct
option is the simplest. } 28. gxf5+ Kxf5 29. Rf1+ Ke6 30. Rg1 { With that being
said, White does have some pressure here. In any case - especially after my
opponent took with the king on e6 I could have stopped, calculated and maybe
considered playing on - as I objectively shouldn't be risking that much unless
I get braindead somehow by Miracle. } 1/2-1/2


