{ The following game was played in the 4th round of the Croatian 2nd League -
and it was the second round in a day (as is customary in the 2nd Croatian
League). In the morning, I have played one of the best games of my life
against IM Branko Rogulj and I was in a very positive mindest. In this game I
faced a relatively older (58 years of age) FM from Croatia Mladen Vrban, rated
2280 at the time when the game was played. Even though I didn't prepare for
him deeply (their team's first board FM Roland Margl didn't come and I only
prepared for him - my first mistake), I did notice he plays the Sicilian, so I
decided I will just play my usual Prins in case we meet. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 { I was thinking for a while about doing something else, but ultimately decided
to stick to my plan before the game. These second games in the Croatian League
are always very difficult to play somehow (not sure why they are so different
compared to the regular double rounds), so I wanted to play something I am
familiar and experienced with. I also was fairly certain my opponent doesn't
prepare - which turned out to be the right assumption. } 2... d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. f3 e5 { [%emt 1:27:00] It was a heartening sign that he started thinking
here. After the game, he kept talking about how he had some "files" with the
analysis. Without even thinking about the "quality" of those files - I was
100% sure I would know more than him even in the worst case scenario. } 6. Nb3 d5 { [%emt 1:27:00] } 7. Bg5 Be6 { [%emt 1:21:00] It was heartening that my
opponent was spending quite some time here - as allowing the "Prins Endgame"
is arguably THE main reply, recommended, for example, by Anish Giri in his
Lifetime Repertoire. Among others. } 8. Bxf6 gxf6 { [%emt 1:21:00] } 9. exd5 Qxd5 { [%emt 1:12:00] } 10. Qxd5 Bxd5 { [%emt 1:12:00] } 11. Nc3 Bb4 { [%emt 1:03:00]
This is a surprise as I knew this was a bad line. After White's reply Black is
basically forced to give up the bishop pair - and that is their main
compensation for their structural deficit. Here I knew White should have - in
computer terms - +1 advantage, although even the fact that I am evaluating
even now in terms of computer, and not human, evaluations, speaks volumes of
my approach to this position. } (11... Be6 { This is by far the mainline, which
I faced recently against two Indian players. Among others. }) 12. O-O-O { Now Black is in problems as it is a big question what exactly has the bishop's
forray to b4 achieved. } 12... Bxb3 { [%emt 1:03:00] I kinda expected this, but I knew
this leads me to a very good endgame where my bishop should be superior to the
knight - to say nothing about the structure and the slight lead in development. } (12... Bxc3 { I remembered that this is met by the capture of the bishop on
d5. } 13. Rxd5 $18 Bb4 14. Rb5 { I calculated this over the board, saw I win the
b7 pawn - sapienti sat. // STockfish confirms this is indeed the best. Not
much to add here. }) (12... Be6 { I didn't 100% remember what is problematic
with this move, but I was planning to play the standard } 13. Nd5 { When Black
probably has to give up the bishop with } (13. Nb5 { Is also given by the engine,
with the idea of } 13... Na6 14. a3 Be7 15. Na5 { Creating a very annoying pressure
against the b7 and a7 pawns. As a matter of fact, Black should probably just
give one. Pesky engine line. }) 13... Bxd5 14. Rxd5 $16 { And this exchange is
almost always beneficial for White in these positions. I thought I am clearely
better here. }) 13. axb3 { I played this basically without thinking. } (13. cxb3 { I briefly considered, but what if they don't take on c3? This seemed quite
unnecessary. // The engine does give this with the idea of playing Nd5 next. E.
g. } 13... Nc6 14. Nd5 O-O-O 15. Bb5 Bc5 { And we win a pawn but opposite coloured
bishops + some activity + White's weird structure = close to equality? In any
case, lines like these show why taking away from the center is as weird as it
looks. }) 13... Bxc3 { [%emt 1:02:00] } 14. bxc3 { [%emt 1:34:00] } 14... Ke7 { [%emt 1:01:
00] I didn't think this was particularly needed. I was expecting my opponent
to develop the knight. I guess his idea was to go for the Nd7-Nf8-Ne6 maneuver
without allowing the Bb5 pin. // Wow, the computer actually praises this
decision very highly. } (14... Nc6 { and planning } 15. Bd3 { I am not 100% sure whether the knight is better on c6 or d7 (or should I say -
less worse?). } 15... Ke7 16. f4 { //Tbh, it is hard to say as stockfish always wants
to play f4 in these positions and then there is arguably not much difference
between the knight on c6 and d7 (although the knight on d7 is probably a bit
more flexible). }) (14... Nd7 15. Bb5 { Seems to win on the spot due to } 15... Rd8 (15... O-O-O 16. Rd6 $18) 16. Rxd7 Rxd7 17. Rd1 { Not the most difficult calculation of my life, but it makes the pauper happy,
sooo. }) 15. Bd3 { [%emt 1:30:00] This seemed like a lawful place for the bishop,
eyeing the h7 pawn and the weak e4 and f5 squares. } (15. Bc4 { I also
considered placing the bishop to c4, but I didn't like that am not attacking
the h7 pawn + wasn't sure where the bishop belongs. // The computer does think
both moves are fine - as long as White follows things up with f4 ideas. There
is something to be said about preventing Nd7 and introducing Bd5 ideas too,
although I am not sure if it is necessary. } 15... Nc6 { I thought he goes Rd8 next
and is kinda fine. There are some games here, which I am including below for
future reference 1-0 (51) Varga,Z (2520) -Roeder,M . } (15... Nd7?? 16. Bxf7 { And White should be winning already? Kinda amazing that Bok fell into this
against Blazeka - although I guess it was just an online game. // Yup, this is
just won for White, even if Bok managed to draw. } 16... Rac8 17. Kb2 Rc7 18. Bd5 Rhc8 19. c4 b5 20. Rhf1 Nb6 21. f4 bxc4 22. Bxc4 Nxc4+ 23. bxc4 Rxc4 24. Rd2 Rb8+ 25. Kc1 Ra4 26. Rdf2 e4 27. Kd2 Rd8+ 28. Ke3 f5 29. Rd2 Ra3+ 30. Ke2 Rxd2+ 31. Kxd2 a5 32. Rb1 e3+ 33. Ke2 a4 34. Rb7+ Ke6 35. Rxh7 Rc3 36. Ra7 a3 37. h4 Rxc2+ 38. Kxe3 Rxg2 39. Kf3 Ra2 40. Ra6+ Kf7 41. Kg3 Ra1 42. h5 a2 43. Kh2 Kg7 44. Kg2 Kh7 45. Kh2 Rf1 46. Rxa2 Rxf4 47. Kg3 Rg4+ 48. Kf3 Kh6 49. Rh2 Ra4 50. Rh1 Rb4 51. Rh2 Kg5 52. h6 Rb3+ 53. Kg2 Rb2+ 54. Kg1 Rxh2 55. Kxh2 Kxh6 56. Kg3 Kg5 57. Kf3 f4 58. Kf2 Kg4 59. Kg2 f3+ 60. Kf2 Kf4 61. Kf1 Ke3 62. Ke1 f2+ 63. Kf1 Kf3 { 1/2-1/2 (63) Blazeka,M (2336)-Bok,B (2613) Chess.com INT 2016 }) 16. Bd5 Rad8 17. Bxc6 Rxd1+ 18. Kxd1 bxc6 19. Ke2 { I guess this primitive idea of
taking on c6 and going for the rook endgame is also possible in a position
like this - even if the edge for White is smaller than in the lines with f4
idea executed. } 19... Rd8 20. Ra1 Rd7 21. Ra4 f5 22. Rh4 Rd5 23. Rxh7 Ra5 24. Rh6 f6 25. Rh7+ Ke6 26. h4 Ra1 27. h5 Rc1 28. Kd3 Rg1 29. Rg7 Rh1 30. Rc7 Kd6 31. Rh7 Rh2 32. h6 Ke6 33. b4 Rxg2 34. Rh8 e4+ 35. fxe4 fxe4+ 36. Kxe4 Rg4+ 37. Kd3 Rh4 38. h7 Kf5 39. c4 a6 40. c3 Kg6 41. Rc8 Rxh7 42. Rxc6 Ra7 43. b5 axb5 44. cxb5 Kg5 45. b6 Rd7+ 46. Kc4 f5 47. Rc7 Rd1 48. b7 Rb1 49. Kc5 f4 50. Kc6 f3 51. Rf7 { 1-0 (51) Varga,Z  (2520)-Roeder,M (2435) Budapest 1998 }) 15... Nd7 { [%emt 0:
33:00] My opponent spent ages here and this move surprised me a lot. I didn't
quite understand at first what is the idea, but I realized my opponent wants
Nf8-Ne6 and then Rd8 of some sorts, when there should be approximate equality.
I kinda felt I should have the advantage, but over the board I couldn't quite
figure out what to make of my superior pieces. // Once again - according to
the computer there is not that big of a difference between this move and Nc6
if White goes for the f4 plan. } (15... Nc6 16. Bf5 { With the knight on c6,
this is a better version for White as the knight is kinda far away from the
better e6 square, although even here } (16. f4 { There is a GM game where White
played this thematic break - which I kinda know the engine also considered as
the strongest even with the knight on d7. This just showcases the dangers of
preparing an opening purely with the engine - I really wasn't aware of this
idea at all and it wasn't on my radar at all. With that being said, I could
have tried a bit harder to find something - even if it is debatable whether I
would have actually found it. } 16... exf4 17. Rhf1 { This is the idea if Black takes
- we simply collect that pawn and it doesn't matter if the knigt jumps to e5 -
we move the bishop to e4 and don't give a damn. } 17... Ne5 18. Rxf4 Rag8 19. g3 h5 20. Rdf1 Rh6 21. Ra4 a6 22. Be4 Rb8 23. Rf4 Ng4 24. Bg2 Nxh2 25. Rh4 { 1-0 (25)
Korneev,O (2476)-Meissner,F (2359) Bad Woerishofen 2023 }) 16... Rad8 { And now
White has to go for the same Rhe1-f4 plan. } 17. h4 h6 18. g4 { Was an
instructive plan by another Prins afficionado GM Steven Zierk. Not sure how
good it is - I am always worried of some h5 strikes in this positions. } 18... Rxd1+ (18... h5 { Stockfish indeed confirms this is better (there is a variation in
the game that I feared that went like that). Here Black is close to equality. }) 19. Kxd1 Rd8+ 20. Ke2 Kd6 21. Be4 Kc7 22. f4 exf4 23. Rf1 Ne5 24. Rxf4 Rd6 25. Bf3 Ng6 26. Rc4+ Kb8 27. Re4 Re6 28. h5 Rxe4+ 29. Bxe4 Ne7 30. Ke3 Kc7 31. Kd4 b6 32. Bd5 Kd6 33. Bxf7 a5 34. Be8 Nc8 35. c4 Ne7 36. c3 Kc7 37. c5 f5 38. g5 hxg5 39. h6 Ng8 40. h7 Nf6 41. h8=Q { 1-0 (41) Zierk,S (2499)-Csonka,B (2498)
Chess.com INT 2021 }) 16. Bf5 { [%emt 1:27:00] Played a bit too routinely - and
way too quickly (after just three minutes), completely failing to sense the
critical moment. In tis position, I showcased my old habit of playing too
routinely, trying to do without calculating and trying to keep control at all
costs. It is true that this was the 2nd game of the day which exacerbated my
bad tendencies, but it is not a sufficient excuse. With that being said, I am
still not 100% sure what to play instead as the alternative plans didn't
really cross my mind. // Tbh, it is not SUCH a horrible move - but I guess at
some point I should find the f4 plan nevertheless. } (16. f4 { This idea of f4 kept
escaping my attention (despite me constantly drilling my students to look for
pawn breaks). This is not your usual break in regular Prins endgames, but here
with the knight and the bishop the situation is different. Maybe I should have
tried calculating more but I was not aware of these idea in these position
prior to this game (what if Black doesn't take anyway). // Indeed, stockfish
agrees this is super strong, e.g. } 16... exf4 (16... Rhg8 17. Rd2 h5 18. Re1 { Although at the first glance it is not so easy to improve on White's position.
I guess Bf5 and then maybe Bxd7-fxe5 would come? } 18... Rad8 19. Bf5 Nf8 { Although
even here things aren't that simple due ot } 20. fxe5 (20. Rf2 Ng6 { And still a
lot of work needs to be done as after } 21. Bxg6 fxg6 22. fxe5 f5 { The e5 pawn
is insignificant. Amazing how much there is to calculate even in a simple
position. Underestimating it is another bad habit of mine. }) 20... Rxd2 21. Kxd2 Rxg2+) 17. Rhf1 $18) (16. Rhe1 Rhg8 17. g3 h5 18. f4 { Is apparently also good although I have trouble understanding why } 18... Rad8 19. Bh7 Rh8 20. Bf5 { The standard idea. } 20... Nc5 21. Rxd8 Rxd8 22. fxe5 { Note to
self - pressure on e5 is possible in this variation. }) 16... Nf8 { [%emt 0:31:
00] This kinda confused me and I wasn't sure how I want to proceed. To be fair
it makes sense to get the knight to the good square on e6 and then potentially
f4. Here I started getting nervous as I didn't see anything immediate. //
Stockfish actually thinks this is the "best move", which probably means the
position is quite stable so the evaluation doesn't depend on an individual
move. Black basically wants to unravel with Ne6-Rd8 next, approximately. } (16... Nc5 17. Rd5 { It is indeed much worse for Black as after } 17... Ne6 18. Rhd1 { I actually
managed to double on the d-file, am threatening Rd7 and Black can't challenge
really as the h7 pawn is loose. } 18... Nf8 19. c4 Rg8 20. g3 h6 21. c5 a5 22. Rd6 Rb8 23. Rb6 Rg5 24. g4 { A model example of utilizing the dominating bishop and
lead in development in these positions 1-0 (24) Brodsky,M (2559)-Apalev,S  
(2255) Maikop 2004 }) 17. Be4 { [%emt 1:22:00] Kinda admission of failure - as
it was clearly not my intention to move the bishop again. // Still, this is
not such a bad move, tbh. } (17. Rd3 Rd8 { I didn't think was too good for me. } 18. Rxd8 (18. Kb2 { The computer thinks White has some edge here, tho, e.g. } 18... Ne6 19. Be4 { A key move. The idea is to try and provoke b6 so that the a-pawn is
