{ Fast forward a few moves later. The position is still equal, but White has
definite counterplay due to the following nasty move. }
43. b5 { [%emt 0:00:11] } 43... cxb5 { [%emt 0:00:02] } 44. Rd5 { [%emt 0:00:07] A very unpleasant idea to face
in time trouble. Note only is the knight on e5 pinned - the bishop on h4 is
hanging and also the c-pawn is strong. } 44... Bg3 { [%emt 0:00:00] This is sufficient,
but the drawing path still remains very tricky. } 45. c6 { [%emt 0:00:05] } 45... Rc3?? { [%emt 0:00:04] But this is a losing move. } (45... Kf6 { Was necessary,
although it is not easy to see that } 46. c7 Ra2+ { Draws on the spot due to } 47. Kd1 Ra1+ 48. Kc2 Nd3 { Attacking the c7 pawn and preparing Rc1. Impossible to
see in severe time trouble. }) 46. Nc5 { [%emt 0:00:02] And the c-pawn will
promote. A tremendous upset by the young star! } 1-0


