{ Indjic has managed to completely outplay Fabiano Caruana and here he was
close to reaping the rewards of his powerful play. }
40. Qh5? { [%emt 0:00:38]
But this is too hasty. } (40. Kg2 a2 41. Qh5 Qxd6 42. Qh8+ Ke7 43. Qxg7+ Kd8 44. Qf7 { And now Black
doesn't have any checks and the g-pawn will decide the issue. }) 40... Qxd6 { [%emt 0:00:02] } 41. Qh8+ { [%emt 0:00:01] } 41... Ke7 { [%emt 0:00:01] } 42. Qxg7+ { [%emt 0:00:01] } 42... Kd8 { [%emt 0:00:02] } 43. Qf7 { [%emt 0:01:06] } 43... Qd1+ { [%emt 0:00:
10] } 44. Kg2 { [%emt 0:00:14] } 44... Qc2+ { [%emt 0:00:03] } 45. Kh3 { [%emt 0:00:33] } 45... Qxc3 { [%emt 0:00:02] And suddenly this endgame is completely drawn as Ne7 will
happen on the next move. White is actually the one who should repeat here, but
Indjic, through inertia, continued to play for the win and even ended up
losing in the end. An unbelievable turn of events and one of those games that
makes me say were were quite unlucky in this match, as this was a gargantuan
opportunity! } 0-1


