[FEN "2r2k1r/p3qp2/1pn1pN1p/8/3P1R1Q/P3P3/6PP/5RK1 w - - 0 25"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ [%evp 0,12,214,119,225,125,143,0,34,-22,0,73,37,-84,-102] In this position,
Yilmaz is completely winning. But being very low on time, he starts to drift
until he throws his entire advantage away. }
25. Rg4 { This is not ideal as it
removes the attack from the f7 pawn. White is still winning, but now Black can
at least grab the a3 pawn. } (25. Qh5 { Keeping an eye on the pawn on f7, was
the simplest. Although there were many move that retain the advantage. }) 25... Qxa3 26. Rg3 { Continuing to drift. This defends the e3 pawn but it is a bit
too passive. } (26. Qg3 { With the idea of playing Rg8, while also defending the
e3 pawn, was much better. White retains a decisive advantage here. }) 26... Ne7 { Trying to get to f5. Now White's task is no longer easy. } 27. e4 (27. Rgf3 { Was stronger, e.g. after } 27... Nf5 28. Qe4 { White is still winning - but it is not
at all so obvious any more. }) 27... Qb2 { A nasty move,
attacking the d4 pawn. The game is already quite unclear. } { [%csl Rd4][%cal Rb2d4] } 28. Qf4 Qxd4+ 29. Kh1 Nf5 { A very nice defensive resources that shocked Yilmaz in time trouble. } 30. Ra3 (30. Nd5 { Was the only way to retain some advantage, but good luck
finding that with just seconds on the clock. }) 30... Qxf6 { And now Black is
even better and Xu Yi went on to win this game. A remarkable swindle. } 0-1


