[SetUp "1"]

{ Polina has played a wonderful game and completely outplayed her opponent.
Along the way, she missed a few simpler converstions. But this endgame is
still won if Black finds the only winning move. }
53... b4? { [%emt 0:00:06]
This move throws away the win - but not the draw yet. } (53... Rd8! { This
tremendous rook retreat basically paralyzes the pawns after } 54. g5 Rh8 { And now Black has enough time to push the b-pawn. Not an easy find with little
time on the clock. }) 54. g5 { [%emt 0:00:01] } 54... b3 { [%emt 0:00:01] } 55. h7? { [%emt 0:00:01] But this move gives Black a new opportunity. } (55. g6 b2 56. g7 b1=Q 57. g8=Q+ { Would have lead to some sort of a crazy computer draw - but it
was the only way. }) 55... Rd8?? { [%emt 0:00:01] But this move not only throws
away the win - but also a draw. } (55... b2 { Pushing the pawn was winning as
after } 56. h8=Q b1=Q { Black is apparently winning! Once again - easy to
evaluate it with the engines, not with the human brains. }) 56. g6 { [%emt 0:00:
01] } 56... b2 { [%emt 0:00:00] } 57. g7 { [%emt 0:00:01] } 57... b1=Q { [%emt 0:00:08] } 58. g8=Q+ { [%emt 0:00:00] } 58... Ka3 { [%emt 0:00:02] } 59. Qxd8 { [%emt 0:00:10] } 59... Qxh7 { [%emt 0:00:00] And now White has a theoretically won queen endgame that is
also very difficult to play in time scramble for the defending side.
Fortunately for us, Boyer blundered the f2 pawn shortly and this crazy
encounter finally ended in a draw. } 1/2-1/2


