[Event "Pro Chess League 2023"]
[Site "Chess.com"]
[Date "2023.02.14"]
[Round "1"]
[White "Heinemann, Josefine"]
[Black "Deac, Bogdan-Daniel"]
[Result "0-1"]
[WhiteElo "2336"]
[BlackElo "2700"]
[TimeControl "300+2"]
[Annotator "USER"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Croatia Bulldogs - Berlin Bears, Pro Chess League Week 2 Highlights"]
[ChapterName "Heinemann, Josefine - Deac, Bogdan-Daniel"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/aLlFXzje/nmvfgexg"]
[FEN "5rk1/pp2np2/2r1p1p1/q2pP1Pp/2n2N1P/2P2P2/PPB2Q2/1K1RR3 b - - 0 25"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Deac alraedy has a decisive advantage due to the fact that the kingside is
closed and his pieces are threatening the queenside. But here he found a nice
combination. }
25... Nxb2! { [%emt 0:00:12] Bam! Destroying the
king's shelter and removing the defender of the c3 pawn. } { [%cal Ra5c3] } 26. Kxb2 { [%emt 0:00:
12] } 26... Qxc3+ { [%emt 0:00:04] } 27. Kb1 { [%emt 0:00:02] } 27... Qb4+ { [%emt 0:00:27] This double attack is the point! The knight on f4 is
loose and will be captured on the next move. } { [%csl Rf4][%cal Gb4b1,Gb4f4] } 28. Bb3 { [%emt 0:00:33] } 28... Qxf4 { [%emt 0:00:01] This is not yet the end of the variation as the queen is
somewhat short on squares. } 29. Rd4 { [%emt 0:00:02] } 29... Qf5+ { [%emt 0:00:59] } 30. Bc2 { [%emt 0:00:01] } 30... Rxc2 { [%emt 0:00:58] The most elegant. Just like in the
previous week in round 1, Deac sacrifices an exchange to simplify the position
and enters a completely winning endgame where the rooks will not have any open
files and where all White's pawns are weak. } (30... Qh3 { Was also winning. }) 31. Qxc2 { [%emt 0:00:00] } 31... Qxf3 { [%emt 0:00:01] And Deac went on to convert
this with ease. } 0-1


[Event "Pro Chess League 2023"]
[Site "Chess.com"]
[Date "2023.02.14"]
[Round "2"]
[White "Bluebaum, Matthias"]
[Black "Daneshvar, Bardiya"]
[Result "0-1"]
[WhiteElo "2663"]
[BlackElo "2510"]
[TimeControl "300+2"]
[Annotator "USER"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Croatia Bulldogs - Berlin Bears, Pro Chess League Week 2 Highlights"]
[ChapterName "Bluebaum, Matthias - Daneshvar, Bardiya"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/aLlFXzje/fyZUpLoa"]
[FEN "3r1r2/2p2nk1/bpP2b1p/4pPpP/1qN1Q3/1B2PP2/7B/1R1R2K1 w - - 0 41"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ This game featured a very unconventional opening that led to a very
unconventional and complicated position with a very non-standard pawn
structure.At this point of the game, both players were extremely low on time
and here Bluebaum loses control of the game. }
41. Ba2? { [%emt 0:00:03]
Allowing a nasty double attack! } (41. Rdc1 { A move like this rook move would
have kept the approximate balance. }) (41. Nd6 { White could have also played
this crazy move, exploiting the fact that the queen on b4 is exposed. This
owuld have actually ensured some advantage for the first player. }) 41... Qa4 { [%emt 0:00:07] A very nasty double-attack on the rook and
the bishop on a2. } { [%cal Ra4d1,Ra4a2] } 42. Rxd8 { [%emt 0:00:16] } 42... Rxd8 { [%emt 0:00:00] } 43. Bb3 { [%emt 0:00:00] } 43... Qb4 { [%emt 0:00:00] } 44. Qc2? { [%emt 0:00:03] Trying to keep
things safe but decentralizing the queen further. } (44. Bg3 { Trying to bring
the bishop back in the game, was the only chance to stay in the game. }) 44... Qc5 { [%emt 0:00:03] Black's pieces are too active and his king is
safe. This position is a nightmare to play when low on time and on the next
move, Bluebaum makes the final mistake. } { [%cal Rc5c6] } 45. Qe4 { [%emt 0:00:02] A final
mistake in a difficult position. } 45... Bxc4 { [%emt 0:00:02] A
surprising exchange, deflecting the queen from the defence of the e3 pawn due
to the Nd6 idea. } { [%cal Gf7d6,Rc5e3] } 46. Qxc4 { [%emt 0:00:01] This is a must, but this loses by
force. } (46. Bxc4 Nd6 { Wins a piece for Black. } { [%cal Rd6c4,Rd6e4] }) 46... Qxe3+ { [%emt 0:00:01] } 47. Kh1 { [%emt 0:00:04] } 47... Qxf3+ { [%emt 0:00:01] } 48. Kg1 { [%emt 0:00:00] } 48... Nd6 { [%emt 0:00:04] A cool move, covering all the
threats. White has no checks while his king is decisively exposed. Bluebaum
went on to resign very shortly afterward. } { [%csl Rf5] } 0-1


[Event "Pro Chess League 2023"]
[Site "Chess.com"]
[Date "2023.02.14"]
[Round "3"]
[White "Yilmaz, Mustafa"]
[Black "Bluebaum, Matthias"]
[Result "0-1"]
[WhiteElo "2629"]
[BlackElo "2663"]
[TimeControl "300+2"]
[Annotator "USER"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Croatia Bulldogs - Berlin Bears, Pro Chess League Week 2 Highlights"]
[ChapterName "Yilmaz, Mustafa - Bluebaum, Matthias"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/aLlFXzje/q2tUUdUf"]
[FEN "4r1k1/pp3pp1/3q4/3p1P2/3NrR1Q/5R2/PP4P1/7K b - - 0 38"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ As mentioned in the report, for the large part of this game, Mustafa has been
playing with an extra piece. However, Bluebaum refused to go away and kept
posing some practical problems, which cost Yilmaz some time on the clock. By
move 38, he managed to keep control, but the weakness of the king with the
time pressure would lead to a blunder just a few moves later. }
38... Re1+ { [%emt 0:00:05] } 39. Rf1? { [%emt 0:00:13] This is a mistake that suddenly
throws the game away. } (39. Kh2 { Was necessary, when after } 39... R1e4 { White would
have to find one of the possible winning moves such as } 40. f6 (40. Nb5) (40. Qg5)) 39... Rxf1+ { [%emt 0:00:01] } 40. Rxf1 { [%emt 0:00:00] } 40... Re4 { [%emt 0:
00:00] This double attack is very nasty. } { [%cal Re4h4,Re4d4] } 41. Qf2 { [%emt 0:
00:01] The only way to keep the knight on d4 protected. } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gf2d4] } 41... Qh6+ { [%emt 0:00:02] } 42. Kg1 { [%emt 0:00:02] } 42... Rh4 { [%emt 0:00:00] And
amazingly enough, now White has to give up the knight due to the mating threat
on h1. } 43. Qg3 { [%emt 0:00:13] } 43... Rxd4 { [%emt 0:00:01] And all of a sudden,
Black is winning. Even though some adventures were still ahead, Bluebaum did
manage to swindle his way out of this one. An amazing turnaround. } 0-1


