[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Croatia Bulldogs - Berlin Bears, Pro Chess League Week 2 Highlights"]
[ChapterName "Bezold, Michael - Roebers, Eline"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/aLlFXzje/3Pl4kXZ4"]
[FEN "5rk1/1p4p1/2n3qp/p1r5/P1Npp3/1P4PQ/2P2P2/3RR1K1 b - - 0 43"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Let's also take a look at the other "fatal" game from the third round
featuring another amazing turnaround - one between Bezold Michael and Roebers
Eline. We join the action on move 43 and we can see that Eline has a totally
dominating position, with a powerful central pawn duo, safer king and better
placed pieces. There are many moves here that ensure a decisive (-7 or even
-8!!) advantage for Black. However, under severe time pressure, Eline decided
to go for the most forcing option. }
43... Rxc4 { [%emt 0:00:08] This is
objectively correct, but it does raise up the stakes and makes the worth of
every subsequent move much higher. } 44. bxc4 { [%emt 0:00:02] } 44... Ne5 { [%emt 0:00:
01] } 45. Re2 { [%emt 0:00:20] } 45... Nf3+ { [%emt 0:00:01] } 46. Kf1 { [%emt 0:00:08] } 46... Qc6? { [%emt 0:00:03] But this is the move that gives it away. Eline decides
to go for the c4 pawn, but overlooks a very nasty defence by the opponent in a
severe time trouble. } (46... e3 { A move like this one, trying to open up the
king ,was completely winning, for example. Among other options. }) 47. Qh5 { [%emt 0:00:09] A very nasty defence, returning the queen and
intending to bring her via b5 back into the game. } { [%cal Gh5b5,Gb5b3] } 47... Qxc4 { [%emt 0:00:02] This
is also apparently not the strongest, but at this point it is no longer easy
to play as the a5 pawn was also hanging (and Eline was under severe time
pressure). } 48. Qb5 { [%emt 0:00:10] } 48... Qf7 { [%emt 0:00:03] } 49. Qb3 { [%emt 0:00:
06] And now White manages to exchange queens and avoid the worse. The game
should now be totally equal, but Bezold managed to win this in the end, which
was quite heartbreaking for Eline - but hopefully games such as this one will
serve as good lessons for her subsequent development! } 1-0


