[FEN "5rk1/2q1pp1p/pnPp1bp1/1p1B4/2r2P2/P1N1Q2P/1PP3P1/3RR1K1 b - - 0 24"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In this very complex and tactical position, White has managed to get the pawn
on c6 and Black the rook on c4. However, Black is completely winning as the
structure is very solid, the pawn on c6 is quite weak and all of White's
pieces are under the pressure. }
24... Rxc3 { [%emt 0:00:29] This is very pretty
and practical - especially in time trouble, even though the engine doesn't
necessarily think it is the best! } (24... Bxc3 { The computer points out that
this move was actually quite powerful as Black will simply eliminate both of
White's minor pieces and then win some pawns. } 25. bxc3 (25. Bxc4 Bxe1 26. Bxf7+ Rxf7 27. Qxe1 Qxc6 { Leaves Black a piece up. }) 25... Nxd5 26. Rxd5 e6 27. Rd3 Qxc6 { And Black has an extra pawn and the same good structure as in the
game. }) 25. bxc3 { [%emt 0:00:04] } 25... Nxd5 { [%emt 0:00:00] } 26. Rxd5 { [%emt 0:00:
01] } 26... Qxc6 { [%emt 0:00:01] Even though it is not the
strongest, Black still has tremendous compensation for the exchange due to the
powerful dark-squared bishop and better pawn structure. The pawns on the
c-file are sitting ducks and Deac went on to convert the game, although not
without some adventures. } { [%csl Gf6][%cal Rf6c3] } 0-1


