{ It is clear that White is significantly better here due to the positioning of
the pieces and the bishop pair, but it is not 100% obvious how to continue. }
22. Ne5 { Would be incredibly strong - simply exchanging a pair of knights,
opening up the bishop on g2 and trying to activate the king. Black actually
lacks a good reply here. } (22. Nd4 { [%emt 0:00:05] Was played in the game,
which still preserved a large chunk of the advantage, but made the task much
more difficult. }) 22... Nxe5 (22... Kh7 23. Nxg6 { Is no better. }) (22... Nge7 23. Rd1 { Is also pretty hopeless for Black. }) 23. Qxe5 { And now the weakness of the b6 pawn is much more pronounced.
