[Event "Best of Deac Bogdan-Daniel: Introduction"]
[Date "2023.02.14"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "USER"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Best of Deac Bogdan-Daniel"]
[ChapterName "Introduction"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/Z9HYIFdP/iAB8qttd"]

{ Ever since he was very young, Deac Bogdan-Daniel was very well known to be a
talented young player and a real chess prodigy. --- He acquired his FM title
in 2014, probably upon reaching the mandatory rating qualification of 2300 in
March 2014. He was awarded his first IM norm for his result at the Gibraltar
Masters (2014), the second IM norm for his 7.5/11 at the Romanian Championship
2014 in May 2014 and his third IM norm for his result at the 29th Swarzach
Open in Austria in August. As he had already achieved an official rating of
2400 in July 2014, his IM title took effect from 23 August 2014, at the 9th
and final round of the Swarzacher Open when he clinched his final IM norm by
drawing with GM Vitaly Kunin. Two years later, he gained his GM title when he
won his third GM norm at the Zalakaros Open on 4 June 2016, having won his
first two GM norms at the Zalakaros Open 2015 and at the Graz Open in February
2016. He had all ready reached the 2500 rating mark the previous month. He was
both the youngest IM and GM in the history at the time he obtained these
titles --- And even though he later slowed down a little bit and didn't
immediately storm the chess world (or top 10) as you might expect for someone
with such a potential, he recently joined the exclusive 2700 club and is
knocking on the door of the world's elite. --- In this study/.pgn we will take
a glimpse into his career/journey and check some of the best games/game
fragments of Deac Bogdan-Daniel's career. }
 *


[Event "World School-ch U15 8th"]
[Site "Iasi"]
[Date "2012.05.01"]
[Round "4"]
[White "Sozin, Stepan"]
[Black "Deac, Bogdan Daniel"]
[Result "0-1"]
[WhiteElo "2123"]
[BlackElo "1913"]
[Annotator "USER"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Best of Deac Bogdan-Daniel"]
[ChapterName "Sozin, Stepan - Deac, Bogdan Daniel"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/Z9HYIFdP/bh1DGYlk"]
[FEN "r2qr1k1/pp3pp1/5np1/2Pp4/PP1P4/4bB2/1B4PP/R2QR2K b - - 0 21"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Let's start by examining a game from Deac's young age. The following game was
played at the World School U15 championship held in 2012. Deac was only 11
years old and his rating was sitting at 1913. His opponent was Stepan Sozin,
rated 2123. --- We join the action on move 21. We can see that WHite has the
bishop pair and nice queenside structure, while Black has some activity in the
center and the active bishop on e3. White's queen is also somewhat weak and it
is precisely what Black can exploit with the next accurate move. }
21... Ne4 { A very powerful move, basically forcing White to
give up the bishop on f3 due to the threat of Nf2 that can't be stopped. } { [%csl Gf2][%cal Ge4f2,Re1e3] } 22. Bxe4 (22. Rxe3 { Of course, loses to } 22... Nf2+ { And the queen is
gone. } { [%cal Rf2d1,Rf2h1] }) 22... Rxe4 { Now White has lost the bishop pair and the bishop on b2 is
very passive, while Black's pieces are dominating the center. Things are still
not lost, though, but the next move blunders it all away. } 23. Ra3 { Trying to attack the bishop and trying for some tricks. } { [%csl Re3][%cal Ra3e3] } (23. Qb3 { Objectively, moving the queen out of the way,attacking the
bishop on e3 and then looking to get some Bc1, was the way to go. Black is
better but ther eis a lot of chess to be played. } { [%cal Gb2c1] }) 23... Qg5 { Bringing the queen closer and preparing to swing the other rook.
The problem for White is that now the rooks are not coordinated and there are
some issues with the back rank. } { [%csl Ge3][%cal Ga8e8,Gg5e3] } 24. Rexe3 { This was what White had envisioned,
but it fails tactically. } (24. Ra1 { It is quite significant that returning the
rook is the engine's best move, which speaks volumes about White's entire idea. }) 24... Rxe3 25. Bc1 { White was probably relying
on this trick to exchange some pieces and save the position, but overlooked a
nasty counterblow. } { [%csl Re3][%cal Rc1g5,Ra3e3] } 25... Qg4 { Due to the weakness of the
last rank, Black has this move, unpinning. Now the game is over as the queen
can't be captured and Black will exchange rooks and remain a clean exchange up.
Sozin continues playing for a while but was ultimately forced to lay down his
arms. } { [%cal Rg4d1,Ge3e1,Re3a3] } 0-1


[Event "European Team Championship"]
[Site "Hersonissos GRE"]
[Date "2017.10.28"]
[Round "1.20"]
[White "Bogdan-Daniel Deac"]
[Black "Neil Berry"]
[Result "1-0"]
[WhiteElo "2560"]
[BlackElo "2283"]
[Annotator "USER"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Best of Deac Bogdan-Daniel"]
[ChapterName "Bogdan-Daniel Deac - Neil Berry"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/Z9HYIFdP/NJwmKdMt"]
[FEN "1br3k1/pp3npp/2bq1p2/3p4/P3r3/1P1QPNP1/1BR1BP1P/3R2K1 w - - 0 24"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ A fabuluous move, exploiting all sorts of pins
and the weakness of the back rank. } { [%csl Rf7][%cal Gc2c8,Ra8h8] }
24. Qxd5! (24. Nd4 { It is true that
White is much better after this simple move, but the text move is much more
attractive and forcing! }) 24... Bxd5 (24... Qxd5 25. Rxd5 { is no
better, as the bishop is pinned to the rook, so White wins a clean pawn. } { [%cal Rc2c8] }) 25. Rxc8+ { Now we see the point. Not only does White win a rook and
the bishop for the queen, but Black also has to lose more coordination due to
the awkward position of the knight on f7 and the king on g8. } { [%cal Ra8h8] } 25... Nd8 26. Bc4 { Now a pin on the d-file also appears. } { [%cal Rd1d6,Rc4g8] } 26... Rxc4 27. bxc4 { And the bishop on d5 is dropping next, the knight is still
pinned and the bishop on b8 is also short of squares. White is completely
winning, so Deac's opponent resigned. A very pretty combination! } { [%cal Ra8h8,Rd1d8] } 1-0


[Event "GCT Bucharest Classic"]
[Site "Bucharest ROU"]
[Date "2021.06.06"]
[Round "2"]
[White "Maxime Vachier-Lagrave"]
[Black "Bogdan-Daniel Deac"]
[Result "0-1"]
[WhiteElo "2760"]
[BlackElo "2627"]
[Annotator "USER"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Best of Deac Bogdan-Daniel"]
[ChapterName "Maxime Vachier-Lagrave - Bogdan-Daniel Deac"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/Z9HYIFdP/VNEhFPty"]
[FEN "r4rk1/2p3pp/p4n2/2b5/Pp6/3R1Q2/2B1RPPP/q4NK1 w - - 0 25"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Even though Deac was a very solid and strong GM for a while, until 2021 he
didn't really get many opportunities to play against the world's very best
players. It all changed when it was announced that one of the legs of the
Grand Chess Tour would be held in Romania - as Deac and his compatriot
Lupulescu were invited to participate as local players. --- Now, even though
Deac's rating was 2600+ and even though everyone knew that he was probably
somewhat underrated due to the global pandemic that prevented him (just like
many others) from playing and improving further, he was still seen as a major
underdog in a tournament where almost everyone outrated him by 100+ points.
And even though he did end up on a negative -1 score, everyone was positively
surprised with his performance. Not only did he accumulate 6 draws - he also
managed to defeat the top French Grandmaster Maxime Vachier-Lagrave in a very
tense game. --- We join that encounter on move 25. The position is very
complicated and double-edged, with Black having a dangerous queenside majority,
but White having a better development and a target in form of the Black king.
The players have just repeated the moves once - and Maxime could have done
that again if he wanted. Alas, he decided to play for the win - although at
the moment such a position is fully justified. }
25. g4 { A very strong move,
trying to dislodge the knight on f6 form the very good defensive post. } 25... b3 { An extremely good response in return - almost the only move in the position.
The point of this move is to either divert the bishop and the rook. } (25... a5 { If Black does nothing and makes some random move, then White wins with the g5
advance e.g. } 26. g5 { The knight has no good squares here. }) (25... Kh8 { Going to h8 is possible, but after } 26. g5 Ng8 27. Qh3 { There are potential issues on h7, which is why it is advantageous to divert
the bishop from c2. } { [%csl Gc2][%cal Rh3h7] }) 26. Bxb3+ (26. Rxb3 { Taking with the rook is logical,
but it reveals another point of the move b3 - freeing the square d4 for the
queen. } 26... Qd4 { Now the g4 pawn is under the attack and
the knight will be moved next move to g4 or d5, e.g. } { [%csl Rg4][%cal Rd4g4] } 27. g5 (27. h3 Nd5 { And the situation is completely unclear because Black
activated and is pressuring the f2 pawn. } { [%cal Rf8f2,Rc5f2] }) 27... Ng4) 26... Kh8 27. g5 Ng8 28. Qd5 (28. Qh3 { Is now less powerful as there aren't any threats on h7, so Black
can play } 28... Qc1 { Targeting the g5 pawn. White is better,
but the game continues. } { [%csl Rg5][%cal Rc1g5] }) 28... Bd6 29. Rh3 g6 { The culminating moment of this
game. } 30. Qd3 { Quite a surprising mistake for a player of MVL's
caliber. White creates the threat of Qxg6, but Black has a fairly easy way of
dealing with it. } { [%cal Rd3g6] } (30. Qe6 { Was the right move. After } 30... Qg7 { The situation is
complicated, but White is definitely the one with the advantage. }) 30... Rf5 { And just like this, Black deals with the threat and
collects the weak pawn on g5 next as there is no good way of defending it.
Deac went on to win this game! Perhaps not the most remarkable "combination"
nor the most convincing game, but such a career milestone definitely deserves
to be featured in the "Best Of" collection. } { [%csl Rg5][%cal Rf5g5] } 31. Qe3 { Fails to defend the pawn
due to } 31... Bf4 { 0-1 Black wins. } 0-1


