{ Hi and welcome to the "Meet the Bulldog" series - a series in which I will introduce the players of the Croatia Bulldogs team competing in the Pro Chess League, season 2023, by taking a look at 5 memorable, important and beautiful
game fragments from their respective careers. In the very first episode of the series, we will take a look at the 5 best games from the career of Eline Roebers, a 16-year-old International Master from the Netherlands who is currently considered to be one of the brightest new talents on the horizon! }
 *


[Event "23rd European Teams Women"]
[Site "Catez SLO"]
[Date "2021.11.13"]
[Round "2.4"]
[White "Eline Roebers"]
[Black "Iulija Osmak"]
[Result "1-0"]
[WhiteElo "2304"]
[BlackElo "2423"]
[Annotator "USER"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Eline Roebers Top 5 Games - Meet The Bulldog #1"]
[ChapterName "Eline Roebers - Iulija Osmak"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/GGJ4wYWp/PslzM3Zt"]
[FEN "3r1bnr/ppkn3p/2p2pp1/5p2/2B5/2B3NP/PPP2PP1/3R1RK1 w - - 0 17"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Even though Eline showcased her talent by winning the World Junior U14 Championship in 2020 (held online) and winning the Brugse Meesters Open in Belgium at the age of 15 (which elevated her rating to 2297), the wider chess audience first heard about the name after she distinguished herself at the European Women's Team Championship held in November, 2021, where she won an individual bronze medal on the board 2, scoring the impressive 7/9.
Her game against strong Ukrainian IM Julia Osmak was particularly impressive. We join
the game on move 17. After a very enterprising opening where she sacrificed a pawn, Eline obtained a very promising - almost winning - position, with a big compensation for the pawn.
In these types of positions, the advantage can slip very easily, yet Eline handled it absolutely masterfully. Let's see how! }
17. Ne2 { A very instructive moment. One of the standard
rules of the positional play is "improve your worst placed piece". Yet, in
practice, it is not always easy to recognize which piece is the worst placed
piece - or find the correct timing to move it. Here, Eline correctly realizes
that the knight has no prospects on g3 and rushes to move it to a better spot
on d4 or f4. } { [%cal Ge2f4,Ge2d4] } (17. Rfe1 { It would be very natural to move the rook to e1 in
this position. However, it is not yet clear whether the rook belongs here or
not. If you have a choice between a move you know you will have to make (Ne2)
and a move you are not sure if you should make (Rfe1), it is always better to
go for the former. }) 17... Ne5 18. Bb3?! { Okay, this is maybe not the most
energetic, but it does not alter the evaluation of the position. } (18. Nd4 { This knight jump, threatening Ne6, was stronger, as it
would have improved the knight with a gain of tempo. } { [%csl Re6][%cal Gd4e6] }) 18... Rxd1 19. Rxd1 Bc5 { Black is desperately trying to develop the kingside and bring the rest of the
pieces into the game. } (19... Nh6 { Maybe it was a bit more
tenacious to try to develop the knight to h6 first and move the bishop to e7,
potentially, but Black's life is very difficult all the same! } { [%cal Gh6f7,Gf8e7] }) 20. Nf4 { Now with the bishop on c5, Ne6 is a massive threat, so
Black has to lose more time. } { [%csl Rc5][%cal Gf4e6] } 20... Bb6 (20... Nh6 21. Ne6+ Kb6 { Is winning in many
ways, but the most direct seems to be. } 22. Nxc5 Kxc5 23. f4 Nc4 24. Bxf6) 21. Bb4 { Another very strong move, improving the bishop even further.
This is the consequence of Black removing the bishop from the f8-a3 diagonal. } { [%cal Rb4f8] } 21... Kc8 { This is some sort of desperation, trying to avoid Ne6, Bd6, etc. But
Black still loses time instead of developing. } 22. Bf8 { There is
a deadly threat of Bg7 now. } { [%cal Gf8g7] } 22... h5 23. Kf1! { A very powerful human move. Black
is almost in zugzwang and has no moves. } 23... g5 { This is desperation, but it was
hard to offer Black any useful advice at this point. Now Eline finishes the
game with a very nice and precise piece of calculation. } 24. Bg7! { Attacking the rook that defends the g8 knight. } { [%cal Rg7h8,Rg7f6,Gh8g8,Rb3g8] } 24... Rh7 { It seems at first glance as if White's two pieces are hanging,
but Eline has envisioned the following powerful shot. } { [%cal Rf4h5] } 25. Nxh5 { Defending the bishop and diverting the rook on h7. Black's
position is collapsing. } { [%cal Gh5g7,Rh5f6] } 25... Rxh5 26. Bxg8 { The bishops are
extremely deadly. f6 is also under the attack and there is no way for Black to
defend it. } { [%cal Rg7h6,Rg8h7] } 26... g4 27. Bxf6 { And Eline went on to win the game. A good example of
Eline's fantastic ability to handle the initiative. } 1-0


[Event "44th Olympiad (Women)"]
[Site "Chennai IND"]
[Date "2022.08.06"]
[Round "8.11"]
[White "Eline Roebers"]
[Black "Cori T, Deysi"]
[Result "1-0"]
[WhiteElo "2344"]
[BlackElo "2371"]
[Annotator "USER"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Eline Roebers Top 5 Games - Meet The Bulldog #1"]
[ChapterName "Eline Roebers - Cori T, Deysi"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/GGJ4wYWp/SVWcRlE9"]
[FEN "3r4/1pkb1p2/pN2p1pb/2P1r3/3R4/8/PPP1BP1P/1K2R3 w - - 0 26"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ One of Eline's most successful tournaments so far was the Chess Olympiad held in Chennai in 2022, where she played on board 1 (!), scored 7.5/10 (!!) and
won the silver medal (!!!). Her games from this event are some of the most fascinating and entertaining chess games I have ever seen, with a lot of topsy-turvy encounters, tactical fights and evaluation swings (check, for example, her game against Marie Sebag or Mariya Muzychuk).
However, for the
purposes of this video/article/.pgn, I have decided to choose a nice combination she executed in the 8th round in her game against Deysi Cori from Peru.
This game was also quite complicated and combative, but after her opponent missed a nasty intermediate check of the knight on b6 earlier, by move 26 Eline obtained a completely winning position. However, White needs to be exact - there is only one winning combination. Can you find it? }
26. Rxd7+ { This capture on d7 actually wins material and is the only clear winning move. } (26. Nxd7 { Is also, sufficient! }) 26... Rxd7 27. Nxd7 Kxd7 (27... Rf5 { Was
played in the game, but after } 28. Bd3 Rxf2 29. Ne5 { Eline had no problem with
converting her advantage. }) 28. Bb5+ { The point of the
small combination, winning an exchange. } { [%cal Rb5d7,Re1e5] } 28... axb5 29. Rxe5 { Perhaps not the most remarkable tactical combination of all time, but I wanted to single it out due to the importance of the event and the class of the opponent (and also - most of Eline's other games from the 2022 Olympiad are so rich, complex and double-edged that they are worthy of separate videos :D). } 1-0


[Event "37th European Chess Club Cup (Women)"]
[Site "Mayrhofen AUT"]
[Date "2022.10.05"]
[Round "3.4"]
[White "Eline Roebers"]
[Black "Viktoria Radeva"]
[Result "1-0"]
[WhiteElo "2352"]
[BlackElo "2263"]
[Annotator "USER"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Eline Roebers Top 5 Games - Meet The Bulldog #1"]
[ChapterName "Eline Roebers - Viktoria Radeva"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/GGJ4wYWp/AEJzfbxP"]
[FEN "2r1r1k1/1p3pp1/4p3/pP2P1Np/1b1BN2n/4Q1R1/1nq2PP1/5RK1 w - - 0 27"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In the previous two games, we have seen two queenless positions where Eline showcased her calculating ability and handling of the initiative. These two traits/strengths of her style, however, are more apparent in sharp and complicated positions with the queens of the board - that are actually featured in the majority of her games.
Let's take a look at a few such typical positions, starting from the following game taken from a successful competition by Eline - European Chess Club for Women held in October 2022., where she made 5/7.
We join her game against Viktoria Radeva from Bulgaria on move 27. Eline has sacrificed a few pawns in order to obtain a winning initiative on the kingside. Can you figure out how to break through in the position? }
27. Nf6+ { As Capablanca used to say "In such positions,
combinations are as natural as a baby's smile". Eline sacrifices a knight to
open up the king and deliver a deadly discovered check! } { [%cal Rf6e8,Rf6g8] } 27... gxf6 { There is no
particular choice - the knight has to be accepted. } (27... Kh8 28. Nxf7#) (27... Kf8 28. Ngh7+ Ke7 29. Rxg7 { are quite hopeless. }) 28. Ne4+ Ng6 29. exf6 { A very impressive quiet move. Eline
correctly calculates/judges that this strong - relatively slow - recapture is
the best way to go, as now the threats of Qh6 and Rxg6 are simply deadly. } { [%csl Gf6][%cal Ge3h6,Rg3g6] } 29... Bf8 { What else? } (29... a4 30. Qh6 { It may seem as if Black has Bf8 to response to
Qh6, but after } 30... Bf8 31. Rxg6+ { Black loses on the spot. } 31... fxg6 32. Qxg6+ Kh8 33. f7+ Bg7 (33... e5 34. Qg8#) 34. Qxg7#) 30. Rxg6+ { A very nice tactical finish! } 30... fxg6 31. f7+ { Opening up the bishop on d4.
Three pieces coordinate nicely and deliver checkmate on the dark-squares. } { [%csl Gd4,Ge3,Ge4][%cal Gd4h8,Ge3h6] } 31... Kxf7 32. Ng5+ Kg8 (32... Ke7 { is no better: } 33. Qxe6+ Kd8 34. Bb6+ Rc7 35. Nf7#) 33. Qe5 { And here Black resigned as the mate can be delayed, but
not avoided. Brutal attack by Eline! } { [%cal Gd4h8] } 1-0


[Event "37th European Chess Club Cup (Women)"]
[Site "Mayrhofen AUT"]
