[FEN "6k1/7p/1P1p2p1/3P1p2/B2Qnb2/8/6PP/1q4BK w - - 0 45"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Let's take a look at another game from the European Chess Club Cup for
Women held in October 2022. In this game, Eline faced a 2260-rated player from Ukraine and on move 45, a tense and sharp position has arisen where White has a strong passed pawn, but where the king on h1 is in some danger if White is not careful. Here Eline demonstrated her ability to calculate by finding a very nice, study-like way to win. Can you find it? }
45. Bc2 { Absolutely fantastic move, diverting the queen on b1 from the
ideal post on b1. } { [%csl Gb6][%cal Rc2b1,Gb1c2] } (45. Bc6 { White needed to be careful as Black actually had
the threat of diverting the queen from the g1-a7 diagonal: } 45... Be5 46. Qe3 f4 { And now the queen has to move and allow the deadly Bd4. } 47. Qe2 Bd4 { [%cal Rd4g1,Rb1g1] }) 45... Qxc2 { Basically forced! } (45... Qc1 { Moving the queen
along the 1st rank and trying to maintain the pin loses the sight of the
b-pawn and allows the simple } 46. b7 { [%cal Gb7b8] }) (45... Qb5 { Moving the
queen along the b-file allows White to simply exchange the knight } 46. Bxe4 fxe4 47. Qxe4 { And this endgame is completely winning for White - the b-pawn
is too strong, while Black also has a weak king. }) 46. b7 Qb1 47. Qa7 { An extremely pretty "quiet" move, simply threatening to queen the pawn. } { [%cal Gb7b8] } 47... Nf2+ { The only way to prolong the game, but not a sufficient one. } 48. Qxf2 { If the bishop wasn't on f4, this would have worked, but
as it is, Black has to lose a piece. } { [%csl Rf4][%cal Rf2f4] } 48... Qxb7 (48... Be5 49. Qa7 { And the pawn queens all the same. } { [%cal Gb7b8] }) 49. Qxf4 { And White had an extra piece,
which Eline converted into a full point! } 1-0


[Event "Tata Steel Challengers"]
[Site "Wijk aan Zee NED"]
[Date "2023.01.15"]
[Round "2"]
[White "Eline Roebers"]
[Black "L'Ami, E."]
[Result "1-0"]
[WhiteElo "2361"]
[BlackElo "2627"]
[Annotator "USER"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Eline Roebers Top 5 Games - Meet The Bulldog #1"]
[ChapterName "Eline Roebers - L'Ami, E."]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/GGJ4wYWp/DwchcHOv"]
[FEN "r1b2r1k/4n2p/3p1P2/1p1Pn1pq/p1pBPQ2/P1P1R3/1PB4N/R5K1 w - - 0 35"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Last but not the least, in January 2023 Eline participated in the biggest tournament of her career - Tata Steel Challengers 2023. Despite being the
lowest-rated player by a wide margin (hundreds of rating points), at the very
beginning of the tournament, in round 2, she managed to stun the chess world
by beating the strong and experienced Dutch Grandmaster and reigning Dutch
Champion, Erwin L'Ami, in a fantastic attacking display.
We join the game on move 35. L'Ami has just pushed his g-pawn forward, hoping to jump in with the knight to g6 and then to f4 or h4. This was met with a powerful refutation.
Can you find the move Eline played in the game? }
35. Bxe5!! { Boom! This is not only pretty, but also very necessary as White can't
afford to lose time by a mere trifle such as retreating the queen. } { [%cal Rf6e7] } (35. Qg3 N7g6 { And suddenly the position
is completely unclear! The knights are very well placed and Black has good
control over the f4 and h4 squares. The bishop on c2 is dormant and it is
pretty much anybody's game. } { [%csl Rc2,Ge5,Gf4,Gg6,Gh4][%cal Gg5f4,Gg5h4] }) 35... gxf4 36. fxe7+ { This is the point of the
queen's sacrifice. Even though seemingly everything in White's position is
hanging - the pawn on e7 is a hero that threatens to queen on the next move,
forcing Black's reply. } 36... Kg8 (36... Rf6 37. Bxf6+ Kg8 38. Rf3 { Doesn't really
help. }) 37. exf8=Q+ Kxf8 38. Bxd6+ { This is also a check, unfortunately for
Black. } 38... Ke8 39. Bxf4 { And White has two minor pieces, rook and a pawn for the
queen + a very dangerous pawn duo on d5 and e6, and Eline went on to convert
the advantage very easily. A nice piece of calculation and a great end to a
great game - I definitely suggest you to check it in its entirety (just like
all the other games presented in this study - and many other games by Eline). } 1-0


[Event "Two Paradoxical and Beautiful Chess Studies: A & K. Sarychev, 1928."]
[Date "2022.11.30"]
[White "Video #2"]
[Black "A & K. Sarychev, 1928."]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "USER"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Two Paradoxical and Beautiful Chess Studies"]
[ChapterName "A & K. Sarychev, 1928."]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/6lYqChDc/NxtApkqT"]
[FEN "8/1pPK3b/8/8/8/5k2/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The following study, composed in 1928. by A & K. Sarychev - two Russian
composer about whom I was not able to find that much info - is featured in
Dvoretsky's Endgame Manual in the chapter on the pawn endgames. It is a very
instructive and fascinating study featuring a version of the paradoxical idea
that is familiar from the famous Reti study.  How should White play here to
save the game? }
1. Kc8!! { This paradoxical and
counterintuitive move is the amazing solution to the study - and the only way
to draw the game. It looks absolutely crazy to put the king in front of the
pawn, block the advance of the c7 pawn and force the pawn from b7 to advance.
But the point of this move is to force the pawn away from b7 in order to
prevent the bishop from defending it from the c8 square. } { [%csl Rb7][%cal Rc8b7] } (1. Kd6 { In order to
understand the point of provoking the advance of the b7 pawn, let's take a
look at what happens if White tries to deal with the b-pawn/create the threat
of c8 at once! } 1... Bf5 2. Kc5 Ke4 3. Kb6 Bc8 4. Ka7 b5) (1. Ke6 { Is even worse as
Black has } 1... Ke4 { With the threat of Bf5, so now after } { [%cal Gh7f5] } 2. Kd6 (2. c8=Q Bf5+ 3. Kd6 Bxc8) 2... Bf5 { Black even has an extra tempo (king on e4
instead of f3) compared to the previous variation. }) (1. c8=Q { Queening
immediately loses at once to } 1... Bf5+ 2. Kc7 Bxc8 { And the
pawn is protected and White can't capture the bishop and deal with the pawn
due to } { [%csl Gb7][%cal Gc8b7] } 3. Kxc8 b5 { When the pawn promotes. Otherwise, the
endgame is trivially won. } { [%cal Gb5b1] }) 1... b5 { Of course, Black advances the pawn as far
as possible. } (1... b6 { Makes no sense as after } 2. Kb7 { White draws immediately by attacking the b6 pawn and threatening c8Q. } { [%cal Rb7b6,Gc7c8] } 2... Bf5 3. Kxb6) 2. Kd7 { Now the king returns. All this might look completely pointless,
but there is a method to all the madness! } 2... b4 (2... Bf5+ 3. Kd6 b4 4. Ke5 { Transposes to the game. }) 3. Kd6 { Creating the threat of c8Q. } { [%cal Gc7c8] } 3... Bf5 { Dealing with the threat. } { [%cal Gf5c8] } 4. Ke5 { The point! White attacks the bishop and gains a tempo to catch the pawn on b4. } { [%csl Rf5][%cal Ge5d4,Re5f5] } 4... Bc8 5. Kd4 { And now we see the point of
White's entire play. Now that the b-pawn has been advanced, the bishop is
unable to keep the control of the c8 square and keep defending the pawn. At
the right moment, White will just give up the c7 pawn and capture the b-pawn
no matter what Black does, e.g. } { [%csl Rb4,Rc8][%cal Gd4c4,Gd4b4] } 5... Be6 (5... b3 6. Kc3 Be6 7. c8=Q) 6. c8=Q Bxc8 7. Kc4 *


[Event "Two Paradoxical and Beautiful Chess Studies: R.Reti, 1921"]
[Date "2017.07.26"]
[White "Video #2 - Part 2"]
[Black "Reti Study famous"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "USER"]
[Variant "From Position"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Two Paradoxical and Beautiful Chess Studies"]
[ChapterName "R.Reti, 1921"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/6lYqChDc/8IjaS0GB"]
[FEN "7K/8/k1P5/7p/8/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Even though the idea seen in the previous study is executed brilliantly, it
was not exactly new. The method of catching the seemingly un-catchable
passed-pawn with the king far-far behind it was made famous by the celebrated
study composed by Richard Reti back in 1921 (7 years before Sarychev brothers
composed their beauty). --- In the diagram position, we can see that Black has
a passed pawn on h5 and that White king is very far away on h8. At first
glance, it seems as if the win for Black is trivial, but White actually has a
way to save the game in a very paradoxical, counterintuitive and brilliant way
- due to the existence of the pawn on c6. }
1. Kg7! { The first step. The king doesn't go directly toward the h-pawn, but
takes a diagonal route, so that it also retains the option of moving toward
the c6 pawn, if the opportunity appears. } { [%cal Gg7f6,Gf6e5,Re5f4] } 1... h4 { Of course, what else should
Black do rather than push the pawn? } 2. Kf6 { Continuing
down the same diagonal route. } { [%cal Gh8g7,Gg7f6] } 2... Kb6! { The most
venomous attempt, trying to win the c6 pawn. Now again White is in a seemingly
desperate position - but now the beautiful point of the study is revealed! } { [%csl Rc6][%cal Rb6c6] } (2... h3 { Advancing the h-pawn seems more logical, but here White is in time to
support the c6 pawn. } 3. Ke6 h2 4. c7 { Threatening to
promote. } { [%csl Gc8][%cal Gc7c8] } 4... Kb7 5. Kd7 { The point. Now simultaneous
promotion is inevitable. } { [%csl Gd7][%cal Gc7c8] } 5... h1=Q 6. c8=Q+ { And this endgame is a dead draw. }) 3. Ke5!! { Once again continuing down the diagonal route. Now
White threatens to play Kf4 and catch the pawn, as well as Kd6, supporting the
c6 pawn. Black is unable to deal with both threats. } { [%cal Ge5d6,Ge5f4] } 3... h3 { What else? } (3... Kxc6 4. Kf4 { And the king catches the h4 pawn. } { [%csl Gf4][%cal Gf4g4,Gg4h4] }) 4. Kd6 { Now the c-pawn will also advance! } { [%cal Gc6c7,Gc7c8] } 4... h2 5. c7 Kb7 { This
transposes to the same position mentioned in the note to Black's 2nd move. } (5... h1=Q 6. c8=Q { Is also a draw. }) 6. Kd7 h1=Q 7. c8=Q+ { With a familiar
drawn endgame. Absolutely fantastic! } *


