[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/chessentialsBLOG"]

{ Vjeko: The following game was submitted to me by the user mrt4b11, rated around 700 on Chesscom at the time when this game was played. It was a rapid game where each side had 30 minutes for the move, without any increment. }
1. Nc3 { Vjeko: I wouldn't necessarily recommend beginners NOT to play one of the two main openings (1.e4 or 1.d4) - simply because playing in accordance with the general principles (control the center) at the beginning of your journey follows a very streamlined and logical way of learning (from general to more specific). Although it has to be said that the objective value of the opening on that level isn't really the determining factor of the outcome of the game. } 1... d5 2. e3 e5 3. Nf3 { Vjeko: White is developing pieces which is sensible, but they are not placing any pawns into the center, which makes it easy for the opponent to control the center. it is possible to play chess like this, but it requires a good understanding of pawn breaks, dynamics, maneuvering and tactics/calculation - which is why it probably isn't to be recommended to lower rated players - certain degree of mastery is required to handle these positions more successfully. } 3... Nc6 4. d4 exd4?! { Vjeko: I am not 100% sure whether this mistake is the one that is most relevant at this level, but I do want to point out that this habit of "Opponent offers an exchange - I automatically accept it" , of exchanging without thinking, is one that plagues a lot of players at the lower levels. In this particular instance - Black misses the opportunity to gain space and kick the knight on f3 away. } (4... e4 { Vjeko: Here, for example, taking the space and advancing the pawn to e4, attacking the knight on f3 with a gain of tempo, is a very principled way of playing the position. It would have lead to a position where Black has total control of the center, which is generally in their favour (as controlling the center should be one of the main goals of the opening). }) 5. exd4 { Vjeko: Notice now how both sides have an equal share in the center as the pawns are on d4 and d5. } { [%csl Rd5,Yd4] } 5... Bf5?! { Vjeko: This is also not the best opening move. It is a bit tricky to explain why as it does develop the piece (which is a good principle to follow), but in chess, there is often some difference in priority when it comes to the development of your pieces (as another principles states - develop your knights before the bishops). In this particular instance, it is a bit early to decide on the position of the bishop on c8 - mainly because White has ideas of exchanging the bishop with Bd3 or playing Bb5 and pinning the knight on c6 - as happened in the game. } (5... Nf6 { Developing the knight is, in principle, more sensible - unless there is a very concrete reason why a bishop's development should be prefered. }) 6. Bb5 { Vjeko: This pin on the knight on c6 is indeed quite annoying. On one hand, we are taught that bishops shouldn't be exchanged for knights for no reason - but on the other hand, here White has a clear idea in mind - double the opponent's pawns - which justifies this move. } { [%csl Yc6][%cal Rb5e8] } 6... Bd6? { Vjeko: But this is the first really big mistake - a tactical blunder that hangs the d5 pawn. } 7. Qe2+? { Vjeko: And White returns the favour, missing that the d5 is hanging. The worst thing about this move is that it was played after only 2 seconds of thought (instantly) - and playing fastly, especially at this level, is the biggest mistake of them all. } (7. Nxd5 { Vjeko: The pawn on d5 was undefended and could have been taken. It has to be mentioned that White has to see one move further and check the possibility of } 7... Bb4+ { Vjeko: This creates the threat of a discovered attack on the knight - but it transpires that the knight is attacking the bishop on b4 and can simply take it. } { [%cal Rd8d5] } 8. Nxb4 { Vjeko: And now the knight can't be recaptured as the knight on c6 is pinned. It is possible to miss these things, but it is a pity if this capture isn't even considered. And I suspect it wasn't given that both players were playing extremely quickly at this point - White had 29:28 on the clock, while Black had 29:35 (out of 30 minutes). } { [%cal Rb5e8] }) 7... Be7 { Vjeko: This can also be regarded as a mistake. There is a principle that states you shouldn't move the same piece twice in the opening - yet Black does that here immediately after moving the bishop to e7 first. Although this is understandable to a certain extent as the d5 pawn is at least defended now. } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gd8d5] } 8. Bf4?! { Vjeko: This is also nominally a mistake - but a good type of mistake, as White continues developing and bringing pieces into the game. } (8. Ne5 { Vjeko: Objectively speaking, it was better to jump with the knight to e5 and attack the knight on c6. General principles (develop your pieces) can be broken if there is a concrete reasoning for it (attack the knight on c6), although judging when to do so is above the level of a 700 rated player (and not only 700 rated players), so I wouldn't necessarily lose my head over this one. } { [%cal Re5c6,Rb5c6] }) 8... Nf6 9. Bxc6+ { Vjeko: A good move. As mentioned earlier, giving up the bishops for nothing is usually not the best idea, but here it does double the c-pawns and ruins Black's pawn structure, so it can be justified. } 9... bxc6 10. h3? { Vjeko: But this move can definitely be classified as a very typical mistake. Instead of continuing the development (say by castling the king), White makes a random pawn move on the edge of the board with no clear purpose or point. The idea might have been to play g4 and attack the king, but such aggressive intentions in almost all sorts of positions are also very typical of this level - you can't just go for an attack unless you have a big positional domination or more pieces close to the enemy king (neither of which is the case here).
---- As a general rule of thumb - unless you have a very good reason why you would want to play such a move, it is better to avoid it and do something more natural. } (10. O-O { Vjeko: Of course, castling here is much better - White always can play the move h3 later. In general - if you have a choice between a move you know you want to make and a move you are not sure whether you want to make, it is almost always better to choose the former. }) 10... c5? { Vjeko: This is also a very typical mistake at this level - premature aggression and trying to initiate some active play before castling. Even on general principles, this is wrong - but here it also blunders a pawn. } (10... O-O { Vjeko: Of course - Black should castle first and then think later. As a general recommendation to all the players up to, say, 1000 (or even 1500 level) - try to make it a rule/goal to castle in every game by move 10-15. }) 11. Rd1? { Vjeko: This move is also a mistake and probably a consequence of a defensive mindset. White tries to defend the d4 pawn with the rook, but it was definitely not required. Not only because the knight on f3 was already defending the pawn - but also because the pawn could have been taken. } (11. dxc5 { Vjeko: Due to the pin on the e-file, Black can't immediately recapture the pawn on c5 so this move should have definitely be considered. Once again - the players were playing too fast - White had 28:56 left on the clock after 11.Rd1 was played. } { [%cal Re2e8] }) 11... O-O 12. O-O Rb8 { Vjeko: A good move. Rooks do belong to open files and here Black attacks the pawn on b2. } { [%cal Rb8b2] } 13. Nh4 { Vjeko: Also not a bad move. White displays aggressive intentions, but now that the development has been completed, this is justified. It has to be mentioned that, apart from attacking the bishop, this move also prepares to potentially get the knight to f5 in the future. These kinds of moves that also have some higher purpose apart from the fact that they "attack something and hope the opponent doesn't see it" usually moves we should be looking for in our games (at all levels). } { [%csl Rf5][%cal Rh4f5] } 13... Ne4? { Vjeko: And there immediately comes a very typical mistake for this level. Black focuses on own ideas (attacking the knight on h4), but fails to ask two questions:
A) What is the purpose of my opponent's last move (what do they want to do)?
B) Are there any pieces in my position that are not 100% defended?
This type of problem can be solved by practicing more tactics and training your patterns - but also to being more vigilant and concentrated during a chess game. Once again - Black was playing very, very fast up to this point - and there is a very positive correlation between not using your time and blundering. } { [%cal Re7h4] } 14. Nxf5 { Vjeko: Now White is a piece up for nothing and this type of material advantage is a decisive factor when it comes to the outcome of the chess game. From the objective standpoint, this position can be regarded as "winning for White" purely because they have a clear extra knight. } 14... Nxc3 15. bxc3 Re8 16. Qg4 { Vjeko: Not a bad move - creating the threat of a mate in 1. } { [%cal Rg4g7] } (16. Nxe7+ { Vjeko: From the practical/simplicity viewpoint, it is also very natural to capture the bishop on e7. Remember - when you have the material advantage, it is to your advantage to exchange pieces, as it makes your task much simpler. Seasoned chess readers might remember the immortal chess phrase KISS - Keep It Simple Stupid. --- On the other hand, one of the very common mistakes at higher echalons is precisely aiming to simplify at all costs when ahead in material, instead of continuing to play aggressively and create threats. But anyway, it is not very relevant for this game, so pardon me for this digression. }) 16... cxd4? { Vjeko: Another very big mistake, totally ignoring White's last move and the idea behind it. Similar causes for error as on move 13 (overfocusing on your ideas and not paying attention to what your opponent is doing + still playing way too quickly). } 17. Bh6? { Vjeko: This is also a somewhat surprising mistake. White correctly recognizes that the g7 pawn should be the object of the attack - but fails to recognize it is currently not defended at all. } (17. Qxg7# { Vjeko: This would have ended the game immediately. When you are attacking a certain weakness, make sure to always count the number of attackers and defenders! }) 17... g6 18. Nxd4 f5 { Vjeko: Another typical move at this level - let me just create a 1-move threat without considering whether it works or whether there is any point to it. Here, White can actually take this pawn due to the pin - but even if they don't - it is not recommendable to move the pawns in front of your own king. } 19. Qe2 (19. Nxf5 { Vjeko: It was actually possible to take the pawn as the g6 pawn is pinned. There is a saying that the pin is one of the most commonly overlooked tactics at all levels, so I would definitely recommend everyone up to, say, 1000(1500) level to drill their pins regularly. } { [%cal Rg4g8] }) 19... Bc5 20. Ne6 { Vjeko: But this is not the best move. White creates a one-move threat against the queen and the bishop on c5, but once again overlooks the pin due to which the knight will be unable to move. In general - when you are material up, you don't want to complicate things. } { [%csl Re6][%cal Re8e2] } (20. Qd3 { Vjeko: Simply moving the queen here, for example, would be quite good and would have kept all the advantage (an extra piece). }) 20... Qe7?! { Vjeko: This move is sensible - pinning the knight to the queen. But maybe this is not the most accurate implementation of this idea. } { [%cal Re7e2] } (20... Qd6 { Vjeko: It was better to keep the d5 pawn defended and keep the knight on e6 pinned, but it is probably too harsh to call this move a mistake. } { [%cal Re8e2] }) 21. Rxd5 { Vjeko: This is strictly also a mistake, but I will refrain from commenting on it as this is only due to a very specific tactic that is way above the level of players involved in this game. } 21... Qxe6 22. Re5?? { Vjeko: But this mistake does need to be emphasized. Instead of simplifying the position and taking the extra piece, White simply blunders a full rook. My main problem with this move is not the move itself, but that it was once again played way too quickly - White only spent 15 seconds on it and at this moment they had 27:15 left on the clock (out of the starting 30 minutes). } (22. Qxe6+ { Vjeko: As mentioned earlier, when you are material up, you should be more than happy to exchange material - especially queens. Here, this would have won easily as the bishop on c5 is hanging. } 22... Rxe6 23. Rxc5 { Vjeko: And White remains a piece and a pawn up which is a decisive material advantage. If you are unable to see these things, it means your tactics, puzzles and pattern recognition needs some practice (E.g. Lichess has studies devoted to hanging pieces here: https://lichess.org/training/hangingPiece). But I also feel the first and foremost reason for such blunders is not using enough time to think and playing too fast. }) 22... Qxe5 23. Qc4+ Kh8 { Now suddenly Black is a full rook up, which is a decisive advantage in the favour of the second player. } 24. Bf4 Qf6? { Vjeko: This is a mistake as well, as it blunders the bishop, but it has to be said Black spend more than 2 minutes on it, which means they need some practice when it comes to recognizing which pieces are unprotected. } { [%csl Rc5] } 25. Qxc5 { Vjeko: Now we have a strange position where the material imbalance is not as clear - Black has a rook (5 points) vs bishop and a pawn (4 points), which means that Black is only slightly better. But many things can happen in a position like this. If you want to practice - you can write down which pieces are now undefended in Black's position and suggest a way to defend them. } 25... Rbd8?! { Vjeko: The pawns on c7 and a7 are undefended and Black should probably do something to defend them. } { [%csl Rc7,Ra7] } (25... Qb6 { Vjeko: Bringing the queen, for example, is one possibility that defends both the weaknesses. } { [%csl Rc7,Ra7] }) 26. g3 (26. Qxc7 { Vjeko: White could have tried taking some pawns. Remember also: When you are material down, you want to be exchanging some pawns as it makes it more difficult for the opponent to promote the queen in many endgames. Although this is maybe something more relevant at higher levels. }) 26... c6 27. Bc7 Rd5 28. Qxa7 Rd7 29. a4? { Vjeko: But this is a mistake, overlooking the pin once again - this time a horizontal one on the 7th rank. } (29. Qa5 { Vjeko: White had to move the queen away as the bishop on c7 can also retreat on the next move. }) 29... Qf8? { Vjeko: But this is a tactical blunder that leaves the rook on d7 undefended. } (29... Qf7 { Vjeko: Going to f7 was winning, as the bishop on c7 is now pinned and can't move, so White loses a piece. } { [%csl Rc7][%cal Rf7a7] } 30. Be5+ (30. Bb6 Rxa7) 30... Rxe5) 30. f4? { Vjeko: Missing a tactical shot based on the discovered attack. } (30. Be5+ { Vjeko: This discovered check would have turned the tide into White's favour as now the rook on d7 is undefended. I would suggest practicing some discovered attacks: https://lichess.org/training/discoveredAttack } { [%cal Re5h8,Ra7d7] } 30... Rxe5 31. Qxd7 { Vjeko: And now White has two extra pawns, which is a decisive material advantage in their favour. It is beyond the scope of this study to explain how to go about converting that advantage (as it is more complicated than converting with an extra piece), but you can take it as a fact for now. }) 30... Ree7? { Vjeko: Again missing the tactical opportunity, although this one was more difficult to see. } (30... Qf7 { Vjeko: Once again worked as after } 31. Be5+ Rxe5 { The queen on a7 is attacked and if } { [%csl Ra7] } 32. Qb8+ Re8 { Black wins. I do want to emphasize that this type of tactic - in contrast to the tactics mentioned earlier - is what I would consider to be above this level (as it featured quite a few intermediate moves). }) 31. Be5+ Rxe5? { Vjeko: Remember - you don't always need to capture the pieces. } { [%cal Ra7d7] } (31... Kg8 { Vjeko: Black could have moved the king and kept the extra exchange. }) 32. Qxd7 { Vjeko: A very good, intermediate move. White now wins back the exchange (rook for a bishop) and again reaches the position with a two extra pawns - similar to the one we examined before. } 32... Qc5+ 33. Rf2?! { Vjeko: This is a position very difficult to handle for a 700 rated player, in my opinion, but according to the principle mentioned earlier - always look for opportunities to exchange pieces when you are ahead in material - especially queens. Still, if I were White's coach, I wouldn't be as focused on the final phase of this game as much as on some of the earlier mistakes. } (33. Qd4 { Vjeko: This move would have blocked the check and basically forced the exchange of the queens, as the rook on e5 is also under the attack. If the queens are exchanged, the endgame after } 33... Qxd4+ 34. cxd4 { Vjeko: should be easilly won for White as two pawns in an endgame are a decisive material advantage. }) 33... Re1+ 34. Kg2 h5 35. Qd8+ (35. Qd4+ { Vjeko: Queen exchange!! } { [%cal Rd4h8,Rd4c5] }) 35... Kh7 36. Rd2?? { Vjeko: But this is a bad - but also very logical - blunder. White wants to play Rd7 and checkmate the enemy king, but in return, it weakens his own king and allows a deadly check on g1. 45 seconds were spent on this move which is an indication that White tried to figure out what to do in this position and couldn't understand the dangers present to the king. Perhaps trying to focus on your opponent's ideas (potential checks) can help, although I feel that appreciating the king safety is something that comes with experience and increase of the general chess strength. } 36... Qg1+ { [%csl Rg1] } 37. Kf3 Qf1+?? { Vjeko: Now instead, it is Black's turn to miss mate in one, even though they did spend 30 seconds and gave a check (in accordance with the checks,captures,threats) principle. } (37... Re3# { Vjeko: This check would have led to a mate. I guess this reveals Black's lack of practice of some mating patterns, although to be fair, this one is not the most common one, so I think it is understandable that the second player missed this during the game. }) 38. Rf2 { Vjeko: And now comes the culminating moment of the game. } 38... Re2?? { Vjeko: The final mistake, once again showing not-so-full mastery of the pin mechanism. Black probably realized that White can't take the rook on e2 due to the pin - but they forgot that the rook can now capture the queen on f1. This is an understandable and instructive error that reveals the value of playing these kinds of training games. If I were Black's coach, I would probably tell them to focus on tactical patterns - and in particular pin, as they missed several instances of utilizing it throughout the game. https://lichess.org/training/pin } 39. Rxf1 { I feel this is a very instructive game featuring many typical mistakes for this level. If I had to group them and sort them in some sort of hierarchy, I would roughly divide them into two tiers, as follows:
Tier 1: Mistakes very typical and relevant at this level:
A) Playing way too quickly throughout the game and not spending the time to think (typical of not only this level, but especially of this level)
B) Not counting attackers/defenders correctly, not capturing hanging pieces, or leaving the pieces hanging. This is partly solved by playing more and getting better overall, but also by practicing this particular aspect - and spending more time when playing the moves.
C) Missing basic tactical opportunities throughout the game. Mates in one, discovered attacks, pins, and so on. This is why the importance of tactics is emphasized for lower-rated players and I would definitely suggest both of these players practice their tactics daily - and do so by focusing on one tactical pattern at a time (e.g. one day/week I only do pins, the other day/week I only do discovered attacks, etc.).
I would consider these three areas the most urgent for the players around 700 level (especially on the basis of this game). Some other typical mistakes that may be useful at this level (and higher levels), but that are maybe not the most urgent are:
A) Violating general principles (Not occupying the center in the opening, not prioritizing castling, moving the bishops before the knights, etc.).
B) Not keeping things as simple as possible when ahead in material.
C) Making random moves without a clear idea/purpose (10.h3?!).
D) Playing too defensively at times (11.Rd1?) or too aggressively at times (10...c5). } 1-0


[Event "World-ch01 Steinitz-Zukertort +10-5=5"]
[Site "USA"]
[Date "1886.01.11"]
[Round "1"]
[White "Zukertort, Johannes Hermann"]
[Black "Steinitz, William"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Annotator "Vjekoslav Nemec"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "D10"]
[Opening "Slav Defense"]
[StudyName "Steinitz - Zukertort 1886 World Chess Championship"]
[ChapterName "Game #1"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/fB11Bc7Q/eFfsHnWb"]

1. d4 { A funny piece of chess trivia - the first ever World Chess Championship
game featured the advance of the queen's pawn. I think this move was already a
bit surprising in the 19st century as in the era of romantic and combative
chess it was customary to open with the king's pawn. Zukertort himself was a
combative genius so you would expect him to be 1.e4 player - but he actually
became famous for playing several less-confrontational setups, such as 1.Nf3
or what would later become known as Colle-Zukertort opening (although he did
play 1.e4 on a semi-regular basis, as well). } 1... d5 2. c4 c6 { It is very
interesting to analyze these old games as I personally wasn't fully aware that
any Slav setups were played as early as 19th century - yet Steinitz embarks on
one here. } 3. e3 { As mentioned to the note to White's first move - Zukertort
was very fond of playing slow, unpretentious setups and often played the move
e3 with the dark-squared bishop on c1. There is no denying that this is not
the most ambitious way of playing in the opening - but it is the one where you
are getting a game and then just play chess. } 3... Bf5 { This non-standard move
violates one of the basic principles (knights before bishops), but it was
played by some very strong grandmasters - including Magnus Carlsen. You would
think this weakens the b7 pawn, but it transpires it is not so easy for White
to exploit it. } 4. Nc3 { Continuing to develop normally can't be particularly
wrong. } (4. cxd5 cxd5 { and then bringing the queen to b3, Black can calmly defend
everything with the natural queen move } 5. Qb3 Qd7 { [%cal Gd7d5,Gd7b7] }) (4. Qb3 Qc7 { eyeing the c1 bishop and defending the b7 pawn. The d5 pawn is immune as after } { [%cal Rc7c1] } 5. cxd5 cxd5 { The c-file is open and the bishop on c1
is hanging, so White doesn't have time to take the pawn on d5. An unusual
pattern that arises due to the absence of the knight on c3. } { [%csl Gb1][%cal Rc7c1] }) 4... e6 5. Nf3 Nd7 { Both sides make natural developing moves and bring the pieces into play. } 6. a3?! { But this move is probably not
necessary, as White doesn't need to fear any Bb4 ideas. Zukertort was probably
already contemplating the idea of playing c5 next and then profiting from the
fact that b4 can be played, but it transpires that this whole concept is not
particularly good for White. } { [%cal Ra3b4,Gc4c5,Gb2b4,Gc1b2] } (6. Bd3 { It is better to get
the bishop out, maybe offer the exchange for the opponent's active bishop and
prepare castling short. } { [%cal Ge1g1,Rd3f5] }) 6... Bd6 { Maybe also it is better to wait with this
move and first develop the knight as it is not 100% clear whether the bishop
belongs to d6 or e7. } (6... Ngf6 { Seems more logical. But as usual when
talking about these games by old masters - we really shouldn't forget the
context and time and be overly critical when going over them armed with
databases and engines - especially in the opening stage. }) 7. c5 { But this idea is just plain wrong. White removes the tension in the center and
intends to gain space on the queenside, but it transpires that this justifies
the positioning of the bishop on d6 and allows Black to create counterplay
with the help of the thematic e5 break. } { [%cal Rc5d6] } (7. Bd3 { Developing the bishop was
probably once again better. }) 7... Bc7 8. b4 { Colle's idea - reinforcing the queenside, preparing to develop the bishop to
b2 and taking it from there. But, it transpires that this is not particularly
good for White structurally. Black has a clear idea to play e5 while it is not
100% clear what White's plan is. } { [%csl Ga3,Gb4,Gc5][%cal Gc1b2] } 8... e5 { A thematic
break for this type of structure - creating ideas of playing e4 and gaining
space or taking on d4 and then pressuring the weak d4 pawn. It was also
possible to finish the development first and then strike with e5 as it won't
run away anytime soon. } { [%csl Rd4][%cal Re5d4,Ge5e4] } 9. Be2? { Not a good move as it allows Black to gain
even more space in the center and create dangerous play on the kingside. } (9. dxe5 { Taking the pawn and freeing the d4 square for the knight was preferable.
Say after } 9... Nxe5 10. Nd4 { The fact that the bishop is on f5 and that Black
hurried somewhat with the e5 pawn break is telling. This is a clear example of
how sometimes being patient with the execution of your plans in chess is
better than executing them at once. }) 9... Ngf6 { Black returns the favour and
continues developing, missing the opportunity to advance the pawn further down
the board. } (9... e4 { Would secure a large advantage in the center and on the
kingside. Say after } 10. Nd2 { It is very dangerous for White to ever castle
short and Black can already create a lot of pressure in numerous ways, say by
moving the queen with } 10... Qg5 { A typical situation for this kind of
structure - White has very little active play (even if they execute the b5
pawn push, it will not achieve anything in a while), while Black has extremely
dangerous play on the kingside and central stability. Black is already,
therefore, clearly better. } { [%cal Rg5g2] }) 10. Bb2? { Once again allowing the chance to go
e4. } 10... e4! { Which Steinitz now indeed does! Better late than never. } 11. Nd2 h5 { A very strong move, well-ahead of the time I
would say. Steinitz immediately marches the pawn down the board, gaining some
more control over the g4 square and potentially opening up the path for the
rook via h6 to enter the game and pressure the kingside. } { [%csl Gh5][%cal Gh8h6,Gh6g6] } 12. h3 { Trying to control the g4 square and prevent the advance of the
h-pawn all the way to h3. } { [%csl Gg4][%cal Gh3g4] } (12. O-O { Note that castling here would be
suicidial - not only because Black has the immediate tactical shot at their
disposal - but also because White can never find safety for the king on the
kingside long-term. } 12... Bxh2+ { This sacrifice already works here. } 13. Kxh2 Ng4+ { The reason why h5 was played earlier. This standard Greek gift
sacrifice works here and I will not get into too many details. You can check
some of my other articles/videos to learn more about it elsewhere. } { [%csl Gg4] }) 12... Nf8 { A very strong idea, intending to maneuver the knight via
g6 to h4 and create further threats on the kingside. It is not the only way to
handle the position, but it is very strong. Black has time to maneuver as the
center is quite closed. } { [%cal Gf8g6,Gg6h4] } (12... Rh6 { Bringing the rook, with a
very similar idea of attacking the g2 pawn, was also very good. } { [%cal Gh6g6] }) 13. a4 { Trying to play b5 is White's only plan and source of counterplay
in this position - but as we will see - even once it is played, it is hard to
find a follow-up. } { [%cal Gb4b5] } 13... Ng6 { Continuing the journey to h4. } { [%cal Gg6h4] } 14. b5 Nh4 15. g3? { Underestimating the danger and allowing a very nice temporary
sacrifice of the piece. } (15. Bf1 { Defending the pawn with the bishop and
trying to say as flexible and solid on the kingside as possible, was arguably
the best defense - although one difficult to make even in 2022, let alone 1886
(when the defensive skills were significantly less developed). }) 15... Ng2+ { A very powerful move that must have shocked Zukertort!
Black aims to sacrifice a piece on the next move. } { [%cal Rg2e3,Rg2e1] } 16. Kf1 Nxe3+ 17. fxe3 Bxg3 { A fully correct piece sacrifice. Black obtains two
pawns for the piece, but more importantly - the king on f1 is exposed as the
pawn shield is removed. Furthermore, it is very important that White has lack
of space in the center and on the kingside, meaning that the pieces on the
queenside can't easily join the defense. } { [%csl Ra1,Rb2,Rc3,Rd2,Rf1] } 18. Kg2 Bc7?! { This natural move
seems to be one of the only two imprecisions made by Steinitz in this game.
The drawback of this move is that it allows the queen to come to f1 with the
gain of tempo and allow the king to escape via f2 and e1 under better
circumstances than in the game. } (18... h4 { Trying to
entrench the bishop on g3 is actually better as it prevents the king from
escaping. If now White tries to undermine the bishop with } { [%csl Gg3][%cal Gh4g3] } 19. Nf1 Bc7 { Now the queen is unable to go to f1, Black has various attacking ideas (Rh6,
Nh5, Qd7) and if the king tries to escape then } 20. Kf2 Qc8 21. Ke1 Bxh3 { Snatches the third pawn and retains a decisive advantage for White. }) 19. Qg1? { A losing mistake! The idea behind this move is to create the escape route
for the king to go to e1, but it transpires that the g1 square is not optimal
for the queen. } (19. Qf1 { Going to f1 was much
better as it would have arrived with a tempo on the bishop on f5, and forced
it to move due to very specific tactics. At the same time, Rh6-Rg6 wouldn't
have arrived with a gain of tempo. A very hard defensive idea to see. } { [%csl Rf5][%cal Gf1b5,Rf1f5] } 19... Qd7 { This seems logical, but it actually loses to } (19... Be6 { when after } 20. Kf2 { Black still has
the initiative, but White has a better version of events compared to the game
as the rook is still on h8. } { [%csl Rh8] }) 20. bxc6 bxc6 21. Nb5 { And there is no good reply, e.g. } { [%csl Rb5][%cal Ge2b5] } 21... Bb8 22. Nd6+ Bxd6 23. cxd6 { And now with the
dark-squared bishop gone (an important attacking piece) - White's king feels
much safer and White is actually the one who is winning. }) 19... Rh6 { Now Rg6 is a massive threat. } { [%cal Gh6g6] } 20. Kf1 (20. Kf2 { Going with the king to
f2 is not possible here as after } 20... Rg6 21. Qf1 Bg3+ { The bishop returns with vengeance and White is just losing. Note how
the pieces on the queenside are bystanders in all these variations. } { [%csl Rb2,Rc3,Rd2][%cal Rg3e1] }) 20... Rg6 21. Qf2 { [%cal Rf2f5] } 21... Qd7 { Now we have a very similar position
to the one we examined previously, but with the difference that the rook is on
g6. Also, the h3 pawn is hanging. } { [%cal Rd7h3] } 22. bxc6?! { It is debatable whether now
was the right moment to include this exchange - as only Black will be able to
use the b-file to include the a8 rook in the future. } 22... bxc6 { Now the a8 rook has gained access via the b-file. } { [%cal Ga8b8,Rb8b1] } 23. Rg1 { Giving up the
third pawn but trying to exchange some pieces. } (23. Nb5 Bxh3+ 24. Ke1 Bg3 { And White is totally lost. }) 23... Bxh3+ { Now Black gains the third pawn for
the piece, establishing approximate material equality. In the meantime, all
the pluses of the position (better placed pieces, more space to maneuver,
safer king) have been retained, which means that Black is already completely
winning and that he can play relatively slowly and improve the position -
mainly by pushing the kingside pawns. Which is exactly what Steinitz does. } 24. Ke1 Ng4 25. Bxg4 Bxg4 26. Ne2 Qe7 27. Nf4 Rh6 { Making way
for the g and f-pawns. } { [%cal Gg7g5,Gf7f5] } 28. Bc3 g5 { Kicking
White's only active piece away from a good square. Note that Black is not in
hurry - White's two pieces on the queenside (the bishop on c3 and the knight
on d2) are lacking good squares forever. } { [%csl Rc3,Rd2,Rf4][%cal Rg5f4] } 29. Ne2 { Now the knight
on e2 will also find it hard to find a useful square. } { [%csl Re2] } 29... Rf6 30. Qg2 Rf3 { In good position, it is easy to make nice tactical
moves. This move is not only flashy, but it actually attacks the e3 pawn. } { [%csl Re3,Rf3][%cal Rf3e3] } 31. Nf1 { Trying desperately to defend. } { [%csl Ge3][%cal Gf1e3] } (31. Nxf3 { Taking
the rook would be futile, as after } 31... exf3 { Black
actually obtains two pieces for the rook and increases the material balance in
his favour. } { [%csl Rg2][%cal Rf3e2,Rf3g2] }) 31... Rb8 { Seizing the b-file and emphasizing why it was a
mistake for White to open it earlier. White can't contest it with his pieces
huddled on the last rank. } 32. Kd2 f5 { Now comes the
f-pawn. Note how all White's pieces are paralyzed either by Black's pawns or
even by White's own pawns. The game is essentially over - White can barely
move. } { [%csl Gf5][%cal Gf5f4] } 33. a5 f4 34. Rh1 Qf7 { Another very good move,
intending to open the f-file and then play Rf2. There is nothing White can
really do about it. } { [%cal Rf7f2,Rf4e3] } 35. Re1 fxe3+ 36. Nxe3 Rf2 37. Qxf2 { Pure desperation in
a lost position. White could have resigned here. } (37. Qg1 Qf3 { Eventually wins the knight on e2, though, and is not an improvement. } { [%cal Rf2e2] }) 37... Qxf2 38. Nxg4 Bf4+ 39. Kc2 hxg4 { Black has material advantage, better placed
pieces and a safer king, so the outcome of the game is not in doubt. } 40. Bd2 e3 41. Bc1 Qg2 42. Kc3 Kd7 43. Rh7+ Ke6 44. Rh6+ Kf5 45. Bxe3 Bxe3 46. Rf1+ Bf4 { And here Zukertort finally decided to resign. A very convincing start to the
match by Steinitz, that demonstrated his superiority in handling strategical
positions and in understanding pawn structures and pawn play, in general. } 0-1


[Event "World-ch01 Steinitz-Zukertort +10-5=5"]
[Site "USA"]
[Date "1886.01.13"]
[Round "2"]
[White "Steinitz, William"]
[Black "Zukertort, Johannes Hermann"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Annotator "Vjekoslav Nemec"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C45"]
[Opening "Scotch Game: Schmidt Variation"]
[StudyName "Steinitz - Zukertort 1886 World Chess Championship"]
[ChapterName "Game #2"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/fB11Bc7Q/rQcWzl76"]

1. e4 { In contrast to Zukertort who was prone to experimenting, Steinitz was
primarily a 1.e4 player throughout his career. } 1... e5 { In contrast to his White
repertoire that was very modern and nuanced - with Black Zukertort was a very
classical player and played 1...e5 exclusively throughout his life. } 2. Nf3 { In this game, Steinitz doesn't go for the King's Gambit, even though that
opening was still going quite strong in those years. Steinitz himself played
it a lot in his career - although arguably more frequently in his youth,
before he started laying foundations for the more-modern school of chess
thought. } 2... Nc6 3. d4 { Even though the Scotch game was not as popular as, say,
the Evans' Gambit or the King's Gambit back in the day, it was still played
quite frequently back in the day. Steinitz himself faced it more than 20 times
as Black in his career, although he only employed it 5 times in his life. } 3... exd4 4. Nxd4 { Zukertort has faced this variation a grand total of 13 times in his
career (at least according to the database). Prior to the match, he faced it
against Mortimer in the London tournament in 1883. } 4... Nf6 (4... Bc5 { Was
Zukertort's choice in the afore-mentioned game against Mortimer, but here he
decides to play the other big mainline. }) 5. Nc3 { This move transposes to the
Four-Knights variation, which is considered to be relatively toothless and
harmless. This is the only instance of Steinitz ever having this position in
his tournament practice. } (5. Nxc6 { Taking on c6 is nowadays the main move
that leads to very sharp, uncompromising play. }) 5... Bb4 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Bd3 d5 { This is actually a very modern variation that is still existing to this
day. The general consensus is that it is very dry and that it is hard for
White to get an advantage, but it still appears quite frequently at all levels
as the play is very interesting and somewhat imbalanced. } 8. exd5 { The
traditional main line. } (8. Bd2 { In the engine era, this move, intending to
sacrifice the pawn on e4 for the two bishop advantage, has also appeared and
has been tested in some high-level games. }) 8... cxd5 9. O-O O-O { The starting
tabiya of this variation. } 10. Bg5 { This developing move, trying
to pressure the knight on f6, is the main move in this position. White is
currently threatening to capture on f6 and then on d5 and is not at all
worried by the possibility of Black taking on c3 and doubling the pawns - as
it is not worth giving up the bishop pair to ruin the pawn structure. } { [%cal Rg5d8] } 10... c6 { Reinforcing the pawn on d5. Having c6-d5 pawn duo in
the center is very characteristic of this variation. } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gc6d5] } 11. Ne2 { This standard
maneuver of the knight is typical of this variation, but usually it is played
after the queen has been moved in front of it. } (11. Qf3 { It is far more common to move the queen to f3 here, pressure the f6 knight and
then to try rerouting the knight via e2. } { [%cal Rf3f6,Rg5d8] }) 11... Bd6 { Retreating the bishop is
a very standard idea, but here it can be prone to exchanging via Bf4. Black
can maybe play more energetically now that Qf3 hasn't been played. } (11... h6 12. Bf4 Re8 13. c3 Bf8 { Usually this wouldn't have been so good as White
would have been able to play Re1 and create some pressure with Nd4 next, but
here this is not the case so Black has time to get in the timely c5 pawn
advance, say, after } 14. Ng3 c5 { It is not entirely clear how
big of an accomplishment this is, but it is a way to treat the position
differently and arguably - a bit more ambitiously. } { [%csl Gc5,Gd5] }) 12. Ng3? { But this move
is a bad mistake. Maybe Steinitz was hoping for some Nh5 ideas, but the knight
is completely misplaced here - and playing Ng3 is not the idea White has in
mind with the whole Ne2 maneuver. } (12. Qd2 { [%cal Gg5f4] }) (12. Bf4 { challenging the bishop immediately. In this
case, we would have reached a very typical position for this variation. }) 12... h6 { This is the problem. There is no pressure on the f6 knight without the
queen on f3, so Black can spend a tempo to chase the bishop away and start
grabbing the initiative. } 13. Bd2 Ng4 { Introducing all kinds of Qh4 and Nxf2 threats. } { [%csl Rg3][%cal Gd8h4,Rg4h2,Rg4f2,Rd6g3] } 14. Be2?! { Probably not the
best defensive move, but it was really difficult to decide on the alternative. } (14. h3 { Is seemingly suicidial due to } 14... Nxf2 15. Kxf2 Qh4 { But the stubborn
computer insists that White has some drawing chances after } 16. Qf3 f5 17. Kg1 Bxg3 18. Bf4 { As the bishop on c8 is severely restricted by the pawns. It is
telling that the engine thinks the best defense consists of giving up a pawn
instead of the bishop pair. }) 14... Qh4 { Of course! } { [%cal Rh4h2] } 15. Bxg4 { The only move, but this simply gives up the bishop pair in a fairly open
position - which gives Black a clear plus. } (15. h3 { Now loses on the spot due
to } 15... Nxf2 16. Rxf2 Qxg3) 15... Bxg4 16. Qc1 { This endgame should be extremely
favourable for Black due to the bishop pair, despite the fact that they
nominally have worse pawn structure (three pawn islands compared to two). The
knight on g3 should be severely restricted. However, now we will get the
opportunity to see how undeveloped the chess "technique" was back in the day
compared to today. Zukertort already goes wrong on the very next move. } 16... Be2?! { Not such a bad move per se, but the idea associated with it is
wrong. Zukertort reroutes the bishop to a6 while inviting the rook to e1 with
a game of tempo. As it turns out, the bishop will be far from optimally placed
on that square. } { [%csl Ra6] } (16... Bd7 { The idea of moving the bishop
is correct because Black wants to prevent the move Bf4, but it is much better
to keep the bishop on the h3-c8 diagonal. One justification can be seen if
White tries to play in the very same manner as in the game. } { [%cal Gh4f4,Gd6f4] } 17. Bc3 { Now this
runs into the advance of the d-pawn. } 17... d4 { Here White doesn't have the same Re4
resource as could happen in the game. } 18. Bd2 c5 { And Black's
situation has significantly improved. } { [%csl Gc5,Gd4] }) (16... Be6 { Taking the c4
square under some additional control, is also possible. } { [%cal Ge6c4] }) 17. Re1 Ba6 { Now the
problem for Black is that White can activate the dark-squared bishop and
create the idea of Be5, offering to exchange the dark-squared bishops. } 18. Bc3 { White wants to play Be5 on the next move and there is
actually very little Black can do about it. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gc3e5] } 18... f5 { But this is overly aggressive.
Black places another pawn on the light-square. The idea is to push f4 and kick
the knight from g3 - potentially even to go all the way to f3. But Black will
simply not have time for that. Any other, less aggressive move, would have
probably maintained the balance. } (18... d4 { doesn't work here due to } 19. Re4 { when the d4 pawn drops on the next move. } { [%cal Re4d4] }) 19. Re6 { First gaining a tempo by attacking the bishop. } { [%cal Re6b6] } 19... Rad8 20. Qd2 { Bringing the
queen into the play and not fearing the f4 pawn push. } (20. Be5 { Seeking to
exchange the bishops, was also very interesting. The point is that after } 20... Bxe5 21. Rxe5 f4 22. Nf5 { Actually loses the f4 pawn for Black. } { [%cal Rf5h4,Rc1f4] } 22... Qf6 23. Qxf4 { Perhaps Black has some saving chances after } 23... Bc8 24. g4 Bxf5 25. gxf5 { but it is clear a position like this is not what Zukertort had in mind
when he moved the f-pawn forward. }) 20... d4 { Relying on some "cheapos" to try
and limit the dark-squared bishop, but this exposes the d4 pawn and allows
White some additional options. Some other, semi-waiting move would have
definitely been better. } (20... f4 { This is just bad here due to Rg6. } 21. Rg6 Rf7 22. Bxg7 { White wins on the spot due to the Nf5 ideas. } { [%cal Gf7g7,Gg3f5] }) 21. Ba5 { White hits the rook on d8 and gains an
important tempo. } { [%csl Rd8][%cal Ra5d8] } (21. Qxd4 { Would be bad here, of course, due to the
discovered attack. } 21... Qxd4 22. Bxd4 Bxg3 { And Black wins a piece
and with it - the game. } { [%cal Rd8d4] }) 21... Rd7 22. Rxd6 { A very nice positional
pseudo-sacrifice, eliminating the opponent's dark-squared bishop and ending in
a position where White will have a knight against the bishop and where the
weakness of Black's pawns should be very relevant. } 22... Rxd6 23. Bb4 { Another move
made possible by the inclusion of moves Qd2 and d4. } 23... Qf6 24. Rd1 { A little bit imprecise. It turns out that the d4 pawn is sufficiently defended
and that it will be hard to win it - so probably it was better to deploy the
rook on the open file. } { [%cal Ga1e1] } (24. Re1 { Placing the rook on the open
file seems to be a stronger option, although the game remains very close to
being balanced. } { [%cal Re1e8] }) (24. Bxd6 { Is not as strong here due to } 24... Qxd6 25. Qa5 c5 { And here the excursion of the queen to a5 is not as powerful and Black should
be fine. At least. }) 24... Rd5 { A good decision, keeping an
active rook and taking control over some important squares on the 5th rank. } { [%cal Gd5a5,Gd5f5] } (24... Rfd8 { Would be significantly inferior due to } 25. Bxd6 Rxd6 26. Qa5) 25. Bxf8 { Now White has to take the exchange and restore the material balance. } 25... Qxf8 { Let's take a moment to stop and talk about the evaluation of this
endgame. We have a position with heavy pieces on the board and with the knight
vs bishop scenario. Since the pawns are on the both sides of the board and the
board is fairly open, bishop is expected to be better. --- But the fact that
Black's pawn structure is quite a mess works against the second player, which
is why the position is probably objectively balanced - but easier to play for
White. } 26. Nh5 { A good decision, aiming to get the
knight to a better square - f4! } { [%csl Gh5][%cal Gh5f4] } 26... Qe8?! { This move, attacking the knight, is
apparently not the best as the queen is not optimally placed on Qe8. } (26... Re5 { Moving the rook out of the way of Nf4 and preparing to get the queen to
d6 was apparently a better setup available to Black - although it is really
not easy to understand for a human why. } 27. Nf4 (27. Qxd4 { loses to } 27... Rd5) 27... Qd6 { The queen is nicely placed in the center. } 28. h3 c5 { And apparently this is a better version for Black compared to the position in
the game. } 29. b4 { Is now no good due to } 29... cxb4 { when it is impossible to take
on d4: } 30. Qxd4 Re1+ $19) 27. Nf4 Re5 28. h4 c5 { Now it seems as if Black has
managed to consolidate everything, but there is a strong move available to
White in this position. } 29. h5 { A logical move, trying to blockade the
kingside pawns and entrench the knight on f4 (g5 is now no longer possible),
while at the same time creating the possibility of jumping to g6. However -
White had a stronger option at their disposal. } (29. b4 { This
undermining move, breaking the c5 and d4 pawn duo and trying to isolate the d4
pawn, was the best chance for trying to play for an advantage. Black's best
bet is probably to ignore this tension and make a useful move, say by moving
the king. } { [%cal Rb4c5] } 29... Kh7 30. bxc5 Rxc5 { And the weakness of the c2 pawn
is counterbalanced by the weakness of the c2 pawn. But White can also try to
pick up the a7 pawn and Black's king is also less secure than White. At the
very least, this would have provided White with some practical chances. } { [%csl Rc2,Rd4] }) 29... Re4 { Black continues with logical play and
improves the position of the rook somewhat. From e4, it attacks the f4 knight
and now Qb8 is a possible threat. } { [%csl Ge4][%cal Re4f4,Ge8b8] } 30. c3 { A logical move, trying
to undermine the pawn on d4, but it transpires it is not so easy to exchange
there with the rook so nicely placed on e4. Furthermore, this makes it easier
for Black to create a passed pawn in the future as the pawn can be pushed to
d3 at the opportune moment. } { [%cal Rc3d4] } (30. b3 Qb8 31. Nd3 { Nothing horrible
for White is apparent. If Black exchanges, then a pretty drawish endgame with
the heavy pieces will arise. }) (30. f3 { The computer really wants
to play f3 and expel the rook from the active e4 square. As we will see, this
resource will be hugely important throughout this endgame. It is not very
natural to give up the e3 square to the rook, but the argument is that
reducing the pressure on the f4 knight is more important. } { [%cal Rf3e4] } 30... Re3 31. Qf2 Kh7 32. b3 { And nothing horrible for White is
apparent. If Black tries to attack the knight - say by Qb8 - then we can
always defend it with Qg3 or Qh4. } { [%csl Gf4][%cal Ge8b8,Gf2g3,Gg3h4] }) 30... Qb8 { Now the knight is
under the attack. } { [%cal Rb8f4] } 31. g3 { White defends the
knight, but opens up the long diagonal and makes the move f3 even more
psychologicaly difficult. It was precisely this weakening that playing 30.f3
was meant to avoid. --- The position is still fine, but little by little, it
becomes more and more difficult to play! } { [%csl Gg3][%cal Gg3f4,Ra8h1] } 31... Qe5 { Centralizing the queen makes a
lot of sense. } 32. Ng6?! { But this is a blank shot and a step in the wrong
direction. } (32. cxd4 Rxd4 (32... cxd4 { Is also not scary as now White
obtains a mobile pawn duo on the queenside. } { [%csl Ga2,Gb2] }) 33. Qc1 { Nothing horrible for
White is apparent. }) (32. f3 { It was also possible to play this thematic move,
forcing the rook away from the e4 square. } 32... Re2 { This would be forced, aiming
for simplifications or an imbalanced position. } (32... Re3 { Going to e3 would
have simply lost the vital d4 pawn. } 33. cxd4 cxd4 34. Qxd4 Qxd4 35. Rxd4 { And this endgame is hopelessly lost for Black. The a7 pawn will be very likely
dropped and White's queenside pawn duo will eventually be pushed and cost some
material. }) 33. Nxe2 Bxe2 { [%cal Re5g3] } 34. Kg2 (34. f4 Qe4 35. Re1 d3 { Is also pretty unclear. As a matter of fact - White has to give up material at
once when after } 36. Rxe2 dxe2 37. Kf2 Qh1 38. Qxe2 Qh2+ 39. Kf3 Qxh5+ { This endgame is pretty equal and perpetual is imminent. }) 34... Bxd1 35. Qxd1 { And this queen endgame is completely equal - as many queens endgames are. }) 32... Qd6 33. Nf4 { Admitting that jumping to g6 was a waste of time. } 33... d3 { Black finally decides to push the pawn to d3. The position is still within the
realms of equality, but little by little, Zukertort poses little problems to
his lustrious opponent. } (33... Qc6 { Trying to seize control of the long
diagonal at once was arguably even stronger. The point is that this move
prevent f3 resource as after } 34. f3 (34. Kh2 { Is already the only move, when
after } 34... Bb7 { Black has a very annoying battery down the long diagonal - the
consequence of the g3 move. White already needs to be very careful and find
some } 35. Rg1 { defense, when the game goes on but when it is clear that Black
is calling all the shots. }) 34... Re3 { The f3 pawn will drop as Re3 is still
possible. }) 34. b3 { Trying to isolate the d3 pawn and play c4 next. } (34. f3 { Expelling the rook now, was possible, as the e3 square is no
longer available. } { [%cal Rf3e4] }) (34. Nxd3 { Note that White can't take the pawn due to nice
tactics: } 34... Bxd3 35. Qxd3 Re1+ { And White loses material. } { [%cal Re1d1,Rd6d1] }) 34... c4 { Of course, Black doesn't allow this. } 35. Rb1? { But this is a
serious mistake - a loss of time in a very sensitive position. The rook has no
business on b1. } (35. f3 { Was necessary here, forcing the rook away and
gaining time to move the forces onward and defend the f3 pawn, shutting down
the long diagonal. } 35... Re8 { Going to the 8th rank is not as powerful here due to } 36. Qf2 Bb5 37. Kg2 a5 38. Rd2 a4 39. bxc4 Bxc4 40. Qd4 { And White has it all
covered. }) 35... Kh7 36. Kh2 (36. f3 { Amazingly, moving the pawn here no
longer works as after the precise } 36... Re8 { Black switches to queenside play, say
after } 37. Kg2 Bb5 38. Qf2 a5 { when a4 is coming next and White is in trouble,
mainly because the rook is on b1 and not on d1. Say, if White tries covering
the 2nd rank then } 39. Rb2 a4 40. bxc4 Bxc4 41. Qd4 Qxd4 42. cxd4 { Makes all
the difference as the rook is not on d2 so the capture of the d3 pawn is not
threatened. One small tempo that makes a major difference. } 42... Re1 43. Rd2 Ra1 $19) 36... Qb6 { Keeping an eye on f2, creating the potential
threat of Re2 and also pinning the b-pawn. } { [%cal Rb6f2,Rb6b1] } 37. Kg1? { This move is
apparently another mistake, but once again, it is a very difficult position to
handle. } (37. Rb2 { Covering the 2nd rank and trying to get in f3 to shut down
the long diagonal was mandatory, apparently, but not easy. It transpires that
Re2 is not dangerous here due to the fact that e2 square is covered twice. } 37... Re2 38. Nxe2 Qxf2+ 39. Kh3 { Although here Black can keep the game going with } 39... Bb7 40. Nf4 Qf1+ 41. Kh4 { With a fascinating position, e.g. } 41... Qf3 42. Kh3 Qh1+ 43. Qh2 Qf1+ 44. Kh4 Qd1 45. Qh3 Be4 { And Black has some winning chances due to
the strong d-pawn and the weak White king, despite being a full rook down.
Crazy! }) 37... Bb7? { Returning the favor! This move looks very logical -
placing the bishop on the long diagonal - but the problem is that Black
removes the defender of the d3 pawn. At first glance, it doesn't look like
this should be relevant, but in a very concrete variation, it turns out that
having the bishop on a6 can be beneficial. } (37... Re5 { The point of
this move is to clear the long diagonal in advance in preparation of Bb7-Qc6
at the moment where White is in a sort of zugzwang - it is extremely hard to
come up with a move for White in this position. } { [%cal Ge5a5,Ge5h5] } 38. Rf1 { Moving the rook to
f1 doesn't work here as Black can simply take on b3. } (38. Kh2 Re2) 38... cxb3 39. axb3 Qxb3 { This is completely won due to the passed d and a-pawns, better
placed pieces and weakness of the White king. }) 38. Rb2? { The final mistake.
Now this comes a move too late. } (38. Rf1 { Moving the rook to f1, intending to
take on c4 and also to play f3 if the queen moves from b6 was the only move to
try and keep the game going, although the position remains highly unpleasant
for White. } 38... Qc6 (38... cxb3 39. axb3 Qxb3 40. Qxd3 { The d-pawn drops. This variation is the reason why it
was bad to move the bishop from a6. Without the c4 pawn restricting White's
position, this position is now dead equal. }) 39. f3 { The point of White's play. We have already emphasized the importance of this
f3 move earlier - and this was the last chance to go for it. The reason why we
put the rook on f1 is so that this pawn is defended once the rook from e4
moves, of course. } { [%csl Gf3][%cal Gf1f3] } 39... Qc5+ 40. Kg2 { and nothing terrible is apparent for White.
Next he can take on c4 and then on d4 and play only a slightly inferior
endgame. }) 38... Qc6 { Now this battery is deadly as the rook is significantly
inferior on b2 compared to f1. } 39. f3 Qc5+ 40. Qf2 (40. Kg2 Re3 { Loses on the spot here - the f3 pawn can't be defended. This is why it
was important to move the rook to f1 earlier. } { [%cal Re3f3] }) 40... Re1+ 41. Kh2 (41. Kg2 Re3 { And once again the weakness of the f3 pawn is decisive. } { [%cal Re3f3,Rb7f3] }) 41... Qxf2+ 42. Rxf2 Bxf3 { A very nice tactical finish, snatching a pawn and
emphasizing that the rook can't move for the 2nd rank as it has to control the
d-pawn (which now turns out to be Black's "winning condition in the endgame",
as the popular Youtuber Andras Toth would describe it). } 43. g4 { This is
desperation, but White could have already resigned here. As a matter of fact,
it is interesting to observe how late the participants in the World
Championship resigned, compared to the modern standards. } (43. Rxf3 d2 { is, of course, bad, as the pawn promotes inevitably. }) 43... Be2 44. Ng2 d2 45. Ne3 cxb3 46. axb3 Bxg4 { And here Steinitz finally desided to call it a day. A
very interesting, topsy-turvy encounter which demonstrates the level of play
in these non-tactical, strategical, maneuvering games at a time. } 0-1


[Event "Steinitz - Zukertort World Championship"]
