{ In the first two games, the players in the first-ever World Chess
Championship match have exchanged blows and the score was standing tied at 1-1. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. e3 Bf5 { Just like in the modern times - the players do
repeat the same variation that was featured in the very first game of the
match. } 4. a3?! { But here once again, Zukertort goes for the faulty plan
involving the preparation of the c5 pawn push that is definitely not the most
critical or best way to handle this position. } 4... e6 5. c5 a5 { Very strong! This time Steinitz doesn't even allow his opponent to
execute the b4 pawn push, although it was certainly possible to simply
continue developing as in the first game. } { [%csl Rb4][%cal Ra5b4] } 6. Qb3 { This
whole play leaves a very strange impression from the modern standpoint. White
only now creates pressure against the b7 pawn, but it is fairly easy for Black
to deal with this. I feel it is more natural to try and get in b4 after all if
you hinted at it with your previous moves. } { [%csl Rb7][%cal Rb3b7] } 6... Qc7 { Calmly
defending the b7 pawn and placing a queen on an active square. } { [%csl Gb7][%cal Gc7b7] } (6... b6 { In order to illustrate why White's play is suboptimal, let's just mention that
temporarily sacrificing the b-pawn is also possible. The point is that after
something like } 7. cxb6 Nd7 8. b7 Ra7 { The b7 pawn will very
likely be lost and Black will be left with a very nice position as it will be
very difficult for Black to clamp down the c-file and prevent the liberating
c5 pawn break. The b2 pawn could also become a target in the future. } { [%csl Rb2,Rb7] }) 7. Nc3 Nd7 8. Na4 { Trying to utilize the weakness of the queenside
squares, but White is seriously violating the opening principles by moving the
same piece twice in the opening. } { [%cal Ga4b6,Gb3b6] } 8... Ngf6 { Continuing the normal development is
quite reasonable. } (8... e5 { It was already possible to strike in the center
immediately, too and aim for a somewhat similar structure as seen in the first
game. }) 9. Ne2 { The knight is aiming to g3 to hit the bishop on
f5, but this is also somewhat artificial and slow. } { [%cal Ge2g3] } 9... Be7 10. Ng3 Bg6 11. Bd2 { One problem for the knight on g3 is that it can be attacked with
h5-h4 in some variations. But more importantly - it doesn't control the e5
square, making the e5 break easier to execute. } { [%csl Rg3] } 11... O-O (11... h5 { Is also
possible! }) 12. Be2 Rfb8 { Very strong and logical play,
demonstrating that White's entire conception on the queenside has been a
failure. Now Black will play b6 and open up the position on the queenside and
exploit the lead in development and the fact that his pieces are better placed! } { [%cal Rb8b2,Gb7b6] } 13. O-O (13. Qd1 { The computer already suggests it is better to move the
queen and then meet the b6 advance with } 13... b6 14. cxb6 Nxb6 15. Nxb6 Rxb6 16. Bc3 { Trying to hold the position. There is no denying Black is better, but this is
better compared to what could have happened in the game. }) 13... b6 14. cxb6 Nxb6 15. Nxb6?! { Apparently, this is another mistake as it forces the queen
to go to a very unfavourable square, but it is not very human to keep the
queen in line of fire of the rook on b8. } (15. Bc3 { Nevertheless, moving the
bishop to c3 and trying to defend the b2 pawn, freeing the queen to go to d1,
was probably a better approach, although even here Black retains a massive
advantage, of course. }) 15... Rxb6 16. Qc3 { The queen is
really not particularly well placed here and all White's pieces are not very
harmonious at the moment. } { [%csl Rc3,Re2,Rg3] } 16... Qb7 { A logical move, increasing the
pressure on the b2 pawn. There are some other options available, but the
evaluation of the position doesn't fundamentally change either way. } { [%cal Rb7b2] } (16... a4 { Pushing the a-pawn and trying to lock the structure on
the queenside was also perfectly sensible. } { [%csl Gb3][%cal Ga4b3] }) (16... h5 { Trying to
gain some more space on the kingside and kick the knight on g3 away first, is
another way of handling the position. Remember this pattern as it is very
common to use your flank pawn to push the knight that is on g3/g6 or b3/b6. } { [%cal Gh5h4] }) 17. Ra2 { The only way of defending the b2 pawn,
since the bishop is controlling the b1 square. } { [%csl Gb2][%cal Ga2b2,Rg6b1] } (17. b4 { The computer wants to
give up a pawn here, but it is really not a human decision - especially not in
1886. White claims that after } 17... axb4 18. axb4 Bxb4 19. Rxa8+ Qxa8 20. Qa1 Qxa1 21. Rxa1 Bd6 { he has some drawing chances in the resulting position a pawn
down. Whereas it might be true that this attempt to cut the Gordian knot might
be a better defensive try than slow and passive suffering, it is by no mean
obvious if Black should be able to draw this and it is perfectly
understandable that one doesn't want to give up a pawn just like that. }) 17... Nd7 { A solid idea, preparing the c5 pawn push. } { [%cal Gc6c5] } 18. Bd1 { Zukertort tries to activate the bishop and move it to a4. It is hard to
say how much it benefits him, but it is also hard to come up with a better
move. } { [%cal Gd1a4] } 18... c5 { Steinitz has obtained a strategically won position and here he
continues playing strong and logical moves, opening up the position futher and
eliminating the weak pawn on c6. } 19. Ba4 c4 { Another
good move, clamping down on the position further and making sure that the b2
pawn will never move. } { [%csl Gc4][%cal Rb8b2] } 20. Qc1 Nf6 21. Bc3 Bd6 { Both sides continue
maneuvering a bit and improving their position. Steinitz is in absolutely no
hurry as White has no active plan in this position and his pieces are horrible. } 22. f3 Qb8 23. f4?! { This is an ugly positional move as it surrenders all
the light squares in the position. But White's position is unenviable in any
case. } 23... Bd3 { The bishop is sitting very nicely on d3 now. } { [%csl Rd3] } 24. Re1 h5 { [%cal Gh5h4] } 25. h4?! { Probably it was better not to do this as
now the h4 pawn will be a target and the g4 square is also weakened. } { [%csl Gg4] } (25. Nh1 { The idea of going with the knight to f2 at once was argaubly
better, although White's position remains lost, of course. } { [%cal Gh1f2] }) 25... Qd8 26. Bd1 g6 27. Qd2 Rbb8 28. Qf2 Be7 { All the forces aimed
toward the h4 pawn. } { [%csl Rh4][%cal Rd8h4] } 29. Bf3 Ne4?! { But this is actually not the most precise
move as it allows White to exchange the passive knight on g3 for the good one
on f6. It is true that Black wins the pawn on h4 all the same and retains a
winning position, but objectively it was stronger to jump to g4. } (29... Ng4 { Jumping to g4 was stronger. Black is happy to eliminate the light-squared
bishop - the defender of the light-squares. } 30. Bxg4 hxg4 { The
pawn on h4 will be won and Black has a better version compared to what could
have potentially happened in the game. } { [%cal Re7h4] }) (29... Ne8 { Was also
fairly reasonable, avoiding all exchanges and simply collecting the h4 pawn
for now. } { [%cal Rd8h4] }) 30. Bxe4?! { But this is a mistake in return. As I mentioned
earlier, in this situation it is better to keep the light-squared bishop than
the knight as the bishop controls some important light-squares. With that
being said, White's position would remain lost in any case - and knights are
trickier to handle - as the course of this game will demonstrate. } (30. Nxe4 dxe4 31. Bd1 Bxh4 32. g3 Be7 33. Kg2 { And here Black has won
a pawn and has positional domination, but he yet has to find a breakthrough. }) 30... dxe4 31. Nh1 { This is the problem. You can notice
how passive the knight is here. However, the ideaof Nf2-g4 does give White at
least some practical hope. } { [%csl Rh1][%cal Gh1f2] } 31... Bxh4 32. g3 Be7 33. Qd2 Qd5 34. Nf2 a4 { A natural
move, but it is interesting to observe how the computer wants to go about
converting this position. } (34... f6 { This move is the engine's top choice.
Basically, the computer wants to open up the position as it claims it is much
easier for Black to transfer the forces from the queenside into the action.
Say, after } 35. Raa1 Kf7 36. Kg2 g5 { The rooks will
transfer to the kingside, the bishop will go to d6 and Black will win on the
kingside - after pressuring the queenside the entire game. An amazing example
of the flexibility in chess and how it can be strong to play over the entire
board. } { [%cal Gb8h8,Ga8g8] }) 35. Kg2 Rb3 36. Rh1 { Zukertort is already preparing the
initiative on the kingside. } { [%cal Gh1h8] } 36... Kg7 37. Raa1 Bd8 { A good move. The
idea is to play Ba5, eliminate the important bishop on c3 that glues the
entire position together and then invade on the queenside. However, from this
point onward, the game takes a completely unexpected turn. } { [%cal Gd8a5] } 38. g4 { The
culminating point of this entire game. } 38... hxg4?? { The first mistake! Steinitz
willingly - and with a loss of time - opens up the position on the kingside,
the h-file and invites the knight to g4. Almost immediately, the position goes
from hopelessly lost for White to clearly better for the first player - and
the momentum of the game shifts completely. } (38... Ba5 { It was very strong to
simply ignore White's demonstration on the kingside and continue with the
implementation of the desired plan on the queenside, involving the elimination
of the bishop on c3. It looks a bit risky to allow White to take on h5, but as
it transpires - Black can ignore that capture, too. } 39. gxh5 Bxc3 40. bxc3 Rab8 { And Black doesn't really care about the capture on g6 as
Rb2 is coming and White has no time to prepare Ng4-Qf2 attacking mechanism. } { [%cal Gb3b2] }) 39. Nxg4 { Now suddenly the knight
is very active on g4 and White has all sorts of ideas such as Qf2-Qh4,
doubling on the h-file or the nice tactic that was seen in the game. } { [%cal Gd2f2,Gf2h4,Gh1h2,Ga1h1,Rh1h7,Rg4f6] } 39... Ba5?? { As they say - mistakes come in pairs. Whereas with his previous
move Steinitz allowed White to grab the initiative, here he misses a simple
tactical shot and allows Zukertort to obtain the winning attack out of nowhere.
The problem with this move is that the bishop no longer controls the f6 square,
allowing the nasty Rh7-Nf6 combo. } { [%csl Rf6] } (39... f5 { For better or for worse, it was
necessary to kick the knight away from the g4 square and avoid all tricks
associated with Rh7-Nf6. It is true that this move allows the knight to go to
e5. } 40. Ne5 { But after something along the lines of } 40... Bf6 41. Qf2 Rg8 42. Rag1 Rb7 { Black's position is tough - maybe even lost already - but at least the
game goes on. }) 40. Rh7+ { This nice tactical blow wins on the spot as the rook
arrives on the h-file with a gain of tempo. } 40... Kf8 (40... Kxh7 41. Nf6+ Kg7 42. Nxd5 { and here Black doesn't have
time to capture on d5 as the bishop on a5 is also hanging: } 42... exd5 43. Bxa5 $18) 41. Rh8+ Kg7 42. Rh7+ Kf8 43. Qf2 { Now the
queen arrives and Black is getting killed on the dark-squares all of a sudden. } { [%csl Re7,Rf6,Rg7][%cal Gf2h4] } 43... Bd8 (43... Bxc3 { Taking on c3 doesn't help as White can simply recapture. } 44. bxc3 { And Black's problem here is that the rooks aren't doubled
on the b-file so there is no Rb2 ideas - meaning that they are completely
helpless against Qh4 with mating attack. } { [%cal Gf2h4] }) 44. Ne5 { Now
everything works for White as Black's king is too weak and all the pieces are
unable to help in the defence, so the game concludes very shortly. } { [%cal Rh7f7] } 44... Kg8 45. Rah1 Bf6 46. Rxf7 Rf8 47. Rxf6 { Here Steinitz resigned as it is impossible to
defend any longer. } 47... Rxf6 48. Qh4 { The king is getting checkmated
very very soon. An absolutely shocking game that demonstrated vividly
Steinitz's superior understanding of the game, but it is all in vain if you
commit blunders like 38...hxg4 and 39...Ba5. } { [%cal Gh1h8] } 1-0


[Event "Steinitz - Zukertort World Championship"]
[Site "New York, NY USA"]
[Date "1886.01.18"]
[Round "4"]
[White "Wilhelm Steinitz"]
[Black "Johannes Zukertort"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Annotator "Nemec, Vjekoslav"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C67"]
[Opening "Ruy Lopez: Berlin Defense, Rio Gambit Accepted"]
[StudyName "Steinitz - Zukertort 1886 World Chess Championship"]
[ChapterName "Game #4"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/fB11Bc7Q/1dvQdYvz"]

{ Thus, after winning the third game in a surprising turn of events, Zukertort
took the lead in the match. Steinitz was probably very eager to even the score,
although this generic sentence that is very typical for the chess literature
is pretty silly, given that probably both sides wouldn't mind winning. }
1. e4 { As usual in his career - Steinitz opens with his favourite move. } 1... e5 { And
Zukertort replies with his favourite move, as well. } 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 { This time, Steinitz deviates from the Scotch he employed in game 3 and decided
to go for the good old Ruy Lopez - an eternal opening that has been featured
in World Championship matches to this day. } 3... Nf6 { But this move, leading to the
so-called Berlin Defence of the Ruy Lopez, can be regarded as trully
revolutionary at a time. This whole variation became very famous when Vladimir
Kramnik unexpectedly revived it in his 2000 World Championship match against
Kasparov - with great effect. Nowadays, it is considered to be one of the main
replies for Black in the 1.e4 e5 complex - one that was seen regularly on the
top level in the 21st century. --- I was, nevertheless, very surprised to see
that it was Zukertort's main defense in the Ruy Lopez. He employed it in 48
games in his career, compared to only 21 games with the other main move, 3...
a6. --- It does make some sense, though, given that the peak years of the
great Russian master Chigorin - who did a lot for the popularity of the 3...a6
system - were just ahead. } 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1 { One of the main move in this
position, avoiding the notorious "Berlin Endgame". } (5. d4 { This move, which
was Kasparov's choice in the match against Kramnik, leads to the so-called
Berlin Endgame - a variation that arises by force after } 5... Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 { which has been fascinating the top players for a long,
long time. Entire books could be (and have been) written about it by people
much knowledgable about it than me, but I thought I could mention that this is
the starting point of an enormously important theoretical position. }) 5... Nd6 6. Nxe5 { Threatening a discovered check on c6, due to which
Black doesn't have time to take the bishop on b5. } { [%cal Re5c6,Re1e8] } 6... Nxe5 (6... Nxb5 7. Nxc6+ { wins for White on the spot. }) 7. Rxe5+ Be7 { Now the bishop is
indeed under attack and has to retreat. } { [%cal Rd6b5] } 8. Bf1 { The most
common place to retreat the bishop, as it is not in the way of the pawns nor
is it blocking the rook on e5 from retreating all the way to e1 (as it will be
soon attacked by the bishop on f6). } { [%cal Ge5e1,Gd2d4] } 8... O-O 9. d4 Bf6 { [%cal Rf6e5] } 10. Re1 { A natural retreating move - but not the only possibility in this position. } (10. Re2 { First of all - White can try to
retreat the rook to e2. The idea is that in the not-so-distant future, White
will be willing to double the rooks on the e-file with Rae1, so by placing the
rook on e2, White prepares for this maneuver later down the road. The downside
is, of course, that the bishop is blocked, which gives Black some additional
options such as b6-Ba6. } { [%cal Ga1e1,Rb7b6,Rc8a6,Yf1e2] }) (10. Bd3 { It is also possible to go for this very
tricky and dangerous exchange sacrifice. At first glance it seems as if it
shouldn't work as White doesn't have many pieces in the attack, but White's
results in practice - even at the very high level - are pretty good, so it is
definitely an option worth studying. }) 10... Re8 { Immedaitely
challenging the rook on e8. } { [%cal Re8e1] } 11. c3 { Defending the d4
pawn is quite natural, although not yet necessary at this point. } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gc3d4] } (11. Bf4 { In the 21st century, this developing move has been tried. White's point is
that they are not really worried about the d4 pawn due to } 11... Rxe1 12. Qxe1 Bxd4 (12... Ne8 { defending the c7 pawn and intending to
play d5 next, reaching the symmetrical structure we will also see in the game. } { [%csl Gc7][%cal Ge8c7,Gd7d5] }) 13. c3 Bf6 14. Bxd6 cxd6 { When the doubled d-pawns provide
White with some chances. The game is still close to being equal, but that is
true of the majority of the variations in the Berlin anyway. } { [%csl Rd6,Rd7] }) 11... Rxe1 12. Qxe1 Nf5 { A typical scenario for this variation. Black intends to
place the pawn on d5 next, reaching a perfectly symmetrical structure that can
also be reached via some other openings (French Exchange, Petroff Defence).
This kind of structure is, in general, very solid - although by no means
completely dead drawn as some people would assume. } { [%cal Gd7d5] } 13. Bf4 { Preventing the idea of d5 for the moment due to some tricks with Bxc7 and Qe8. } { [%cal Rf4c7,Ge1e8] } 13... d6 { Preventing the threat of Bxc7. } (13... d5?? { loses to } 14. Bxc7 { as the
bishop is immune now } 14... Qxc7 15. Qe8# { A pattern worth remembering! }) 14. Nd2 Be6 15. Bd3 Nh4 { Rerouting the knight to g6 to kick the bishop away
from f4. } { [%cal Gh4g6] } (15... g6 { It is also possible to reinforce the
knight, vacate the g7 square and aim for some Ng7-Bf5 ideas. In general, if
Black manages to exchange some pieces, it should be even easier to defend. } { [%cal Gf5g7,Ge6f5] }) (15... Bg5 { Trying to exchange some pieces was seen in quite a number of games,
including a very high profile encounter: 1/2-1/2 (30) Anand,V (2773)-Radjabov,
T (2757) Wijk aan Zee 2019 }) 16. Ne4 { [%cal Re4f6] } 16... Ng6 17. Bd2 { Good play.
White is not in a hurry to capture on f6 as in this symmetrical position, the
power of the bishop pair is not as pronounced. Yet. } 17... d5 { Nevertheless, it was
maybe better not to open up the h2-b8 diagonal and give up the bishop pair. In
general, Black's position has a huuuge margin of safety and these kind of
positions are lost by making small inaccuracies/concessions - and this move
definitely belongs to that category. } 18. Nc5 { A
bit surprising, as it was also possible to take on f6. } { [%csl Rf6][%cal Rc5b7,Rc5e6] } (18. Nxf6+ Qxf6 { I am not 100% sure what Steinitz didn't like here, but from the modern
viewpoint this should be preferable as now, with the pawn on d5, White can
hope for some opening of the position much later down the road, say after some
b3-c4 is executed in a timely manner. More importnatly, there is zero risk of
White ever losing this position - even though the same could be said about the
position that arose in the game. }) 18... Bc8 { The
only move, but the sufficient one. Black removes the attacked bishop, defends
the b7 pawn and intends to play b6 next, kicking the knight away. } { [%csl Gb7][%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7] } 19. Qe3 b6 20. Nb3 { Now this knight is somewhat sidelined on b3, and you can
definitely queston why it wasn't exchanged on f6 back on move 18. } { [%csl Rb3] } 20... Qd6 { But this move is really strange - why give up the e8 square and total control
over the e-file to White? } (20... Be6 { Blocking the e-file and
preparing to play Qd7-Re8/Rc8 was far more natural. } { [%cal Re3e8] }) 21. Qe8+ Nf8 { It is true that the queen will be kicked out after the subsequent Bb7,
but in the meantime White will manage to occupy the e-file uncontested as now
Be6 is never possible. } { [%cal Gc8b7] } 22. Re1 Bb7 23. Qe3 { Still, Black's position is
extremely solid. } 23... Ne6 { It is not 100% clear how necessary this move is,
although it isn't bad. } (23... Rd8 { It was also possible to
try to get the rook to e7 to contest the e-file with Rd7-Re7 next. } { [%cal Gd8d7,Gd7e7] }) 24. Qf3 { A good idea, trying to get the queen to f5 and create
some threats against the kingside - or force the knight to go back to f8. } { [%csl Gf5][%cal Gf3f5] } 24... Rd8 25. Qf5 Nf8 26. Bf4 { White is definitely making some progress as the pieces
are gradually becoming more and more active. } 26... Qc6 27. Nd2 { Another very good move, following the principle of improving the
worst place piece. There was really not much for the knight to do on b3, so it
returns back to the game. White would love to get in Nf3-Ne5 next. } { [%csl Gd2][%cal Gd2f3,Gf3e5] } 27... Bc8 { Also a very good move, bringing the bishop back into the main center of action
(it was not doing much on b7). } 28. Qh5 g6 29. Qe2 Ne6 { Black is also managing
to push the opponent's pieces a bit and get his pieces to active squares. } 30. Bg3 Qb7 { A very tricky move to annotate. Black is intending to
start playing more ambitiously and go for the c5 push on the next move, since
all the pieces (knight on e6 and the bishop on f6) are perfectly positioned to
create pressure on the d4 pawn. --- Furthermore, Zukertort has correctly
judged that the capture on c5 would be in his favour, as he would obtain a
mobile pawn duo in the center. However, there was a very hidden and nuanced
flaw in his concept. } { [%cal Gc7c5] } (30... Ng7 { Objectively speaking, going
with the knight back to g7 and preparing to play Bf5, liberating the position
somewhat, was arguably better. But also less ambitious, for sure. } { [%cal Gc8f5] }) 31. Nf3 c5 { The first real, extremely critical moment of the game. } 32. dxc5?! { This
move is definitely not the best, as it gives Black a mobile c and d-pawn duo
in the center and removes an important central pawn from d4 that was
controling some important squares such as e5. However, it was not at all easy
to judge that White could have actually sacrificed the d4 pawn. } (32. Qd2 { The idea
is to seize the dark-squares and prepare a discovery on a piece the will come
on d4, say } { [%csl Rd4][%cal Gd2h6,Rd2d4] } 32... cxd4 33. cxd4 Nxd4 (33... Bxd4 34. Rxe6 $18) 34. Nxd4 Bxd4 35. Ba6! { An astounding decision, giving up the bishop and sacrificing one - or two
- pawns to get rid of the opponent's dark-squared bishop and create a decisive
attack on the kingside. It is really not easy to judge from afar that this
position is completely won for White irrespective of what Black does. } 35... Qxa6 (35... Bxf2+ 36. Bxf2 Qxa6 37. Bd4 { The bishop immediately gets
positioned on the crucial diagonal and Black is helpless against Qh6 or
Qf4-Qf6 ideas. } { [%csl Rf6,Rg7,Rh6][%cal Rd4h8,Gd2f4,Gf4f6,Gd2h6] }) 36. Qxd4 { Qf6/Qh4 and Be5 is coming and
Black is helpless against the attack on the dark-squares, objectively speaking. } { [%cal Gd4f6,Gg3e5] }) 32... bxc5 { Now the pawns on c5 and d5 are mobile and can
advance further without any problems. The position is still equal, of course,
but the character of play has significantly changed. } { [%csl Gc5,Gd5] } 33. Ne5 c4 { A good move, restricting the light-squared bishop and fixing the b2 pawn
as a target. Black correctly judges that the weakness of the d4 square is
kinda irrelevant here. } { [%csl Rd3,Rd4] } 34. Bb1 { Now this bishop is somewhat dead
as it is severely restricted by Black's pawns on light-squares. } { [%csl Rb1] } 34... Bg7 35. Rd1 Bd7 { Very patient play. Zukertort keeps improving the
position and intends to bring the bishop to a4 to harass the rook on d1 or to
e8 to defend the f7 square in a very harmonious fashion. } { [%cal Gd7a4,Gd7e8] } 36. Qf3 { But this is the first step in the wrong direction.
White attacks the f7 and d5 pawns and creates a seemingly dangerous pin on the
d5 pawn in relation to the queen on b7, but it transpires that this pin is not
so dangerous. Thus, with this move White merely manages to leave the b2 pawn
undefended. } { [%csl Gb2][%cal Rf3f7,Rd1d5,Rf3b7] } (36. h3) (36. Nxd7) 36... Be8 { Calmly defending d5 and f7 and setting a nasty trap
- in which Steinitz, shockingly, falls. } 37. Nxc4?? { Losing a game on the
spot. Steinitz though this was a winning tactic, but he forgot he has problems
on the last rank. } (37. Qe2 d4 { Note that here capturing on c4 is dangerous as after } 38. Nxc4 Bb5 { Black's pieces are all active while White's
pieces lack coordination and there is a nasty pin on the knight on c4. Black
is clearly better here. } { [%cal Rb5e2,Ge6d4,Gg7d4] }) (37. Rd2 { Defending the
pawn with the rook from d1 was the best solution as it would have prevented
Black from moving the d4 pawn due to the pin by the queen. The position would
have remained approximately equal, even though a lot of chess remains to be
played. } { [%csl Gb2][%cal Gd2b2,Rf3b7] }) 37... dxc4 { A cold shower. White can't
capture the queen on b7 because of the back rank issues - and the preliminary
exchange on d8 doesn't help. } { [%csl Rg1][%cal Rd8d1] } 38. Rxd8 (38. Qxb7 { loses to } 38... Rxd1#) 38... Nxd8 { Possibly, Steinitz missed that the queen would be
defended by the knight from d8 at the end of this variation. Now White is just
down a piece for nothing. } { [%csl Gb7][%cal Gd8b7] } (38... Qxf3 39. Rxe8+) 39. Qe2 Ne6 { And Steinitz
realized he has nothing to play for, so he resigned. Another pretty shocking
game, decided by Steinitz's colossal blunder. However, whereas in the previous
game the blunders came in a completely winning position, here Zukertort
actually played extremely well and managed to outplay Steinitz to a certain
extent in a very technical, strategical position - which is quite surprising
if you take into the account how his White games looked like. --- In any case,
after four games, Zukertort took a commanding, two points lead in the match,
although there was still a long road ahead to the title at this particular
point. } 0-1


[Event "Steinitz - Zukertort World Championship"]
[Site "New York, NY USA"]
[Date "1886.01.20"]
[Round "5"]
[White "Johannes Zukertort"]
[Black "Wilhelm Steinitz"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Annotator "Nemec, Vjekoslav"]
[Variant "Standard"]
