{ So, after 4 games, Zukertort took a 3-1 lead in the match and was surely
enjoying the momentum in the match. He was surely looking to increase the lead
since he had White in game 5 (although I guess the colour of the pieces back
in 1886 was not as relevant as it is today, as the previous game of the match
demonstrated). }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 { After going for 3.e3 in two
consecutive games, Zukertort is the first to deviate and develops the knight
to c3, entering the main line of the Slav defence. } 3... Nf6 4. e3 { But ultimately,
he decides to move the e-pawn and go for the very quiet variation against the
Slav, which is perhaps not the most ambitious, but which is extremely solid. } 4... Bf5 { Steinitz again decides to provoke the opponent somewhat by moving the
bishop to f5 and leaving the b7 pawn undefended. This move is still played
nowadays, although it is the 4th most popular move according to my database. } 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Qb3 { As we have seen in previous games,
this early excursion of the queen is an attempt to try and punish the early
development of the bishop to f5. } { [%cal Rb3d5,Rb3b7] } 6... Bc8 { A very solid, although
somewhat passive decision. Black retreats the bishop and loses two tempi, but
claims that White will also have to subsequently move the queen from b3, as
her majesty is not ideally placed on this square. } { [%csl Rb3] } (6... Nc6 { Nowadays, the
variation involving the sacrifice of the pawn on b7 has also appeared. The
point is that after } 7. Qxb7 Bd7 { Black has quite a few threats associated
with Rb8 and then e5, say after } 8. Qb3 Rb8 9. Qd1 e5 { With very unclear
consequences. Definitely a variation that requires further preparation from
both sides. }) 7. Nf3 Nc6 { Maybe it is better not to commit the knight to c6
yet precisely of what happens in thi game. } (7... e6 { Moving the e-pawn is
maybe more solid, when Black wants to play Be7 and O-O before developing the
queenside further. Still, the position is quite passive for the second player
and practical results are very good for White in this position. }) 8. Ne5 { An annoying knight jump, creating some pressure
on the c6 knight and intending to increase the pressure on c6. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gf1b5,Re5c6] } 8... e6 (8... Nxe5 { Taking the knight on e5 is almost always a horrible idea in such positions as
after } 9. dxe5 Nd7 { White can simply take the pawn on d4 or play even more
strongly with } 10. e4 { when Black is struggling to come up with a good
response as both after } 10... d4 (10... dxe4 11. e6) 11. e6 { White gains a
tremendous initiative and ruins Black's pawn structure. }) (8... a6 { Preventing the bishop from coming to b5 is worth considering, although
it is a bit slow to make a purely defensive pawn move on the flank in such a
position. } { [%cal Ga6b5] }) 9. Bb5 { It is a question how problematic this pin is for Black,
though. } (9. f4 { Reinforcing the knight on e5 and
intending to develop the bishop to d3 next, is also worth considering. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gf4e5,Gf1d3] }) 9... Qc7?! { This is probably not optimal as it is a bit unnatural to place the
queen on the open c-file. } (9... Bd7 { Steinitz probably wanted to avoid giving
up the bishop pair based on principle (he was known to uphold the principles
very firmly in his games), but in this fairly static and relatively closed
position, it is not 100% clear that the bishop pair is such a major asset. } 10. Nxd7 Qxd7 { And it is true that White has the bishop pair, but they gave up the
strong knight and have also moved it quite a few times, so the position should
be reasonably fine for Black. }) 10. Bd2 { Preparing to bring the
rook to c1 and disturb the queen on c7. } { [%cal Ga1c1] } 10... Bd6?! { Another opening inaccuracy. } (10... a6 { It was probably best to challenge the bishop on b5 immediately, and
then after } 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. Na4 { To challenge the knight on e5 at once with } 12... Nd7 { as now } 13. f4 f6 { Is quite acceptable for Black. Not an easy variation
to figure out, but definitely more combative than what happened in the game. }) 11. f4 { Firmly establishing the knight on e5. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gf4e5,Gd4e5] } 11... O-O (11... a6 { Is now not as powerful as White can retreat the bishop now that the
e5 pawn is sufficiently protected. } 12. Bd3 { And this
position is very unpleasant for Black as the knight on e5 is very problematic
to deal with and White also has ideas of Na4, etc. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gc3a4] }) 12. Rc1 { Bringing the rook to the open c-file and eyeing the queen on c7. } { [%csl Rc7][%cal Gc1c7] } 12... Bxe5?? { But this move is a catastrophic decision that would be below par even for
an average club player nowadays. Black voluntarily gives up the bishop pair
but , more importantly - invites the pawn on e5 that will kick the knight from
f6 away. Furthermore, the f-file is opened. } (12... Qb6 { moving away from the sight of the c-rook, was much, much better. Black's
position is extremely unpleasant, but it is much better compared to what
happens in the game. }) 13. fxe5 Ne8 14. O-O { This position is simply horrible for Black as the entire kingside is deserted
and White virtually has an automatic attack with Qc2-Bd3, doubling on the
f-file, etc. } { [%cal Gb3c2,Gb5d3,Gf1f3,Gc1f1] } 14... f6 { Trying to radically tie the Gordian knot and undermine the
construction on the kingside, but Black is not sufficiently developed to open
up the position in such manner. } 15. Bd3 { Improving the
bishop and preventing Black from taking on e5 due to Bxh7 and Rxf1 tricks. } { [%cal Rd3h7,Rf1f8] } 15... Rf7 (15... fxe5 { loses for Black due to } 16. Bxh7+ Kxh7 17. Rxf8) 16. Qc2 { Increasing the pressure on h7 and forcing Black's reply. } { [%cal Rc2h7] } 16... f5 { Desperately trying to close the position, but now the pressure on e5 is
relieved so White gets all the time in the world to improve the position and
open things up with a timely g4. } { [%cal Gg2g4] } (16... g6 { Doesn't quite work due to the
simple } 17. Bxg6 hxg6 18. Qxg6+ { And this position is
completely lost for Black as all the pieces are stuck on the queenside and
White can also include the knight via Nb5-Nd6, while taking on f6 also seems
very strong. } { [%cal Ge5f6,Gc3b5,Rg6e8] }) 17. Ne2 { Improving the knight and intending to
bring it to f4. } { [%cal Ge2f4] } 17... Bd7 18. Rf2 { Trying very patiently to
double on the f-file, but the position was ripe for more aggressive measures. } { [%cal Gc1f1,Gg2g4] } (18. g4 { Was already extremely strong here, as after } 18... g6 19. gxf5 gxf5 20. Nf4 Rg7+ 21. Kh1 { White will play Qd1-Qh5-Rg1
and simply win as his pieces are much faster in transfering to the kingside
and also better placed (look at that wonderful knight on f4). } { [%csl Gf4][%cal Gc2d1,Gd1h5,Gf1g1] }) 18... Rc8 19. Bc3 { Still in the very same patient manner, although this does allow Black
some defensive resources. } (19. g4 { Was once again worth considering. }) 19... Qb6 20. Qd2 Ne7 21. Rcf1 { But this doesn't pay attention to Black's defensive
resources and kinda allows Steinitz back in the game. } (21. Nf4 { It was necessary to do something against the idea of Bb5 that
happened in the game. The knight now pressures e6 and prevents Bb5, while also
against g5 the knight can go to h5, which is a huge improvement compared to
what could have happened in the game. } { [%csl Re6][%cal Rf4e6] } 21... Bb5 { This just drops the e6 pawn. } 22. Bxb5 Qxb5 23. Nxe6 { And Black is busted as they lose a key pawn and their
defensive structure should collapse. }) 21... Bb5 { Good defensive play. Due to
White's slow play, Black manages to activate the slumbering bishop to a
certain extent and invites some piece exchanges, reducing a significant part
of White's advantage. } 22. Bb1 { Trying to keep the important bishop on the
board. It is not entirely clear whether it was better to do so or to exchange
it as now the bishop on b5 is somewhat annoying and preventing the knight on
e2 from moving, though. } (22. Bxb5 Qxb5 23. Nf4 { Was maybe better,
although now the impact of g4 has been significantly reduced without the
light-squared bishop. } { [%csl Gf4] }) 22... Qa6 { Trying to increase the
pressure on the long diagonal and activate the queen somewhat is sensible, but
Black had another nice idea in the position. } { [%cal Ra6f1] } (22... g5 { is actually very strong as it
opens up the g6 square for one knight and the g7 square for the other knight.
At first glance it looks as it allows g4 under strong circumstances, but it
turns out that after } { [%csl Gg5][%cal Ge8g7] } 23. g4 Ng7 { Black's position is very solid and it is not
easy to make progress as White. }) 23. g4 { Finally this advance comes, although
under worse circumstances as could have happened earlier in the game. } 23... g6 { Reinforcing the f5 pawn and opening the g7 square
for the knight, along the lines of what was considered in the previous note. } { [%csl Gf5][%cal Gg6f5,Ge8g7] } 24. h3 { Now once again it is hard for White to create
direct progress, so Zukertort now switches to slow maneuvering and quiet
improving of the position. } { [%csl Gg4][%cal Gh3g4] } 24... Rc7 25. Re1 { Moving the rook out of the way and
preparing to jump with the knight on f4. } 25... Ng7 { [%cal Gg7f5,Ge7f5] } (25... Bxe2 { It was worth considering to eliminate the knight on e2 before it jumps to f4.
However, this would leave the bishop on b1 unopposed, so it is hard to say
whether it is preferable or not. }) 26. Nf4 { The culminating point
of the game. } { [%csl Gf4] } 26... Nc8? { This move is a big mistake. Steinitz voluntarily moves
the knight away from the kingside and providies White with a golden
opportunity to capture on f5 under very favourable circumstances. I am not
even sure what this move is about as it is hard to understand where the knight
will go from c8. } (26... g5 { [%cal Rg5f4,Ge7g6] } 27. Ng2 Ng6 { And Black
is still clearly worse, but it is much better compared to what happens in the
game as the knight is much better on c8 instead of g6. } { [%csl Gg6] }) 27. gxf5 { Now this
happens at the very right moment as the knight on c8 is far away from the
kingside and also doesn't reinforce the f5 square. } 27... gxf5? { Mistakes often
come in pairs. Here Steinitz opens up the g-file and enables Zukertort to
easily steamroll him along it. I am not sure what he missed - maybe he thought
he would be in time to defend with the doubled rooks on the 7th rank, but with
the knight on c8 and the queen and the bishop on the queenside, it is hard to
imagine how Black will survive the attack. } (27... Nxf5 { For better or for
worse, it was better to capture with the knight and keep the position on the
kingside closed. Black's position is objectively still very much lost, but at
least White's winning plan is not as straightforward. } 28. e4 { Advancing the
e4 pawn and intending to follow things up with d5 is probably the most direct. } 28... dxe4 29. Bxe4 { And it is very difficult to prevent d5 next, with
a decisive effect. } { [%cal Gd4d5] }) 28. Rg2 { Now White will simply bring everything to the
kingside (Reg1, Qd1/Qh5, Qf2, etc). It is much easier for the first player to
mobilize the attacking forces and the position is desperately lost. It is
maybe somewhat surprising that the engine gives +8, but hopefully it is easy
to understand why White should have a decisive advantage. } 28... Kh8 29. Kh2 { [%cal Ge1g1] } 29... Qc6 30. Reg1 Ne7 31. Qf2 { Qh4 and Bb4 are
incoming and Black is just busted. } { [%cal Gc3b4,Gf2h4] } 31... Qe8 { The final blunder in a losing
position. } 32. Rxg7 { And here Steinitz resigned as he loses the material by
force. } 32... Rxg7 33. Rxg7 Kxg7 34. Nxe6+ { A catastrophic game by
Steinitz on all fronts, where he got a losing position out of the opening and
almost never got back to the game - even if there were a few opportunites to
defend more stubbornly. Thus, by winning the 4th game in a row, Zukertort
increased the lead to 3 points in the match (4-1) and things started to look
very desperate for Steinitz. } { [%cal Re6c7] } 1-0


[Event "Steinitz - Zukertort World Championship"]
[Site "St. Louis, MO USA"]
[Date "1886.02.03"]
[Round "6"]
[White "Wilhelm Steinitz"]
[Black "Johannes Zukertort"]
[Result "1-0"]
