{ So, after losing game 5 - the fourth consecutive in a row - Steinitz found
himself in a quite a desperate situation, with the score standing at 4-1. And
even though back in the day matches were unlimited (first to 10 victories wins)
, it was surely not psychologically easy to play when being 3 games down and I
am sure Steinitz was willing to do anything he could do stop the bleeding,
which is why I feel game 6 was extremely important and sort of a turning point
in the match, as we will soon see. }
1. e4 { As usual, Steinitz opens with his
favourite move... } 1... e5 { ... and Zukertort replies with his standard move. } 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1 Nd6 6. Nxe5 Nxe5 7. Rxe5+ Be7 { And again
we see the same variation of the Berlin defence we have seen already in the
4th game of the match. } 8. Nc3 { This time Steinitz is the
first to deviate and develops a knight, not losing time to retreat the bishop
to f1. Now the idea is to play Nd5 so Black's reply is forced. } { [%cal Gb5f1,Gc3d5] } (8. Bf1 { You might recall this was Steinitz's choice in the 4th game, which he ended up
losing (although not due to the opening). }) 8... O-O (8... Nxb5 9. Nd5 { Is actually pretty bad for Black as the bishop on
e7 drops and their king has to be displaced. } { [%csl Re7][%cal Rd5e7,Re5e7] }) 9. Bd3 { This is
idea! White doesn't retreat the bishop all the way up to f1, but keeps it on a
more aggressive post - on d3. This variation is also quite relevant in the
21st century. } { [%csl Gd3] } 9... Bf6 10. Re3 { White tries to keep
the rook on the 3rd rank and potentially introduce some ideas connected with
Bxh7 and Rh3. } { [%csl Ge3][%cal Rd3h7,Ge3h3] } 10... g6 { Dealing with the threat of Bxh7. } (10... a6 11. Bxh7+ { is a threat in the position, as after } 11... Kxh7 12. Qh5+ Kg8 13. Rh3 { Black is getting mated. } { [%cal Rh3h8] }) 11. b3 { Since all the pieces are blocking the center and preventing the d-pawn
from moving, White decides to develop the bishop to b2 - or even a3 -instead.
This is the main move in this position even today - which demonstrates that
old masters had a very good intuitive understanding of the game. } { [%csl Rc3,Rd3,Re3][%cal Gc1b2] } 11... Re8? { But this move is a mistake as it allows a very strong reply. } (11... b6 { From the theoretical perspective, trying to fianchetto the bishop is the most
sensible. The point is that this move also prepares to deal with the idea of
Ba3. } 12. Ba3 c5) 12. Qf3?! { A natural move, bringing the queen
into the game and trying to increase the pressure - but not the best move,
strictly speaking. } { [%cal Rf3f8] } (12. Ba3 { Casts a serious doubt on
Black's position as the positional threat of Bxd6 is incredibly annoying. A
couple of games here saw } { [%csl Rd6][%cal Ra3d6] } 12... Rxe3 13. fxe3 Ne8 { But here White has a very strong
sacrifice: } 14. Nd5 { And it is not advisable to accept the exchange due to } 14... Bxa1 15. Be7) 12... Bg5? { But this is already a serious imprecision, as
Black moves the same piece for the second time without any concrete
justification and falls desperately behind in development. } (12... Rxe3 { It was absolutely necessary to capture the rook on e3. The idea is to
coordinate the pieces after the recapture, say } 13. fxe3 Ne8 (13... Bxc3 { was seen in an old Soviet game between Liublinsky and Spassky's future trainer,
Bondarevsky. However, even though Black manages to ruin White's pawn structure,
two bishops are too big of a price to pay. } 14. dxc3) 14. Ba3 d5 { And Black manages to push in the center due to the pin on the knight on c3 and
will finish the development with Be6 next and should be close to equalizing
the position. } { [%cal Gc8e6] }) 13. Rxe8+ Nxe8 14. Bb2 { Now Black is not really in time to
play the space gaining d5 move, which gives White some time to build up the
initiative and create some threats! } 14... c6 { Hoping to play d5 next,
which would solve all problems (as it would allow Black to develop the
light-squared bishop and also to gain some space in the center and restrict
the opponent's pieces. } { [%cal Gd7d5] } (14... Bxd2 15. Bc4 { There is no good way of defending the f7 pawn ,for
example if } 15... Nd6 16. Ne4 Nxc4 { White has many ways to win, e.g. } 17. Nf6+ Kf8 18. Nxh7+ Kg8 19. Nf6+ Kf8 20. bxc4 { With overwhelming advantage due to the
difference in development and activity of the pieces. }) 15. Ne4 { This is the difference! Now that Black didn't manage to play d5 in time,
White manages to execute this knight jump as all the pieces are active and
developed and some threats begin to appear on the kingside. } { [%cal Re4g5] } 15... Be7 { Still, Black very much wants to play d5 next so White should try to find a
convincing follow-up. } { [%cal Gd7d5] } 16. Qe3 { Very strong play by Steinitz. The
intention is to play Qd4 and increase the pressure along the long diagonal.
This is the best move in the position, according to the engine. } { [%cal Ge3d4] } 16... d5 17. Qd4 f6 { The only defence against mating ideas, but now White can
make an argument that the king's shelter has been further compromised because
the pawns have been moved. } { [%csl Rf6,Rg6,Rh7] } 18. Ng3 { The best
square for the knight. It seems as if it is restricted severely by the pawn on
g6, but actually it helps prepare the subsequent h4-h5, further weakening the
kingside shelter. } { [%csl Gg3][%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5] } 18... Be6?! { A logical move, bringing the bishop
into the game, closer to the king and making room for the rook later down the
road. However, the computer doesn't think it is necessarily the most precise -
although its defensive resources are pretty crazy. } { [%cal Ga8h8] } (18... Qd6 { Is the move
computer wants to make. The idea is to fight against the h4-h5 plan with the
help of some crazy maneuvers. } 19. Re1 { Preventing Qe5 and bringing the rook
into the play. } (19. h4 Qe5 { Would be one idea by Black. }) 19... Bd7 { And now
if White tries the same push of the h-pawn there is an amazing defence. } 20. h4 Bd8 21. h5 Bb6! { Creating a nasty pin and threatening the
g3 knight. } { [%cal Rb6g1,Rd6g3] } 22. Qh4 g5! { And Black manages to repel the attack and suddenly
stands better as White has to move the queen to a very passive square. }) 19. Re1 Ng7 { But this is a little bit strange as it makes the knight
passive and also the bishop dependant on its protection, which gives White a
couple of moments to charge the h-pawn. } { [%csl Gg7] } (19... Nc7?! { Might be potentially better, as the knight has some hope of going to d5
in the future (after c4-d5 is played). } { [%cal Gc6c5,Gd5d4] }) (19... c5 20. Qf4 { might be worth doing as Black has another very creative defensive resource } 20... Qc7 { Indirectly defending the bishop on e6 and activating
the queen somewhat } { [%cal Ge8c7,Gc7e6,Rc7f4] } 21. Qf3 Bf7 { And Black can make an argument his pieces are
somewhat more active compared to the game, although after the same push of the
pawn } 22. h4 { White retains some advantage. }) 20. h4 Qd7 21. h5 { Very strong
and typical - ruining the structure on the kingside and opening some diagonals
and files. A typical procedure when it comes to the attacking play. } 21... Bf7 { Adding some more protection to the g6 pawn and removing the
bishop from the vulnerable e6 square is quite logical. } { [%cal Gf7h5] } (21... Nxh5 { Capturing
the pawn in any way isn't particularly attractive as after, say } 22. Nxh5 gxh5 23. Qe3 { [%cal Re1e6] } 23... Kf7 24. Bxh7 { Black can't survive with such a king for
too long. }) (21... gxh5 { Taking with the pawn is no better as after } 22. Qf4 { It is very tricky to defend all the weaknesses in the position } { [%csl Rf6] } 22... Kf7 23. Qh6 { White should be completely won here. } { [%csl Rf6,Rh5] }) 22. hxg6 Bxg6 { It looks a bit strange and unnatural to capture with the bishop here, but it
is actually the best move as Black is quite cramped so trying to exchange some
pieces is actually beneficial for them! } (22... hxg6 { Taking with the pawn is
very uncomfortable for Black too as after } 23. Qh4 { There
is a lot of pressure on the f6 pawn and it is very hard to defend it, e.g. } { [%cal Rh4f6,Rb2f6] } 23... Ne8 24. Ne2 { Now the knight comes to f4 and Black is actually not
helped by the fact that the bishop is still on the board on f7. } { [%cal Ge2f4] }) 23. Qe3 { A logical move, trying to gain a tempo to transfer the
queen somewhere to the kingside. However, it was not the only attacking move
at White's disposal. } { [%cal Ge3h6,Re1e7] } (23. c4 { It was possible to try to increase the pressure
in the center with the help of this undermining move. }) (23. Be2 { It was also
possible to try and move the bishop away and avoid the exchange of the bishops
as the c2 pawn is immune: } 23... Bxc2 24. d3 { The bishop will get trapped
with Qc3 next. } { [%csl Rc2] }) 23... Kf7 24. Qf4 { Creeping with the queen
closer to the kingside and eyeing the f5 square. But the problem is that the
queen on f4 isn't protecting the bishop on d3 any more. } { [%cal Ge3f3] } (24. Qf3 { Maybe not allowing the doubling of the d-pawns was preferable? In any case,
the main bulk of White's advantage seems to be gone, which probably means that
the whole sequence starting with 22.Qe3 wasn't the most precise. } { [%cal Gf3d3] }) 24... Re8?! { Returning the favour and missing the opportunity to exchange the bishops
before White can play Re3. } (24... Bxd3 { Taking on d3 and doubling the pawns
seems quite logical. I guess both players were under the impression that this
would exchange a vital defender of the kingside - but the computer - as usual,
finds an amazing defensive resource. } 25. cxd3 Kg6!! { Simply patching up all
the holes and covering the light-squares with the king seems to work out. No
human will ever play like this, of course - but this variation does reveal the
depth of defensive possibilities in positions like this one. }) 25. Re3 { The rook joins the action and threatens to go to
f3, increasing the pressure on the f6 pawn. } { [%csl Ge3][%cal Ge3d3,Ge3f3] } 25... Ne6? { But this is the losing
move - a one-move threat that actually forces the opponent's queen to go to a
nice aggressive post. } (25... Qd6 26. Qg4 Qb4 { Situation is not at all
so clear due to the hanging pawn on d2. } { [%cal Rb4d2,Rb4g4] }) (25... Bd8 { Creating the tension between the rooks on the e-file was also possible - and
probably even the best! The point is that now } { [%cal Re3e8,Re8e3] } 26. Rf3 Re1+ 27. Kh2 Ne6 { Is very harmonious for Black as the rook is activated on e1. } 28. Qg4 d4 { And it transpires that due to the activity of the pieces, Black is not even
worse any more. }) 26. Qg4 { A very nice post for
the queen, where she helps with f4-f5 and also supports Nf5 ideas. } { [%csl Gg4][%cal Gg3f5,Gf2f4] } 26... Nf8 { A shameful retreat, but it is hard to suggest what else should Black do in
this position. } (26... d4 27. Rxe6 Qxe6 28. Bc4) 27. Nf5 { The knight is very powerful here and
Black faces insurmountable difficulties since all White's pieces are
participating in the attack. } { [%csl Gf5][%cal Gf5h6] } 27... Bc5 { The only move in the position, seeking to
alleviate pressure with the help of osme exchanges. } (27... a6 28. Nh6+ { Starting a tactical sequence where White
will end up on top. } 28... Kg7 29. Bf5 { [%cal Rg4d7,Rg4g7] } 29... Qd8 30. Bxg6 { Not the
only winning move, but the most direct one. } 30... hxg6 (30... Nxg6 31. Nf5+ { Doesn't really change much as White has overwhelming advantage in the acitivty
of pieces. } 31... Kf7 32. Qh5) 31. Nf5+ Kf7 32. Qh4 { Threatening
the deadly Qh6-Qg7 , as well as Nxe7 and Qxf6. Black can't deal with both
threats. } { [%cal Rh4f6,Gh4h6] } 32... gxf5 (32... Qc7 33. Nxe7 Rxe7 34. Qxf6+ { Is also winning fairly
simply. }) 33. Qh5+ Ng6 34. Qh7+ { And next White will regain the knight on g6
with a decisive advantage. }) 28. Nh6+ Kg7 29. Nf5+ Kf7 30. Nh6+ Kg7 31. Nf5+ Kf7 32. Nh6+ Kg7 33. Nf5+ Kf7 34. Nh6+ Kg7 { The good old times before the
threefold repetition was a thing xD. But it suggests that Steinitz was
struggling to find the decisive blow and now the game starts taking a very
strange turn. } 35. Bxg6?! { Not a move that loses a massive amount of
advantage - but White really shouldn't be exchanging queens in this position. } (35. Qh4 { Was incredibly strong - simply attacking the f6 pawn and preparing
Ng4. This would have led to a decisive advantage - but possibly at this tense
moment, nerves started playing a crucial role? }) 35... Qxg4 36. Nxg4 Rxe3 { The only move, as both the rook and the pawn on f6 were under the attack. I
guess this is what Steinitz was counting on as the pawn on f6 will fall and
White should have a winning endgame - but only after the correct recapture on
the next move. } 37. fxe3? { A bad decision that makes the win much more
difficult - if possible at all. White voluntarily brings another pawn closer
to the center of the board and creates a situation where he doesn't have a
pawn majority on the kingside and where we have a 5v4 on the queenside
scenario - which makes the defense significantly simpler. } (37. dxe3 Kxg6 38. Nxf6 { Would have led to a won endgame as now White has a passed f-pawn and can
slowly start pushing the kingside pawns. In a situation like this, it is
necessary to create as much asymmetry as possible! }) 37... Kxg6 38. Nxf6 Bb4 39. d3 Ne6 (39... Be7 { Was worth considering, kicking the knight around with
the help of some tempo moves, e.g. } 40. Ng4 h5 41. Ne5+ Kf5 { And Black's
position is very sturdy and solid, despite White's extra pawn and I am not
100% sure whether this position is objectively won (even though in practice
White can torture the opponent forever). }) 40. Kf2 h5 41. g4? { Another
astounding decision. It is well known that in such endgames, reducing the
number of pawns is heavily in favour of the weaker side. Here Steinitz
voluntarily offers his opponent to eliminate the last kingside pawn and enter
a minor piece endgame with 4v5 scenario on the queenside. } 41... h4? { But this is
a fatal error that loses the game on the spot. Now White obtains a passed
g-pawn while the h-pawn will be permanently weak. Surely, Zukertort wasn't
really thinking about winning the game? } (41... hxg4 42. Nxg4 Kf5 { It is incredibly
difficult - if at all possible - to win this position as White - mainly
because it is very difficult to create a passed pawn under the right
circumstances. }) 42. Nh5 Bd6 43. Kg2 { Now the
king will go to h3 or the bishop to f6 and the h4 pawn will eventually be
collected. } { [%csl Rh4][%cal Gg2h3,Gb2f6] } 43... c5 44. Bf6 Ng5 { This makes the task easier, but it was already
difficult to offer any kind of advice to Black as the endgame is now purely
lost. Quite amazing to see the level of endgame play in the World Championship
match at a time. } 45. Bxg5 Kxg5 46. Kh3 Be5 47. Nf4 { A good deicison -
correctly evaluating the consequences of the resulting tactical mayhem. } 47... d4 { Trying to divert the defender of the f4 pawn had
to be taken into account on the previous move. } { [%csl Rf4][%cal Ge3d4,Re5f4] } (47... Bxf4 48. exf4+ Kxf4 49. Kxh4 { Leads to an easily won pawn endgame for White. }) 48. Ne6+ Kf6 49. exd4 { An annoying intermediate move, not giving Black time to
take the knight on e6. } { [%csl Re5][%cal Rd4e5] } 49... cxd4 (49... Kxe6 50. dxe5 Kxe5 51. Kxh4 { Once again
leads to a lost pawn endgame. }) 50. Nc5 { Now the knight attacks b7 and also
the h4 pawn is under the attack and Black might have as well resigned here,
although we have seen resignations came quite late for modern day standards in
this match - so it is not surprising that the game continues for a while. } 50... Kg5 51. Nxb7 Kf4 52. Na5 (52. Kxh4 { Was also good enough. }) 52... Bf6 53. Nc6 Ke3 54. Nxa7 Kd2 55. Nc6 Kxc2 56. a4 Kxd3 57. Nb4+ Ke2 (57... Kc3 58. Nd5+ { also wins for White: } 58... Kxb3 59. Nxf6 Kxa4 60. g5 { And the knight
will always be in time to stop the d-pawn. } { [%cal Gf6e4] }) 58. a5 Be7 59. Nd5 Kf3 { Trying to prevent Nf4. } { [%cal Gf3f4] } (59... d3 { doesn't help as after } 60. Nf4+ Ke3 61. Nxd3 Kxd3 62. a6 Bc5 63. g5 { One of the pawns will promote - the bishop is
too stretched! }) 60. Nxe7 d3 61. Nd5 { And the knight
will have no problems when it comes to dealing with the d-pawn, so Zukertort
finally resigned. A fascinating, tense struggle during which Steinitz was
winning for the majority of the game, but which also showcased that the skills
of converting the advantage and transitioning to the endgame weren't fully
mastered at a time. In any case, this was a much-needed win for Steinitz, who
reduced the score to 4-2 and gained some momentum, as the subsequent games
will demonstrate. } { [%csl Gc3][%cal Gd5c3] } 1-0


