{ Thus, after winning the 6th game of the match, Steinitz reduced the deficit
to "only" two points. More importantly, after managing to break the 4-game
losing streak and winning in relatively convincing fashion, the momentum was
definitely on his side! }
1. d4 { As usual in this match, Zukertort starts with
1.d4. } 1... d5 2. c4 e6 { This time, Steinitz deviates from 2...c6 which he usd in
the previous 3 games of the match and goes for the more classical queen's
gambit setup. } 3. Nc3 { In contrast to the previous games, where Zukertort
played e3 immediately, here he delays it for the moment, preferring to
pressure the d5 pawn instead. } 3... Nf6 4. e3 { But nevertheless, Zukertort employs
his favourite move, securing the center. By modern day standards, such play is
considered not-so-ambitious since the bishop on c1 is locked behind the pawn
chain, but it is, of course, very much playable. } 4... c5 { A thematic
strike in the center in all sorts of queen's gambit positions. Maybe in the
given instance, it is more precise to delay it for a bit and castle kingside
first, although sooner or later Black will play it anyway. } { [%cal Rc5d4] } (4... Be7 { Developing the kingside before playing on the queenside seems like a viable
idea as it reduces White's options to a certain extent and avoids the need to
transpose to some sort of Tarrasch position, say after } 5. Nf3 O-O { As now Black also has the extra option of taking on c4 if White
moves a bishop (winning the classical struggle for the tempo in the Queen's
Gambit). } { [%cal Gf1d3,Rd5c4] }) 5. Nf3 Nc6 { Now by transposition, we have reached a very
theoretical position of the e3 lines against Tarrasch/Semi-Tarrasch setups. } 6. a3 { This semi-waiting move, maintaining the tension in the center
and preparing the move b4 next, is the most common move in this position,
although by far not the only one. } { [%cal Gb2b4] } 6... dxc4 { A reasonable move, clarifying the
situation in the center a bit. It is true that it allows White to develop the
light-squared bishop with the gain of tempo, but it allows Black to initiate
the play on the queenside with a6-b5 next - which makes a lot of sense now
that White has moved the a-pawn once (as now playing a4 to prevent b5 would
cost another tempo). Note that this is not the only possibility in this
position - but it was played by some very high profile players such as Nepo,
Nakamura, Grischuk, Ding, etc. } 7. Bxc4 cxd4?! { But this is a mistake. Black
goes for the position with an isolated pawn where he has allowed White to
develop the bishop with the gain of time to c4 and where his knight will be on
c6 in a situation where the kingside pieces haven't yet been moved - which is
not necessarily the most favourable isolated queen's pawn position for Black.
However, it is hard to understand Steinitz's reasoning as this particular pawn
structure was not fully understood back in that time. } (7... a6 8. O-O (8. a4 Be7 { Should be very reasonable for Black. Yes, our queenside expansion has been
stopped, but we want to castle next and also can consider playing b6-Bb7 to
develop the light-squared bishop next. The fact that White lost quite a few
tempi, that the bishop on c1 is still locked and that Black has access to the
b4 square all work in the favour of the second player. } { [%csl Gb4][%cal Ge8g8,Gb7b6,Gc8b7] }) 8... b5 { A very
desirable move in all sorts of Queen's Gambit positions. Black should always
be a little careful when doing this before developing the kingside, but here
there isn't any danger associated with the quick d5 advance. } 9. Ba2 Bb7 { Black wants to play Qc7/Qb6, develop the
dark-squared bishop and castle in peace next. } { [%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8,Gd8c7,Gc7b6] }) 8. exd4 { So, we reach a
position with an isolated queen pawn which is a standard pawn structure that
can arise out of many openings. It is a very important pawn structure where
White's nominal deficiency in the pawn structure is compensated for in terms
of activity and dynamic potential - it is not at all uncommon for White to
generate play on the kingside in these positions or to break up the position
at the right moment with a timely d5 advance. --- So why is this particular
version very favourable for White? Well, the main reason is that Black took on
c4 at the moment when the bishop was on f1, allowing it to go to c4 at once.
Furthermore, in the meantime White made a useful move a3, covering the b4
square, which is a move they want to do in this structure anyway. It is not a
huge advantage, but usually Black obtains a more favourable version of this
structure in other openings, so it can definitely be regarded as an
achievement for White. } 8... Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Be3 { White develops the bishop and
covers the d4 pawn. It is definitely a natural looking move that is playable
in these structures, but I am not 100% sure if it is the most human way of
handling the position. As mentioned earlier, in this structure White generally
wants to create pressure on the kingside and control the d5 square - and the
text move doesn't achieve any of these aims. It is also not necessary to
defend the d4 pawn just yet. } (10. Re1 { Not blocking the e-file
and placing the rook seems to be a most common way of handling the position,
not yet determining the position of the dark-squared bishop. } { [%cal Re1e8] }) (10. Bg5 { I would also expect that the bishop would be better placed on g5, fighting
indirectly for the d5 square by attacking the f6 knight, although in the given
position with the bishop on e7 this is also not the most prudent timing for
this move (although keeping the option of going to g5 later instead of
developing to e3 might be worth investigating). }) 10... Bd7?! { But this is
also not the most precise. Steinitz finishes the development and connects the
rooks, but it will take a while to get the bishop to a purposeful square. } (10... b6 { Intending to fianchetto the bishop seems quite natural.
Usually, Black needs to take the advance of the d5 into consideration but here
the immediate } { [%cal Gc8b7] } 11. d5 { is not problematic due to } 11... Na5 { Not the
only move, but it makes sense to move the knight with a gain of tempo. } { [%cal Ya5c4] } 12. Ba2 exd5 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Bxd5 Bb7 { And Black manages to exchange some pieces and
liberate the position, reaching a symmetrical and equal position. }) 11. Qd3 { A good move, bringing the queen in the
center and preparing the standard Ba2-Bb1 battery. } { [%csl Gd3][%cal Gd3h7,Gc4a2,Ga2b1] } 11... Rc8?! { I am also not 100%
sure if this is the most necessary move in the position. } (11... Na5 { Perhaps
it was better to bring the bishop to an active diagonal with the help of this
knight maneuver, say after } 12. Ba2 Bc6 13. Ne5 { Although here Black should be
willing to exchange the bishop with } 13... Bd5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 { And now White obtains
the bishop pair, but Black at least exchanges some pieces (which is, generally,
in the favour of the second player in these isolated pawn positions), although
the position does remain somewhat unpleasant after } 15. Rac1) 12. Rac1 { A natural looking move, but I am not 100% sure if the rook belongs to the
c-file (or at least if it is the most urgent requirement in the position). } (12. Rad1) (12. Rfd1 Qa5 { Now this is met
very strongly by the advance of the d-pawn. } 13. d5 exd5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Bxd5 { The threat is now Bxf7 and Qxd7. } { [%cal Rd5f7,Rd3d7] } 15... Rfd8 16. b4 { The
difference compared to the variation that could have arisen in the game. The
rook on d1 adds some protection to the bishop on d5, which means that some
discovered attacks with Bf5 don't really work (as they will with the rook on
c1). } 16... Qc7 17. Qe4 { And now White threatens Bf4,
Rc1 is also coming and due to the difference in the piece activity, Black is
completely busted. } { [%cal Ge3f4,Re4e7,Rd5c6,Ga1c1] }) 12... Qa5 { A good move, activating the queen
and vacating the d8 square for the f8 rook. } { [%cal Gf8d8] } 13. Ba2 { White now
finally retreats the bishop and prepares the battery with Bb1 (now that the
rook has been moved to c1), but it turns out that such routine play in IQP
positions doesn't yield tangible benefits. } { [%cal Ga2b1] } (13. d5 { Even with the rook on c1,
White should have gone for the advance of the d-pawn. The difference is that
now after } 13... exd5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Bxd5 Rfd8 { Moving the b-pawn doesn't work as
Black has a nasty intermediate move } 16. b4?! (16. Bd2 { Instead
kicks the queen away under better circumstances and keeps some advantage for
White, although it is definitely not easy to evaluate such a symmetrical
position where there is a potential nasty pin looming along the d-file. } { [%cal Rd2a5] }) 16... Bf5 { If the rook were on d1, this wouldn't be possible, but
here the discovered attack on d5 saves the day for Black. } { [%cal Rd8d5,Ra5d5] }) 13... Rfd8 { Now Black will get the bishop to e8 and achieve quite a
harmonious setup. } { [%cal Gd7e8] } 14. Rfe1 Be8 { The bishop looks somewhat
passive here, but it does some additional protection to the kingside and gets
out of the way of the rook's influence over the d-file. } { [%cal Ge8g6] } 15. Bb1 { Since White can no longer achieve the d5 advance under good circumstances,
White now redeploys the bishop on the b1-h7 diagonal and tries to play for the
kingside attack. } { [%cal Rb1h7] } 15... g6 { Black nips
the battery in the bud and also intends to play Bf8-Bg7, followed by Ne7-Nd5,
with total control over the d5 square. This move also creates a potential
threat of e5. } { [%cal Rb1h7,Ge7f8,Gf8g7,Gc6e7,Ge7d5,Re6e5] } (15... Bf8 { It is also possible to start by moving the bishop,
but then White has time to go for } 16. h4) (15... e5 16. d5 { and now Black has no time to capture the
d5 pawn due to the hanging h7 pawn: } 16... Nxd5 17. Qxh7+ { This is precisely what 15.
..g6 is intending to prevent. }) 16. Qe2 { It is very human and
natural to sidestep the pin on the d-file, but it transpires that this is not
the most critical move in the position - even though the best move is
EXTREMELY difficult to find and understand from the human perspective, as we
will soon see. } { [%cal Gd8d1] } (16. h4 { Here, it looks logical to move the h-pawn and try to
pressure the g6 point, but here Black gains some time for } 16... e5 { when } 17. Qe2 { doesn't quite work that well as the pawn is on h4 and not on h3, so in the line } (17. d5 { Is not possible as after } 17... Nxd5 18. Nxd5 Qxd5 { White loses a pawn,
for which it is not an easy task to prove the compensation (even if the engine
does claim that the position is equal). }) 17... exd4 18. Nxd4 Nxd4 19. Bxd4 Rxd4 20. Qxe7 Qd8 21. Qxb7 Ng4 { Black gets a lot of counterplay. }) (16. h3 { Apparently, going for some semi-waiting move and
preventing any Ng4 tricks was the best way to handle the position. The point
is that now the advance of the e5 pawn doesn't quite work that well as after } { [%csl Gg4][%cal Gh3g4] } 16... e5 (16... Bf8 17. b4!! { And now taking the pawn on a3 is not possible as after } 17... Qxa3 (17... Qc7 18. b5 { Is also very bad for Black. }) 18. Nd5 { White wins material
with the help of the good old Nd5 tactical shot, executed under different
circumstances. }) 17. Qe2 exd4 18. Nxd4 Nxd4 19. Bxd4 Rxd4 20. Qxe7 Qd8 21. Qxb7 { The fact that the pawn is on h3 and not on h4 works hugely in White's favour
as there aren't any Ng4 ideas and White does win a pawn (even if converting it
will be an extremely challenging - if at all possible - task). }) (16. b4 { Doesn't work immediately as Black can simply take the pawn on a3: } 16... Qxa3 { And the knight on f6 is protected so there aren'y any
Nd5 tricks. } { [%csl Gf6][%cal Ge7f6] }) 16... Bf8 { Now with the queen on e2 Black
doesn't need to fear any sort of b4-Nd5 ideas and can just continue with the
desired maneuver. } { [%cal Gf8g7,Gc6e7] } 17. Red1 { White overprotects the d4 pawn, but this
switching into a defensive mode is rarely a good idea in the IQP positions as
Black's static/structural advantage needs to be disputed in more dynamic means. } (17. Ne4 { Jumping with the knight to e4 is apparently the best move. It
looks a bit counterintuitive to exchange pieces since I mentioned earlier it
generally favours Black in these structures, but with this move White either
brings the currently slumbering bishop on b1 into play or creates some
pressure against the f6 knight/on the dark-squares on the kingside. } 17... Nxe4 (17... Bg7 18. Bg5 { Is quite unpleasant for Black. }) (17... Nd5 18. Bg5 { Is also not very convenient for Black. }) 18. Bxe4 Bg7 19. Rc5 Qc7 20. Rec1 { And the pawn on d4 is indirectly defended and White has
some unpleasant pressure along the c-file. Of course, this was a somewhat
cooperative variation by Black (they didn't need to let the rook to c5), but
it illustrates how White can seek more active play in a position like this. } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Rc1c8] }) 17... Bg7 18. Ba2 { I think these last few moves illustrate very well how these
IQP positions were quite a big terra incognita back when this game was played.
Zukertort cotinues moving relatively aimlessly while Steinitz keeps improving
the position until he obtains a decisive strategic advantage. } (18. Qd2 { The immediate queen move, inteding to play Bg5 and fight
for the d5 square, was more prudent. This move also creates potential
discoveries against the queen on a5. } { [%cal Gd2g5,Rd2a5] } 18... Ne7 19. Bg5 Ned5 20. Nxd5 Qxd5 21. Qf4 { And apparently this position is balanced, although definitely easier to handle
for Black due to the eternal weakness of the d4 pawn. }) 18... Ne7 { Black now has quite a good control of the d5 square - while Bc6
is also coming. } { [%cal Ge7d5,Ge8c6] } 19. Qd2 { I am also not sure whether this move was necessary,
but White wanted to have a reply against Nd5 ready. } 19... Qa6 { Black sidesteps any
sort of Nd5 discoveries, but it is not 100% clear whether this was necessary. } (19... Ned5 20. Nxd5 Qxd2 21. Nxf6+ Bxf6 22. Bxd2 { When White wins a piece. }) (19... Bc6 { But it was possible to continue maneuvering and bringing the pieces
to optimal squares. Usually when the bishop appears on c6 in these positions
White can jump to e5, but here this is not so scary for Black as after } 20. Ne5 Nf5 { Black can change direction and jump to f5 (since
he has a very good control over the d5 square). Black is not worried about
Nxc6 as it would lead to more exchanges and since White would voluntarily give
up the good knight on e5. Now Black wants to challenge the knight, say with
Nd7 and White is again struggling with the weak pawn on d4 (although the
position is not desperate/lost by any means, of course). } { [%csl Rd4][%cal Rf5d4] }) 20. Bg5 { Now White
hits upon the right idea and starts fighting for the d5 square. } 20... Nf5 { Now it
turns out that this is not 100% accurate - but only due to a very hidden and
