chances in the resulting position. }) 21... Nxd4 { A logical move, simplifying
the position significantly. } (21... Ne7 22. Qf4 { There aren't any Nh5 resources so
Black is in significant trouble. } { [%csl Rf6] }) (21... Nxg4 22. Bxd8 Rxd8 { And this
position is quite unclear as White still has structural weaknesses and Black
has eliminated the opponent's pesky dark-squared bishop. Still, it is
understandable that Steinitz went for the game continuation. }) 22. Nxd4 e5 { The justification of the previous move, trying to
exploit the pin on the d-file. Also note how it is now useful to have the
