White has to give up material almost by force, as we will soon see. } { [%cal Rd1h1] } 32. Be7 (32. Bxh6 { Doesn't help as after } 32... Qh1+ 33. Kg3 Bxh6 34. Qxh6 Qg2+ { Black is
totally winning as f2 will fall next with check and Black will probably win
the queen on h6, as the following variations demonstrate. } 35. Kf4 (35. Kh4 Qxf2+ 36. Kg5 Qe3+ 37. Kf6 Qxh6) 35... Qxf2+ 36. Ke5 Qc5+ 37. Kf4 (37. Kf6 Qd6+ 38. Kg5 Qd2+ 39. Kf6 Qxh6) 37... Qd4+ 38. Kg3 Qg1+ 39. Kf4 Qc1+) 32... Be5+ { The strongest! } (32... Qh1+ { is also winning though. }) 33. f4 (33. Qxe5 { The bishop on e5 can't be taken as it would lead to the same tactical
pattern that also occurs in the game. } 33... Qh1+ 34. Kg3 Qf3+ 35. Kh4 Qxf2+ 36. Qg3 g5+ { And White loses the queen. }) 33... Bxf4+ { Nevertheless! } 34. Qxf4 Qh1+ 35. Kg3 Qg1+ 36. Kh4 Qe1+ 37. Qg3 g5+ { And here Zukertort resigned as
the queen on g3 will be lost. A very tense and instructive encounter that also
featured a few shocking mistakes and that also demonstrates how much our
understanding of the IQP positions - and chess game as a whole - has advanced
ever since (just like many other fields of human activity). In any case, after
this game, the gap in the match was reduced to a single point and a completely
new phase of the match began! } { [%cal Re1g3] } 0-1


[Event "Steinitz - Zukertort World Championship"]
[Site "St. Louis, MO USA"]
[Date "1886.02.10"]
[Round "9"]
[White "Johannes Zukertort"]
[Black "Wilhelm Steinitz"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Annotator "USER"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "D37"]
[Opening "Queen's Gambit Declined: Vienna Variation, Quiet Variation"]
[StudyName "Steinitz - Zukertort 1886 World Chess Championship"]
[ChapterName "Game #8"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/fB11Bc7Q/qfexKRiv"]

{ After 8 games in the World Chess Championship 1886, Johannes Zukertort still
maintain a +1 lead, but the momentum was clearly in Steinitz's favour as he
won two out of the last three games. In the 9th game - the final one to be
played in Saint Louis - Steinitz managed to continue his successful streak and
score another victory, equalizing the score. We are going to examine this game
now. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3 { The first surprise. Zukertort
refrains from the usual scheme of placing the pawn on e3 and decides to go for
a more mainstream variation of the Queen's Gambit. } 4... dxc4 { And Steinitz
deciedes to go for the Vienna variation - that is currently all the rage at
the top level. } 5. e3 { This is a safer, but also more modest approach to
handling the Vienna. White secures the d4 point and intends to recapture the
c4 pawn. But this gives Black time to strike in the center with c5 almost
immediately. } (5. e4 { Now Black has two options - the more standard
pin of the bishop to b4 - or the ultra modern and popular advance of the
b-pawn. } 5... Bb4 (5... b5)) 5... c5 { Striking in the center is very
thematic in all kinds of Queen's Gambit positions. } { [%cal Rc5d4] } (5... a6 { Intending to
play b5 or to force White to include a4 before taking on c4 is also possible -
and arguably a bit more precise as it limits White's options somewhat. But
whereas such minor details in the opening are very important in 2022, they
weren't nearly as relevant in 1886. }) 6. Bxc4 cxd4 { But this move is not the
most precise. The problem is that now we obtain a position with an isolated
pawn where White has placed the bishop on c4 in one go (without losing a tempo
to play Be2 or Bd3 first), which is inevitably in the favour of the first
player. } (6... a6 { This is why this little move, trying to either prepare b5
or to force White to play a4 and weaken the b4 square, is currently the most
popular move in this position! }) 7. exd4 Be7 8. O-O O-O { Once again -
positions with the isolated queen pawn were not fully understood back in the
day (and for many years afterward, though). } 9. Qe2 { This
is the second most common move in this position. White vacates the d1 square
for the rook and intends to potentially play for the very quick push of the d5
pawn. I am not a big expert in these positions, so take what I am going to
write with a grain of salt, but I always felt that the plans involving the
Bb1-Qd3, Bb1-Qc2 or Bc2-Qd3 battery are more dangerous. } { [%cal Gf1d1,Gd4d5] } (9. Re1 { Placing the
rook on the open file and keeping the queen flexible for the moment is the
main way of handling the position, with numerous games played. I guess in the
end the choice between these moves is to a large extent - a matter of taste. }) 9... Nbd7?! { But this seems to be an imprecision. The knight is headed toward
b6 via b5, but this is simply a very passive square for the knight.
Furthermore, on b6 it will control the d5 square, but it will relinquish any
control over the e5 square. } (9... a6 { Taking control over the b5
square and hinting at b5 with a gain of tempo is possibly a better way to
handle this position. } { [%cal Gb7b5] }) (9... Nc6 { It is also quite sensible to move the
knight to c6. It seems as if this runs into some Rd1-d5 ideas, but the point
of this move is to move the knight to the side of the board and then finish
the development with b6-Bb7. For example, after } 10. Rd1 Na5 11. Bd3 b6 12. Ne5 Bb7 { Black has at least managed to complete the development and has a nice
control over the d5 square - even if the knight on a5 is currently a bit
sidelined. I feel this is a better way of handling the position than what
Steinitz did although, once again - it is easy for me to say so when I am
checking the modern databases and engines. }) 10. Bb3 Nb6 11. Bf4? { But this
is just a very weak move. The bishop has absolutely no purpose on f4 and will
merely allow Black to gain a tempo by placing the knight on d5. } (11. Rd1 Nbd5 12. Ne5 { Now White starts to have some interesting attacking ideas such as Rd3-Rg3,
among others. Black is still suffering a bit as it is a bit tricky to develop
the queenside and this position is significantly better for White, despite the
fact that Black has a firmly entrenched knight on d5. }) 11... Nbd5 { Now this move comes with a gain of tempo. } { [%csl Rf4][%cal Rd5f4] } 12. Bg3?! { Another imprecision - the bishop doesn't really do much on g3.
One of the reasons why these IQP (isolated queen pawn) positions are not easy
to handle on a club level is - White has to play more energetically due to the
long-term strategic risk due to the static weakness associated with the
weakness of the d4 pawn. Routine play such as the one executed by Zukertort,
simply moving the pieces to some pseudo-active squares without real purpose
often leads into an inferior position. --- Furthermore, the bishop can easily
be eliminated with the help of some Nh5 move later. } { [%csl Rg3][%cal Gf6h5] } 12... Qa5 { Steinitz seemed to be fond of this maneuver in this type of position, but I
have to admit I haven't seen it in more modern practice, probably because it
is usually not optimal. The idea is to vacate the d8 square while also
pressuring the c3 knight, but it is very questionable whether the queen is
placed that well on the queenside. } { [%cal Ra5c3] } (12... b6 { Developing the bishop to b7 is
very harmonious and logical and probably should have been prioritized, as it
is always possible to determine the position of the queen much later. Now
taking on d5 doesn't have that much sense as after } 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Ne5 { Black has no problems with the development of the light-squared bishop. } 14... Bb7) 13. Rac1 { Again a little bit routine, defending the c3 knight but
failing to play in the most energetic manner. } { [%cal Gc1c3] } (13. Nxd5 { Surprisingly enough,
taking on d5 was much more energetic. The point is that after } 13... Nxd5 14. Ne5 { It is not super easy for Black to develop the bishop on c8 and the knight is
quite powerful on e5. For example, the natural rook move leads to some issues
after } 14... Rd8 (14... b6 15. Nc6 { loses on the spot. }) 15. Qh5 g6 16. Qf3 { A very
typical variation for these positions with the isolated pawn in which White
obtains a serious advantage in a very dynamic fashion. }) 13... Bd7?! { Insisting on developing the bishop to d7 and refraining from developing it to
b7. } (13... b6 { Was once again more harmonious as now there is also the idea
of Ba6, although it is a bit unnatural to play this move with the queen on a5. }) 14. Ne5 { Now we can see that the bishop on d7 is much
less happy than the bishop on b7. } { [%csl Rd7][%cal Re5d7] } 14... Rfd8 { A logical continuation of the entire
concept that begun with Qa5, but it transpires that this entire concept is
flawed. However, it would take a few generations until these positions would
be understood more properly. } 15. Qf3?! { This is a little bit meek/not the
most precise too. } (15. f4 { Advancing the f-pawn is the way to go in these
positions. The great patriarch Mikhail Botvinnik was the first to realize the
potential of the advance of the f-pawn in such positions in his game against
Milan Vidmar in Nottingham - played in 1936! I will refrain from further
analysis, but this idea in combination with Bh4, pressuring the kingside,
turns out to be very unpleasant for Black. }) 15... Be8 { Now Black achieves a very harmonious setup. This bishop retreat is a
very typical motif as now the rooks are connected and the vulernable f7 point
quite securely defended. } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Ge8f7] } 16. Rfe1 Rac8 17. Bh4 { Finally
Zukertort stumbles on the right idea. In many IQP positions, this bishop
belongs on the h4-d8 diagonal, fighting for the d5 square and sometimes
threatening to exchange itself for the knight on f6. } { [%cal Rh4d8] } 17... Nxc3 { Here Zukertort
decides to finally take on c3 and transform into a position with the
soc-called hanging pawns on c3 and d4. This is a typical transformation that
can happen in the IQP positions, but judging when is the best moment to go for
it is always a very difficult task as it allows White to fix the structure
somewhat! In the given instance, it was probably better not to go for it as it
is very hard to blockade the pawns (in particular the one on c3 by preventing
it from going to c4). } (17... Bc6) (17... b5 { was
pretty much playable, maintaining the status quo for the moment and keeping
the tension in the position! }) 18. bxc3 { Now White gets the
hanging pawns and their potential usually depends on the positioning and the
quality of the other pieces. On one hand, Black's setup is very harmonious,
but on the other hand, White's pieces are also quite active, which means that
White should be able to obtain a small edge. } { [%csl Gc3,Gd4] } 18... Qc7 19. Qd3? { White defends the d4 pawn in order to push c4, but this is not optimal
as now Black gets the opportunity to block the pawn from advancing. } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gd3d4] } (19. a4 { Preventing the idea of b5 was one possibility, although now White does leave
some dark-square weaknesses once the c4 pawn is pushed! }) (19. Bg3 { Harassing
the queen on c7 and then intending c4 is also possible, e.g. after } 19... Bd6 20. c4 { As now the d4 pawn is not hanging. } { [%csl Rd4][%cal Rd8d4] }) 19... Nd5?! { Missing the opportunity to stop the c-pawn in its tracks. } (19... b5 { Is a very storng blockading move, pretty much preventing the
c4 idea once and for all and making sure that the pawn on c3 is fixed/backward. } { [%csl Rc4][%cal Rb5c4] }) 20. Bxe7 { In principle, exchanging pieces helps Black as it reduces White's
attacking potential and they also have less space, although the advantages of
such approach are not as visible with the hanging pawns on the board as with
the isolated queen pawn. } (20. Bg3 { Keeping the bishops on the board was also
possible and objectively stronger. }) 20... Qxe7 21. Bxd5? { But this move is
horrible. White voluntarily gives up the good bishop on b3 for a blockading
knight on d5 and ends up in a bad version of the knight vs. bishop scenario.
Zukertort was maybe thinking that this bishop will be blocked if he plays c4,
but this move is the best evidence that these types of standard positions were
quite poorly understood at a time - even by the very best players in the world. } (21. c4 { For better or for worse, White should have pushed the c-pawn
immediately and kept the bishop on the board. In some cases, the bishop can
switch on the b1-h7 diagonal and create some threats against the king, but in
any case it is very influental in the center and there is no reason to give it
away like that. }) 21... Rxd5 (21... exd5 { which would be
positionaly desirable due to the fixing of the weakness on c3, but here White
has the deadly } 22. Ng6 { winning material by force. } { [%cal Rg6e7,Re1e7] } (22. Nc6 { [%cal Rc6d8,Rc6e7] })) 22. c4 { Finally
advancing the hanging pawns, but now this comes under much less favourable
circumstances. } { [%csl Rd5][%cal Rc4d5] } 22... Rdd8 23. Re3 { This is what Zukertort was aiming for - he
indicates he is planning to go for some sort of a kingside attack, but in a
position like this with limited amount of pieces, it simply can't work. } 23... Qd6 { Increasing the pressure on the d-file and on the d4 pawn. } { [%cal Rd8d3] } 24. Rd1 f6 { Kicking the knight away from e5. You can notice how Black
is slowly pushing White's forces away and intending to play against the weak
pawns on the open c and d-files. This is a typical scenario for these
positions with hanging pawns if White doesn't play precisely and energetically. } { [%csl Re5,Rf6] } 25. Rh3! { Absolutely the best reply in the position. Instead of going down
quietly and positionally, Zukertort decides to follow his previous sharp play
and tries to create some threats on the kingside. This not only leaves the
knight en prise, but virtually forces Black to weaken the kingside further and
create some potential for the knight sacrifices later in the game. } (25. Nf3 { Going back to the knight would be extremely meek and an admission of the
failure. Black has many good moves out of which the most powerful seems to be: } 25... Qa6 { Attacking both c4 and a2. Here you can notice how
gladly White would have the bishop on b3 that would glue the entire position
together. Here after } { [%cal Ra6c4,Ra6a2] } 26. Rc1 b5 { Black has a large advantage and White faces
an uphill and cheerless battle for survival. }) 25... h6 { Also the best - and
also very practical - move in the position. Black refrains from entering any
sort of complications involving the capture of the knight and simply deals
with the threat of Qxh7. } (25... fxe5 { Capturing the knight would be
completely impractical as it would lead to murky complications - which is
exactly what White is hoping for. For example, one possible variation is } 26. Qxh7+ Kf8 27. Rf3+ Bf7 28. Qh8+ Ke7 29. Qxg7 { And here Black has to be
extremely careful. White already has the two pawns for the piece and also an
ongoing initiative, which provides him with sufficient compensation for the
sacrificed material - and with an easier position to handle. }) 26. Ng4 { Now some sacrifices on h6 and f6 are in the air due to the
weakening of the Black's kingside shelter. } { [%cal Rg4h6,Rg4f6] } 26... Qf4 { A good move, covering all the threats and also attacking the knight on
g4. } { [%csl Rg4][%cal Gf4h6,Gf4f6] } 27. Ne3 Ba4 { Another good move, distrubing the
rook on d1! } { [%csl Rd1][%cal Ra4d1] } 28. Rf3?! { But this is not the best decision. Rook does gain a
tempo on the queen, but the queen wanted to retreat anyway, while the rook
will be somewhat exposed and the advance of the f-pawn becomes a serious idea. } (28. Rd2 { It transpires that simply moving the rook up the d-file was the best
move, due to a very surprising variation starting with } 28... f5 29. g3 Qd6 30. d5 { whne Black has to find the crazy } { [%csl Rf5][%cal Re3f5] } 30... b5 { with a very
complicated and murky position, where Black should have the upper hand, but
where the situation is much more messy compared to what happened in the game. }) 28... Qd6 29. Rd2 Bc6?! { Also not the best reaction! } (29... f5! { Advancing the f-pawn was very strong. The point is that now } { [%cal Gf5f4] } 30. d5 { is met with } (30. g3 { Preventing the f4 advance might be the best move, but
here after some } 30... b5 { White's pieces are somehow stuck and Black
has a clear initiative - especially since White had to play the move g3
voluntarily, without gaining a tempo against the Black queen. } { [%csl Re3,Rf3] }) 30... f4) 30. Rg3? { Also not the best idea. Zukertort wants to threaten Qg6
or Rg6, but Steinitz calculates better and finds a nice refutation of this
attacking mechanism. } { [%cal Gd3g6] } (30. d5 { should
have been played. The idea is that in the line involving the undermining } 30... b5 (30... Be8 { Is safer and also possible, just maintaining the tension, although
Black doesn't have a big advantage here, either, objectively. }) 31. Rxf6 { A beautiful sacrifice that can't really be accepted. } 31... bxc4 { This is already
the only move, seeking to destroy White's cneter or obtain a strong passed
c-pawn. } (31... gxf6 32. Qg6+ Kf8 (32... Kh8 33. Qxh6+ Kg8 34. Qg6+ Kh8 35. Rd4 { Also wins on the spot! } { [%cal Gd4h4] }) 33. Qxf6+ Kg8 34. Qg6+ Kf8 35. dxe6 { is even winning for White! }) 32. Qg6 c3 33. Qf7+ Kh8 34. Rxh6+ gxh6 35. Qf6+ { And here things finally end in a perpetual check as after } 35... Kh7 36. Qf7+ Kh8 37. Qf6+ Kh7 { The same is completely equal. }) 30... f5 31. Rg6 { I guess this was the point of Zukertort's idea, but the cheapo of Nxf5 is very
easily dealt with. } { [%cal Rg6d6,Re3f5] } (31. c5 Qe7 32. Nc4 { The threat of
activating the knight via d6 or e5 is significant. } { [%csl Rc4][%cal Gc4d6,Gc4e5] } 32... Bb5 { Pinning the knight and intending to eliminate it on the next move, as Black
put the pawns on the light squares and has some serious weaknesses on the dark
squares. } { [%csl Rd3][%cal Rb5d3] } 33. Qc2 { Trying to escape the pin and jump with the pony anyway. } 33... Bxc4 34. Qxc4 Rxc5 { A nice tactical shot, utilizing the pin on
the d-file. } { [%cal Rd8d2] } 35. dxc5 Rxd2 36. h3 { And Black should objectively be winning in
a position like this, but it is a loong way until it will be converted into a
full point. A large part of resisting in inferior positions involves making
our opponent's job as difficult as possible, so I imagine a line like this one
would be automatically chosen by a number of modern grandmasters. }) 31... Be4 { Defending the f5 pawn with a gain of tempo. Now
White's rook on g6 will be stuck out of the game, the king is weak on the back
rank and the pawns on d4 and c4 are quite exposed, which means that White's
position is suddenly strategically winning. } { [%csl Rd3][%cal Ge4f5,Re4d3] } 32. Qb3 Kh7 { A simple move, exploiting the bad position of the rook on g6. } { [%csl Rg6][%cal Rh7g6] } 33. c5 { Trying to complicate matters by attacking the e6 pawn, but White's piece
coordination is too weak for such fancy tactical ideas to really work. } 33... Rxc5 { A strong reply, utilizing the pin on the d-file once again. } { [%cal Gc5c1,Rd8d2] } 34. Rxe6 Rc1+ { And now also utilizing the weakness of the back rank to force a
major concession! } 35. Nd1 { White's position is pretty hopeless at this point. } (35. Rd1 Rxd1+ 36. Nxd1 (36. Qxd1 Qxe6) 36... Qxd4 { When both Bd5 and Qxd1 are threatened and White is dead lost. } { [%cal Rd4d1] }) (35. Nf1 { Is maybe slightly more resistant, although the position remains completely
lost after any simple queen retreat, such as } 35... Qc7 { Black's pieces are simply dominating the position.
The current threat is Rxf1, as well as Bd5 and White can't deal with both. } { [%csl Gc1,Gc7,Ge4][%cal Rc1f1,Ge4d5,Rd5b3,Rd5e6] }) 35... Qf4 36. Qb2 (36. Qe3 { Loses to } 36... Qxe3 37. fxe3 Bc2 { Winning
the sad knight on d1. } { [%csl Rd1] }) 36... Rb1 37. Qc3 Rc8 { A nice diversion, although in
such a winning position, it is easy to find winning moves. } 38. Rxe4 Qxe4 { And here Zukertort finally decided to resign the game and thus, Steinitz
managed to equalize the match before it moved from Saint Louis to Morphy's
hometown of New Orleans, where the entire battle was about to start anew! } 0-1


[Event "World-ch01 Steinitz-Zukertort +10-5=5"]
[Site "USA"]
[Date "1886.02.08"]
[Round "8"]
[White "Steinitz, William"]
[Black "Zukertort, Johannes Hermann"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[Annotator "mistr"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C67"]
[Opening "Ruy Lopez: Berlin Defense, Rio Gambit Accepted"]
[StudyName "Steinitz - Zukertort 1886 World Chess Championship"]
[ChapterName "Game #9"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/fB11Bc7Q/oCVviPIC"]

{ Thus after winning the 6th and 7th games, Steinitz reduced the score to just
-1, and the momentum in the match clearly shifted in his favour! In the 8th
game he again had the White pieces, so he was surely looking to strike when
the iron was hot. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1 Nd6 6. Nxe5 { So far, we have seen the same variation as in Steinitz's previous White
game. } 6... Be7 { But here Zukertort is first to deviate from the previous game and
plays a different move, blocking the action along the e-file and threatening
the bishop on b5. } (6... Nxe5 7. Rxe5+ Be7 8. Nc3 { Was how the 6th game went,
which was - as you might recall - won by Steinitz after a fascinating battle. }) 7. Bd3 { Steinitz once again deploys the bishop on d3 as in the previous game
and seeks to gain some attacking chances. } 7... O-O 8. Qh5 { The justification of
previous play, threatening mate in one and trying to force a weakening on the
kingside. } 8... f5 { Limiting the scope of the bishop on d3 and playing in a more
ambitious way, not allowing the immediate draw involving a sacrifice on g6. } (8... g6 { Is also playable, but among other things it allows } 9. Nxg6 fxg6 10. Bxg6 hxg6 11. Qxg6+ Kh8 12. Qh6+ { With repetition. It would be very
interesting to see if Steinitz would have gone for this in case Zukertort
played this and what was Zukertort's reasoning of avoiding it. I guess quick
professional draws were not considered particularly attractive back in 1886
and players considered it as a matter of principle to play for a win (although
I may be reading too much into it). }) 9. Nc3 { A natural developing move,
although it does allow an exchange on e5. } (9. Nxc6 { Mabye it was worth
including this exchange in order to avoid Nxe5-Bf6 maneuver that could have
occurred to the game, although this would have opened the d-file and widened
the scope of the bishop on c8 after } 9... dxc6 { It is very debatable which approach
was better. }) 9... Nxe5 10. Rxe5 g6 { It is also unclear whether including this
move to force the queen away and defend the f5 was necessary. } (10... Bf6 { Black could have deployed the dark-squared bishop on the long diagonal with a
gain of tempo. } 11. Re1 b6 { And then prepared to fianchetto of the other
bishop to b7, achieving a very harmonious position with all pieces developed.
Maybe this is a bit more promising compared to the game, although in either
case Black has a very reasonable position - it is debatable whether such early
attacking concept with Bd3-Qh5 should realistically work for White. }) 11. Qf3 { Now the queen is preventing the b6-Bb7 plan, although Black has alternative
ideas/ways to develop. } 11... c6 { Black covers the d5 square and prepares Nf7 and
then d5, gaining a share in the center. White actually needs to be very
careful now not to be worse. } 12. b3? { White follows the same developing
scheme that brough him a lot of success in the previous game, but this is
faulty in this particular case as it doesn't deal with Black's idea. } (12. Re1 Nf7 13. Bf1 { Also moving the bishop away. } 13... d5 14. d4 { And finally placing the d-pawn in the center! Black is very pleasant
in this position as they have no weaknesses, White has no attack, the
structure is symmetrical and Black also has a nice potential outpost on e4.
But objectively, this should be around equal and would have been significantly
much better for White compared to what happened in the game. }) 12... Nf7 { Now this comes with a tempo on the rook and Black is ready to push the d-pawn
next. } 13. Re2?! { But this is another imprecision. White is trying to be
clever and leave the rook on e2 in order to have the e1 square available for
the other rook, but it turns out that this leaves the queen on f3 very short
on squares. } (13. Re1 { For better or for worse, White should have retreated
the rook all the way back to e2. The point is that now the e2 square is
available for the queen and after } 13... Ng5 14. Qe2 Ne6 15. Bb2 { Black at least
doesn't have the same f4-f3 ideas that might come with tempo and White's
position is more harmonious compared to what happened to the game. }) 13... d5?! { Not a bad move, gaining space in the center and opening up the bishop on
c8, but the alternative idea of Ng5 was possibly stronger. } (13... Ng5 { It was also possible to start with the immediate jump of the knight, hitting
the queen and forcing her to an uncomfortable square. } 14. Qe3 (14. Qg3 f4 { Is not an improvement for White. }) (14. Qf4 Ne6 { Also allows Black to play Ne6
with a gain of tempo. }) 14... Ne6 { And now with the queen on e3 and the rook
on f2 the pawn advance f4-f3 is a constant threat (potentially weakening the
White queenside) and Black is clearly in the driver's seat. It is actually
somewhat surprising to see how massively the engine evaluates this in Black's
favour (around -3), but when you consider the placement of the pieces, it does
make some sense. }) 14. Bb2?! { Developing the bishop and continuing with the
plan. Probably it was better to retreat the rook to e1 and open up the e2
square for the queen, along the previous lines, but as it is. } 14... Bf6? { But
this move is a serious mistake, as it misses the crucial moment to harass the
White queen and improve the knight on f7. It turns out that the bishop on e7
was not the most urgent piece that required some improvement and that this
gives White time to bring the rook to e1 and initiate the exchange of these
bishops with Nd1 (and exchanging pieces will be definitely in White's favour
due to the fact he has less space). } (14... Ng5 { Now was the last
opportunity to harass the queen on f3 as after } { [%cal Rg5f3] } 15. Qe3 Ne6 { a very similar variation compared to the variation we have seen
previously arises where the queen on e3 and the rook on e2 are lacking
coordination and f4-f3 ideas are on the cards. Also, in some instances the
bishop on e7 can go to g5 - which is why it was not a bad idea to retain its
flexibility for the moment as it has more option later down the road! } { [%cal Gf5f4,Gf4f3] }) 15. Rae1 { Now White manages to coordinate to a certain extent. Furthermore, with
the bishop on f6, the f-file is covered so potential counterplay with f4 is
less deadly. } 15... Qd6 { Continuing the development and preparing Bd7, now that the
queen is on a more active square d6. } (15... Ng5 { Is not as powerful here as
after } 16. Qf4 Ne6 { is not possible now: } 17. Rxe6 { and White just wins -
plain and simple. }) 16. Re8 { The best move, seeking some exhanges! As
mentioned earlier, White has less space, so any exchange is definitely to his
benefit. } 16... Bd7 17. Rxa8 Rxa8 18. Nd1 { Seeking more exchanges
and highlighting one of the downsides of placing the bishop on f6 earlier. } { [%cal Gd1b2,Rb2f6] } 18... Ng5 { Gaining a tempo on the queen to improve the knight, but this comes a little
bit too little, too late. } 19. Qe2 Re8 20. Qf1 Bxb2?! { The final imprecision,
giving up all the chances to fight for the initiative. } (20... d4 { Trying to
keep more pieces on the board and shut down the bishop on b2 (and the knight
on d1, as well) was the only attempt to fight for an advantage. White would
probably have to try to undermine this construction with, say } 21. Rxe8+ Bxe8 22. c3 { when after } 22... c5 23. cxd4 cxd4 { The pawn
on d4 secures the space advantage and is limiting two of White's minor pieces.
With the rooks exchanged, this is less favourable for Black compared to the
lines that could have arisen earlier, bu it is still more than what happened
in the game. } { [%csl Yb2,Yd1,Gd4][%cal Rd4c3] }) 21. Rxe8+ Bxe8 22. Nxb2 { And here, maybe even somewhat
surprisingly, the players agreed to the first draw in the match. Strictly
speaking, it is a perfectly reasonable decision since the position is dead
equal due to the symmetry, lack of weaknesses and limited amount of pieces on
the board. Thus, Zukertort kept his lead and the tension in the match was
maintained. } 1/2-1/2


[Event "Game 10"]
[Site "USA"]
[Date "1886.02.26"]
[Round "10"]
[White "Steinitz, William"]
[Black "Zukertort, Johannes Hermann"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[Annotator "mistr"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C67"]
[Opening "Ruy Lopez: Berlin Defense, Rio Gambit Accepted"]
[StudyName "Steinitz - Zukertort 1886 World Chess Championship"]
[ChapterName "Game #10"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/fB11Bc7Q/GwZzjPBL"]

{ Thus, after 9 games of the 1886 World Chess Championship between Zukertort
and Steinitz, the match was tied at 4-4 (draws not counting). Starting from
game 10, the match was moved to New Orleans (from Saint Louis) and entered a
new and a very tense stage. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1 Nd6 6. Nxe5 Be7 7. Bd3 O-O { So far we have been following the same variation
of the Berlin that was also featured in the 8th game. But here Steinitz is the
first to deviate! } 8. Nc3!? { A very interesting move, bringing the knight
into the game and intending to develop the bishop via b3-Bb2/Ba3. Even to this
day, it has become a very relevant option that was played in quite a few
high-profile games. } 8... Nxe5 9. Rxe5 c6 { This is one of the two main moves. Black takes the d5 square under control,
limits the knight on c3 and intends to move the knight from d6 and play d5 in
the near future. } { [%csl Rc3,Gd5][%cal Gc6d5,Gd7d5,Gd6e8] } (9... Bf6 { Kicking the rook away with this immediate bishop
move is another possibility. There are quite a few high-profile games here
involving the name of the strong American grandmaster Dominguez Perez Leinier,
who is the main proponent of this variation with White. }) 10. b3 { White continues with the idea of developing the bishop and placing it
to either b2 or even a3. } { [%cal Gc1b2] } 10... Re8? { But this is not a very precise move, as it
allows White to create a very unpleasant pin and restrict the opponent's
pieces to a certain extent. } (10... Ne8 { Black should have moved
the knight to e8 and then aimed to get a fair share in the center with the
help of the move d5 next. This thematic knight maneuver is very thematic in
these Berlin positions and is definitely the best move in this particular one. } { [%cal Gd7d5] }) 11. Ba3 { Pressuring the knight on d6 and the bishop on e7
and introducing some potential threats of Rxe7 if Black is not careful. White
also simply wants to double on the e-file next and Black already needs to be
extremely careful here. } { [%cal Ra3f8,Re5e7] } 11... Bf8 { The best move, retreating
the bishop to a safe square and challenging the rook on e5 immediately. } { [%csl Gf8][%cal Re8e5] } 12. Re3? { But this move is too meek as it allows Black to simplify the position
by exchanging some pieces and solve the majority of the problems. } (12. f4 { Advancing the f-pawn was the best way to maintain the tension and keep the
pressure. It turns out it is extremely difficult for Black to find a good
reply now all of a sudden, as taking on e5 doesn't lead to anything good: } 12... Rxe5 13. fxe5 Ne8 14. Bxf8 Kxf8 15. Qh5 { And due to the difference in
piece activity and the fact that the knight on e8 is severely restricted by
the pawn on e5, White is completely winning. } { [%csl Rf8] }) 12... Rxe3 13. fxe3 (13. dxe3 { Opening the d-file and trying to preserve a bit more
asymmetry in the position was maybe a better attempt to keep some life in the
position, although White's advantage is small, if tangible, at all. } { [%csl Ge3,Gf2,Gg2,Gh2] }) 13... Ne4 { A very nice simplifying tactical idea, inviting
some further exchanges due to the exposed bishop on a3. The knight also moves
out of the way of the d-pawn, allowing Black to plan for the thematic d5,
opening up the bishop and finishing the development. } { [%csl Ra3][%cal Rf8a3,Re4c3] } 14. Bxf8 Nxc3 15. Qh5 { A smart intermediate move, not allowing Black to ruin the pawn structure on
the queenside and isolate the e-pawn. } (15. dxc3 { There is nothing
majorly wrong with the immediate capture on c3, but it does isolate the e3
pawn and provides Black with a long-term static advantage, meaning that White
will be the one who will have to defend the subsequent position. } { [%csl Re3] } 15... Qxf8) 15... g6 { The best move, kicking the queen away and not
allowing any attacking chances that could have appeared if Black captured on
f8. } { [%csl Rh5][%cal Rg6h5] } (15... Kxf8 { Well, here White has the devilish } 16. Rf1 { Threatening mate on f7. } { [%csl Rf7][%cal Rf1f7] } 16... Qe8 (16... g6 17. Bxg6) 17. Qxh7 d5 18. Bg6 { When the attack crashes through and White will be the one
winning the material and obtaining a completely winning position. }) 16. Qe5 { One of justifications behind White's queenside
excursion! Mate on g7 is threatened, but the knight on c3 is also attacked,
meaning that White will be able to capture on c3 with the queen and avoid the
worsening of the pawn structure. } { [%csl Rc3][%cal Re5c3,Ge5g7] } 16... Qxf8 17. Qxc3 Qg7 { Initiating further
exchanges, although at this point, any move was sufficient for equality. } 18. Qxg7+ Kxg7 19. e4 { Trying to restrict the pawn on d7, but also
limiting the bishop. In any case the position is dead equal as the pawn
structure is almost symmetrical and the material is heavily limited. } { [%csl Rd7,Ge4] } 19... d6 20. Re1 Bd7 21. Kf2 Re8 { And here the players agreed to a draw, which is very
sensible as such a position is dead equal and can only be won if one side
makes a major blunder - which is unrealistic to expect on such a level, even
if we saw some shocking mistakes earlier in the match. } 1/2-1/2


[Event "World-ch01 Steinitz-Zukertort +10-5=5"]
[Site "USA"]
[Date "1886.03.01"]
[Round "11"]
[White "Zukertort, Johannes Hermann"]
[Black "Steinitz, William"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Annotator "Nemec Vjekoslav"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C49"]
[Opening "Four Knights Game: Spanish Variation, Gunsberg Counterattack"]
[StudyName "Steinitz - Zukertort 1886 World Chess Championship"]
[ChapterName "Game #11"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/fB11Bc7Q/bnNdDbX6"]

{ Thus, after 10 games, the score in the 1886 World Championship Match remained
tied and the match intrigue continued in the important 11th game, where
Zukertort had the White pieces again. }
1. e4!? { Probably a bit of a surprise.
Since his results in the White games weren't spectacular so far, Zukertort
switches from 1.d4 and plays 1.e4 - a move that was his main weapon throughout
his career - for the first time in the match. } 1... e5 { This was to be expected
from Steinitz, as he hardly played anything else throughout his career. } 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 { But this was a bit of surprise. Zukertort has played this move
only a few times in his career, usually preferring to develop the
light-squared bishop either to c4 or to b5. } 3... Nf6 { But this is also a bit of a
surprise, potentially, given that Steinitz played this only once - back in
1867. } (3... g6 { Throughout 1882 and 1883, Steinitz used to regularly move his
g-pawn in this position, which is not the best way of handling this variation.
Possibly, Zukertort was aware of this and hoped to see this on the board? }) 4. Bb5 { An old move, attacking the knight on c6 and
pressuring the pawn on e5. Nowadays, it has been demonstrated that White has
no objective advantage here, although this move does remain a playable option
and was seen in some very high profile games. } { [%csl Re5][%cal Rb5c6,Rf3e5] } 4... Bb4 { An older reaction that is
also the most common move in the position. Black sticks to the "copycat"
approach and pressures the c3 knight and - consequently - the e4 pawn as well. } (4... Nd4 { Some 20-30 years later, the great and creative Akiba Rubinstein
would introduce this creative knight jump into the practice. This move
involves a pawn sacrifice (as the pawn on e5 hanging) and is much sharper than
4...Bb4, but it hasn't been refuted to this day and several top players such
as Ding, Nepomniachtchi, Caruana and Dominguez Perez have employed it in their
respective careers. To a large extent, Black's choice here is a matter of
taste. }) 5. O-O { The most common move, simply continuing the development and
not being tempted with the e5 pawn. } (5. Bxc6 { White can't really afford to
grab the pawn on e5. } 5... dxc6 6. Nxe5 { Here Black has several ways of regaining
the pawn on e4 back, for example after } 6... Qe7 { [%cal Re7e4] } 7. f4 Bxc3 8. bxc3 Nxe4 { These positions should be quite equal and this is definitely not the way
to go for White. }) 5... O-O { Continuing in the same copycat style and asking
White to demonstrate a plan. } 6. Nd5?! { This
move is a logical follow up in situations where the knight is developed on c3,
but in this specific position, it is a bit premature. } { [%csl Rd5][%cal Rd5b4,Rd5f6] } (6. d3 { Continuing with
the natural looking moves, reinforcing the e4 pawn and intending to maybe
bring the c3 knight to the kingside via e2-g3 seems more natural. In that case,
we would get a position resembling some sort of Ruy Lopez/Berlin, where slow
play and maneuvering are in order. }) (6. Bxc6 { It is also possible to take on
c6 in order to ruin the structure and then go for the advance of the d2 pawn. } 6... dxc6 7. d3 { Although in these positions - which usually arise from the Berlin
- White would rather have the knight on d2, from where it can jump to c4 and
potentially a5. With the knight on c3 that is kinda being restricted by the
pawn on c6, White has no advantage, although Black's long-term deficiency in
the structure (doubled pawns) doesn't make this position an automatic and dead
draw and there is a lot of play left! }) 6... Nxd5 (6... Nxe4 { Of course,
grabbing the pawn on e4 would be huge blunder as the bishop on b4 is
indirectly attacked! } 7. Bxc6 { Eliminating the defender! } { [%csl Gb4][%cal Rd5b4] } 7... dxc6 8. Nxb4 { And White wins the piece and the game. }) 7. exd5 e4! { A very typical procedure in 1.e4 e5 openings - the pawn
on e4 has been removed, so Black takes the opportunity to advance their own
pawn, remove it from the attack and threaten the knight on f3. } { [%csl Rf3][%cal Re4f3] } 8. dxc6 { Perhaps not the most pragmatic decision, as it allows Black to open some
diagonals for the bishops. } (8. Ne1 { Retreating the knight was recommended by
some commentators as the best option, although this was clearly not what
Zukertort had in mind when he embarked on the entire 6.Nd5 concept. With such
a passive knight, it is clear that White can't count on a serious advantage,
although the game continues. }) 8... exf3 9. Qxf3 { The best move. White doesn't
really have time to be greedy and take on d7 or b7. } (9. cxb7 Bxb7 { Is also
pretty bad for White as the kingside is under a lot of pressure. } 10. g3 (10. gxf3 Qg5+ $19) 10... Qg5 { And the pawn on f3 is a
strong asset, Qh5-Qh3 is threatened and the bishop on b7 is a monster. White
is actually just dead lost here. } { [%csl Rg1][%cal Gb7h1,Gg5h5] }) (9. cxd7 fxg2 $17 { Is very much horrible
for White. }) 9... dxc6 { A better recapture, opening the
light-squared bishop immediately. } { [%cal Gc8h3] } 10. Bd3?! { White blocks
the pawn on d3 and hopes to get the bishop to b2 via b3-Bb2, but it will
transpire that this developing scheme is flawed as the pawn on d2 can come
under the attack. } { [%cal Gb2b3,Gc1b2] } (10. Bc4 { Next,
White wants to play d3/d4 and then develop the dark-squared bishop. Black has
a slight lead in development, but their structure is worse, which means that
the position is probably objectively equal. } { [%cal Gd2d3] }) 10... Bd6 { A logical move, even
though it violates the principle of moving the same piece twice in the opening.
The bishop wasn't doing much on b4, so Steinitz repositions it on a more
active post on d6, while keeping the flexibility of the bishop on c8. Other
moves are also possible. } 11. b3?! { But this whole idea involving the
development of the bishop to b2 is faulty precisely due to Steinitz's next -
very accurate response. } (11. Re1 Qg5 12. Bf1 { And next White wants to play d3 and develop the
dark-squared bishop. Not the most ambitious approach, but also a very safe one. } { [%cal Gd2d3] }) 11... Qg5 { A very accurate move, attacking the d2 pawn
and preventing White from developing the bishop on c1. Also, the threat is now
Qe5. } { [%cal Rg5d2,Gg5e5] } 12. Bb2? { Zukertort decides to give up the d2 pawn, hoping for some
compensation when Black captures it, but it turns out that this concept isn't
objectively correct. } (12. h3?? { White had to be careful, though. For example,
a careless move such as this one would already lose to } 12... Qe5 $19 { With the dual threat of Qxa1 and Qh2 mate, ensuring that Black wins on
the spot! } { [%cal Re5a1] }) (12. Re1 { It was still better to revert to a variation that was
mentioned in the context of the previous line, put the rook on the open file
and prevent Qe5. White still needs to be careful as the pressure on d2 is
annoying, but it is much better to do so and not to give up the d2 pawn for no
reason. }) 12... Qxd2 { Steinitz was very known for his principled play and
would quite often take the offered material - even under much less favourable
circumstances than here. } 13. Bc1 { I guess this was the point of
Zukertort's idea. The queen is now kicked away from the kingside and to the
kingside - but irrespective of that, White is unable to really create some
actual threats. However, it is hard to come up with a convincing alternative. } { [%cal Rc1h6] } (13. Qe4 { Looks strong, but Black has a convincing reply } { [%cal Rc2h7] } 13... Qh6 { Bringing the queen back, covering g7 an defending everything, when Black is a
pretty clean pawn up (even though it is doubled). }) (13. Qh5!? g6 14. Qh4 Qf4 $15 { White is probably forced to exchange queens and go into an endgame
where he is a pawn down. Still, due to the symmetrical structure and Black's
doubled c-pawns, it is not the easiest extra pawn to convert, although it is
clear that only Black is playing for a win if the queens ever get removed from
the board. }) 13... Qa5 $17 { Now Black is a pawn up for "nothing", although
things are never so easy in practice - especially since the extra pawn is
doubled and the structure is symmetrical. } 14. Bf4 { Trying to exchange the bishop and potentially expose the weak c7 pawn, but it
is debatable whether White - who is a pawn down - should aim to exchange the
pieces. Still, suggesting the alternative is not easy - and the bishop on d6
does do a good job of pressuring the h2 pawn. } { [%csl Rc7][%cal Rf4c7] } 14... Be6?! { Black develops the
bishop and refrains from exchanging on f4. It is correct to be patient, but it
transpires that this is not the most accurate execution of the "don't exchange
on f4" idea, as this move blocks the e-file and allows White some attacking
ideas associated with Qe4 and/or Re1-Re3 - as happened in the game. } (14... Bxf4 15. Qxf4 { wouldn't be ideal as
now the pawn on c7 is exposed. } { [%cal Rf4c7] }) (14... Re8 { As now } 15. Bxd6 cxd6 { There
is no Qe4 resource. }) 15. Rae1?! { This is a natural move but the problem is
that it doesn't really try to pose Black any direct problems. } (15. Bxd6 { White could have put much more resistance by taking on d6, although it is not
very obvious why this is so great. } 15... cxd6 16. Qe4 { [%cal Rd3h7] } 16... g6 (16... Qh5 17. Qb4 { Is a very annoying double attack. } { [%cal Rb4b7,Rb4d6] }) 17. Qf4 Qe5 18. Qb4 { And next Rae1 is coming so White has quite some compensation for the pawn.
In any case, a variation such as this one was much more resistant compared to
the game, although it is hard to blame players in 1886 for not finding the
most accurate defensive resources! }) 15... Rfe8 { Continuing to develop and not
being tempted by the pawn on a2 - which in this case is probably a smart idea. } (15... Qxa2? 16. Bd2 { Would run into all sorts of issues as the queen is
suddenly trapped and unable to escape. } 16... Qa3 { This seemingly saves Black, but
White has a powerful winning reply: } (16... Kh8 17. Bc3 { And now
Ra1 is threatened. } { [%cal Ge1a1] }) (16... Qb2 17. Bc3 { And now again Black is unable to take
on c3 due to the discovered attack. } 17... Qxc3 18. Bxh7+ Kxh7 19. Qxc3) 17. b4!! { Threatening Bxh7. } { [%cal Rd3h7] } 17... Bxb4 (17... Qb2 { Again runs into } 18. Bc3) 18. Qe4 { A fatal double attack. White wins a piece and with it
the game. Very nice tactical resource and not an everyday pattern. } { [%cal Rd3h7,Re4b4] }) 16. Re3 { White is intending some sort of attack involving the Bxh7
sacrifice and lifting the rook via the 3rd rank. The drawback of this move is
that it blocks the bishop from reaching d2, so now Black is indeed able to
capture the pawn on a2. } { [%cal Ge3h3,Gf3h5] } 16... Bd5?! { But this is a bad move, relinquishing a big
part of Black's advantage due to a very direct tactical idea. } (16... Qxa2! { Here, it was possible to capture the a2 pawn as now White doesn't
have the Bd2 resource available. Steinitz probably didn't want to do so on
principle, but it transpires that White doesn't have the immediate way of
punishing the opponent. The queen can always go to b2 or back to a5 and White
would be hard pressed to demonstrate the compensation for the two missing
pawns. } { [%cal Ga2b2] }) 17. Bxh7+!? { A good and fully correct sacrifice, exploiting the
position of the queen on a5 as well as the rook on e3. } (17. Qh3 { [%cal Gh3d7,Rh3h7] } 17... g6 18. Rxe8+ Rxe8 19. Bxd6 cxd6 20. Qd7! $10 { Inflitrating with the queen
and winning the pawn on b7 back, with approximate equality. } { [%cal Rd7e8,Rd7b7] }) 17... Kxh7 18. Qh5+ Kg8 19. Rh3 { This was White's point. Mate on h8 is
threatened and due to the positioning of the queen on a5 and the bishop on d5,
there is also the idea of c4, winning the bishop on d5. } { [%cal Rh5a5,Rh5h8] } 19... f6 { Trying to make some space for the king and dealing with the threat of Qh8. } { [%cal Gg8f8,Gg8f7] } (19... Kf8 20. Bxd6+ cxd6 21. c4 { Leads to a very equal position, too, as White
wins the piece back and Black has a very unsafe king. }) 20. Qh7+? { An
amazing mistake. Zukertort possibly thought that this position is a draw and
that Black can't escape, but this is losing in a number of ways. } (20. Bxd6 { For better or for worse, White should have taken the piece back. After } 20... cxd6 21. c4 { An endgame with heavy pieces will be reached where Black might have a
pawn or two, but where White will constantly have threats against the Black
king, which means that the position will remain dynamically balanced. }) 20... Kf7 21. Qh5+ Kf8 22. Qh8+ Kf7 (22... Bg8 { Black could have played this move
here and then White has no attack. Quite amazing that both players missed this,
to be completely honest - overlooking this kind of resources sometimes happens
in bullet, but you wouldn't expect it in a World Championship Match. }) 23. Qh5+ Kf8 24. Qh8+ Kf7 25. Qh5+ Kf8 26. Qh8+ Kf7 27. Qh5+ Kf8 28. Qh8+ Kf7 29. Qh5+ Kf8 30. Qh8+ Kf7 31. Qh5+ { It is quite amusing to observe these games from the
era before the concept of three-fold repetition was introduced. For those of
you who don't know what I am talking about - in modern chess, once a position
is repeated three times, a player has the right to call an arbiter and declare
it drawn. Of course, back in 1886, this was not a thing, hence the last 10
moves :D. } 31... Ke7 { Finally Steinitz decides to step away and move the king to
safety at the precise moment when the queen on h5 is not really attacking the
g7 pawn. Although this is a bit strange as after the next move, the king will
have to go to f8 anyway, so you might be wondering why not Kf8-Bg8 immediately? } (31... Kf8 32. Qh8+ Bg8 { Is still very much winning. Black can cover g7 very
easily and White has no objective attack. }) 32. Re3+ Kf8 { The only move. The
king has to go back. } (32... Kd7 { Would suddenly allow some nasty checks
starting with } 33. Qf5+ { Keeping the pin along the 5th rank. } { [%cal Rf5a5] } (33. Qg4+? Be6 $19) 33... Kd8 34. Rxe8+ Kxe8 35. Bxd6 cxd6 36. c4 $44 { And White again regains the piece due to the horizontal pin and
the situation is completely unclear. } { [%csl Rd5][%cal Rf5a5] }) 33. Qh8+ { White has to go down this
route as there aren't any better alternatives. } (33. Rxe8+ Rxe8 34. Bxd6+ cxd6 35. c4 { Trying to win back the piece now doesn't work due to the simple
refutation: } 35... Re5 { [%cal Re5h5] } 36. Qh8+ Bg8) (33. Bxd6+ { Trying to win the
piece immediately (without the preliminary exchangeon e8) also isn't ideal, as
after } 33... cxd6 34. c4 Rxe3 35. fxe3 Qc3 { Black will win
the e3 pawn while activating the queen with the gain of time, which makes a
difference between the position being lost and the position being drawn. Here
White has no hope, although one could make an argument it was still better to
go for this than a position with a piece down that arose in the game. } { [%csl Re3][%cal Rc3e3] }) 33... Bg8 34. Bh6 { Trying to muddy the waters by
attacking g7, but as we have mentioned earlier - Black easily defends. } { [%csl Rg7][%cal Rh6g7,Rh8g7] } 34... Re7 { Covering the g7 point! } { [%csl Gg7][%cal Ge7g7] } (34... gxh6?? 35. Qxf6+ Bf7 36. Qh8+) 35. Rxe7 (35. Rfe1?? Qxe1+ $19) 35... Kxe7 { Okay, the g7 will fall after all, but White
doesn't have enough attackers - mainly because the queen is controlling the e1
square and thus preventing the rook from entering the game via e1. } { [%csl Re1,Rg7][%cal Rh6g7,Ra5e1] } 36. Bxg7 { Essentially capitulation, but White at least tries to attack the
f6 pawn. } { [%cal Rg7f6] } (36. Qxg7+ Bf7 $19 { Qh5 and Rg8 are coming next and this is not even a very
difficult conversion task - the king will hide on the queenside and it is a
big question who will be attacking who in the resulting position. } { [%cal Ga5h5,Ga8g8] }) 36... Qf5 $19 { Defending the f6 pawn and dealing with the only
possible threat. } { [%csl Gf6][%cal Gf5f6] } 37. Re1+ { Okay, now White does get this check, but it is
only one check. } 37... Kf7 { Keeping the f6 pawn defended and
also attacking the g7 bishop, relinquishing all hope. } { [%csl Gf6][%cal Gf7f6] } 38. Bh6 Qh7 { Now Black
manages to exchange queens and transpose to an easily won position where White
only has a pawn for the piece. } 39. Qxh7+ { White could have as well resigned
here. } 39... Bxh7 40. c4 a5 41. Be3 c5 42. Rd1 a4 { And here Zukertort finally
decided to resign. A very difficult game to annotate from the modern viewpoint,
where White basically self-destructed by playing for some sort of
pseudo-attack that was destined to fail. It is a little bit strange that
Zukertort felt pressured to play in this style given that he outplayed
Steinitz in quite a few quiet positions and given that his Berlin was
functioning very well, but as it was, here Steinitz took the lead for the
first time after the 1st game and never looked back. } 0-1


[Event "Steinitz - Zukertort World Championship"]
[Site "New Orleans, LA USA"]
[Date "1886.03.03"]
[Round "12"]
[White "Wilhelm Steinitz"]
[Black "Johannes Zukertort"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Annotator "USER"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C67"]
[Opening "Ruy Lopez: Berlin Defense, Rio Gambit Accepted"]
[StudyName "Steinitz - Zukertort 1886 World Chess Championship"]
[ChapterName "Game #12"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/fB11Bc7Q/ITsux4AZ"]

{ After winning the 11th game in the 1886 World Chess Championship Match, for
the first time since game 1, Steinitz took the lead in the match. As it would
later transpire, he would never relinquish it again until the end of the match.
However, the second half of the match was not such a smooth walkover as the
result might suggest as quite a few games saw a gigantic fight. The best
evidence is the 12th game, in which Steinitz managed to build upon his lead,
but I don't think you need to be Maurice Ashley to call his performance "not
so smooth" in this one. --- Let's take a look at this important game that
determined the subsequent course of the match to a large extent! }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. Re1 Nd6 6. Nxe5 Be7 { So far, the players
have repeated the variation that has been previously in the match in several
games. Now, however, Zukertort is the first to deviate. } (6... Nxe5 { In the
previous games in the match, Zukertort captured on e5 first. Both moves are
possible and have the right to exist! }) 7. Bxc6 { But this move is not the most
critical. White willingly captures on c6 and goes for the "Ruy Lopez Exchange"
pawn structure - a pawn structure where Black has the doubled c-pawns but
where they have the bishop pair. Even in the regular Ruy Lopez Exchange, it is
very debatable whether White has any objective advantage - and here White
actually managed to eliminate the e4 pawn and the knight is sitting pretty
comfortably on d6, which means Black probably has a better version compared to
the regular Ruy Exchange. There is a good reason why this move is not the most
popular in the 21st century. } (7. Bf1 { Retreating the bishop to f1 is a very
typical move in this type of position. }) (7. Bd3 { It is also possible to
develop the bishop to d3 (which is something Steinitz already did under
different circumstances in previous games). Either of these moves is probably
better than the capture on c6. }) 7... dxc6 8. Qe2 { But
this move, in particular, is very strange. White voluntarily moves the queen
in order to create a one-move threat and prevent castling, but this
relinquishes some control over the d4 square. } { [%csl Gd4][%cal Re2e7] } (8. d4 { It is
probably better to push the pawn in the center while White has the opportunity.
In principle, if Black manages to push c5 and gain some space on the queenside
- and prevent White from playing d4, that should be favourable for the second
player. We will see a possible variation in the game where Black could have
done so, which is why it is probably a good idea to get the pawn in the center
at once (even if it can possibly be undermined by c5 later in the game). } { [%csl Gd4] }) 8... Be6 { A reasonable move, covering the e-file and preventing the
cheap trick. } { [%cal Re1e8] } (8... Nf5 { It is also possible to move
the knight and defend the e7 bishop, preparing to castle next. An additional
advantage of this move is that it covers the d4 square which makes it more
difficult for White to push d4. For example, if } { [%csl Ge7][%cal Gf5e7] } 9. c3 { Black can already play } 9... c5 { Controlling the d4 square and preventing
the central expansion. Now the d2 pawn is backward and can potentially become
weak - which is precisely a scenario White would like to avoid. } { [%csl Gd3,Rd4][%cal Rc5d4,Gd8d2] }) (8... O-O 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Qxe7 { Black
loses a pawn and the bishop pair and ends up in a horrible position. }) 9. d3?! { This is a bit too passive. White needs to adopt a more central mindset and
aim to place the pawn on d4. } (9. d4 { Is of course, quite reasonable, although
Black doesn't have any problems and can easily castle soon, say after } 9... Nf5 10. c3 O-O { Black has no problems in a position like this - especially without the
pawns on the e-file - as the bishop pair and potential activity on the open
files more than compensates for the doubled pawns. }) (9. Nc3 { It
is also very interesting to try to play without moving the d-pawn at all and
