{ Thus, after winning back-to-back games in rounds 11 and 12 of the World Chess
Championship 1886, Steinitz found himself in a very comfortable situation,
enjoying the two-point lead. Furthermore, given that the game 12 was
especially painful for his opponent and also given that it was already
established by then that Zukertort would get exhausted during a long event due
to this health issues (as already happened in the 1883 London chess tournament)
which ultimately led to his decline and premature death, Steinitz was probably
very optimistic before the 13th game and seeking to increase the lead. Let's
see how this played out and check this fascinating game which turned out to be
a major titanic battle. }
1. d4 { After the unsuccessful attempt to confuse
matters and play 1.e4 in his previous White game, in this encounter he goes
back to his favourite move. } 1... d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bf4 { But now Zukertort
is the first to deviate by playing this developing move, placing the bishop on
f4. It is definitely a possible place for the bishop in these Queen's Gambit
structures as it exerts influence over the queenside and it leads to somewhat
different play compared to the positions where the bishop is placed on g5. ---
Even though it is more common to play this move when the knight has been
placed to f3 (see the variation below), it also has the right to exist here -
and it has been played by the creative grandmaster Baadur Jobaava a lot. } (4. Nf3 Be7 5. Bf4 { this
leads to a very topical variation that is seen quite often at the highest
level nowadays. The difference compared to the game is that White already has
the knight on f3 and Black the bishop on e7 - and White tries to make an
argument the inclusion of these moves is in their favour. }) 4... c5 { One of
the possible replies Black has in this position - and one that is very
sensible. Since White's last move wasn't directly fighting for the central
squares (say by attacking the knight on f6), Black takes the opportunity to
strike in the center immediately. } 5. e3 { One of the two possible
moves, reinforcing the center, but allowing Black to go for a position where
White has an isolated pawn. } { [%cal Ge3d4] } (5. Nf3 { In the 21st century, this develping move
was played by none other but the World Champion Magnus Carlsen (among others).
After } 5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 { A very fresh position arose in the game (46) Carlsen,M 
(2847)-Aronian,L (2781) chess24.com INT 2021. Definitely a reference for
anyone who wants to investigate this line deeper. }) (5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Nxd5 exd5 7. dxc5 Bxc5 { White already has to be very
careful as both Qb6 and Qa5 are possibilities. Actually, it seems White
already has to lose a pawn by force after } { [%cal Gd8b6,Gb6a5] } 8. Nf3 Qb6 9. e3 Qxb2 { Which is not
really a scenario you want to have on move 9 of the game. }) 5... cxd4 { Black
decides to go for the position with an isolated pawn, which is very sensible -
although not the only way to handle the position. } 6. exd4 dxc4 7. Bxc4 { Thus, we have reached a position with an isolated pawn where White has already
developed the bishop on f4. To be completely honest, I don't think this is
particularly great for White by any means (as the bishop usually belongs
elsewhere in these structure), but it is definitely playable, as well. } 7... Nc6 (7... Bd6 { Maybe the most precise move involves developing the bishop from f8
to d6, exploiting the fact that the opponent's bishop is on f4. This utilizes
the positioning of the opponent's bishop, as well as the fact that Black
didn't really previously move the bishop from f8 (which means that this comes
with a tempo). }) 8. Nf3 Be7 { Black continues in a very safe and
solid style, but once again, maybe placing the bishop on d6 was more active. } { [%csl Ge7] } (8... Bd6 9. Ne5 { but it was still an option
worth considering as Black is fighting for the center and now the d4 pawn is
also a bit weak (meaning that Black might have ideas of Qb6, targeting d4 and
b2). } { [%csl Rd4][%cal Gd8b6] }) 9. O-O O-O { For players on the lower rating end - please note how both
players castle very early and at the first opportunity in this game - before
move 10. Definitely a good rule of thumb to follow in your own games! } 10. Re1 { A good move. Rooks belong on (semi) open files and e1 is the
lawful place of the f1 rook in these positions with an isolated pawn. } { [%cal Ge1e8] } 10... Bd7?! { We have already seen in the ninth game of the match that
Steinitz also went for this Bd7-Qa5-Rfd8-Be8 developing scheme in this
position - and already back then I commented that this method of development
is not particularly harmonious and that it is better to aim to place the
bishop on the a8-h1 diagonal. } { [%cal Gd8a5,Gf8d8] } (10... b6 { and intending the fianchetto of the bishop to b7 is more modern -
and probably better way of playing. } { [%cal Gc8b7] }) (10... a6 { Trying to get in
b5 and then play Bb7 is also an idea worth considering. Here White has
multiple options, though, including the very thematic tactical idea of meeting
b5 with d5 e.g. } { [%cal Gb7b5] } 11. a3 b5 12. d5 { With complications
that are not at all so unfavourable for White. } { [%csl Rc6][%cal Rd5c6] }) 11. Qe2 Qa5 12. Nb5? { But this is a blank shot - a move that goes in a totally wrong direction.
White does create some potential Bc7,Nc7 or Nd6 threats, but they are not at
all so dangerous - and it is definitely not worth moving the important knight
that fights for the d5 square away from the center. } (12. a3 { covering the b4 square,
preventing the knight from jumping there and intending b4 next, exploiting the
position of the queen on a5. } { [%cal Ga3b4,Gb2b4] } 12... Rfd8 13. b4 Qf5 14. Bc7 Rdc8 15. Bg3 { White has a very good position - mainly because of the fact
that the queen on f5 is severely misplaced and can be harassed further, say
with moves such as Bd3. The d5 break is also constantly in the air. } { [%csl Rf5][%cal Gd4d5,Gc4d3] }) 12... a6 { Kicking the knight away and demonstrating the trip was an unfortunate
excursion. } (12... Rac8 { Black could have also just placed the rook on the
c-file. I am not sure what was Zukertort's idea in this case. }) 13. Bc7 { This was one of the points of the previous move, but this is
easily dealt with. } { [%cal Rc7a5] } (13. Nd6 { but here the knight is lose and Black has the decisive tactical shot } 13... Qc7 { exploiting the pin on the knight on d6 and winning
a piece! } { [%csl Rd6,Rf4][%cal Rc7f4] }) 13... b6 14. Nc3 { The knight has to go back. You could potentially
make an argument that this induced some weaknesses on the queenside, but White
lost some time to do so, which gives Black a few tempi to consolidate. } 14... Rfc8 { Kicking the bishop on c7 away. Black probably didn't
want to move the other rook in order not to weaken the a6 pawn - but it was
also a possibility. } { [%csl Rc7][%cal Rc8c7] } (14... Rac8 15. Bf4 b5 { when Black gains some space on the queenside. To human eyes, it looks very
natural to place the rooks on c8 and d8, although the chess engine claims
there is not much of a difference and that both moves are equally good. }) 15. Bf4 b5 { Gaining some space on the queenside and
kicking the bishop on c4 away. } { [%csl Ga6,Gb5][%cal Rb5c4] } 16. Bb3 Qb6? { But this is a big blunder,
ignoring the possibiltiy of White executing a thematic break. } (16... b4 { It was necessary to kick the knight from c3 at once. The point is
to kick one of the pieces exerting influence over the d5 square at all costs.
Neither player probably realized the urgency and the strength of the potential
central breakthrough, as we will seethat these ideas of b4 and d5 will be
missed over the course of the next few moves, as well! } { [%csl Rc3] }) 17. Red1? { Returning the favour. White misses the opportunity to execute a thematic
central blow under very favourable circumstances. } (17. d5 { In
positions with an isolated pawn, getting rid of the isolated pawn with the
help of this thematic advance is an extremely common idea. Here it is very
powerful as it activates the pieces tremendously. } { [%csl Gd5] } 17... exd5 (17... Na5 18. dxe6 { is objectively better, but here Black simply ends up with a horrible pawn
structure after } 18... Bxe6 19. Bxe6 fxe6 { And here White can choose between winning
a pawn or playing for more with some developing move such as } (19... Qxe6 20. Qd2 $18) 20. Rad1 (20. Qxe6+ { is also sufficient for an advantage, although
White probably doesn't want to exchange queens in a positions like this one. })) 18. Nxd5 Nxd5 19. Bxd5 { And here suddenly White no longer has a big weakness
on d5 and all the pieces are active. The current threat is Bxc6, Rad1 and Ne5
are also coming and the position can already be evaluated as winning for White
- such is the effect of a difference when it comes to the piece activity. }) 17... Na5 { A good move, moving the knight away from the
square where it can be attacked by the d-pawn and also hitting the bishop on
b3. } { [%csl Rb3][%cal Ra5b3] } 18. Bc2 Nc4 { Logical, but not necessariyl the best! } (18... b4 19. Ne4 (19. Na4 Qb5 { Is also very pleasant for
Black as they do want to exchange queens, as the pawn structure is heavily in
their favour. }) 19... Nd5 { and once the knight is
established on d5 with a gain of tempo, Black manages to stabilize the
position. Next on cards is Bb5. If White is unable to generate some attacking
play - which is not easy to do in a position like this now that d5 has been
firmly occupied - they risk ending up worse due to the isolated pawn in the
center. } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Rd5f4,Gd7b5] }) 19. Bd3 { Hitting the knight on c4 and defending
the pawn on b2. } { [%cal Rd3c4,Ge2b2] } 19... Nd6? { But this is a bad move. The knight is weirdly placed
on d6 and is disrupting the coordination of Black's pieces, allowing a very
strong blow for White on the next move. } (19... Be8 20. d5 Bb4 { Is good for Black, as now Nxb2 is a threat and
Black can ignore the capture on e6, now that f7 is protected by the bishop and
the d7 bishop is not hanging, e.g. } 21. dxe6 Nxb2 22. exf7+ Bxf7 { This is very favourable for White as all Black's pieces are active, the
bishop on d3 is under the attack, the knight is also hanging and White is in
serious trouble. } { [%cal Rb4c3] }) 20. Ne5 { It is logical to activate the knight in a position
where the e5 square is available, but once again this misses the point of
these positions with an isolated pawn. } (20. d5!? { This move was again strong and very logical, now that the e7 bishop is
potentially a target. We can stop here as White always has time to play Ne5
next after getting rid of the weakness and activating the position further. } { [%csl Re7][%cal Re2e7] }) 20... Be8 21. Bg5 { Now that d5 is no longer so easy to execute, it is not so
easy for White to find an active plan. It is logical to try and fight for the
d5 square by attacking the knight on f6, but it transpires that the timing for
this exact move is a bit misguided in this specific instance! } (21. a3) (21. Ng4) 21... Qd8 { A logical move, reinforcing
the knight on f6 and getting the queen closer to the center of the action.
However, a stronger alternative was available. } (21... h6! { Asking this
bishop a concrete question with this little pawn move was very strong. At
first glance it doesn't seem to achieve much, but after } 22. Bh4 (22. Bxf6 { is probably better, but here Black simply gains the two bishops as after } 22... Bxf6 { d5 is not that strong: } 23. d5 b4 $19) 22... g5! { This looks very risky,
but it works out due to very concrete reasons. } 23. Bg3 b4! { Again this move, kicking the knight on c3 away. Now if the knight goes
to e4 Black wins a piece after } { [%csl Rc3][%cal Rb4c3] } 24. Ne4 (24. Nb1 Nf5 { Is also very much in
Black's favour. }) 24... Ndxe4 25. Bxe4 Nxe4 26. Qxe4 f5 { With f4
next, when WHite has some compensation, but not more. } { [%cal Gf5f4] }) 22. Qf3 { Creeping the
queen closer to the kingside. } 22... Ra7 { Intending to activate the
rook via the 7th rank. } { [%cal Ga7c7] } (22... b4) (22... h6 { were valid alternatives
again. }) 23. Qh3 { Creating a threat of Bxf6 and
Qxh7. } { [%csl Rh7][%cal Rh3h7,Rg5f6] } 23... h6 24. Be3 Rac7 (24... b4 { Was once again very interesting. }) 25. d5 { Finally, White recognizes the time for this thematic break has arrived! Better
late than never! } 25... b4 { And finally, Black recognizes that this move is somewhat
annoying, disturbing the knight on c3. Now a very critical moment in the game
arises. } 26. Ne2? { This is way too passive. White is okay with trading of
the pawn on d5 for the pawn on a6, but this simply doesn't work out in his
favour! } (26. dxe6 { For better or for worse, taking on e6 should have been
tried. This leads to some fascinating variations after the logical piece
capture } 26... bxc3 { here, the best move for Black by far is: } 27. bxc3!! { A tremendously patient move played in the heat of the battle. Now
White still retains the idea of taking on f7, while Bb6 is also a major threat! } { [%cal Ge6f7,Re3b6] } (27. exf7+ Nxf7 { The knight on e5 is under attack and the b2 pawn
is still hanging. You might think this would allow White to win the queen, but
after } { [%csl Re5][%cal Rf7e5,Rc3b2] } 28. Nxf7 Bxf7 29. Bh7+ Kxh7 30. Rxd8 cxb2 31. Rdd1 bxa1=Q 32. Rxa1 { Black has two pieces and a rook for the queen and a pawn - which is a decisive
material advantage. }) 27... Rb8 { The best move, dealing with the threat. } (27... a5 28. Bb6 { allows White to regain some material and gain
the upper hand! } { [%cal Rb6d8] }) 28. exf7+ Bxf7 (28... Nxf7 { Is now not so desirable as there
is no pawn on c3 so after } 29. Nxf7 Bxf7 30. Bh7+ Kxh7 31. Rxd8 Bxd8 32. Bf4 { The situation is unclear as the material balance is much closer. } { [%cal Rf4b8] }) 29. Nxf7 Kxf7 30. c4 { And it transpires that the position is completely
unclear as White has two pawns for the pieces and Black's pieces coordination
and king safety are disturbed. Not an easy variation to see/evaluate - but
definitely much better compared to what happened in the game. }) 26... Nxd5 27. Bxa6 { Now White manages to exchange a central pawn for the edge
pawn, which is not in his favour. Furthermore, the knight on d5 can now
eliminate the bishop on e3, securing Black the advantage of the bishop pair. } { [%cal Rd5e3] } 27... Ra8 (27... Nxe3 { was also possible at once! } { [%cal Re3d1] } 28. Bxc8 Nxd1) 28. Bd3 Bf6?! (28... Nxe3 { Why not take the bishop pair first and think later? }) 29. Bd4 Nb5 { Ah okay, Black can still take the bishop pair, but
this also gives the option of giving up the light-squared bishop. } { [%cal Rb5d4] } 30. Nf3? { But this is a mistake. White allows the strong dark-squared
bishop to be taken under extremely unfavourable circumstances - as Black also
gains some ideas of jumping to f4 now. } { [%cal Rd5f4] } (30. Bxb5 { for better or for worse,
White should have captured on b5. } 30... Bxb5 31. Qf3 { And here White is
significantly worse - maybe even objectively lost, due to the shaky placement
of the pieces, Black's bishop pair and the fact that the rooks on the a- and
c-files are very active. Nevertheless, this would have been infinitely better
than what happened in the game. }) 30... Nxd4 31. Nfxd4 { Trying to
keep the f4 square under control, but allowing a nasty tactical idea. } { [%cal Ge2f4] } 31... Ra5 { This is a bit slow as it allows White to get the queen to f3 and cover the f4
square. Steinitz probably wanted to cover the b5 square and prevent Bb5 or Nb5
- but objectively, a stronger move was available. } (31... Ba4 32. Re1 (32. b3 Be8) 32... Bxd4 33. Nxd4 Nf4) (31... Bxd4 32. Nxd4 Nf4 33. Qe3) 32. Qf3 Ba4 33. Re1 Ne7 34. Qe4 g6 35. b3 Be8 36. Bc4 Nf5 37. Nxe6 fxe6 38. Bxe6+ Kg7 39. Rad1 Qe7?! (39... Qb8 40. Bxf5 Rxf5) (39... Qa8 40. Bxf5 gxf5 41. Qxb4) 40. Nf4 Re5 41. Qb1 Rxe1+? (41... Bc6 42. Bxf5 gxf5 43. Nh5+ Kh8) 42. Rxe1 Bc3 43. Nd5 Qc5 44. Nxc7 Qxc7 45. Rd1 Nd4 46. Bc4 Bc6 47. Qd3 Ba8? (47... Qf4 48. Qe3 Qe4 49. Qxe4 Bxe4) 48. Qe3 Qd6 (48... Qb7 49. f3) 49. a3! Bc6 50. axb4 Qf6 51. Kf1 (51. Qxc3 Ne2+ 52. Bxe2 Qxc3) (51. b5 Nxb5 (51... Bxb5 52. Bxb5 Nxb5 53. Rd7+) 52. Bxb5 Bxb5 53. Qc5 Be8 54. Rd6) 51... Nb5 52. Qe6 Qxe6 53. Bxe6 Bxb4 54. Bd7 Nc3 55. Rd4 Bxd7 56. Rxd7+ Kf6 57. Rd4 Be7 58. b4 Ke5 59. Rc4 Nb5 60. Rc6 Bd6 61. Rb6 Nd4 62. Rb7 g5 63. b5 Kd5 64. b6 Kc6 65. Rh7 Kxb6 66. Rxh6 Kc7 67. h4 gxh4 68. Rxh4 Nf5 69. Rh7+ Kd8 70. g4 Ne7 71. Kg2 Ke8 72. Kf3 Bc5 73. Rh5 Bd4 74. Kg3 Kf7 75. f4 Bc3 76. Rb5 Be1+ 77. Kf3 Bc3 78. g5 Ba1 79. Kg4 Bc3 80. f5 Bd4 81. Rb7 Bc3 82. Kh5 Bd4 83. Kh6 Bg7+ 84. Kh7 Be5 85. g6+ Kf8 86. Rxe7 { And here Steinitz resigned as White will promote one of the pawns by
force after } 86... Kxe7 87. g7 Bxg7 88. Kxg7 { and the pawn endgame was winning. A
fascinating, titanic battle fully worthy of a World Chess Championship Match.
Alas, it would later transpire to be Zukertort's last wind in the match, as he
wouldn't win another game until the end of the match. However, we are getting
ahead of ourselves - in this particular moment, the deficit was reduced to
just one point and the match tension once again reached the culminating point. } 1-0


