1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. Qc2 Be7 7. e3 Nbd7 8. Bd3 O-O 9. Nge2 Re8 10. O-O Nf8 11. f3 { A standard plan of preparing e3-e4. } 11... g6 { Practice has seen 20(!!) various continuations for Black in this position.
The most common of them, besides the text move, are: } (11... Be6) (11... Nh5) (11... Ng6) (11... h6) (11... c5) 12. Rae1 { An obvious move but its value is
questionable, as shown in the present game. White should rather play } (12. Rad1 { , overprotecting the d4-pawn in view of e3-e4 }) (12. Kh1) 12... Ne6 13. Bh4 (13. Bh6!?) 13... b6!? { A relatively new but good plan. } (13... Ng7 { is hardly appropriate here as ...Bc8-f5 can be met with e3-e4. A recent
example: } 14. Kh1 Nf5 15. Bf2 c5 16. Bxf5!? Bxf5 17. e4 dxe4 18. fxe4 cxd4 19. Nxd4 Be6 (19... Bd7 20. e5) 20. Nxe6 fxe6 21. Qb3 Qd7 22. Rc1 Ng4 23. Bg1 Bg5 24. Rcd1 Qc6 { 1-0 (30) Gretarsson,H (2507)-Lagerman,R (2315) Glasgow 2012 } 25. Ne2! $36) (13... c5 { is clearly premature due to } 14. dxc5 Nxc5 15. Bb5) (13... Nh5 { doesn't solve any problems: } 14. Bxe7 Rxe7 15. Qd2 Re8 16. Bc2 Nhg7 17. Rd1 Nf8 18. e4 Be6 19. Kh1 $14 { 1-0
(45) Gonzalez Vidal,Y (2475)-Bautista Sanchez,J (2223) Barbera del Valles 2007 }) (13... Bd7!? { needs more tests although in the following game White (a
strong GM) outplayed his opponent: } 14. Kh1 Rc8 15. Qb1 a5?! 16. e4 dxe4 17. fxe4 Ng4 18. Bxe7 Qxe7 19. h3 Qh4 20. Kg1 Nh6 21. Qc1 Ng5 22. Rf4 Nxh3+ 23. gxh3 Qxh3 24. Rf2 Ng4 25. Nf4! Qh4 26. Rg2 $16 { 1-0 (50) Georgiev,K (2666)
-Bellia,F (2418) Zaragoza 2011 }) 14. Kh1 Bb7 15. Qb3?! $146 { A new but hardly
promising continuation. However, it is not easy to suggest something instead. } (15. Bf2 { is too slow: } 15... Rc8 16. Bg1 c5 { etc. }) (15. Rd1 Rc8 16. e4?! dxe4 17. fxe4 Ng4 18. Bf2 (18. Bxe7 Qxe7) 18... Nxf2+ (18... Bg5!?) 19. Rxf2 Nxd4 20. Nxd4 Qxd4 21. Ba6 Qxf2 22. Qxf2 Bxa6 23. Rd7 Bc4 $44 { 0-1 (35) Kaufman,R
(2333)-Lengyel,B (2251) Budapest 2010 }) (15. Nf4 Nxf4 16. exf4 Nh5 { 1/2 (16)
Genocchio,D (2446)-Recuero Guerra,D (2441) Presolana 2011 }) 15... Rc8 (15... c5 16. dxc5 Nxc5 17. Qd1) 16. e4 { That was the idea of White's previous move but
Black has prepared a strong reply. } 16... c5! 17. Bb5 (17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Nxd5 Bxd5 19. Qxd5 Qxd5 20. exd5 Nxd4 $15) 17... Rf8 (17... cxd4! { was stronger and
gave Black an upper hand as White had no time to capture the e8-rook: } 18. Bxf6 (18. Bxe8 Nc5! 19. Qc2 dxc3 { , and White must give up a second piece for the
rook as } 20. Bb5 a6 21. Bd3 (21. b4 axb5 22. bxc5 d4) 21... cxb2 { is even
worse for him }) 18... Bxf6 19. Nxd5 (19. Bxe8? dxc3 20. Nxc3 (20. Bb5 cxb2 $19) 20... Nc5 $19) 19... Nc5!? (19... Bxd5 20. Qxd5 (20. exd5 Nc5) 20... Rf8 $15) 20. Nxf6+ Qxf6 21. Qa3 Red8 $15) 18. e5?! (18. exd5 Nxd5 19. Bxe7 (19. Bf2 Nxc3 20. bxc3 cxd4 21. cxd4 Qd5 $15) 19... Nxe7 20. dxc5 Nxc5 { is pleasant
for Black }) (18. Rd1 { with unclear consequences, e.g. } 18... g5!? (18... dxe4 19. dxc5) (18... cxd4 19. Nxd4 Nc5 20. Qc2 a6 21. Be2 $14) (18... a6 19. exd5! Nxd5 20. Bxe7 Qxe7 21. Nxd5 Bxd5 22. Qxd5 axb5) (18... c4 19. Qc2 a6 20. Bxf6 Bxf6 21. exd5 axb5 22. dxe6 b4 $44) 19. Bf2 c4 20. Qc2 a6 21. exd5 Nxd5 (21... axb5 22. dxe6 b4 23. Ne4 Qd5 $44) 22. Nxd5 Qxd5 23. Nc3 Qd8 24. d5 Nf4 25. Bc6 Bxc6 26. dxc6 Nd3 27. b3 b5 28. a4 Rxc6 29. axb5 axb5 30. Bg1 Bc5! $13) 18... Nh5 19. Bxe7 Qxe7 20. Nxd5 Bxd5 21. Qxd5 Rfd8 22. Qe4 cxd4 $17 { As
a result of the clash in the centre, Black has a clear advantage: his rooks
are centralised, his knights are strong, and his passed d4-pawn can't be
successfully blocked. } 23. f4? (23. Nc1 Nhf4 (23... Nc5 24. Qg4 Ng7) 24. Nd3 Nd5 $17) 23... d3! 24. Nc3 Rd4 25. Qf3 Nhxf4 { Black has won a pawn and
easily converts his material advantage. } 26. Re4 Rcd8 27. Rxd4 Rxd4 28. Ne4 d2 29. g3 Nh3 30. Nf6+ Kh8 31. Be2 Neg5 32. Qc6 Rd8 33. Kg2 Qxe5 34. Bd1 h5 35. b4 Kg7 36. a4 Kh6 37. Qb7 Qe6 38. b5 Kg7 39. Qxa7 Rd5 40. Qa8 Rf5 41. Rxf5 Qxf5 42. Qg8+ Kxf6 43. Qd8+ Kg7 44. Qd4+ Kh7 45. g4 hxg4 46. Qxg4 { 0-1 White resigns. } 0-1


