1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3 c6 4. Bg2 Bg4 5. O-O Nbd7 6. c4 e6 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Bxf3 Be7 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Nc3 Bd6 { The combination of moves Be7 and Bd6 is already
very suspicious to me. } 11. Qd3 O-O 12. Bd2 Re8 13. Rab1 { My plan was to go
for the minority attack, but in the given position, Black is able to handle it
in several ways. } 13... a5 14. Rfe1 { Now I decided to switch the plan and go for e4. } 14... h6 15. e4 Nxe4 16. Nxe4 dxe4 17. Bxe4 Nf6 18. Bf3 Qd7 19. Kg2 a4 20. a3 Bc5 { Another very computerish decision. The tactic itself is obvious, but it is not
clear why you wouldn't put a rook on the d-file or knight on d5 instead. } 21. Bc3 (21. Rxe8+ Rxe8 22. b3 { Is actually indicated by my strong engine on a
pretty solid gaming configuration, but we don't know which one did our boy
NT_99 use. }) 21... Red8 22. Rbd1 Bb6 { This is apparently not the best move and
is one of two innacuracies commited by my opponent. But still, there is
nothing wrong with Black's position. } 23. Qc4 Nd5 24. Bd2 Ba5 25. Bxa5 Rxa5 26. Re5 Rb5 { A move with a deep tactical idea I missed. } 27. Rd2? { Blunder that
loses the game. } (27. Qc2 { And White retains an edge. }) (27. Qxa4 Rxb2 28. Qc4 { Is more or less equal, although it is easier to play Black IMHO because he
has two pawn islands and White has three. }) 27... Nb6 { Now there will be a pin
on the d-file or a fork on c4. } 28. Qe2 Rxe5 29. Qxe5 Nc4 { The thing that made
me suspect/realize I am playing against a cheater is that my opponent thought
for 15seconds for both this and his next move. } 30. Qe2 Nxd2 31. Qxd2 Qxd4 32. Qc2 Qd2 33. Qf5 Qd3 34. Be4 g6 35. Qe5 Qd4 { My opponent's centipawn loss 23.
This is probably as high as they will get. I think this was one of smarter
cheaters (or should I say - less dumb) because I really had a hard time
convincing myself there is something weird about this game and I had to
analyze a lot of his games to ultimately decide he is and report him. Thank
god, it seems I was right. } 0-1


