1. g3 { This was the second game I played against this guy. He also won the
first one (also given in this article). He even challenged me to a game here
and I accepted since I didn't suspect anything and since I liked the prospect
of playing against someone of my own rating. } 1... g6 2. Bg2 Bg7 3. c3 c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. O-O e5 6. b3 Nge7 7. Ba3 { To be fair, I don't recall many examples of
cheaters playing such wonky openings against me, but this one is a textbook
example. } 7... d6 8. Bb2 O-O 9. Ng5 h6 10. Bxc6 Nxc6 11. Nf3 { I am completely
winning here and honestly - I should beat anybody from this position, but I
got agitated because I realized there is something fishy against my opponent
so I started playing badly. } 11... e4 12. Nh4 Bh3 13. Ng2 Ne5 14. Qc2 f5 15. c4 Qd7 16. Bxe5 Bxe5 17. Nc3 Rae8 { Of course, i still have a good position, but over
the last 8 moves his situation has significantly improved. Needless to say,
all his moves starting from 12 Nh4 were the first engine moves. } 18. Rae1 h5 19. Nd5 Kg7 20. Ndf4 Bxf4 21. gxf4 Qe7?? { A huge blunder. I realized it soon
that the game is gone of the drain, but as I was kicking myself, I realized my
opponent is taking more than 30 seconds to make a very obvious double attack. } 22. Qc3+ { I resigned here and accused him of cheating. Sure enough, he got
banned soon after I reported him. My only regret is that I didn't play a move
and actually see how long it will take him to capture the bishop on h3. } 1-0


