1. d4 { [%clk 0:15:00] } 1... Nf6 { [%clk 0:15:00] } 2. Bg5 { I have taken up Trompowsky after going over the Chessable course about it by Polish FM Kamil Plichta. It is a very good practical weapon. } { [%clk 0:15:14] } 2... Ne4 { [%clk 0:15:02] } 3. h4 { The main line recommended by mr. Plichta, with a very cool name - the Raptor. I am still not sure whether it is fully correct, but it is definitely dangerous for Black and very fun. } { [%clk 0:15:27] } 3... Nxg5 { [%clk 0:15:09] } (3... c5 4. d5 Qb6 5. Nd2 { Is another big line analyzed by Kamil. }) 4. hxg5 { [%clk 0:15:41] } 4... g6 { This is actually very solid and not so bad setup (although perhaps it is not the most accurate to start with g6). White should nominally have the edge here due to the g5 pawn, but once Black plays h6 and removes it, he might be left with the two bishops and solid pawn structure. I have had some trouble playing against this and the current game is a good example. } { [%clk 0:15:07] } 5. e3 { [%clk 0:15:43] } (5. Qd2 { Perhaps it is better to start with the queen move, in order to prevent h6. Perhaps that is why Black's move order is not the most precise. }) 5... h6 { Now Black gets in this pawn advance . } { [%clk 0:15:17] } 6. Nf3 { Of course, I don't want to take on g6 and enhance his development, but advance of the f-pawn is definitely a serious alternative. } { [%clk 0:15:43] } (6. f4 { And White gets a nice grip over black's position. Even so, since Black hasn't played d5 yet, he might consider going for the d6-e5 plan, e.g. } 6... Bg7 7. Nf3 hxg5 8. Rxh8+ Bxh8 9. Nxg5 d6 10. Nc3 e5 { Although the engine laughs at this idea, so perhaps it is not the correct one. }) 6... Bg7 { [%clk 0:15:29] } 7. Nbd2 { But now I should have taken (?!) since Black has spent a move on his bishop? I don't understand this position at all. } { [%clk 0:15:32] } 7... d5 { A human move. } { [%clk 0:14:30] } (7... h5 { Is the engine idea, and probably it has a lot of sense - since White hasn't played f4, g5 might become weak. }) 8. c3 { [%clk 0:13:43] } (8. gxh6 { Once again ignoring this move. } 8... Rxh6 9. Rxh6 Bxh6 { I somehow thought White can't have any advantage in a position like this, but perhaps he does have some slight lead in development. }) 8... Bg4? { But this is definitely faulty - this bishop move doesn't achieve anything and Black shouldn't think about giving up his bishop pair. } { [%clk 0:14:03] } (8... hxg5 { Is probably the best reaction. Black's position is probably preferable. }) 9. Qb3 { [%clk 0:13:51] } 9... b6 { [%clk 0:12:25] } 10. Bb5+?! { Now is my turn to go wrong. I thought provoking c6 is desirable as then c4 would gain in strength, but I never get the opportunity to play that move. This move is not so bad in itself, but the associated idea is rather faulty. I was way too superficial here. } { [%clk 0:13:59] } (10. c4 { Was the best move - exploiting the weakening of the light-squares. Also, you should aim to open up the position when you have the lead in development. }) 10... c6 { [%clk 0:12:17] } 11. Be2? { And this is the real howler, which just allows Black to equalize. } { [%clk 0:13:42] } (11. gxh6 { I should have played this. After } 11... Rxh6 12. Rxh6 Bxh6 13. Bd3 { A human move. Now Black has played the weakening b6-c6 and White has some lead in development, so he probably has some advantage. } (13. Ne5 { Is pointed out by the engine as even stronger. })) 11... hxg5 { [%clk 0:12:07] } (11... h5!?) 12. Rxh8+ { [%clk 0:13:52] } 12... Bxh8 { [%clk 0:12:22] } 13. Nxg5 { [%clk 0:14:06] } 13... Bxe2 { [%clk 0:12:35] } 14. Kxe2 { [%clk 0:14:21] } 14... e5 { Okay, it turns out this is not so bad for White, but only if he finds a computerish resource at this point. } { [%clk 0:11:46] } 15. Nh3? { This is very human, but it relinquishes all hope of getting an advantage. } { [%clk 0:14:20] } (15. Ngf3 e4 16. Ng1 { Was something I really disliked, although it is apparently not the end of the world. At least my knight is not as much out of play as in the game (on h3). }) (15. f4 { Was one computer idea. }) (15. Rh1 { Was the other. }) 15... Nd7 { [%clk 0:11:33] } 16. Rh1 { Another quite pointless move - the rook doesn't do much here. Re1 should have been preferred. } { [%clk 0:14:16] } 16... Qe7 { [%clk 0:10:43] } 17. Kd1 { [%clk 0:14:28] } 17... O-O-O { [%clk 0:10:51] } 18. Kc1 { I was quite worried here. Black has a very comfortable position. } { [%clk 0:14:41] } 18... exd4 { Apparently it is better to preserve the tension. } { [%clk 0:10:41] } (18... Bg7 19. Kb1 Kb7 { And White struggles to find an active plan, while Black can improve his position. }) 19. cxd4 { Probably not so bad, but now Black gets the idea of c5, opening the diagonal. } { [%clk 0:14:44] } (19. exd4 { I thought this is dangerous because of the queen's invasion, but } 19... Qe2 { Doesn't really achieve anything. }) 19... Nf8 { I liked this maneuver very much in the game. } { [%clk 0:08:28] } 20. Kb1? { I have no idea why I didn't put my knight to f4 - now I will never get that chance. I was just very flustered here. } { [%clk 0:14:47] } 20... Ne6 { [%clk 0:08:33] } 21. Rc1 { [%clk 0:14:56] } 21... Kb7 { [%clk 0:08:42] } 22. Qc2 { My game is based on creating one move threats. } { [%clk 0:13:23] } 22... Rc8 { [%clk 0:08:14] } 23. Qd3 { [%clk 0:13:17] } (23. g3 { With the idea of Nf4 was nevertheless a way to include the inactive piece and seek the balance. }) 23... Qf6 { A good move, creating a strong threat of c5. } { [%clk 0:06:37] } 24. Rc2 { [%clk 0:12:10] } 24... Qd8 { [%clk 0:04:51] } (24... c5 { I wasn't sure whether this didn't work. } 25. dxc5 Rxc5 26. Nb3 Rxc2 27. Qxc2 { And okay, one one hand the desire not to isolate the pawn is natural, but on the other, Black is just too active here and has a very clear edge. }) 25. Nf3 { [%clk 0:12:08] } 25... c5 { [%clk 0:04:27] } 26. Nhg1 { This is way too passive to be good. } { [%clk 0:10:38] } (26. dxc5 Nxc5 { Seemed troublesome for me, but I was too pessimistic. } 27. Qd1 Ne4 28. Rxc8 Kxc8 29. Nd4 { And White is actually fine. }) 26... cxd4 { [%clk 0:04:29] } 27. Rxc8 { [%clk 0:10:51] } 27... Qxc8 { [%clk 0:04:44] } 28. exd4 { [%clk 0:11:03] } 28... Qc4 { [%clk 0:04:29] } (28... Nf4 { Was just winning on the spot, more or less. Fortunatelly, my opponents missed it. }) 29. Qxc4 { I kinda expected this move and thought the endgame might be tenable for me. } { [%clk 0:11:16] } 29... dxc4 { [%clk 0:04:41] } 30. Ne2 { [%clk 0:11:31] } 30... Kc6 { [%clk 0:04:18] } 31. Kc2 { [%clk 0:11:44] } 31... b5 { [%clk 0:04:13] } 32. Kc3 { [%clk 0:11:53] } (32. b3 { Was probably wiser - the king doesn't feel secure on c3 anyway. }) 32... a5? { But this is probably bad because it allows me to undermine the structure and break down that beautiful pawn chain. } { [%clk 0:04:07] } (32... Nc7 { Heading for d5 immediately, was more problematic. I would have to go for. } 33. b3 Nd5+ 34. Kc2 (34. Kb2 { Is not an easy move. }) 34... cxb3+ (34... Nb4+ { Is probably more problematic. }) 35. Kxb3) 33. a4 { [%clk 0:12:02] } 33... Nc7 { Now the endgame is probably equal. } { [%clk 0:03:39] } 34. axb5+ { [%clk 0:12:06] } 34... Kxb5 { [%clk 0:03:53] } 35. Nf4 { [%clk 0:12:15] } 35... Bf6 { [%clk 0:02:57] } 36. Ne2 { [%clk 0:10:31] } 36... Nd5+ { [%clk 0:03:01] } 37. Kc2 { [%clk 0:10:44] } 37... Nb4+ { [%clk 0:02:20] } 38. Kd2 { [%clk 0:10:58] } 38... Nd3? { But this is too eager - Black should have just went with the knight back and I don't have anything. Now the tactical trick works. } { [%clk 0:02:20] } 39. Nc3+ { Important to force the king back. } { [%clk 0:11:11] } (39. b3 Nxf2 40. bxc4+ Kxc4 { Is just lost. }) 39... Kc6 { [%clk 0:02:15] } (39... Kb4 40. Nd5+ { Loses the bishop on f6. }) 40. b3 { Thanks to this tactical trick suddenly the tables have turned. } { [%clk 0:11:25] } 40... Nxf2 { [%clk 0:01:36] } 41. bxc4 { [%clk 0:11:37] } 41... Ng4 { [%clk 0:01:17] } 42. Kd3 { [%clk 0:11:31] } 42... Be7 { [%clk 0:01:14] } (42... Nf2+ { Why not repeat the position and see what White will do? } 43. Ke3 Ng4+ 44. Ke4 Bg7 { And it is not easy for White to improve - he has to take care of the passed a-pawn. }) 43. Ne4 { I was happy I got this one in, although it is perhaps nothing special. } { [%clk 0:10:54] } (43. Na4 { Blocking the pawn, controlling the c5 square and taking it from there was probably a better approach, although the drawing margin is high nevertheless. }) 43... f5 { Not sure if this advance should have been included. } { [%clk 0:01:23] } (43... Bb4 { Just doing nothing was the other approach. After } 44. d5+ Kc7 { I wasn't sure what to do. Now the engine points out that after } 45. Nc3 Nf2+ 46. Kd4 Bxc3+ 47. Kxc3 Ne4+ 48. Kd4 f5 { The position is still equal, but I still think it is easier to play as White, due to connected passed pawns. }) 44. Nc3 { [%clk 0:10:43] } 44... Bb4 { [%clk 0:00:53] } (44... Nf2+ { Was the correct way } 45. Ke2 Ng4 { And I don't know at all how to improve. I think that advancing the c-pawn can be met by counter-sacrifice } 46. c5 (46. Nd5 { Is not so strong because after } 46... Bd8 47. Nf4 g5 { The bishop is useful on d8 and controls important squares on the kingside. }) 46... Bxc5 47. dxc5 Kxc5 { And there is no way White is winning. }) 45. Na4 { [%clk 0:10:31] } (45. Nd5 { Was strong because of the dual threat Nf4 and Nh4 - suddenly both g6 and f5 are weak. }) 45... Nf2+? { I am not sure if you were playing for a win or smh, but this is a losing move. } { [%clk 0:00:47] } (45... Be7 { Once again preventing all Nh4 ideas and defending the kingside was the best way. }) 46. Ke3 { [%clk 0:10:44] } 46... Nd1+ { [%clk 0:00:58] } 47. Kd3 { [%clk 0:10:15] } 47... Nb2+ { A blunder, but I think the position was bad anyway. } { [%clk 0:00:55] } (47... Nf2+ { After this I wouldn't repeat but probably go for } 48. Ke2 Ng4 49. Nh4 { Winning a pawn on the kingside. Black can still resist, but now probably the game is technically winning. }) 48. Nxb2 { 1-0 Black resigns. } { [%clk 0:10:28] } *


