1. d4 { [%clk 0:15:00] } 1... Nf6 { [%clk 0:15:00] } 2. Bg5 { [%clk 0:15:14] } 2... Ne4 { I know Ne4 is quite commonly played here, but I can't say I am very familiar with theory from this point. Only reply I've seen here is Bf4. } { [%clk 0:15:02] } 3. h4 { New move for me. Do I want to open up white's h file to get a bishop pair? I guess I do. } { [%clk 0:15:27] } 3... Nxg5 { [%clk 0:15:09] } 4. hxg5 { [%clk 0:15:41] } 4... g6 { The plan here is to open up my h file as well. This may take a few moves, but I'll get there. } { [%clk 0:15:07] } 5. e3 { [%clk 0:15:43] } 5... h6 { [%clk 0:15:17] } 6. Nf3 { [%clk 0:15:43] } 6... Bg7 { [%clk 0:15:29] } 7. Nbd2 { [%clk 0:15:32] } 7... d5 { I normally play Grunfeld, so this is almost an automatic response for me. Prevents e4. } { [%clk 0:14:30] } 8. c3 { [%clk 0:13:43] } 8... Bg4 { [%clk 0:14:03] } (8... hxg5 9. Rxh8+ Bxh8 10. Nxg5 e5 { This is very similar to what was played in the game, but without Bg4. Stockfish seems to prefer this. }) 9. Qb3 { Qb3 surprised me. Not that it's a bad move... I just hadn't considered it when playing Bg4. At first I thought I was virtually forced to return my bishop to c8, which of course cannot be good. } { [%clk 0:13:51] } 9... b6 { Only move if I want to make progress. I can't afford to lose b7 here. } { [%clk 0:12:25] } 10. Bb5+ { [%clk 0:13:59] } 10... c6 { [%clk 0:12:17] } 11. Be2 { [%clk 0:13:42] } 11... hxg5 { As planned: opening up my h file to neutralize white's h1 rook. } { [%clk 0:12:07] } 12. Rxh8+ { [%clk 0:13:52] } 12... Bxh8 { [%clk 0:12:22] } 13. Nxg5 { [%clk 0:14:06] } 13... Bxe2 { Losing the bishop pair, but exchanging off my bad bishop vs white's good bishop. } { [%clk 0:12:35] } 14. Kxe2 { [%clk 0:14:21] } 14... e5 { Again: very similar to the variation without Bg4. Trying to open up the center and expose white's king. } { [%clk 0:11:46] } 15. Nh3 { This could have been forced, yet... the knight is very poorly placed on h3. Blocks the h file, and seemingly has no way of returning to play any time soon. } { [%clk 0:14:20] } 15... Nd7 { Completing development. } { [%clk 0:11:33] } 16. Rh1 { Trying to get play on the only open file white has. Yet, that knight is in the way. } { [%clk 0:14:16] } 16... Qe7 { Clearing back rank, pressure on e file. } { [%clk 0:10:43] } (16... Qc7 { This was possible, but cuts off the queen from play on the king side. }) 17. Kd1 { [%clk 0:14:28] } 17... O-O-O { What else? The perfect move here. My king is completely safe. } { [%clk 0:10:51] } 18. Kc1 { [%clk 0:14:41] } 18... exd4 { As planned... opening up the e file to try and get play on the king side. } { [%clk 0:10:41] } 19. cxd4 { This is your typical 'what now?' position. I took quite a bit of time here to figure out how to continue. I would normally want to try to expose white's king by opening up the c file, but my d5 pawn is hanging. And it's unclear where my d7 knight is best placed. It's not d7. } { [%clk 0:14:44] } 19... Nf8 { Trying to get the knight to a better square: e6. } { [%clk 0:08:28] } 20. Kb1 { [%clk 0:14:47] } 20... Ne6 { As planned. } { [%clk 0:08:33] } 21. Rc1 { White has succeeded in counter-acting black's plan. King to safety, and neutralized the c file. } { [%clk 0:14:56] } 21... Kb7 { Must cover c6. } { [%clk 0:08:42] } 22. Qc2 { Building pressure on c6. } { [%clk 0:13:23] } 22... Rc8 { c5 has again become an option. } { [%clk 0:08:14] } 23. Qd3 { Prevents c5. } { [%clk 0:13:17] } 23... Qf6 { Again trying to introduce c5 as a possible move. Threat b2 mate. } { [%clk 0:06:37] } 24. Rc2 { Counter-acting the mate threat. } { [%clk 0:12:10] } 24... Qd8 { Again trying to make c5 possible. } { [%clk 0:04:51] } 25. Nf3 { [%clk 0:12:08] } 25... c5 { Finally, c5 can be played. } { [%clk 0:04:27] } 26. Nhg1 { Trying to get the h3 knight back into the game. } { [%clk 0:10:38] } 26... cxd4 { Opening up the position, while black's pieces are slightly better placed. } { [%clk 0:04:29] } 27. Rxc8 { [%clk 0:10:51] } 27... Qxc8 { [%clk 0:04:44] } 28. exd4 { [%clk 0:11:03] } 28... Qc4 { The idea here is to reconnect my pawns and gain a queen side majority. At this point, I suspected d4 would become a target. } { [%clk 0:04:29] } (28... Nf4 { Stockfish gives me this line as an improvement, and it probably is. } 29. Qc2 (29. Qf1 Qf5+ 30. Ka1 Qc2 { This looks nasty. }) 29... Nxg2 { Wins a pawn. }) 29. Qxc4 { [%clk 0:11:16] } 29... dxc4 { [%clk 0:04:41] } 30. Ne2 { Knight back into play, d4 pawn safe for now. } { [%clk 0:11:31] } 30... Kc6 { [%clk 0:04:18] } 31. Kc2 { [%clk 0:11:44] } (31. Ne5+ Bxe5 32. dxe5 Kd5 33. f4 Ke4 { This can't be good for white. }) 31... b5 { [%clk 0:04:13] } 32. Kc3 { [%clk 0:11:53] } 32... a5 { Trying to prevent the king from coming to b4. } { [%clk 0:04:07] } (32... Nc5 { Stockfish move. I totally missed this possibility, didn't even consider it. }) 33. a4 { I totally missed this. If I had seen this, I probably wouldn't have played b5. } { [%clk 0:12:02] } 33... Nc7 { Trying to get my knight to d5. } { [%clk 0:03:39] } 34. axb5+ { [%clk 0:12:06] } 34... Kxb5 { [%clk 0:03:53] } 35. Nf4 { Now my knight is sorta stuck on c7. I wasn't too happy here. } { [%clk 0:12:15] } 35... Bf6 { The idea here is to kick the knight with g5, so I can play Nd5. } { [%clk 0:02:57] } 36. Ne2 { [%clk 0:10:31] } 36... Nd5+ { [%clk 0:03:01] } 37. Kc2 { [%clk 0:10:44] } 37... Nb4+ { [%clk 0:02:20] } 38. Kd2 { [%clk 0:10:58] } 38... Nd3 { Double attack: b2 and f2. } { [%clk 0:02:20] } 39. Nc3+ { Where is my king going? Kb4 loses bishop. So only one move .... } { [%clk 0:11:11] } 39... Kc6 { [%clk 0:02:15] } 40. b3 { Again, I'm not too happy here. } { [%clk 0:11:25] } 40... Nxf2 { [%clk 0:01:36] } 41. bxc4 { White has 2 connected passers, and even though the stockfish eval is level, I think I prefer white here. } { [%clk 0:11:37] } 41... Ng4 { Desperately trying to get this knight back into play. } { [%clk 0:01:17] } 42. Kd3 { White is in no rush here. Slowly improving position and preparing the pushing of his passers. } { [%clk 0:11:31] } 42... Be7 { [%clk 0:01:14] } 43. Ne4 { [%clk 0:10:54] } 43... f5 { Gaining control of e4. } { [%clk 0:01:23] } 44. Nc3 { [%clk 0:10:43] } 44... Bb4 { [%clk 0:00:53] } 45. Na4 { [%clk 0:10:31] } (45. Nd5 { Likely better than the move played. }) 45... Nf2+ { [%clk 0:00:47] } 46. Ke3 { [%clk 0:10:44] } 46... Nd1+ { [%clk 0:00:58] } (46... Ng4+ { Likely better. }) 47. Kd3 { [%clk 0:10:15] } 47... Nb2+ { This is obviously a case of positional blindness. I thought I was going to capture c4 here, but totally missed Na4. } { [%clk 0:00:55] } (47... Nf2+ 48. Ke2 Ng4 49. Nh4 { Better than hanging my knight... yet, black is about to lose a pawn. }) 48. Nxb2 { 1-0 Black resigns. } { [%clk 0:10:28] } 1-0


