1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 c5 4. O-O { The reverse kingside fianchetto is on the board. } 4... Nc6 5. d4 { White decides to go for Catalan/Reverse Grünfeld positions } (5. d3 e5) 5... e6 { With this we transpose to some sort of Catalan. } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Ge6d5] } (5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 e6 (6... e5 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. c4 { Is a Grünfeld a tempo up for White. Vishy Anand played this 4 times in 2016, with excellent results. })) 6. c4 dxc4 { Trying to clarify the situation immediately } (6... Be7 { Is an invitation to the Tarrasch Defence. } 7. cxd5 Nxd5 (7... exd5 8. dxc5 Bxc5 { [%cal Ga2a3,Gb1c3,Gd5d4] } 9. a3 { [%csl Gd5] })) 7. dxc5 { A bit timid, but not completely innocuous } (7. Qa4) (7. Ne5 { are both theoretical moves here }) 7... Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Bxc5 9. Nfd2 { A very rare move, which was played by some strong players like Carlsen and Ding Liren in 2017 and Karjakin and Harikrishna in 2018. The idea is to uncover the bishop's diagonal, attack c4, prevent c3 and put the knight on e4 } { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gd2c4,Gg2b7,Gd2e4] } (9. Na3 { [%cal Gc5a3] } 9... Ne4 10. Be3 Bxe3 11. fxe3) (9. Nbd2 c3 (9... Na5 { [%cal Ga5c4] } 10. Ne5 { Is worse } { [%csl Gc4][%cal Gc6a5,Ge5c4,Gd2c4] }) 10. bxc3 { [%csl Gc3] }) 9... Na5 { The drawback of the previous move } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gc6a5,Ga5c4,Gf3e5] } (9... c3 10. Nxc3) 10. Na3 { "A knight on the rim is dim" } { [%csl Gc4][%cal Ga3c4] } 10... Bxa3 11. bxa3 { [%csl Ga2,Ga3,Gc1,Gg2,Gb7][%cal Ga1b1,Gb1b7,Gc4c3] } 11... O-O { Ju Wenjun deviates first } (11... Bd7) (11... Nd5 { Was played by Harikrishna }) (11... c3 12. Nb3 Nc6 13. Be3 { [%csl Gc3][%cal Ga1c1,Gc1c3] }) 12. Ne4 { So far, the players have been following the game } { Karjakin, Sergey - Anand, V., 1/2-1/2, 80th Tata Steel GpA, 2018, https://lichess.org/LW29pJaM } 12... e5 { A not particularly good novelty } { [%cal Gc8g4] } (12... Nxe4 { Was anand's choice. After } 13. Bxe4 e5 14. Bb2 (14. Bd2 { Would transpose to the game, though }) 14... Nc6 (14... Re8 15. Bc3 Nc6 { He managed to defend Black's position })) (12... Nd5 { Is more challenging } 13. Bd2 b6 14. Rac1 Ba6 { With complicated position } 15. Bxa5 bxa5 16. Nc5 Bb5) 13. Bd2 { Not going for the e-pawn immediately, but pressuring the knight first } { [%cal Gd2a5] } (13. Bb2 { [%cal Gb2e5] }) 13... Nxe4 (13... b6 { Black is unable to answer with b6 } { [%csl Ga5][%cal Gb6a5] } 14. Nxf6+ gxf6 15. Bxa8) 14. Bxe4 Nc6 15. Bc3 { [%cal Gc3e5] } 15... Be6 (15... Re8 16. Rab1 { Is the illustration why opening of the b-file is a good idea. This once again transposes to Karjakin - Anand game, which continued } { [%csl Gb7][%cal Gb1b7] } 16... h6) 16. Bxc6 (16. Rab1 Nd4 17. Bxd4 exd4 18. Rxd4 Rad8 (18... Rfd8 19. Rxd8+ Rxd8 20. Rxb7 f5 21. Bf3 Rc8 { [%cal Gc4c1] }) 19. Rxd8 Rxd8 20. Rxb7 { Leaves Black with sufficient compensation } 20... f5 21. Bf3) 16... bxc6 17. Bxe5 { The position looks rather harmless. Apparently Ju Wenjun was of the same opinion because, according to Kateryna Lagno, she started playing quickly (and carelessly) } { [%csl Gc6,Gc4,Gd6,Gc5,Gd4][%cal Gf2f6,Ge2e6,Gg3g6,Gh2h6,Ge6a2,Ga1b1] } 17... Rfd8 18. Bc3 (18. f3 Bf5 19. Kf2 Bc2 20. Rdc1 { [%cal Gc1c4] }) 18... f6 (18... Bf5 19. f3 Bc2 20. Rdc1 Ba4 { [%csl Gc4][%cal Ga4d1,Gd8d1] }) 19. f3 Kf7 20. Kf2 Rxd1 21. Rxd1 Rb8 { [%csl Ga2,Ga3,Gb1,Gb2,Gb3,Gb4][%cal Ga2b3,Gd1d8] } 22. g4 { [%csl Gc6][%cal Gg4g5,Gh2h4,Gf2e3] } (22. Rd6 Rc8) 22... c5 { Probably correct - it is important to control the d4 - square } { [%csl Gd4,Gc5][%cal Gf2d4] } (22... h6 23. h4 Rb7 24. a4 Kf8 25. a5 Ke7 26. Rg1 Rd7 27. g5 hxg5 28. hxg5 Kf7 29. Ke3 { [%csl Gd7][%cal Gc6c5,Ge3d4,Gg1h1,Gh1h7,Gd7d1] } 29... c5 30. gxf6 gxf6 31. Rh1) 23. h4 { [%csl Gg7][%cal Gg4g5] } (23. Ke3) 23... h6 24. a4 Ke7 25. a5 Rb7 26. Rg1 Rd7?! { The first imprecision } (26... Kd6 27. g5 hxg5 28. hxg5 Rf7 29. gxf6 gxf6 30. Ke3 f5 { [%csl Gd6] }) 27. g5 hxg5 28. hxg5 Kf7 (28... fxg5 29. Rxg5 Kd6 30. Bxg7) 29. gxf6 gxf6 30. Rh1 { [%cal Gf7g7] } (30. Rb1) 30... Kg7 (30... f5 31. Ke3 { Is slightly less comfortable setup, but Black can still probably hold } 31... Ke7 32. Be5 { The difference - bishop is ideal on e5 } { [%csl Gd6] } 32... c3 33. Bxc3 Bxa2 34. Kf4 { And White has some advantage }) 31. Rb1 Kf7 32. Rb5 { [%csl Gc5][%cal Gb5c5] } 32... Rc7 { [%cal Gc7c5] } 33. Rb8 Re7 34. Rh8 Kg6 35. Rf8 { [%csl Gf6][%cal Gf8f6] } 35... Rf7 { [%csl Gc5,Gf6] } 36. Rg8+ Kh7? { But this is the real mistake - now c5 pawn falls and allows the activation of the king } { [%csl Gc5][%cal Gg8c8,Gc8c5,Gg8d8,Gd8d6,Gd6c6,Gc6c5] } (36... Rg7 37. Re8 (37. Rd8 Rd7 38. Rc8 Rd3) 37... Bd7 38. Rf8 Rf7 { And White has to try something else } 39. Rg8+ Rg7 40. Ra8 Be6 41. Ke3 Re7 42. Kf4 Kf7 { And it is not clear how White makes improvement } { [%csl Ge6,Ge7,Gf7,Gf6] }) 37. Rd8 { Now c5 will fall } { [%csl Gb7,Gf6,Gc5][%cal Gd8d6,Gd6c6] } 37... Kg6 (37... Rd7 38. Re8) 38. Rd6 Re7 39. Rc6 Kf7 40. Rxc5 Rd7 { Now Black is close to being lost, although even here it is not entirely clear } 41. Rc6 (41. a6 Kg6) 41... f5 42. Ke3 { Now comes the king } 42... Re7 43. Kf4 (43. Kd4 Bd7 { And Rf6+ is not possible } { [%csl Gf6,Ge2][%cal Gc6f6] } 44. Rxc4 Rxe2 { [%csl Ga2,Ga5] }) 43... Rd7? { The losing moment } { [%cal Gc6c5,Gc5b5,Gb5b7,Ga5a6] } (43... Bd7 44. Rf6+ { [%csl Gf6] } 44... Ke8 45. e3) (43... Re8 { Was most resillient. } 44. Rc7+ { [%cal Ga5a6] } (44. a6 Rc8 { Now doesn't work } 45. Rd6 Ke7 46. Bb4 c3 { [%csl Ga2,Ga6] } 47. Rc6+ Kf7 48. Rxc8 Bxc8 49. Bxc3 Bxa6 50. Kxf5 Bxe2) 44... Re7 45. Rc5 Ke8 { And it is hard for White to make some progress } 46. a6 { For instance, he shouldn't hurry with this move } { [%cal Ga5a6] } 46... Bd7 { [%cal Ge7e2] } 47. e3 Re6 48. Ra5 Bc8 { [%csl Gf5,Ge3,Gf3] }) 44. Rc5 { Missing a ver ygood chance } { [%cal Gc5b5,Gb5b7,Ge7f7] } (44. a6 Ke7 45. Kg5 Kf7 (45... Rd6 46. Bb4) 46. f4 Ke7 47. Bb4+ Kf7 48. a3 Rd8 49. Rc7+ Rd7 50. Rb7 { [%cal Gf7e8,Gc7b7,Gf6d5] } 50... Kg7 (50... Ke8 51. Kf6) 51. Bc3+ Kf7 52. Bf6 Ke8 53. Kg6 { [%csl Gb7] }) 44... Rd8 { Returning the favour } (44... Rd6 { Controling the sixth rank, was important } { [%cal Gd6a6] } 45. Ke5 Rd7 46. a6 Re7 { And the king is missplaced on g5 } { [%csl Ge5] } 47. Kd6 Rd7+ 48. Kc6 Ke7) 45. Rb5 { [%cal Ga2a4] } 45... Rd7 (45... Kg6 46. Ke5) (45... Rd6 { Is now too late } 46. Rb7+ Rd7 47. a6 Ke7 48. Ke5 { And White will win - there is no defensive d5 check resource }) 46. a6 { [%cal Gb5b7] } 46... Kg6? { But this illogical king move is the real losing moment } (46... Re7 { Was more resilient. After } 47. Bb4 Rd7 48. Rb7 c3 49. Bxc3 Ke8 50. a3 Bc4 { Black can still resist } 51. e3 Bxa6 52. Rxd7 Kxd7 53. Kxf5) 47. Ke5 { The rest is, as they say, a matter of technique - activity of the pieces and the strong a6 are too much for Black to handle } { [%csl Ge6,Ga6][%cal Gd7d5,Gb5b7,Ga6b7] } 47... Re7 48. Rb7 Re8 49. Rxa7 Bf7+ 50. Kd4 (50. Kf4 Rxe2 51. Rd7 Rxa2 52. a7) 50... Rxe2 51. a4 Re6 52. Kc5 Be8 53. Rg7+ Kh6 54. a7 Ra6 55. Re7 { Simplest } { [%cal Ge7e8,Ga6a4] } (55. a5 Bc6 56. Rc7 Bxf3 57. Kb5 Rd6 { Is also good enoguh, though }) 55... Rc6+ (55... Rxa4 56. Rxe8 Rxa7 57. Kxc4) 56. Kb4 Rc8 57. Rb7 (57. Rxe8 Rxe8 58. Be5 Ra8 59. Bb8 { [%cal Gb4c4,Gc4b7] }) 57... Ra8 58. Rb8 Bc6 59. Rb6 { A brilliant technical game by Lagno } { [%cal Gb6h6] } 59... Rc8 { [%cal Ga7a8] } 60. Rxc6+ Rxc6 61. a8=Q *


