1. e4 c5 { Of course - when you are in a must win situation, you play the Sicilian. } 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 { The Rossolimo is pretty trendy these days, due to some two guys playing it in three games in their match. } 3... g6 { As played by Magnus } 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 e5 { This was also seen in the game 5 of the World Chess Championship. } 6. a3 { [%csl Ga2,Gb5][%cal Gb2b4,Gb5c4,Gc4a2,Gc6a5] } (6. Nc3 Nge7) (6. b4 { Was move played by Fabiano Caruana. It makes no sense to go for it when you just need a draw. }) 6... Nge7 7. Nc3 { This is very much possible, but somewhat illogical - why not go for it immediately? } { [%cal Gb1c3] } (7. b4 cxb4 (7... d6 { Is actually the theoretical move here }) 8. axb4 { Is a sacrifice Black shouldn't accept } 8... Nxb4 9. Ba3 Nbc6 10. Bd6 { And he is incredibly tied up. Say } 10... O-O 11. Nc3 b6 12. Nd5 Bb7 13. c4 { With a complete bind } { [%cal Ge7d5] }) 7... O-O 8. Bc4 { This was played in some low-profile games. Now I understand the point of a3 - the light-squared bishop has an escape square } { [%csl Ga2][%cal Gc4a2,Gc6a5] } 8... d6 9. d3 h6 10. Nd5 { Quite logical move, often seen in different variations of the Italian game } (10. b4 { Can always be considered }) 10... Kh7 { Black's plan is clear - go for f5 and checkmate on the kingside. Even when these King's Indian-like attacks don't work, they are often unpleasant to meet in practical play } { [%cal Gf7f5] } 11. c3 f5 { Perhaps a bit premature, but...onwar } 12. exf5!? { Perhaps a bit premature, but...onward } (12. b4 f4 13. h3 g5 14. Nxe7 Qxe7 15. b5 Nd8 16. Nd2 (16. Nh2 Be6)) 12... gxf5 (12... Nxf5 { [%csl Ge4] } 13. Nd2 { And White controls e4 square } { [%cal Gf8f2,Gg6g2,Gh6h3] }) 13. b4 (13. Ng5+ { Was an interesting shot. } 13... Kg6 { The best move, but good luck finding it. Moreover, after } { [%cal Gg8g2] } (13... hxg5 14. Qh5+ Bh6 (14... Kg8 15. Nxe7# { [%cal Ge7g8,Gc4g8] }) 15. Bxg5 { Just wins } { [%cal Gh6g5,Gh5h7] }) (13... Kh8 14. Qh5 { [%cal Gg5f7] } 14... Nxd5 15. Bxd5 Qf6) 14. Nf3 Kh7 { Is the best }) 13... Ng6 14. b5 { [%cal Gb4b5,Gc6a5] } (14. Rb1) (14. Ba2) 14... Na5 15. Ba2 Be6 16. Qa4 { [%cal Gg6h4,Gf7f2,Gf7f3,Gc8g3] } (16. Qe2 { [%cal Ge2h4] }) 16... b6 17. Bd2 Rg8 { Preparing the attack } { [%cal Gg8g2] } 18. Rad1 { [%csl Gd3][%cal Gd3d4] } 18... Qd7 19. Nh4 { The losing move, but it is already hard to play White } (19. Kh1 c4 20. dxc4) 19... Bh8 { [%csl Gh8][%cal Gg8g2] } (19... c4! { Was quite strong } { [%cal Ga4h4] } 20. Nxg6 { [%cal Gh7g6] } 20... Bxd5 { [%cal Gd5g2] } 21. dxc4 Be6 22. Nh4 Bf6 23. Nf3 { [%csl Ga4,Gc4,Ga2][%cal Gg8g2,Ge5e4,Gf5f4,Ga2b1] }) 20. Nxg6 Rxg6 { Still, Black has a strong attack } { [%cal Gg8g6] } 21. Qh4 Rag8 22. g3 Qf7 23. c4 { [%cal Gd2a5] } 23... Bf6? { Nerves, nerves.. } { [%csl Gf6] } (23... f4 { Was the logical continuation of the attack } 24. Bb1 (24. Bxa5 bxa5 25. Bb1 Rg4 26. d4+ { [%cal Gb1h7] } 26... Kg7 (26... Bf5 27. Bxf5+ Qxf5 28. Qe7+) 27. Qe7 Bxd5 28. Qxd6 { [%csl Gd2,Ga5] } 28... Be6 (28... Bb7 29. Rxe5 { [%csl Gg7][%cal Ge5e7,Gg8g3] }) 29. Qxe5+) 24... Rg4 25. d4+ Kg7 26. Qe7 Bxd5 27. Qxd6 Nxc4 { [%csl Gf5,Ge5,Gd6] }) (23... Nb7 { Bringing the knight an preparing f4 was also interesting } { [%cal Gb7d8,Gd8f7] }) 24. Nxf6+ Rxf6 (24... Qxf6 25. Qxf6 Rxf6) 25. f4 { [%csl Ge6][%cal Gf5f4] } 25... Rg4 26. Qh3 Rfg6 { [%cal Gg4g3] } 27. Rf1 (27. Qf1 { Just one more precise move, and black's attack would be stalled } { [%cal Gf1f4] } 27... Qg7 (27... Rxg3+ 28. hxg3 Rxg3+ 29. Kf2 { Leads nowhere } { [%csl Gh4] }) 28. Re2 { [%cal Ga5b7] } 28... h5 { [%cal Gh5h4] } 29. fxe5 dxe5 (29... h4 30. Bf4) 30. Bc3) 27... Qg7 { [%cal Gg7g2] } 28. Kh1? { The losing move } (28. Qh5 { Was more tenacious and is probably still holding. But Lagno was in serious time trouble here } { [%cal Ge6c8,Gc8b7,Gb7c6] }) (28. Kf2 exf4 29. Bxf4 Qb2+ 30. Rd2 Rxf4+) 28... Bc8 { [%cal Ge6c8,Gc8b7,Gb7h1] } (28... Rxg3) 29. Qh5 (29. Kg1 Rxg3+) (29. Rg1 Bb7+ { [%cal Gb7g2] } 30. Rg2 Rxg3 31. hxg3 Rxg3 32. Qxg3 Qxg3 { [%cal Gb7h1] }) 29... Bb7+ 30. Kg1 Rxg3+ 31. hxg3 Rxg3+ 32. Kf2 Rg2+ { 0-1 White resigns. } { Because after } 33. Ke3 (33. Ke1 Qg3+ 34. Rf2 Qxf2#) 33... Qg3+ 34. Rf3 exf4# 0-1


