1. d4 d6 2. Nf3 g6 { The modern defence! A risky choice, but suitable in a must-win situation } 3. e4 Bg7 4. Bc4 { One of the many possible lines } 4... e6 { Assembling the Hyppopothamus has some sense here, because both f4 and c4 are not available. And with the bishop on c4, d5 becomes an idea } { [%cal Ge7e6,Gd7d6,Gc2c4,Gf2f4,Ga2a4,Gb1c3] } (4... Nf6 5. Qe2 { Is the main move order here } { [%cal Ge4e5] }) 5. O-O (5. c3 a6 6. a3 b6 7. O-O Bb7 8. Be3 Nd7 9. Qd2 h6 10. a4 Ne7 11. Na3 { [%csl Gh6,Gg6,Ge6,Gd6,Gb6,Ga6,Gb7,Gg7,Ge7,Gd7] }) 5... Ne7 6. a4!? { [%cal Gb7b6,Ga7a6] } (6. Re1 { Was played by some strong players - Vladimir Kramnik. }) 6... O-O (6... d5 { [%csl Gc4,Gd5] } 7. exd5 exd5 8. Bd3 { [%csl Gh7,Gg6,Gf7,Gf2,Gg2,Gh2][%cal Gf1e1] } 8... O-O { But it is hard to play for the win with Black here }) (6... a6 7. a5 { Is favourable for White } { [%cal Ga5b6] }) (6... b6 7. a5 { [%cal Ga7a6,Gb6b5] }) 7. c3 Nd7 8. a5 { This is probably premature } { [%csl Gb7,Ga7] } (8. Nbd2) (8. Re1 d5 9. exd5 Nb6 { [%cal Gb6d5] }) (8. Bd3) 8... Rb8?! { This can't be good } (8... d5 9. exd5 exd5 10. Bd3 c5 { But still it is difficult to play for the win. Advanced pawn on a6 offers some chances though }) 9. Qe2 b6 { [%cal Ga3a5] } 10. axb6 axb6 { Now White gains an open a-file and the advance of the pawn is justified } { [%cal Ga1a8] } 11. Bf4 Bb7 12. Nbd2 h6 13. h4!? { A measure against g5 } { [%cal Gg6g5,Gh4h5] } 13... Nf6 14. Bg3?! (14. Ba6 { Was probably more precise, avoiding d5 } { [%csl Gb7,Gd6][%cal Gb7a6,Gb7e4] } 14... Bxa6 15. Rxa6 d5 16. e5) 14... d5 { [%cal Ge6d5,Gf6d5] } (14... Nh5 { Is a shot in the blank }) 15. exd5 Nfxd5 { The point - Black wnats to take with the knight and keep the position imbalanced } 16. Be5 { Pretty annoying - exchanging White's bad dark squared bishop for Black's good one } { [%csl Gg7,Ge5,Gg3][%cal Ge5g7] } 16... Nf5 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. g3 { [%cal Gf2h4] } (18. h5 { Was possible here }) 18... Nf6 19. Ba6 { Searching for more exchanges } 19... Ba8 20. Bd3 { Too passive } (20. Qe5 { [%cal Ge5g7] } 20... Kg8 21. Bd3 { [%cal Gc7c5,Gf5d6] } 21... c5 22. h5 { Active play was a bit better } 22... Nxh5 (22... g5 { [%csl Gf5] }) 23. g4) 20... Nd6 (20... c5 { Was a bit unpleasant } 21. Qe5 (21. dxc5 bxc5 22. Nc4 Nd6 { And Black gets a dynamic position he wanted } { [%cal Ga8f3,Gb8b2,Gd8d6] }) 21... Qd5 { [%cal Gf8c8,Gc8c2,Gb8b2] }) 21. Rfd1 Nd7 { [%cal Gc7c5] } (21... c5 { Is now bad } 22. Qe5 { And Black queen can't go to d5 } { [%cal Gd8d5] }) 22. Ne4 (22. b4 { Nipping c5 in the bud! } { [%csl Gc5] } 22... c5 23. bxc5 bxc5 24. dxc5 Nxc5 25. Qe5+ { [%csl Gc5][%cal Ge5g7,Ge5c5] }) 22... Nf5 { Avoiding exchanges and risking it } 23. Ned2 g5 { Once again, not objectively good, but Lagno had to win } { [%csl Gg5] } 24. hxg5 hxg5 25. Be4 Qf6 26. Bxa8 Rxa8 27. Rxa8 Rxa8 28. Kg2 { But this move I didn't understand at first, but from practical point of view, it is understandable } (28. Ne4 { Why not simply win the pawn? } 28... Qh6 29. Nexg5 Rh8 30. Kg2 { Probably Wenjun was terrified of this, but everything is covered here } { [%csl Gh3][%cal Gg5h3] } 30... f6 31. Nxe6+ { [%csl Gf4][%cal Ge6f4] } 31... Kf7 32. Nf4) 28... Rh8 29. Rh1 { Also not the best, but as we have seen, Wenjun wanted to avoid all counterplay } { [%csl Gg5] } 29... Rxh1 30. Kxh1 Nd6 31. Ne5 Qh6+ 32. Kg2 Nf6 33. Ndf3 Nfe4 34. Nh2 Qg6?? { Nerves, nerves.... Lagno wasn't in such a terrible time trouble (According to Chessbomb, she had somewhere around 2.30 minutes left). But under tension, she made one of the worst moves in her career } 35. Nxg6 *


