1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nd2 Qb6 (5... e6 6. Bd3 Be7 7. h3 O-O 8. Ngf3 Bd6 9. Ne5 Bxe5 10. dxe5 Nd7 11. Nf3 h6 12. Bc2 Re8 13. O-O b6 14. e4 $14 { Shirov,A-Sakaev,K/Sochi 1986/EXT 2000 }) 6. Qc2 (6. Qb3 c4 7. Qc2 Nh5 8. Bg5 h6 9. Bh4 g5 10. Be2 Ng7 11. Bg3 Nf5 12. Ngf3 Bg7 13. e4 Nxg3 14. hxg3 e6 15. Nh2 $14 { Kovacevic,V-Pinter,J/Plovdiv 1983/EU-chT }) 6... cxd4 (6... e6 7. h3 Bd7 8. Ngf3 Rc8 9. Qb3 Qxb3 10. axb3 a6 11. Bd3 Be7 12. O-O O-O 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. b4 Bb6 15. Bd6 Rfe8 { Janowski,D-Morrison,J/New York 1918/HCL }) (6... g6 7. Ngf3 Bg7 8. Be2 O-O 9. Ne5 Bf5 10. Qb3 Nxe5 11. Bxe5 c4 12. Qxb6 axb6 13. f3 b5 14. g4 Be6 15. Kf2 Ra7 { Zaitseva,L-Prudnikova,S/Elista 1998/
CBM 64 }) 7. exd4 Bg4 8. Ngf3 (8. Bd3 Bh5 9. Ngf3 Bg6 10. Bxg6 hxg6 11. h3 e6 12. O-O Be7 13. Rab1 O-O 14. Rfe1 Rfe8 15. Qd1 Bf8 16. Ng5 Ne7 17. Qf3 Nf5 18. Be5 $36 { Szurovszky,E-Gal,G/Salgotarjan 1978/EXT 99 }) 8... Rc8 9. Qb3!? { Tony
Miles is a great expert in this kind of positions and also in this game he
manages to create serious advantage out of nothing. } 9... e6 (9... Qxb3?! 10. axb3 a6 (10... e6 11. Ne5 a6 (11... Nxe5? 12. dxe5 Nh5 13. Be3 $16) 12. Nxg4 Nxg4 13. b4 Be7 14. Nb3 $14) 11. b4 e6 12. b5 axb5 13. Bxb5 Nd7 14. h3 Bh5 15. g4 Bg6 16. Ne5! Ndxe5 17. Bxe5 $14) 10. Ne5 Nxe5 11. Qxb6 axb6 12. Bxe5 $14 Nd7 (12... Be7 13. Bb5+ Kd8 14. O-O Bh5 15. a4 $14) 13. Bb5 Kd8 14. Bg3 Nb8 15. O-O Nc6 16. a4! { From now on white's play is simply perfect: he increases
pressure move by move finally getting winning position. } 16... Ra8 (16... Be7 17. Nb3 Bf6 18. a5 Nxa5 19. Nxa5 bxa5 20. Rxa5 $16) 17. a5! { It's necesary to open
a-file even at the cost of a pawn. } (17. Nb3 Na5) 17... bxa5 (17... Rxa5 18. Rxa5 (18. Bd3?! Be7 19. Nb3 Rxa1 20. Rxa1 Kd7 $17) 18... Nxa5 (18... bxa5 19. Ra1 (19. Nb3 Na7 20. Bd3 b6 $15) 19... Na7 20. Rxa5 Nxb5 21. Rxb5 Kc8 22. Ra5 $16) 19. Ra1! f6 20. b4 Nc6 21. Bxc6 bxc6 22. Ra6 $14) 18. Nb3 Be7 19. Ra2 Kc8 20. Rfa1 Bd8 21. Nc5 Bb6 (21... Nb8 22. b4 b6 23. Nb3 Kb7 24. bxa5 bxa5 25. c4! $40) 22. b4 Na7 { After this move black seems to solve all his problems,
but Mies finds very nice way to show that white still has enough attacking
resourses. } (22... Bxc5?! 23. dxc5 f6 (23... e5? 24. Bxc6 bxc6 25. Bxe5 f6 26. Bd6 Kb7 27. bxa5 $16) 24. Bd6 e5 25. bxa5 (25. Bxc6!? bxc6 26. bxa5 Ra6?! 27. Rb2 Kd7 28. Rb7+ Ke6 29. f3 $18) 25... Kd7 26. a6 bxa6 27. Rxa6 Rxa6 28. Rxa6 Rc8 29. Ra7+ $16) 23. Nd7! (23. Bd7+ Kd8 24. Bh4+ Kc7) 23... Bd8 24. Rxa5! Bxa5 25. Rxa5 b6 (25... Kd8 26. Nb6 Ke7 27. Bd3 h6 28. b5 $18) (25... Nxb5? 26. Nb6+ Kd8 27. Rxa8+ $18) 26. Ra2 { This is stronger than } (26. Nxb6+!? Kb7 27. Nxa8 Nxb5 28. Rxb5+ Kxa8 29. f3 Bf5 (29... Bh5 30. c4! $18) 30. Rc5 Bg6 31. Be5 $16 { and black may hold this position. }) 26... Rd8!? (26... Nxb5 27. Rxa8+ Kxd7 28. Rxh8 Bf5 29. Rb8! Kc6 (29... Nxc3 30. Rb7+ Ke8 31. Rxb6 Ne2+ 32. Kf1 Nxd4 33. Be5 $18) 30. f3 $18) 27. Ne5 Bh5 28. Ba6+ Kc7 29. Nxf7+ Kc6 30. Nxd8+ Rxd8 31. Bd3!? (31. Be5! $18) 31... Nb5 32. f3? { Starting to destroy everything that was achieved with extremly good play! } (32. Bxh7 g6 33. Be5 $18) 32... Bg6 $16 33. Bxg6?! (33. Bxb5+ Kxb5 34. Ra7 Kc4 35. Rc7+ Kd3 36. Be5 $16) 33... hxg6 34. Re2?! Kd7 35. Be1 Rc8 36. Re3 Ra8 $14 { Now white's advantage is symbolical and the draw is not far away. } 37. Kf2 (37. h4 Ra2 38. Kh2 Ra3 $14) 37... Ra2+ 38. Re2 Rxe2+ 39. Kxe2 Ke7 40. Kd3 Na3 41. Bh4+ Ke8 42. b5 Nxb5 43. Kc2 Nd6 44. Kb3 Nc4 45. Bg5 Kd7 46. Bf4 Kc6 47. h4 Kd7 48. Kb4 Kc6 49. Kb3 Kd7 50. Kb4 Kc6 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } 1/2-1/2


