1... Rxb7 2. Rxb7 Qd8 3. Nb3 { [%csl Gd8][%cal Gb3a5] } (3. c5 { [%csl Gc6][%cal Gf6g4] } 3... Qa5) 3... Ra8 4. Nac5 { [%csl Gh2][%cal Gg1h2,Gh1a1] } 4... Nxc5 (4... dxc4 5. Bxc4 Nxc5 { [%cal Gb3c5] } 6. Nxc5 (6. dxc5 Bxc4 7. Qxc4 Qd1+ 8. Qf1 Qd5 { [%cal Gf6d7,Gd7c5,Gg7a1,Ga8a1] }) 6... Bxc4 7. Qxc4 Ra1+ { [%cal Gc4f1] } 8. Qf1 Rxf1+ 9. Kxf1) 5. Nxc5 Ra1+ 6. Bf1 Qa5 7. Rb1 { [%cal Ga5e1] } (7. Nb3 Qa4 { [%cal Ga4c2] } 8. Nxa1 { [%csl Ga1,Gc2][%cal Ga1c2] }) 7... Ra2 8. Rb2 { [%cal Gc5b3] } 8... Ra3 (8... Ra1 9. Nb3) 9. Nxe6 fxe6 10. cxd5 { [%cal Ga5d5] } 10... cxd5 11. Qc8+ Kh7 12. Rb7 Qa8 13. Qc7 Qg8 14. Be5 (14. Qe7 { [%cal Ge7a3,Ge7f6] } 14... Ra8 15. Qxf6) 14... Ne8 15. Qe7 { [%csl Ga3] } 15... Ra8 16. Bb5 { [%cal Gb5e8,Ge8g7] } 16... Kh8 17. Bxe8 Bxe5 18. Bf7 *


[Event "World Chess Championship 2018: Game 1"]
[Date "2018.11.09"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B31"]
[Opening "Sicilian Defense: Nyezhmetdinov-Rossolimo Attack, Fianchetto Variation"]
[StudyName "World Chess Championship 2018"]
[ChapterName "Game 1"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/xV6OiytA/lwl3HqwS"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/chessentialsBLOG"]
[UTCDate "2018.11.09"]
[UTCTime "16:49:19"]

1. e4 { Kinda expected since 1 e4 is Caruana's main move, but he has had good results with the Catalan in 2018, so there was an argument we might see that move as well. } 1... c5 { But this is a surprise. Although Carlsen has played the Sicilian recently, he always played 1...e5 in Worl Championship matches } (1... e5 2. Nf3 Nf6) 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 (4... bxc6) 5. d3 Bg7 6. h3 { Svidler mentioned this is the most precise move order. Beats me why } { [%csl Gg4][%cal Gc8g4] } (6. Nc3 Bg4 { Is probably additional option Black has, although it is debatable whether this is so terrible for White }) 6... Nf6 { The point is that black doesn't rush with e5 in order to delay the development on e3 } (6... e5 7. Be3 b6 8. Qd2 h6 9. Qc3 Qc7 10. Nbd2 { Here White has the flexibility to develop the knight to d2 }) 7. Nc3 (7. Be3 Nd7 8. Nc3 e5 { Comes to the same }) 7... Nd7 { [%cal Gd7f8,Gf8e6,Ge6d4] } (7... b6) 8. O-O (8. Be3 e5 9. Qd2 h6) 8... e5 9. Be3 b6!? { Quite sensible - defending the c5 pawn and preparing to move the knight } { [%csl Gc5][%cal Gd7f8,Gf8e6,Ge6d4] } (9... Qe7 { Is by far more common, retaining flexibility. It was even played by Garry Kasparov. But Carlsen has his own opinion. }) 10. Nh2?! { The "gamble" has paid off. The move is natural, but perhaps not the most precise. Svidler was not particularly convinced with Caruana's choice. } { [%cal Gf2f4] } (10. Qd2 { [%cal Ge3h6] } 10... h6 11. Nh2 { [%csl Gh6] } 11... Nf8 12. f4 exf4 13. Bxf4 Ne6 14. Be3 Nd4) (10. a4 a5 (10... O-O 11. Nd2 Re8 12. Nc4 Nf8 13. Qd2 Ne6) 11. Nd2 O-O 12. Nc4 h6 13. Qd2 Kh7 14. Rad1) 10... Nf8 (10... Qe7 11. Qd2 h6 12. a3 { Would return us in the main lines arising after 10 Qd2 }) 11. f4 (11. Qd2 { Suggested by Svidler }) (11. a3 Ne6 12. b4) 11... exf4 12. Rxf4 Be6! { Strong play by Magnus. This counterintuitive move, retaining the flexibility of the knight is not natural. He seemed excellently prepared for this game. } { [%cal Gh7h6,Gg6g5] } (12... h5 { and }) (12... g5 { are weird engine suggestions } 13. Rf2 h5) (12... Ne6 13. Rf2 Nd4 { Was Svidler's idea, but after } 14. Qd2 { Black has to decide whether to develop or prevent Be6. Magnus' choice is much better } { [%csl Gh6][%cal Ge3h6] }) 13. Rf2 h6 14. Qd2 g5! { Excellent. Retaining the flexibility of the knight } { [%csl Gf8][%cal Gf8g6,Gf8d7,Gd7e5] } (14... Nd7 15. Nf3 Ne5 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 17. Bxh6 { Is wrong }) 15. Raf1 Qd6 { [%cal Gf8d7] } (15... Nd7 16. a3 (16. Ng4)) 16. Ng4 { The critical moment of the game. Probably the first imprecision. But it is not easy to play White in this position. } (16. e5 Qxe5 17. Ng4 Qc7) (16. a3 O-O-O 17. b4 c4) (16. a4 { Sopiko's suggestion which is actually the strongest move! Svidler's comment: "This is the first one I don't really hate" } 16... Nd7 17. a5 O-O { And White has at least managed to prevent Black's ideal set-up }) 16... O-O-O 17. Nf6 (17. e5!? { Was an interesting dynamic try. After } 17... Qc7 18. Ne4 Bxe5 19. Nxe5 Qxe5 { White has at least taken Black's dark-squared bishop, although with f5 coming Black is not too sad about it }) 17... Nd7 18. Nh5 (18. Nxd7 Qxd7 { [%cal Gg5g3,Gh6h4] } 19. b3 { Seems like a clear edge for Black. } 19... Be5) 18... Be5 19. g4 { Svidler said he is not particularly fond of this move. The fact it is the first choice of the engine tells something about White's position. The main problem is it is very difficult to suggest what plan to pursue, what White is playing for. } 19... f6 { This was evaluated correctly as better for Black by the commentators, who called it way before the position appeared on the board. They had trouble suggesting White's next move. Caruana had only 18 moves left on the clock at this point and was in serious trouble. } { [%csl Gh5][%cal Ge6f7] } (19... Rhg8 20. b3 { Was a line examined by Grischuk and Svidler. But after } (20. Ne2 Bxb2 { And Black can probably even grab this since after } 21. c3 Ba3 { There is no obvious way to punish Black } 22. Qc2 b5) 20... f6 21. Ne2 Bf7 22. Rg2 Bxh5 23. gxh5 Nf8 24. Rf3 Ne6 25. Ng3 Bxg3 26. Rgxg3 Ng7 { They concluded simple materialistic approach is pretty good }) 20. b3 Bf7 21. Nd1 Nf8!? { An unexpected and inspiring move! Nobody in the commentary expected this pawn sacrifice. A very brave decision by Magnus, who decides to go for the kill. Since Caruana was very low on time, this move had practical value. It is debatable whether it is the best move in the position, though } (21... Bxh5 22. gxh5 Nf8 23. Qe2 Ne6 { Probably Magnus changed his mind and though this would be very hard o breach. }) 22. Nxf6 { There is no better move than taking the pawn } 22... Bg6 { Is suggested by the computer. The point is that after } { [%cal Gf2f7] } (22... Ne6 { [%cal Ge6f4] } 23. Nh5 (23. Nd7 { Is a computerish try, trying to take advantage of the fact f7 is hanging. After } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Gf2f7] } 23... Bf4 24. Nf6 h5 { Black has a serious initiative nevertheless }) 23... Bxh5?! { Very human, although the engine suggest Black loses all advantage with this. } (23... Bg6 { Would return to the previous note, when Black has tremendous compensation for the pawn }) 24. gxh5 Nf4 25. Bxf4 gxf4 26. Rg2?! { After this move, Magnus gets back in the track. } (26. Rxf4! { Was a great resource, but it is not easy to decide on it in your first ever World Championship game, when you are in time trouble and playing against Magnus. After } 26... Bxf4 27. Qxf4 Qxf4 28. Rxf4 { [%csl Gb3,Gc2,Gd3,Ge4,Gh3,Gh5,Gc5,Gc6,Gb6,Ga7,Gh6][%cal Ga2b3] } 28... Rdf8 29. Rxf8+ Rxf8 { And it is very debatable whether Black can win this endgame. }) 26... Rhg8 27. Qe2?! { Mistakes come in pairs... } (27. Rg4 { Was probably still holding } 27... Rxg4+ 28. hxg4 Rg8 29. Qg2 Qd7 (29... Qd4+ 30. Kh1 Kb7) 30. Nf2 Bd4 31. Kh2 Kb7 { And White can still probably hold }) 27... Rxg2+ 28. Qxg2 { The following sequence is virtually forced } 28... Qe6 29. Nf2 Rg8 30. Ng4 Qe8 { [%csl Gh5][%cal Ge8h5] } 31. Qf3 Qxh5 { Black now has a very primitive idea of moving the queen and playing h5. Imagine having to deal with it with just 2 minutes on the clock. } { [%cal Gh5g5,Gh6h5] } 32. Kf2 Bc7! { Strong play by Magnus, retaining the bishop. } { [%cal Gg4e5] } (32... Qg5 33. Nxe5 Qxe5 34. Ke1 { Is completely equal }) 33. Ke2? { The losing move } (33. e5 { Was mentioned by commentators as the only hope. After } { [%csl Gc6][%cal Gf3c6] } 33... Bxe5 (33... Kb7 34. Nf6 Qh4+ 35. Ke2 Rg7 36. Qxf4 Qxh3 { White is still in trouble, but Black has much a harder task }) 34. Qxc6+) 33... Qg5 { Now it should be all over } { [%cal Gh6h5] } 34. Nh2 { [%cal Gf1f2,Gh2f1] } 34... h5? { Svidler: "Such a weird, slow move!" } (34... Qe5 { Was suggested by Svidler. It is simply crushing. The Queen enters b2 and White is completely lost. Say } { [%csl Gb2][%cal Ge5b2,Gg8g3] } 35. Qf2 Qb2 36. Kd1 b5 { With the ideas of c4 and Ba5. Rg3 is also on the agenda - White's pieces are completely paralyzed }) 35. Rf2 { [%csl Gh5,Ge5][%cal Gg5e5] } 35... Qg1 36. Nf1 { Grischuk: "Black's queen has gone in totally wrong direction - it is cut off from the queenside". Even though the engine still suggests Black is winning, from the practical point of view it is not that easy. } 36... h4? { Preventing the capture of the pawn, but allowing a fantastic hidden resource } { [%cal Gg8g3] } (36... Qg7 { The engine suggestion proves Grischuk's evaluation was right }) 37. Kd2? { Caruana was on increment, so it is not surprising he misses his chance } (37. e5 { Was an excellent resource. } 37... Kb7 { Black doesn't have time for this move due to } (37... Bxe5 38. Qxc6+) (37... Rg5 38. Nd2 { And a sample line goes } 38... Qc1 39. Qxf4 Rxe5+ 40. Ne4 Qxc2+ 41. Qd2 Qxd2+ 42. Kxd2 { This is probably holdable for White }) 38. Qxf4) 37... Kb7 { Now Black is winning again } { [%csl Gc6] } 38. c3 Be5 { faltering a bit } { [%csl Gc3] } (38... Rg3 { Was immediately winning } 39. Nxg3 hxg3 40. Rg2 (40. Re2 Qb1 { [%csl Ge5,Ge6,Ge7,Ge8][%cal Ge4e5,Gb1a2,Ga2c3,Gb3c3,Ge4e8] }) 40... Qa1 { And this is just winning - Black will collect all the pawns }) 39. Kc2 Qg7 { Eyeing the c3 pawn. It is hard to say whether there was something better. } (39... b5 { The engine likes this expantion at first, but then quickly changes its mind after } 40. a4 a6) 40. Nh2 Bxc3 { Decided with one minute on the clock } (40... Qg1 41. Nf1 { Would revert us to the previous position }) 41. Qxf4 Bd4 42. Qf7+ Ka6 (42... Kb8 { Doesn't work } 43. Qxg7 Rxg7 44. Rf8+ Kb7 45. Ng4 { And now only White can play for the win }) (42... Kc8 { [%cal Gc8e6,Ge4e7] } 43. Qxg7 Rxg7 44. Rf8+ { [%cal Gg7g3] } 44... Kb7 45. Ng4 { [%cal Gg7g3] }) 43. Qxg7 Rxg7 44. Re2 Rg3 45. Ng4 (45. e5 Bxe5 46. Rxe5 Rg2+ { Loses }) (45. Nf1 Rf3 46. Nd2 Rxh3 47. e5 Re3 48. Rxe3 Bxe3 49. Nf3 Bd4 50. Nxh4 Bxe5 { Was mentioned by Svidler after the break. This seems to be a draw }) 45... Rxh3 (45... Kb7 { Seemed more promising } 46. e5 (46. Rh2) 46... Kc7 47. e6 Kd8 { The key is to utilize the king to stop the pawn. Perhaps this was better than what magnus did in the game }) 46. e5 Rf3 47. e6 Rf8 48. e7 Re8 49. Nh6 h3 50. Nf5 Bf6 51. a3 b5 52. b4 cxb4 53. axb4 Bxe7 { Sooner or later Magnus has to play this. It's the only way to try and make a progress in the endgame. } 54. Nxe7 h2 55. Rxh2 Rxe7 { The position is objectively a draw but white has to play precisely. } 56. Rh6 Kb6 57. Kc3 Rd7 58. Rg6 Kc7 59. Rh6 Rd6 60. Rh8 Rg6 61. Ra8 Kb7 62. Rh8 Rg5 63. Rh7+ Kb6 64. Rh6 Rg1 65. Kc2 Rf1 66. Rg6 Rh1 67. Rf6 Rh8 68. Kc3 Ra8 { Although black allows white to play d4 very comfortably, there is no clear way how he can improve the position. } 69. d4 Rd8 70. Rh6 Rd7 71. Rg6 Kc7 72. Rg5 Rd6 73. Rg8 Rh6 74. Ra8 Rh3+ 75. Kc2 Ra3 76. Kb2 Ra4 77. Kc3 a6 78. Rh8 Ra3+ 79. Kb2 Rg3 80. Kc2 Rg5 81. Rh6 Rd5 82. Kc3 Rd6 83. Rh8 Rg6 84. Kc2 Kb7 85. Kc3 Rg3+ 86. Kc2 Rg1 87. Rh5 Rg2+ 88. Kc3 Rg3+ 89. Kc2 Rg4 90. Kc3 Kb6 91. Rh6 Rg5 92. Rf6 Rh5 93. Rg6 Rh3+ 94. Kc2 Rh5 95. Kc3 Rd5 96. Rh6 Kc7 97. Rh7+ Rd7 98. Rh5 Rd6 99. Rh8 Rg6 100. Rf8 Rg3+ 101. Kc2 Ra3 102. Rf7+ Kd6 103. Ra7 { Best move in the position ! It draws the game almost immediately. After Ra7 was played, Svidler commented that Caruana is at point where he basically doesn't have to think any more and can draw this position blindfolded. } 103... Kd5 { [%csl Ga7][%cal Ga7a6] } 104. Kb2 Rd3 (104... Ra4 105. Kc3 { [%csl Gb4,Gd4] }) 105. Rxa6 Rxd4 106. Kb3 Re4 107. Kc3 Rc4+ 108. Kb3 Kd4 109. Rb6 Kd3 110. Ra6 Rc2 111. Rb6 Rc3+ 112. Kb2 Rc4 113. Kb3 Kd4 114. Ra6 Kd5 115. Ra8) 23. Nh5 Ne6 { The bishop is not hanging } *


[Event "Carlsen - Caruana World Championship Match"]
[Site "0:56:33-1:41:33"]
[Date "2018.11.10"]
[Round "2"]
[White "Magnus Carlsen"]
[Black "Fabiano Caruana"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "D37"]
[Opening "Queen's Gambit Declined: Harrwitz Attack"]
[StudyName "World Chess Championship 2018"]
[ChapterName "Game 2"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/xV6OiytA/H7tVCtoK"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/chessentialsBLOG"]

1. d4 { So, Magnus decides to open with the d-pawn after all. No Petroff defence } 1... Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bf4 { The move 5 Bf4 characterizes the Harrwitz Attack of the Queen's Gambit Declined. It was played by great players in the past - Viktor Korchnoi employed it in matches against Karpov and Kasparov also played it. Carlsen himself suffered the only defeat by Vishy Anand on the Black side of this opening. It is, in any case, highly topical today. } (5. Bg5) 5... O-O 6. e3 (6. c5 b6 { With the knight on b8, c6 is not an option } { [%cal Gb8d7] } 7. c6 (7. b4 a5 8. a3 Ne4 9. Qc1 axb4 10. axb4 Rxa1 11. Qxa1 Nc6 12. Qb2 Bd7 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. Bxe5) 7... Nxc6) 6... c5 { Black strikes in the center immediately, before White has the opportunity to push c5 himself } (6... Nbd7 7. c5 b6 (7... c6) 8. c6 Nb8 9. Qa4 { Is horrible for Black }) 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. Qc2 { Preparing Rd1 while also saving a tempo on the bishop on f1 } { [%cal Gf1e2] } (8. cxd5 { Is less ambitious } 8... Nxd5 9. Nxd5 exd5 { This was played in several games on the top level. Black has been able to hold his ground. } (9... Qxd5 { Is also possible } 10. Qxd5 exd5 { And all four games in my database on the 2500+ level have ended in draws })) 8... Nc6 (8... Qa5 9. Be2 dxc4 10. Nd2) 9. a3 { White makes another useful move, prventing Nb4 and waiting with the development of the bishop } (9. Rd1 Qa5 10. Be2 dxc4 11. Bxc4 Nb4 { Reveals the point of a3 - now Black knight reaches d5 and he should feel comfortable } 12. Qb1 Nbd5) 9... Qa5 10. Rd1 { The main move. White waits with the bishop (again!), prepares b4 in the future and asks Black what will he do } (10. Nd2 Be7 11. Bg3 { Is another possible line. Obviously there is a lot of theory involved }) (10. O-O-O { Has been played in the past.The main line goes } 10... Be7 11. g4 (11. h4 { Was also employed by Garry Kasparov }) 11... dxc4 12. Bxc4 e5 13. g5 { As played in several games on the top level: Anand - Kramnik, 2002, Kramnik - Karpov, 1998 and Kasparov - Khalifman, 1992 }) 10... Rd8 { Played instantly by Caruana - this move is a novelty on the 2600+ level! As it turns out, b4 is not a threat. } { [%cal Gd8d1] } (10... Be7 { Is the main line. Carlsen himself played this already, for instance in his game against Nakamura in 2015 } 11. Be2 Ne4 12. cxd5 Nxc3 13. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 14. bxc3 exd5 { And Black should be OK, although in the afore-mentioned game agasint Nakamura Carlsen managed to gain a clear advantage (which he didn't convert) }) (10... Re8 { Was played by Karpov and by several other top players (most notably Nakamura). } 11. Nd2 e5 12. Bg5 Nd4) 11. Be2 { Confonted with the novelty, Carlsen decides to play it safe. } (11. b4 { Loses.. for White } 11... Nxb4 12. axb4 Bxb4 { [%csl Gc3][%cal Gf6e4] }) (11. Nd2 { Seems more challenging. Still, after } 11... dxc4 (11... e5 12. Bg5) (11... d4 12. Nb3 Qb6 13. Na4 Bb4+ 14. axb4 Qxb4+ 15. Nd2 Qa5 16. Qb3 e5 17. Bg5) 12. Bxc4 (12. Nxc4 Rxd1+ 13. Qxd1 Qd8 { It is doubtful whether White has anything serious here } 14. Qxd8+ Nxd8 { [%csl Gc8] })) 11... Ne4 { Caruana was still playing instantly. He takes the opportunity to compromise White's pawn structure } { [%cal Ge4c3] } 12. O-O Nxc3 13. bxc3 { [%csl Ga3,Gc3,Gc4,Ge3] } 13... h6 { Also played instantly... this curious, semi-waiting move is very strong - Black prepares Ne7 in order to bolster the d5 point but also waits to see what will White do } { [%csl Gg5][%cal Ge2d3,Gd3h7] } (13... Ne7 { Comes too early } 14. Bd3 (14. Bg5 Bd7) (14. Ng5 Ng6) 14... h6 (14... dxc4 15. Bxh7+ Kf8 16. Ne5) 15. Ne5 Bd7 (15... dxc4) 16. Rb1 { With some pressure }) (13... Qxa3 { Black can't take the pawn } 14. Ra1) (13... Bxa3 { Is harder to refute } 14. Ra1 dxc4 15. Ng5 { A key move, gaining the tempo } (15. e4 { [%csl Ga3][%cal Gf4c1] } 15... b5 16. Bc1 { And wins }) 15... g6 16. e4 { With the threat of Bc1 which can't be defended } 16... e5 17. Bc1) 14. a4 { Removing the pawn from attack } (14. Bd3) (14. cxd5 { Before the knight arried to e7, also made some sense } 14... exd5) 14... Ne7 { The speed with which Fabiano played indicates he was still in his home preparation } 15. Ne5 { Carlsen admitted this move was based on a miscalculation } (15. Rb1 { Was mentioned by the engines, but after } 15... Bd6 16. Bxd6 Rxd6 17. Rfd1 Qc7 { White probably doesn't have much }) (15. cxd5 Nxd5 16. Be5 { Bringing the bishop to d4 was possible, but here White has to reckon with } 16... Bd7 17. c4 Bxa4 18. Qa2 Nb4 19. Qa1 { With complications. White probably has sufficient compensatino for the pawn }) 15... Bd6 { Carlsen said he forgot about this move } { [%cal Gd6f4] } (15... a6 16. Bh5 { Was White's idea }) 16. cxd5 Nxd5 17. Bf3 (17. Nxf7 { Is possible. After the forced } 17... Kxf7 18. Bxd6 Rxd6 19. e4 (19. Bh5+ { Removing the bishop from attack } 19... Kg8 20. e4 Nf4 21. Rxd6 Qxh5 22. Rd8+ Kf7 (22... Kh7 23. Rfd1 (23. e5+ Ng6 24. Rfd1 (24. f4)) 23... e5) 23. Rfd1 b6 { With balanced position }) 19... Qxc3 20. Qxc3 Nxc3 21. Rxd6 Nxe2+) 17... Nxf4 18. exf4 Bxe5 19. Rxd8+! { Precise } (19. fxe5 Bd7 20. Bxb7 Rab8 { Is less accurate } { [%csl Ga4,Gc3,Ge5] }) 19... Qxd8 20. fxe5 Qc7 21. Rb1! { A good decision. White's pawns are somewhat weak, so he opts for activity. } 21... Rb8 (21... Qxe5 22. Qd3 { With great compensation } 22... Qc7 23. Rd1 { [%cal Gd3d8] } 23... g6 24. Qd8+ Qxd8 25. Rxd8+ Kg7 { [%cal Gd8a8] }) 22. Qd3 Bd7 23. a5 { A measure against b6 } { [%csl Ge5,Ga5][%cal Gd3d7] } 23... Bc6 24. Qd6 (24. Bxc6 bxc6 25. Rxb8+ Qxb8 { [%csl Ge5,Gc3,Ga5] }) 24... Qxd6 25. exd6 Bxf3 26. gxf3 { White's pawn structure is ugly, but he has sufficient resources to hold this ending. It is instructive to watch how Magnus does it - we all have lost similar games where our pawn on d6 was simply lost } { [%csl Gd6] } 26... Kf8 27. c4 { Onward to c5 } { [%cal Gc4c5] } 27... Ke8 28. a6! (28. c5 Kd7) 28... b6 29. c5 Kd7 { The only move } (29... b5 30. c6 { Just loses }) 30. cxb6 axb6 31. a7 Ra8 32. Rxb6 Rxa7 { And despite White's ugly kingside pawn structure and the fact he will lose the d6 pawn, this ending is drawn. White' doubled f-pawns are even helpful, since Black can't push his pawn to the third rank without massive exchanges } { [%csl Gf2,Gf3,Gg2][%cal Ge6f3,Gf7f3,Gg1g2] } 33. Kg2 e5 34. Rb4 f5 35. Rb6 Ke6 36. d7+ Kxd7 37. Rb5 Ke6 38. Rb6+ Kf7 39. Rb5 Kf6 40. Rb6+ Kg5 41. Rb5 Kf4 42. Rb4+ e4 43. fxe4 fxe4 44. h3 Ra5 45. Rb7 Rg5+ 46. Kf1 Rg6 47. Rb4 Rg5 48. Rb7 Rg6 49. Rb4 { It is surprising Caruana didn't decide to torture Magnus to return the favor. But objectively speaking there is no way he can make some progress. } 1/2-1/2


