1. e4 { So, Caruana decides to have another shot at the Sicilian } 1... c5 { And Carlsen sticks to his choice. He has no reason not to, considering the course of game 1. } 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 { The Rossolimo once again. As Svidler mentioned during game 1 stream, we are all curious what Magnus has prepared in the main lines. } (3. d4) 3... g6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. d3 Bg7 6. O-O { So, Caruana is the first to deviate. You might recall Svidler claiming 6 h3 is the most precise move, but of course, this move has also been played many times. } (6. h3) 6... Qc7!? { And once again Carlsen employs a rare move. According to my database, this was Black's choice in just 4 games, which all ended in White wins. IBlack intends to develop his knight to e7 in the future (after e5) and push f5. I assume this match will do a lot for the development of this variation of the Sicilian. } { [%cal Gg8f6] } 7. Re1 { White obviously wants to push e5, but I am not sure if this rook move is the most precise } { [%cal Ge4e5] } (7. h3 { Was played in the past. The point is that after } 7... e5 { h3 is more useful than Re1 and probably rook is better placed on f1 in case of future f4 }) (7. Qe2 { With a similar idea is also probably better. After } 7... e5 8. Be3 b6 9. a4 a5 10. Nbd2 Ne7 11. Nc4 O-O 12. Nfd2 Be6 13. f4 { For instance, we see how the point of supporting the e5 advance with the Queen instead of the rook } { [%csl Gf1][%cal Gf1f4,Gf1e1] }) 7... e5 { [%cal Gf2f4] } 8. a3 { Going for the b4 plan } { [%csl Gc5,Ga5] } 8... Nf6!? { Changing his track. Magnus realizes his c5 pawn will be attacked and intends to play Nd7 in the future to get it back } (8... c4) (8... Ne7 9. Be3 b6 10. b4 { Is inferior - Black has to take on b4, which is something he'd rather not do } { [%cal Gf6d7] }) (8... a5 { Is also possible, preventing the b4 advance, but here Black has to reckong with } 9. Be3 b6 10. Nbd2 Ne7 11. Nc4 O-O 12. b4 { For example, when White is close to winning } 12... cxb4 13. Bxb6) 9. b4! { A common idea in this positions. It doesn't look logical to undouble the Black pawns. But in this instance, it helps White to develop and create pressure. } 9... O-O (9... cxb4 { Black really doesn't want to take. After } 10. axb4 O-O 11. Bb2 Nd7 12. Nbd2 { [%csl Ge5,Ga7][%cal Ga1a3,Gd1a1,Gd2b3,Gc2c4] } 12... b5 { Else c4 will be played } (12... Re8 13. Ra3 b5 14. Qa1 { Was suggested by Ssvidler and it also looks nice. White has many ideas }) 13. Nb3 { And White's position just looks nice }) 10. Nbd2 (10. bxc5 { Is not a real pawn sacrifice. } 10... Nd7 { And White can't really defend the pawn. } 11. a4 (11. Be3 f5 { [%cal Gf5f4,Gd7c5] } 12. a4 f4 13. Bc1 Nxc5 14. Ba3 b6 15. Nbd2 Re8 16. Bxc5 bxc5 { It is similar to another line which could have arisen in the game. With the pawn on f4, things are probably slightly more favourable for White, since there is no f6 and e5 is a bit loose, but still, with the two Bishops, Black should be ok. }) 11... Nxc5 12. Ba3 b6 13. Bxc5 bxc5 14. Nbd2 { Is fine for Black }) 10... Bg4 { As beginners, we are taught this pin is seldom good, but Carlsen decides to simplify the position } (10... Bd7) (10... Be6 11. bxc5 (11. Bb2 { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gb2e5] } 11... Nd7 12. Ng5 Rfe8 13. Nxe6 Rxe6 { Is slightly unpleasant, though }) 11... Nd7 { Is probably also ok because } 12. Ng5 Nxc5 13. Nxe6 Nxe6 { Brings the kngiht t o a nice square }) 11. h3 Bxf3 (11... Bh5 { Doesn't really work } 12. bxc5 { Is maybe even better, simply snatching the pawn } (12. g4 Nxg4 13. hxg4 Bxg4 14. Qe2 f5 15. Qe3 (15. Qf1 fxe4 16. Nh2))) 12. Nxf3 (12. Qxf3 cxb4 13. axb4 a5 { [%csl Gf3][%cal Gf3b3] }) 12... cxb4 13. axb4 a5! { The point of Black's play. He gets rid of the a7 weakness. The position is simplified, the material is even and White has only academic advantage } { [%csl Ga7] } 14. bxa5 Rxa5 15. Bd2 Raa8 (15... Rxa1 16. Qxa1 { [%cal Ga1a8] }) 16. Qb1 Nd7 17. Qb4 { [%cal Gb4e7] } 17... Rfe8 { Preventing Qe7 } 18. Bc3 { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gc3a1] } (18. Rxa8 Rxa8 { [%cal Ga8a1] } 19. Qe7 Bf8) 18... b5 { b7 was the only real target, but now even it is gone } { [%csl Gb7] } 19. Rxa8 (19. Qb2 Rxa1 20. Rxa1 Nc5 { [%cal Gc5a4] }) 19... Rxa8 20. Ra1 Rxa1+ 21. Bxa1 Qa7 22. Bc3 Qa2! { A very strong move, based on a very good calculation. } 23. Qb2 { Caruana judges correctly it is time to put the ambitions aside } { [%csl Ge5] } (23. Qe7 { Is dangerous for White. After } 23... Qxc2 24. Qxd7 Qxc3 25. Qe8+ Bf8 26. Nxe5 { [%cal Ge5d7] } 26... Qc1+ (26... Qe1+ { Even stronger than the move considered by commentators. } 27. Kh2 Qxf2 28. Nd7 Qf4+ 29. Kh1 Qd6 30. e5 Qe7 31. Qc8 b4 { And only Black can win this } { [%cal Gb4b1] } 32. Nxf8 Qxf8 33. Qxc6 { [%cal Gb4b3,Gd3d5] }) 27. Kh2 Qf4+) 23... Qxb2 24. Bxb2 f6 { The game is completely equal. Carlsen even tries to push a bit, but a player of Caruana caliber will never lose this position. } { [%cal Gc6c4,Gb5b4] } 25. Kf1 Kf7 26. Ke2 Nc5 27. Bc3 Ne6 { Moving the knight to a nice central square. } { [%csl Ge6][%cal Ge6f4,Ge6d4] } 28. g3 { Preventing Nf4 } { [%csl Gf4] } 28... Bf8 { Activating the bishop } 29. Nd2 (29. Bxe5 fxe5 30. Nxe5+ Ke7 31. Nxc6+ Kd7 32. Ne5+ Kd6 33. Ng4 { And White simply risks losing. }) 29... Ng5 { Provoking the advance of the h-pawn. } (29... Nc5 30. Bb4 Nxe4 { Is a variation mentioned by Svidler, which proves it is never to late to lose a chess game. Obviously, Caruana wasn't going to fall for that } 31. Bxf8 Nc3+ 32. Ke3 Kxf8) 30. h4 Ne6 31. Nb3 h5 32. Bd2 Bd6 33. c3 c5 34. Be3 Ke7 (34... b4 35. Kd1 bxc3 36. Kc2) 35. Kd1 Kd7 36. Kc2 f5 37. Kd1 fxe4 (37... b4 38. Kc2) (37... f4 { [%cal Gg3f5] } 38. Bc1 c4 { [%csl Ge4] } 39. dxc4 bxc4 40. Nd2 fxg3 41. fxg3 Nc5 { Was the most testing. White needs to be careful } { [%csl Gg3,Gc3][%cal Gd2c4,Gc5e4] } 42. Nxc4 (42. Ba3 { Is the most direct } 42... Nxe4 43. Nxe4 Bxa3 44. Nd2 { [%cal Gd2c4] } 44... Be7 45. Nxc4) (42. Kc2 { At first I just tried waiting, but then I realized it won't work } 42... Kc6 43. Nxc4 (43. Bb2 Kb5 { [%csl Gc4] } 44. Bc1 Nd3 { And White is running out of moves } { [%cal Gd6c5,Gc5f2] }) 43... Nxe4 44. Nxd6 Kxd6 45. Kd3 Nxg3 46. Bd2 { Is also probably a draw, but why complicate things }) 42... Nxe4) 38. dxe4 c4 39. Nd2 Nc5 40. Bxc5 Bxc5 { [%cal Gf2f4] } 41. Ke2 Kc6 42. Nf1 b4 43. cxb4 Bxb4 { The passer looks dangerous, but apart from creating his own passer, White has an additional resource } { [%cal Gc4c3] } 44. Ne3 Kc5 45. f4 exf4 (45... Kd4 46. Nc2+) 46. gxf4 Ba5 47. f5 gxf5 48. Nxc4 { The point! White } 48... Kxc4 49. exf5 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } { [%csl Gh1,Ga5][%cal Gh5h1] } ½-½


