1. c4 { After Caruana neutralized Carlsen's white pieces with ease in game 2, it was time to try something different. I'm somewhat surprised he didn't go for 1.e4. In my opinion Carlsen has biggest chances there since the positions are usually most aggressive. } 1... e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 { Classical 4 knights position after 1. c4. } 4. g3 (4. e3 Bb4 { Interestingly players could have entered reversed Rossolimo. }) 4... d5 { Most common answer. } 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2 { [%csl Gd5,Ge5][%cal Gf3g5,Gg2d5,Gd2d4] } 6... Bc5 { Nb6 is by far the most played move. Bc5 is somewhat of a "new" move but it was already played by many strong player such as Caruana himself, Karjakin and others. } { [%cal Gf8c5] } (6... Nb6 { [%cal Gd8d4] } 7. O-O Be7 8. a3 O-O 9. b4 Be6 10. Rb1 f6 11. d3 { We could call this a main line. This position has been played thousands of times and there is a ton of theory in it. }) 7. O-O (7. Nxe5 { Just doesn't work } 7... Nxc3 8. Nxc6 (8. Bxc6+ { [%csl Gg2,Gf3,Gh3] } 8... bxc6 9. bxc3 Qd5 10. Nf3 Bh3 { With excellent compensation } { [%csl Gc6,Gc7] } 11. Qb3 Qh5 { [%cal Gh3g2] }) (8. bxc3 Nxe5 9. d4 Bb6 (9... Bd6 { Is just dead equal } 10. dxe5 Bxe5) 10. dxe5 Qxd1+ 11. Kxd1 { Yermolinsky claimed this was okay, but I think White has some chances here } 11... O-O (11... Bxf2 12. e3) 12. f4) 8... Qf6 { And Black wins! } { [%cal Gc3d1,Gf6f2] }) 7... O-O (7... Bb6 8. Nxe5) 8. d3 { So far, everything has been seen on the top level. Sample games: } { Anand, V. - Caruana, F., 1-0, 5th Sinquefield Cup 2017, https://lichess.org/g8zR7cau } { Nepomniachtchi, I. - Aronian, L., 1/2-1/2, chess.com Speed 5m+2spm 2017, https://lichess.org/Cw9ZnLDV } { Nepomniachtchi, I. - Aronian, L., 1-0, chess.com Speed 5m+2spm 2017, https://lichess.org/n5IzcE2W } { Caruana, F. - Adams, Mi, 1-0, 9th London Classic 2017, https://lichess.org/vWwDAvHG } (8. Nxe5 { Doesn't work again } 8... Nxc3 9. Nxc6 (9. Bxc6 Nxd1) 9... Bxf2+ 10. Rxf2 Nxd1) (8. Nxd5 Qxd5 9. Ng5 Qd8 10. Nxh7 Re8 11. Ng5 Qxg5 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. d4 Qg4 14. dxc5) 8... Re8 { This was actually played in a game in which - Caruana was White } { Caruana, F. - Adams, Mi, 1-0, 9th London Classic 2017, https://lichess.org/vWwDAvHG } (8... Bb6 { Was the most common response in this position } 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 10. Ng5 (10. b4 { Was played in Dubov - Karjakin game in FIDE World Cup 2017. } { Dubov, Daniil - Karjakin, Sergey, 1-0, FIDE World Cup 2017, https://lichess.org/WwZzU0Zn } 10... Nxb4 (10... e4 11. Ng5) 11. Bb2 { With strong compensation } 11... e4 12. Ne5)) 9. Bd2 { Most human move in the position. Also possible was Nd5 which could transit to same or similiar position. } { [%csl Gc3][%cal Gd2c3] } (9. Ng5 { Was how that game went. } 9... Nf6 10. Qb3 { [%cal Gb3f7] } 10... Qe7 11. Nd5 Nxd5 12. Bxd5 Nd8 (12... Nd4 13. Bxf7+ Kh8 14. Qd1 (14. Qc4 Rf8 { [%cal Gf8f2] } 15. Bh5 g6 16. Ne4 gxh5 17. Qxc5 Nxe2+ (17... Qxc5 18. Nxc5 Nxe2+) 18. Kg2 Qxc5 19. Nxc5) 14... Bg4 { [%csl Ge2][%cal Ge8f8] })) (9. Nxd5 Qxd5 10. Bd2 Qd8 (10... Qd6) 11. Bc3) 9... Nxc3 { [%cal Gc6d4] } 10. Bxc3 (10. bxc3 { It was also possible to take with the pawn to reinforce center. Unfortunately for white, there is no good way to push pawns in center and his dark square bishop is now significantly weaker than on c3. } { [%csl Gd2] } 10... h6 11. Qc2 Bb6 12. e4 Bg4 13. h3 Be6 14. Be3 Bxe3 15. fxe3 Qd7 16. Kh2 f6 17. d4 { White succeeded in pushing pawns in centar but black is better. Light squares are weak and c4 square will be really nice for bishop or night. } { [%csl Ge6] } 17... Na5 (17... Bc4)) 10... Nd4 { A thematic move in this position. The exchange of knights eases Black's position } 11. b4 Bd6 (11... Bb6 { Also possible it was more thing of preference if you like your bishop on d6 or b6. } 12. a4 a5) 12. Rb1 { [%cal Ga2a4,Gb4b5] } (12. Nxd4 exd4 13. Bxd4 Bxg3 (13... Bxb4 14. e3 { [%cal Ga1b1,Gb1b7,Gd1c1,Gc1c7] }) 14. hxg3 Qxd4 { Leads to an equal position }) 12... Nxf3+ 13. Bxf3 a6 (13... c6 { c6 was better way to move pawns on queen side for black. It's more flexable and natural. } 14. b5 { Caruana was probably not sure about this evaluation } 14... cxb5 15. Rxb5 Rb8 { Is fine for him, though } (15... Bh3)) 14. a4 c6 { This is the critical moment in game. Carlsen spent almost 20 minutes calculating what's really much by his standard. Obviously the critical move is b5. } 15. Re1 { Very weird and not a critical move. Position is objectively very drawish now. } (15. b5 { Was critical, but Magnus wasn't sure about the evaluation after } 15... axb5 (15... cxb5 16. axb5 a5 { Leads to a somewhat of a double edged position } 17. Qa4 { Is kinda nice for White. There is one line demonstrated by Svidler I would like to repeaet here } { [%cal Gf1c1,Gb5b6,Ge5e4] } 17... h6 (17... Qe7 18. b6 (18. Rfc1 Bf5 19. b6 h6 20. Bxa5 Bd7 (20... Ra6 21. Ra1 (21. Bxb7 { Is stronger } 21... Rxa5 22. Qxa5 Qxb7 23. Qa7) 21... Rea8 22. Qb5 Bd7 23. Qxa6 Rxa6 24. Bxb7) 21. Qa2 Ba3)) 18. Ra1 Qe7 19. Bxa5 Bc7 20. b6 Bxb6 21. Qb5 Bxa5 22. Rxa5 Bd7 23. Qb6 Rxa5 24. Qxa5 b5 25. Rc1 Qd6 { White is better but the advantage is not big enough to win a game. }) 16. axb5 Bd7 17. bxc6 Bxc6 18. Bxc6 bxc6 { Black has weakness on c6. Usually only one weakness is not enough to win a game but in these type of positions that is maximum of what white can get. } { Magnus said afterwards he considered that this position was equivalent to half a draw offer }) 15... Bd7 { From now on, Black is very solid - without b5 it is hard to achieve anything } 16. e3 Qf6 17. Be4 (17. d4 e4) 17... Bf5 { Though there is not really a need for this, Caruana decided to simplify even tho his king side structure will be damged. } (17... Rad8 { Was also possible, white doesn't have an easy way how to improve position. }) 18. Qf3 { Carlsen played this move almost instantly. It's logical and after it, white has a nicer structure. } 18... Bxe4 19. Qxf6 gxf6 20. dxe4 { [%csl Gf5] } 20... b5 { Now that white square bishop and queens are off the board this is also possible. } { [%csl Gb4][%cal Gd6b4] } 21. Red1 Bf8 { The game is now completely equal and draw will soon follow } 22. axb5 axb5 23. Kg2 Red8 24. Rdc1 Kg7 25. Be1 Rdc8 26. Rc2 Ra4 27. Kf3 h5 28. Ke2 (28. g4 Kg6 29. h3 { White doesn't get much from pushing the pawns. They can only be a target for black to attack later. } 29... Kg5) 28... Kg6 29. h3 f5 30. exf5+ Kxf5 31. f3 Be7 32. e4+ Ke6 33. Bd2 Bd6 34. Rbc1 { In my opinion after Carlsen didn't play 15. b5 he was okay with the draw. It says much that he didn't even try to do anything in this position. Easy draw could have been reached by repetition by Kd7 Rd1 Ke6 Rc1 Kd7.... } { I agree to an extent - b5 had to be played since it is the maximum White can get from this opening. On the other hand, Magnus correctly evaluated he would have minimal chances for a win in the resulting position, although it would pose Black with the opportunity to go wrong. } 34... Kd7 (34... Bxb4 35. Bxb4 Rxb4 36. Rxc6+ Rxc6 37. Rxc6+) *


