1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O { [%csl Gc6][%cal Gb5c6] } 4... Bg7 5. Re1 { The first surprise. Caruana avoids taking on c6 and plays the rook move instead. } { [%cal Gb5c6] } 5... e5 { Black prevents e5. The move in the game allows a curious pawn sacrifice played by Caruana! } { [%cal Ge4e5] } (5... Nf6 { Is more common move. After } 6. e5 Nd5 7. Nc3 Nc7 8. Bxc6 dxc6 { We enter another theoretical position }) 6. b4!? { This idea is typical in the Sicilian, although it is a bit strange to see it in a position with the knight on c6.
In this concrete position, it is not a novelty - it has been played on the top level before in the games } { Bacrot, E. - Grischuk, A., 0-1, GCT Rapid Paris 2017, https://lichess.org/y2Bv5vKC } { Rapport, Richard - Granda Zuniga, Julio E, 0-1, Camarinas Entrefaros, 2013, https://lichess.org/WswvPhRg } { [%csl Gd4,Gc6][%cal Gb2b4,Gc5b4,Gd2d4,Gc6b4] } 6... Nxb4 (6... cxb4 7. a3 b3 { Was Grischuk's pragmatic decision. He won that game }) 7. Bb2 { The point of White's play - Black can't defend the e6 pawn with d6 due to pin. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gb2e5,Gd7d6,Gb5d7] } 7... a6 (7... f6 { A natural question - why not reinforce the pawn this way.
Well, it is met by a forceful response: } 8. d4 cxd4 (8... exd4 9. c3 dxc3 10. Nxc3 { [%cal Gb5c4] }) 9. c3 dxc3 10. Nxc3 { And Black is in trouble } 10... Ne7 11. Bc4 { [%cal Gd1b3,Ga1d1,Ga1c1,Ge1d1] } 11... a6 12. Ba3) 8. a3 { Caruana was playing instantly here, indicating he is still in his preparation. Magnus, on the other hand, started thinking here. Most probably he was just trying to remember his preparation. Or simply fool Caruana a bit. } { [%cal Ga2a3] } 8... axb5 (8... Nxc2 { Was considered by Svidler during live broadcast, but it doesn't really work } 9. Qxc2 axb5 10. Nxe5 { And White has a strong threat of Nc6 which is not easy to meet. Black probably has to go } { [%cal Ge5c6,Gb2g7] } 10... b6 (10... Kf8 { But then White is clearly better }) 11. Nc6 dxc6 12. Bxg7) (8... Nc6 9. Bxc6 dxc6 10. Nxe5 { Is obviously good for White }) 9. axb4 Rxa1 10. Bxa1 d6 { [%csl Gc5,Ge5] } 11. bxc5 Ne7! { A great move - returning the pawn to complete the development and preparing to take on d6 with the Queen. This position looks scary, but doubled b-pawns aren't that bad } (11... dxc5 12. Bxe5 Bxe5 13. Nxe5 { Is terrible for Black } { [%csl Gc5,Gb5,Gb7] }) 12. Qe2 { Caruana played all this instantly } (12. cxd6 Qxd6 13. d4 exd4 14. Bxd4 O-O 15. Bxg7 Qxd1 16. Rxd1 Kxg7) (12. Na3 { Was an interesting possibility mentioned by Svidler, but here after } 12... dxc5 (12... b4 13. Nc4) 13. Nxe5 b4 14. Nac4 O-O { Black is fine - he has managed to castle and complete his development }) 12... b4 13. Qc4 (13. Qb5+ Nc6 { And Black is fine. The point is that after } 14. cxd6 (14. d4 exd4 15. Bxd4 (15. Nxd4 O-O 16. Nxc6 bxc6 { Attacks both the queen and the bishop on a1 } { [%csl Ga1][%cal Gc6b5,Gg7a1] }) 15... O-O { And Black is fine } 16. Bxg7 Kxg7) 14... Qxd6 15. d4) 13... Qa5 { [%csl Ga1,Gc5,Gb4] } (13... Qc7 14. Qxb4 (14. d4 dxc5 15. dxc5 Nc6) 14... dxc5 { Is also fine for Black }) 14. cxd6 (14. d4 Qxa1 (14... dxc5 15. Qxc5 Qxa1) 15. cxd6 Nc6 16. d5) 14... Be6 { Only here did Caruana start consuming some time } (14... Nc6 15. d4 { Is bad } 15... Qxa1 16. d5 Na7 17. Qxb4 { [%csl Gb7][%cal Gc2c4] }) 15. Qc7 (15. Qd3 Nc6 16. Bb2 O-O { Is excellent for Black } { [%cal Ga5a2] } (16... Qa2 17. Bxe5 { [%cal Gd3b5] } 17... Bxe5 18. Nxe5 Nxe5 19. Qb5+ { [%cal Gb5e5] } 19... Nc6 20. Qxb7 Qxc2 21. d4)) 15... Qxc7 16. dxc7 Nc6 { Black has an extra pawn, but it is falling soon. If White is not energetic, he might easily end in an inferior position } { [%csl Gc7,Gd4,Ge5] } (16... Kd7 17. Bxe5) 17. c3 (17. Ng5 Kd7 18. f4 Ra8 { Is just bad } 19. Nxe6 fxe6 { The doubled e-pawns are not problematic at all for Black }) (17. d4 exd4 18. Rd1 { Is less precise move order due to } 18... d3 19. Bxg7 dxc2 20. Rc1 cxb1=Q 21. Rxb1 Rg8 22. Bd4 b5 { And Black is fine }) (17. Rd1 { Intending d4, was probably the best move } 17... Kd7 18. d4 { And Black has to be creative } 18... b3!? { [%cal Gd4d5] } (18... exd4 19. Nxd4 Nxd4 20. Bxd4 Bxd4 21. Rxd4+ Kxc7 22. Rxb4 Ra8) 19. Nxe5+ Kxc7 20. cxb3 Bxb3 21. Rc1 Bxe5 22. dxe5 Rd8 { With equality }) 17... Kd7! { Great move by Magnus, giving up the pawn for activity and domination. He correctly judged he will be the one pushing despite the lack of material } (17... bxc3 18. Nxc3 { And White's pieces come to life } { [%cal Gc3b5,Gc3d5] }) (17... b3 18. d4 { [%cal Gd4d5] }) 18. cxb4 Ra8 { [%csl Ga1][%cal Ga8a1] } (18... Nxb4 19. Bxe5) 19. Bc3 { [%csl Gb4] } (19. Nc3 Nxb4 20. Rb1 Kxc7 21. Rxb4 Rxa1+) 19... Kxc7 20. d3 (20. b5 Nd4) (20. Ng5 { [%csl Ge6] }) 20... Kb6 { [%cal Gb6b5,Gb5b4] } (20... b5 { Was a more interesting try for advantage, fixing the b-pawn and removing the b5 threat. A sample line goes } { [%csl Gb4] } 21. Kf1 { What else? } (21. Bd2 Rd8 22. Rc1 Rxd3 23. Be3) 21... Rd8 (21... f6 { [%cal Gg7f8] } 22. d4 Bc4+ 23. Kg1 exd4 24. Nxd4 Nxd4 25. Bxd4 { [%csl Gf6,Gb4] } 25... Bf8 26. Bc3 Ra4 27. Bxf6 Bxb4 28. Rc1 { With some chances } 28... Kd7 { [%csl Gb5,Gb1] }) 22. Ke2 f6 23. Na3 Kb6 24. Bd2) 21. Bd2 { A precise move, after which the games is most likely to end in a draw. } { [%cal Gd2e3] } 21... Rd8 { [%csl Gd3][%cal Gd8d3] } (21... Kb5 22. Nc3+ { [%csl Gb4] } 22... Kxb4 { [%cal Gd2b4] } 23. Nd5+ Kc5 24. Nc7) 22. Be3+ Kb5 { [%cal Gd2b4] } 23. Nc3+ Kxb4 24. Nd5+ Bxd5 25. exd5 Rxd5 26. Rb1+ { [%cal Gb1b7] } 26... Kc3 { [%cal Gc3d3] } 27. Rxb7 Nd8 { [%csl Gf7][%cal Gd8f7] } 28. Rc7+ Kxd3 29. Kf1 { And here Black can't make any progress. } { [%csl Gd3] } 29... h5 (29... e4 30. Ne1# { Is the problem }) (29... f5 30. Rxg7) 30. h3 { There is simply nothing else } 30... Ke4 (30... Bf6 31. g4 hxg4 32. hxg4 Bg7 33. Ne1+ Ke4 34. Ke2 { And Black is in trouble } { [%cal Gf2f3] } 34... Rb5 35. f3+ Kd5 36. Rd7+ { [%csl Gd8][%cal Gd7d8] }) 31. Ng5+ Kf5 32. Nxf7 Nxf7 33. Rxf7+ Bf6 34. g4+ { And here a draw was agreed. A fantastic game by both players. } 34... hxg4 35. hxg4+ Kxg4 (35... Ke6) 36. Rxf6 *


[Event "Carlsen - Caruana World Championship Match"]
[Site "0:00:33-0:12:33"]
[Date "2018.11.16"]
[Round "6"]
[White "Magnus Carlsen"]
[Black "Fabiano Caruana"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "C42"]
[Opening "Petrov's Defense: Karklins-Martinovsky Variation"]
[StudyName "World Chess Championship 2018"]
[ChapterName "Game 6"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/xV6OiytA/bR63V1TK"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/chessentialsBLOG"]

1. e4 { So, finally Magnus decides to play 1 e4! } 1... e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 { Of course, this was expected. Caruana has been playing the Petroff throughout 2018 with great success. Some variations were also seen in the notes } 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nd3 { A weird looking move that has been played many times before. White will follow up with Qe2 and enter an endgame in which he has a knight on f4.
This is most certainly not the most critical try. Magnus Vachier Lagrave called it "naive". But it is typical of Carlsen. } { [%csl Gd3][%cal Gd2d5] } (4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Qe2 Qe7 6. d3 Nf6) 4... Nxe4 5. Qe2 Qe7 6. Nf4 { [%csl Gf3][%cal Gd3f4,Gf4d5] } (6. Nc3 { Has been played in the past. After } 6... Nxc3 7. dxc3 Qxe2+ 8. Bxe2 Nc6 { White argues his development compensates for his inferior pawn structure. But the resulting positions are extremely drawish. }) 6... Nc6 { The most direct way of playing. The point is revealed on the following move } (6... c6 7. Nc3 { Leads to similar variations as in the previous note. } 7... Nxc3 8. dxc3 Qxe2+ 9. Bxe2 { [%csl Gc3,Gc2][%cal Gd1d6,Ge1e6] }) 7. Nd5 Nd4 8. Nxe7 { White is forced to go into this endgame } (8. Qc4 { Is unplayable due to } 8... Nc3+ { [%cal Ge7e1] } 9. Be2 (9. Nxe7 Nxc2# { [%csl Gd1,Ge2][%cal Gc3e2,Gc3d1] }) 9... Nxc2+ 10. Kf1 Qxe2+ { [%csl Ga1][%cal Gc2a1] }) 8... Nxe2 9. Nd5 { [%cal Gd5c7,Gf1e2] } (9. Bxe2 Bxe7 { Is dead equal }) 9... Nd4 { [%cal Gd4c2] } 10. Na3 { [%cal Ga3c2,Ga3b5] } (10. Bd3 Nc5 11. Nxc7+ Kd8 12. Nxa8 Nxd3+ 13. cxd3 Nc2+ { Leads to equality }) (10. Nxc7+ Kd8 11. Nxa8 Nxc2+ 12. Kd1 Nxa1 { And due to the threat on f2, Black is winning } { [%cal Ge4f2] } 13. Ke2 b6 { [%csl Ga1] } 14. f3) 10... Ne6 { [%cal Ge6c7] } 11. f3 (11. Nb5 Kd8 { [%csl Gd8] }) 11... N4c5 12. d4 Nd7 (12... c6 13. dxc5 cxd5 14. cxd6 Bxd6 { [%csl Gd5] }) (12... Nxd4 { Obviously Black can't take } 13. Nxc7+ { [%csl Gc2][%cal Ga3c2] }) 13. c3 c6 14. Nf4 { This is the position Magnus has been aiming for. These type of symmetrical structure is pretty drawish - it can result from the French Exchange variation and Berlin defence of the Ruy Lopez.
Still there are some ideas and in the past Magnus has managed to outplay his opponents even from most innocuous positions. But his opponents weren't Fabiano Caruana. } { [%csl Gd4,Gc3,Gd5,Gc6][%cal Gd6d5] } 14... Nb6 { Preparing to take on e6 with the bishop } { [%cal Gc8e6,Gc8f5] } (14... Nxf4 15. Bxf4 Nf6 16. Nc4 { Is already a bit awkward for Black }) (14... d5 15. Nxe6 fxe6 { [%cal Ge2e6] } 16. Bf4 { the backward pawn on e-file is probably something White wants to get } 16... Bxa3 17. bxa3 { [%csl Ge6][%cal Ga1b1,Gb1b6] }) 15. Bd3 { [%csl Gf5][%cal Gd3f5] } (15. g4 { Is a general idea in this structure, but it needs to be prepared. At the moment it is met with } 15... f5 16. gxf5 Nxf4 17. Bxf4 Bxf5 { [%csl Gf3,Gh2] }) 15... d5 16. Nc2 (16. Nxe6 Bxe6 17. Kf2) 16... Bd6 { [%csl Gf4] } 17. Nxe6 (17. Ne2 { Is not something White should be happy with } 17... O-O { [%csl Ge2,Ge6] } 18. Kf2 Re8) 17... Bxe6 18. Kf2 (18. g4 h5 19. h3 (19. g5 { [%csl Gf5] }) 19... hxg4 { [%cal Gh8h1] }) 18... h5 { Preventing g4 } 19. h4 { [%cal Gh5h4] } 19... Nc8 { Going for f5 } { [%cal Gb6c8,Gc8e7,Ge7f5] } 20. Ne3 { [%csl Ge6,Gd3,Gd5,Gc6,Gb7] } 20... Ne7 21. g3 c5!? { A very ambitious move, sharply altering the character of the play. Most importantly - a good psychological decision. The subsequent course of the game showed Magnus played a bit "light-heartedly" and underestimated the dangers. } (21... O-O 22. Ng2 { [%cal Gc1f4] } 22... Bf5 23. Bf4 Bxf4 24. Nxf4 Bxd3 25. Nxd3 { [%csl Gh5,Ge5,Gc5,Gf4][%cal Gh1e1,Gd3c5,Gd3e5] }) 22. Bc2 { Carlsen was critical of this decision } { [%cal Gc5d4] } (22. Ng2 cxd4 23. cxd4 Nc6 24. Be3 { Was probably most solid, defending d4 immediately and putting the rook to c1 }) (22. dxc5 Bxc5 { [%cal Gd5d4] } 23. Rd1! { Preventing d4 } 23... d4 (23... O-O { [%cal Gd5d4,Ge3c2,Gc5f2] } 24. Kg2 d4 25. cxd4 Bxd4 { And Black is even slightly more comfortable } 26. Be4 Rfd8 27. Bxb7 Rab8 28. Be4 g6 29. Rb1 Bxa2) 24. cxd4 Bxd4 25. Bb5+ { [%csl Gd4][%cal Gb5e8,Gd1d4] }) 22... O-O 23. Rd1 Rfd8 24. Ng2 (24. dxc5 Bxc5 25. Kg2 Rac8 { And d4 soon comes }) 24... cxd4 { [%cal Gd1d4] } 25. cxd4 { [%csl Gf4] } (25. Rxd4 Bc5 { [%csl Gd4,Gf2][%cal Gc5f2] }) 25... Rac8 26. Bb3 Nc6 { [%cal Gc6a5,Ga5c4] } 27. Bf4 { [%cal Gd6f4] } 27... Na5 { [%cal Gd1c1] } 28. Rdc1 { A move it was difficult to understand for me } (28. Bxd6 { Leads to problems due to } 28... Nxb3 29. axb3 Rc2+ { [%cal Gc2f2] } 30. Kg1 Rxd6 31. Rxa7 Rb6 { And even though White probably isn't lost yet, the position is very uncomfortable } { [%cal Gb6b3,Gb3b2,Gc2b2] }) (28. Rac1 Nxb3 29. axb3 Bb4 { Is also playable, but here Black has a solid plus - his a-pawn is not hanging so he manages to remove the bishop from being exchanged just in time } { [%csl Ga7][%cal Ga1a7] }) 28... Bb4 { Avoiding the exchange of the dark-squared bishops } (28... Nxb3 29. axb3 Bb4 30. Rxa7) 29. Bd1 Nc4 30. b3 Na3 { [%csl Gd4][%cal Ga3b5] } 31. Rxc8 Rxc8 32. Rc1 Nb5 33. Rxc8+ Bxc8 { White's position is more unpleasant than it looks } 34. Ne3 (34. Bc1 Nc3 35. Ne3 Nxa2 36. Nxd5 Nxc1 37. Nxb4 a6 (37... a5 38. Nd5 Be6)) (34. Be2 Nxd4) 34... Nc3 35. Bc2 (35. Be2 Ba3 (35... Be6 36. a4) 36. Bb8 a6 37. f4 { And the point is that the bishop stays on important diagonal }) (35. a4 Nxd1+ 36. Nxd1 { Is safer, but Magnus probably didn't believe he was worse } 36... Be6) 35... Ba3 { [%csl Ga2,Gd4] } 36. Bb8 { [%cal Gb8f4,Gf4c1,Ga7a6] } (36. Bd3 { Svidler said it is maybe better to play Bd3, because after } 36... Nxa2 (36... Be6 { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gc3a2] } 37. Nc2 Bb2 38. a4 { And White again survives }) 37. Nxd5 Be6 (37... Nc1 { Is impossible now } 38. Bxc1 Bxc1 39. Ne7+ { [%cal Ge7c8] }) 38. Be4 f5 39. Nc7 { And White is fine }) 36... a6 37. f4 { [%csl Ge2][%cal Ge2h5] } (37. Bd3 { The problem is that now this doen't work } 37... Nxa2 38. Nxd5 Nc1 39. Be4 (39. Bc4 b5 { [%csl Ga6][%cal Ga6b5] }) 39... Nxb3 40. Nb6 { And White has to hope he can survive in this position }) 37... Bd7 { [%cal Gc8d7,Gd7c6] } (37... Be6 38. f5) 38. f5 (38. Bd1 { Immediately was also possible, but after } 38... Nxd1+ 39. Nxd1 Be6 40. Ne3 g6 (40... Bb2) 41. Ba7 Bc1 { And White is probably fine, but Black can push }) 38... Bc6 39. Bd1 { [%cal Gd7c6] } 39... Bb2 (39... Nxa2 40. Bxh5 Bb2 41. Ba7 Nc3 { [%cal Gc3b5] } 42. Bb6 Nb5 { Was mentioned by Svidler as a better way of posing problems and I agree. Say } 43. Bf3 (43. Nc2 Nd6 (43... Bd7 { [%csl Gf5][%cal Gd7f5] } 44. g4 { [%cal Gh5d1] }) 44. Bf3 Nxf5) 43... Bxd4 44. Bxd4 Nxd4 45. Bd1 { "It is unenviable to play this as White." }) 40. Bxh5 Ne4+ { The 40th move. } (40... Nxa2 41. Ba7 Nc3 { Was still the transposition to the pervious note } { [%cal Gc3b5] }) 41. Kg2 { Keeping an eye on g3 } { [%csl Gg2,Gg3][%cal Gg2g3] } (41. Kf1 Bxd4 42. Nc2 Ba7 { Is unpleasant } { [%cal Gb8a7] } 43. Bxa7 (43. Bc7 Bd7 { [%csl Gf5] } 44. g4 (44. Bg4 Bc5 45. Bf4 { Hold material, but looks extremely unpleasant }) (44. Nb4 Bc5 45. Nxd5 Bc6 { [%csl Gd5] }) 44... Nf6) 43... Nxg3+ 44. Kf2 Nxh5 45. Bd4) 41... Bxd4 42. Bf4 Bc5 { [%cal Gd5d4] } 43. Bf3 Nd2 44. Bxd5 { Deciding to give up a piece for three pawns and hoping to hold } (44. Nd1 { Was mentioned by Sam Shankland in his analysis } 44... Nxf3 45. Kxf3 d4+ 46. Ke2 Be4 47. g4 Bb1 48. Kd2 { And although the pawn is taboo, it is highly unpleasant for White } 48... Bb4+ (48... Bxa2 49. Kc2 Ba3 50. Nb2 { [%cal Gb2c4] } 50... b5 { [%cal Gb2c4] } 51. Bd2 { And Black is stuck })) (44. Nf1 { Was mentjoned by svidler } 44... Nxf3 45. Kxf3 d4+ 46. Kf2 Be4 47. g4 Bb1 48. Nd2 Bxa2 49. Ke2 { And here, amazingly, White is pretty solid because Black's light squared bishop can't move. But who wants to enter a position where opponent has two bishops and an extra pawn? } { [%csl Ga2] }) 44... Bxe3 45. Bxc6 (45. Bxe3 Bxd5+ { [%cal Gd5g2,Ge3d2] }) 45... Bxf4 46. Bxb7 Bd6 47. Bxa6 Ne4 { What will lose one of his pawns on the queenside and will have to fight for a draw. } { [%csl Gg3] } 48. g4 Ba3 { [%cal Ga2a4,Ge4c3] } 49. Bc4 { [%cal Gb3b4] } 49... Kf8 50. g5 Nc3 51. b4! { A good decision, keeping the farther pawn alive } { [%csl Gc7][%cal Ga2a8,Ga5h5,Gf8e7,Ge7d7,Gd7c7,Gc7b7,Gb7a7] } 51... Bxb4 52. Kf3 Na4 53. Bb5 Nc5 54. a4 { [%csl Gf7][%cal Gf5f6] } 54... f6 { Else White will play f6 himself and fix the pawn on f7 } 55. Kg4 Ne4 56. Kh5 Be1 { Preventing Kg6 } { [%cal Gh5g6] } 57. Bd3 Nd6 58. a5 { Deciding to give up the pawn straight away just to get the king to g6. As Svidler showed in his analysis, White is bound to give it up sooner or later, but delaying it might allow some additional resources for Black (catching it with the king) } { [%cal Gg8e7,Gf8e7] } (58. Kg6 Bxh4 59. gxf6 Bxf6 60. a5 Ke8 61. a6 Nc8 { Is also bad }) (58. gxf6 gxf6 59. Kg6 Bxh4 60. a5 Ne8 61. a6 Bf2 62. Bb5 Nc7 63. Bc6 Ke7 { Is just losing } { [%cal Ge7f6] } 64. Bb7) 58... Bxa5 59. gxf6 gxf6 60. Kg6 Bd8 61. Kh7 { A key move - not allowing Kg8-Kh8, which would easy Black's task. } { [%cal Gf8g8,Gg8h8] } 61... Nf7 { The position is probably a draw, despite the engine displaying a massive advantage for Black - they don't understand fortresses that well. However, there are more adventures yet to come. } 62. Bc4 Ne5 63. Bd5 Ba5 64. h5 { The pawn has to advance sooner or later } (64. Bb3 Be1 65. h5) 64... Bd2 65. Ba2 Nf3 66. Bd5 Nd4 67. Kg6? { The losing move of the game, although it is virtually impossible to find the refutation over the board. } (67. Be4 { Black's idea is to get the bishop to g5 and then the knight to f4 (attacking the h5 pawn). White has to control e2 square once the bishop reaches g5 } { [%csl Ge2,Gg8][%cal Gd2g5,Gd4e2,Ge2f4,Gh5h6] } 67... Ne2 (67... Bg5 68. Bd5 (68. Bd3 { You can't possible allow Ne2 } { [%cal Gd3e2] } 68... Kf7 (68... Nf3 69. Bc2 (69. Be2 Nh4 70. Bd3 Ng2 71. Be4 Ne3 72. Bd3 Kf7 (72... Ke7 73. Be4) 73. Be4 Nf1 { Svidler was worried about Nf1 } 74. Bd3 Ng3 75. Bc4+ Kf8 76. Kg6 { And this setup is a draw. } { [%cal Gc4g8,Gf8h8,Gc4e2,Gg3e2,Ge2f4] }) (69. Be4) 69... Nh4 70. Bd3 Ng2 71. Be4 Ne3 72. Bd3 Kf7) 69. Be4) (68. Bb1 Ne2 69. Bc2 { [%cal Ge2g3,Ge2f4] } 69... Ng3 70. Kg6 Kg8 { [%csl Gb3][%cal Gb3g8] } 71. Bd3 Kh8 { And now Black will swing the knight to e5. White has to push h6 but his king will get moved and he will slowly lose. } { [%csl Gg4,Gh6][%cal Gg3e5,Gh5h6,Gf8h8,Gh5h7] })) 68. Bd3 Nf4 { [%cal Gd2g5] } 69. Bc2 { And now Black can't play Bg5. }) 67... Bg5 68. Bc4 Nf3? { This is where Caruana misses a study-like win. } { [%cal Gf3e5] } (68... Bh4 { As pointed out by a number of commentators, was winning. The point is that White is in zugzwang. } { [%csl Gf5][%cal Gg6h6,Gd4f5] } 69. Bd3 { [%csl Gf5,Ge2] } (69. Ba2 { [%cal Ga2g8] } 69... Ne2 { And White gets go f4 } 70. Bb3 (70. h6 Nf4+ 71. Kh7 Bg5 { And Black will win } 72. Bc4 Ng2 73. Kg6 (73. Bd3 Ne3 { [%csl Gh6][%cal Ge3g4] }) 73... Nh4+ { [%csl Gf5] }) 70... Nf4+ 71. Kh6 Bg5+ 72. Kh7) (69. Bd5 Ne2 { [%cal Ge2f5,Ge2g3] } 70. Bf3 Ng1!! { The most difficult move of the game - who would want to trap his knight like that? Svidler: "A move I believe a human player is more or less incapable of making" } 71. Bd5 (71. Bg4 Bg5 (71... Kg8 72. Kh6 Bg5+ (72... Be1 73. Kg6 Bg3 (73... Bc3 74. Kh6 Bd2+ 75. Kg6 Bg5 { [%cal Gg1h3] } 76. h6 Kh8 77. h7 { And now once again } 77... Bh4 78. Kh5 Be1 79. Kg6 Bc3 80. Kh6 Bd2+ 81. Kg6 Bg5 { And White is in zugzwang } { [%csl Gh7] } 82. Bd1 Nh3 { [%cal Gh3f4] }) 74. Kh6) 73. Kg6 Kh8)) 71... Nh3 (71... Bg5 { Is another zugzwang } 72. Kh7 Ne2 { This is the position White has been trying to avoid } 73. Bf3 (73. h6 { Is forced } 73... Nf4 74. Ba2 Ng2 75. Be6 Ne3 76. Bc8 Ng4 { And h6 falls }) 73... Ng3 74. Kg6 Kg8) 72. Kh7 Nf4 73. Bf3 Bg5 74. Kh8) (69. h6 Nf3 70. h7 Ne5+ 71. Kh5 Kg7) 69... Kg8 { Is winning } { [%cal Gg8h8] }) 69. Kh7 { Now, amazingly, Black is unable to win any longer. } { [%csl Gg8][%cal Gh7g8] } 69... Ne5 (69... Nd4 { And here White is not forced to play Kg6, but can go for Bd3 } 70. Bd3 (70. Kg6)) 70. Bb3 Ng4 71. Bc4 Ne3 72. Bd3 Ng4 73. Bc4 Nh6 74. Kg6 { Caruana has even repeated the position with the knight on g4, so he even didn't have the opportunity to play Ng4 here, due to the three-fold repetition. } 74... Ke7 (74... Ng4) 75. Bb3 Kd6 76. Bc2 Ke5 77. Bd3 Kf4 78. Bc2 Ng4 79. Bb3 Ne3 (79... Ne5+ 80. Kg7 Kxf5 81. h6 { And it is a draw }) 80. h6 Bxh6 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } 81. Kxh6 { What a titanic struggle, worthy of a World Chess Championship. After relatively quiet and calm opening nobody expected such drama. This is the second time a player got a real opportunity to score a win, but can anyone blame Caruana for missing it? Full credit to him for outplaying Magnus on his "home soil". After a rest day, the second half of the match is approaching. The tension is at its peak.
Can't wait for Sunday! } 1/2-1/2


