1. d4 { Before the game Chessentials team was talking about what will be the first move of the game. We agreed that 1.d4 was most likely but hoped for 1.e4 and some craziness in game. } 1... Nf6 { Caruana had no reason to change the opening since he equalized with an ease in game 2. } 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bf4 O-O 6. e3 c5 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. Qc2 Nc6 9. a3 { [%csl Gb4][%cal Gc6b4] } 9... Qa5 { Up until this point, game is following game 2. } 10. Nd2 { [%cal Gd2b3,Gb3a5,Gb3c5] } (10. b4 { b4 ideas are almost never possible in this type of position. Geometry and compensation will almost always go in black's favor. } { [%cal Ga5a1] } 10... Bxb4 $19) (10. Rd1 { Carlsen played this continuation in game 2 and was surprised by rare 10...Rd8 which caught him off guard. In my opinion, if Rd1 was played in this game, Caruana would play main line with 10...Be7 since Rd8 isn't objectively the best move. } 10... Rd8) (10. O-O-O Be7 11. g4 { Well known theoretical line played by names such as Anand, Kasparov, Kramnik and others. In more recent years it has fall in popularity due to black finding a way to equalize. } { Anand, Viswanathan - Kramnik, Vladimir, 1/2-1/2, Leon Man+Comp, 2002, https://lichess.org/Mmgz4I1X } { Kramnik, Vladimir - Karpov, Anatoly, 1/2-1/2, Amber-blindfold 07th, 1998, https://lichess.org/nxJfo18P } { Kasparov, Garry - Khalifman, Alexander, 1/2-1/2, Reggio Emilia-A 9192 34th, 1992, https://lichess.org/FuEZGUXt } (11. h4)) 10... Be7 (10... Qd8 { Again very rare move by Caruana. It can look weird but actually it's quite logical. Black is arguing that Knight on f3 was better than on d2, also queen is better on d8 than a5. } 11. Nb3 { Best continuation for white. } { [%csl Gc5][%cal Gc5e7,Gc5d6] } (11. b4 { After queen has gone back, b4 is possible but allows black to attack the centar right away. } 11... d4 12. bxc5 e5 13. Bg5 dxc3 14. Qxc3 Bf5 $14) (11. Nf3 Qa5 12. Nd2 Qd8 13. Nf3 Qa5 { Black is always happy with a draw. }) 11... Bb6 (11... Bd6 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. Rd1 Ne7) (11... Be7 12. Rd1 { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gc6e7] }) 12. Be2?! { After this questionable move, A. Grischuk called Carlsen's preparation "childish". It's clear Carlsen was on his own at this point and he should've been ready for this position since he had a week since game 2 to prepare it. Rd1 is better in every way. In this kind of position white delays the development of light square bishop to try and capture on c4 after dc4 in 1 tempi. } { [%cal Gd5c4,Ge2c4] } (12. O-O-O { Leading into some extremely double-edged positions. It's understandable Carlsen doesn't want to all-in if he's not forced to. }) (12. Rd1 { Requires from black to play more precisely. } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gd1d8] } 12... Qe7 { [%csl Gd5] } (12... Ne7 13. Bg5 { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gg5e7] }) 13. Bg3 { [%csl Gc4][%cal Ge6e5,Gf1c4] } (13. cxd5 exd5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Rxd5 Be6 16. Rd1 Rac8 { [%cal Gc8c2,Ge6b3,Gc6b4,Gf4d6] } (16... Rfc8 { [%cal Gf4d6] })) 13... Bd7 (13... dxc4 14. Bxc4 { [%cal Gg3d6] }) 14. c5 (14. cxd5 exd5 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. Rxd5 Be6 17. Rd1 Rfc8 $19 { White is a pawn up but is underdeveloped. Black is winning in this position. }) 14... Bxc5 15. Nxd5 { [%cal Gc2c5,Gb3c5] } 15... exd5 16. Qxc5 Qe4 17. Qc1 { [%csl Gd5,Gd1] } 17... Rac8 18. Nc5 Qe7 19. Nxd7 Qxd7 20. Qb1 { Although white is pawn dawn he is better in this position. d5 pawn is extremely weak and white's bishop's are really strong. } 20... h6 (20... d4 21. Bd3 dxe3 (21... Qe7 22. O-O dxe3 23. Bd6) 22. Bxh7+) 21. Bd3 Qe7 22. O-O) 12... Qe7 (12... dxc4 { Decent option for black. After white wasted a move with bishop this is often automatic move. } 13. Nd2 (13. Bxc4 Bd7 14. O-O Bc7 { [%csl Gb6][%cal Gc5b6,Gb6c7] } 15. Bxc7 Qxc7 16. Be2 Rac8 17. Rfd1 Ne7 18. Rac1 Ned5 $10 { With total equality. }) 13... Nd5) (12... e5 13. Bg5 dxc4 14. Bxc4 Be6 15. Bxe6 fxe6 16. Nd2 $16 { This type of position is decent for black, but Caruana correctly assessed there is no need to make long term weaknesses in his position. }) 13. Bg5 { White had a few good alternatives here. All are playable but Carlsen probably decided for this move since it's the most complicated one and black has to always be careful about the pin. } { [%cal Gg5e7] } (13. Rd1 Rd8 14. O-O dxc4 15. Nd2 Bc7) (13. O-O dxc4 14. Nd2 Nd5 15. Nxc4 Nxf4 16. exf4 Nd4 17. Qe4 Nxe2+ 18. Nxe2) 13... dxc4 (13... d4 { Very aggressive line that not good for black. } 14. Ne4 dxe3 15. fxe3 { White has to see this calm move, otherwise black would be better. } (15. Nxf6+ gxf6 16. Bxe3 Bxe3 17. fxe3 b6)) 14. Nd2 { [%cal Gd2c4] } (14. Bxc4 $10 { Safer option that kills most of the game right away. Material is equal with same structure. } 14... h6 { [%cal Gc3e4] } 15. Bh4 (15. Bxf6 Qxf6) 15... Ne5 { [%cal Ge5c4,Gc3e4] } 16. Be2 Bd7 17. Ne4 g5 18. Nxf6+ Qxf6 19. Bg3) 14... Ne5 (14... h6 15. Bh4 (15. Bxf6 Qxf6 16. Nxc4 Bc7) 15... Ne5 { [%cal Gg7g5] }) 15. O-O (15. Nce4 { [%csl Gc4][%cal Gg7f6] } 15... Bd7 16. Qc3 Nxe4 17. Nxe4 f6 { [%cal Gc3e5] } 18. Qxe5 fxg5 (18... Bc6 { [%cal Gc6e4] } 19. O-O (19. Bh4 fxe5 20. Bxe7 Rfe8 { [%csl Ge4] }) 19... Rae8 20. Bxc4 Bc7 21. Bxf6 (21. Qxe6+ Qxe6 22. Bxe6+ Rxe6 23. Nc5 Bxh2+ (23... Re5 24. Bf4 Rxc5 25. Bxc7) 24. Kxh2 Re5 25. Nd7 Bxd7 26. Bf4 Re6 $10) 21... gxf6 22. Qd4) 19. Nxg5) (15. Nxc4 { There is no need for white to rush with taking. }) 15... Bd7 { [%csl Gd7][%cal Gd7c6,Gc8e6] } (15... h6 { White's bishop isn't ideally placed so there is no need to waste a "tempo" for pushing him away. }) 16. Bf4 (16. Nce4 Bc6 17. Nxf6+ { Black isn't all that unhappy about corrupting his structure in this way. He will have more than enough compensation for it with strong bishops, central control and opened g-file. } 17... gxf6 18. Bh4 Ng6 19. Qxc4 (19. Bg3 { [%cal Gd2c4,Gf7f5] }) 19... e5 20. Qg4 Qe6 21. Qh5 Nxh4 22. Qxh4 f5 $15) 16... Ng6 $10 { After this move, both players evaluated position as equal and simplified it without spending any time in next 9 moves. } { [%cal Gd7c6,Gb6c7] } 17. Bg3 Bc6 18. Nxc4 { [%cal Gg3d6] } 18... Bc7 { [%cal Gg3d6] } 19. Rfd1 Rfd8 20. Rxd8+ Rxd8 21. Rd1 Rxd1+ 22. Qxd1 Nd5 { [%csl Ga7,Gb7,Ge6,Gf7,Gg7,Gh7,Gh2,Gg2,Gf2,Ge3,Gb2,Ga3] } 23. Qd4 Nxc3 24. Qxc3 Bxg3 25. hxg3 Qd7 26. Bd3 b6 (26... Be4 { Black is offering a draw with this move. } 27. Bxe4 (27. Be2 Bc6 28. f3) 27... Qd1+ 28. Kh2 Qh5+ 29. Kg1 Qd1+) 27. f3 Bb7 (27... Ne7 28. Ne5 Qd6) 28. Bxg6 { During the live stream, Svidler and Grischuk said that there is no need for black to allow white bishop and knight exchange, but Caruana correctly assessed white can make no progress in this endgame. } { [%cal Gc4d6] } 28... hxg6 29. e4 Qc7 30. e5 Qc5+ (30... f6 31. exf6 (31. Nd6 Qxc3 32. bxc3 Ba6 33. f4 { Entering similar position to one in game. No side can't make any proggress. }) 31... gxf6 32. Qxf6 Qxc4 33. Qd8+ Kf7 34. Qd7+ Kf6 35. Qxb7 Qc1+ $10) 31. Kh2 Ba6 32. Nd6 Qxc3 33. bxc3 f6 { [%cal Ge5d6] } 34. f4 Kf8 35. Kg1 { [%csl Gg2][%cal Gg1d4] } (35. Kh3 Ke7 36. g4 g5 37. Kg3 Bd3 38. Kf3 gxf4 39. Kxf4 fxe5+ 40. Kxe5 Kd7 41. Nf7 Be2 42. g5 Bf1 43. g3 Bc4 44. Nd6 Bd3 45. Nf7 Bc4 46. Nd6 Bd3 $10) (35. g4 { [%csl Gg2] } 35... Ke7) 35... Ke7 36. Kf2 Kd7 37. Ke3 Bf1 38. Kf2 Ba6 39. Ke3 Bf1 40. Kf2) *


[Event "World Chess Championship 2018: Game 8"]
