1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { Finally, an open Sicilian. The predictions that Caruana will "go for it" as the match approaches tiebreaks proved justified. } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 { So, Carlsen decides to go for the Sveshnikov variation. } (4... g6 { Caruana, F. - Carlsen, M., 1/2-1/2, 2nd Sinquefield Cup 2014, https://lichess.org/dAgngFMv } { Morozevich, Alexander - Carlsen, Magnus, 1-0, Moscow Tal Memorial 8th Blitz, 2013, https://lichess.org/E1aTvdT4 } { In the previous game between these opponents, he went for the accelerated Dragon (Sinquefield Cup 2014) }) 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Nd5 { Much less common than 7 Bg5. It seemed Caruana once again managed to surprise Magnus in the opening. Many commentators pointed out Kramnik played this move at the recently concluded Olympiad (against Milos Roganovic). } (7. Bg5 { Is by far the most common move, that Carlsen faced several times before, e.g. } { Giri, A. - Carlsen, M., 1/2-1/2, 3rd Sinquefield Cup 2015, https://lichess.org/3T6laDU6 } 7... a6 8. Na3 b5 9. Nd5) 7... Nxd5 8. exd5 { White immediately obtains the pawn on d5 and queenside pawn majority. He already declares his intention to play on the queenside. } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gc2c5,Gb2b5,Ga2a5,Gf7f5,Gg7g5,Gh7h5] } 8... Nb8 { The main move nowadays. } (8... Ne7 { Was played in the afore-mentioned Kramnik game. It is interesting to note Kramnik himself played this move with good results ... back in 1994. } 9. c4 Ng6 (9... a6 10. Qa4 { Is the point - the knight on e7 blocks the bishop on f8. } 10... Bd7 (10... axb5) 11. Nxd6#) 10. Qa4 Bd7 11. Qb4 Qb8) 9. a4 { A useful move, gaining space on the queenside and preparing Na3-Nc4. } { [%cal Gb5a3,Ga3c4,Ga4a5] } (9. c4 { Takes away the square from the bishop. } { [%csl Gc4][%cal Gb5a3,Ga3c4] } 9... a6 10. Nc3 (10. Qa4 Nd7 11. c5 dxc5 12. d6 { [%cal Gb5c7] } 12... axb5 13. Qxa8 Bxd6 { [%csl Ge5,Gc5,Gb7,Gf7,Gg7,Gh7,Gb5] }) 10... Be7) 9... Be7 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O Nd7 12. Bd2 { A very rare move. The idea is to push a5 and keep it defended. There are only 6 games in lichess database between 2500+ players. } { Oparin, G. - Gelfand, B., 1-0, Nutcracker Rapid 2017, https://lichess.org/ouKRFuux } { Oparin, G. - Gelfand, B., 1/2-1/2, Nutcracker Classical 2017, https://lichess.org/yje89s7M } { Santos Ruiz, Miguel - Fier, A., 1-0, 10th dMP Batavia Blitz, 2018, https://lichess.org/MzVd8hve } { [%csl Ga5][%cal Gd2a5] } (12. Kh1 { Was almost exclusively played here, with the idea of } { [%cal Gf2f4] } 12... a6 13. Na3 f5 14. f4) (12. a5 { You can't play a5 immediately due to } 12... a6 13. Nc3 (13. Na3 Qxa5 { [%cal Ga3c4] })) 12... f5 (12... a6 { Would most likely transpose } 13. Na3 f5 (13... a5 { Was played by Gelfand, but it looks ugly. he lost that game } { Oparin, G. - Gelfand, B., 1-0, Nutcracker Rapid 2017, https://lichess.org/ouKRFuux }) 14. a5) 13. a5 a6 { It is debatable whether Black should play a6. White doesn't treat a6 himself. } { [%cal Gb5a3,Ga3c4,Gc4b6,Gb5d6] } (13... f4 { Was played in one game between 2500 players } { Turkov, Vladimir Sergeevich - Moll, Reinhard, 1/2-1/2, CCO20/F, 2016, https://lichess.org/EK1UrjaM } 14. f3 (14. Bb4 { [%csl Gd6] } 14... Rf6) 14... a6 15. Na3 (15. Nc3 { [%cal Gc3e4] } 15... b5 (15... Nf6 16. Na4 Bf5 17. c4 Qe8 { With complicated play }) 16. axb6 Qxb6+ 17. Kh1) 15... Qe8) 14. Na3 e4 15. Nc4 Ne5 16. Nb6 { The best move. Caruana played this instantly, meaning he was excellently prepared. } { [%csl Gb6] } (16. Nxe5 dxe5 { Although White's queenside pawns look threatening, White has sufficient counterplay. } { [%cal Gc2c4,Gb2b4,Gf5f4,Ge4e3,Ge5e4] } 17. c4 f4 18. Bg4 (18. b4 f3 19. gxf3 Bh3 20. fxe4 Bxb4 { [%cal Gd2b4] } 21. Bxb4 Qg5+ 22. Bg4 Bxg4) 18... Qd6 19. Bxc8 Raxc8) 16... Rb8 17. f4 { Quite logical, hindering Black's pawn duo. This idea is common in King's Indian and other lines. } { [%csl Gf5,Ge4] } 17... exf3 { [%cal Gc2c4,Gb2b4] } 18. Bxf3 g5?! { The critical moment of the game. Here Carlsen had his first long think. This move might actually be the source of his troubles, but perhaps he thought it helpes him to avoid Caruana's preparation. The problem is he doesn't have a follow up } (18... Bg5 { Was mentioned by Svidler ,but after } 19. c4 { Black is once again struggling to find a reply. } 19... Nxf3+ 20. Rxf3 f4 21. h3 Qf6 { And already here White can consider } 22. c5 Qd4+ 23. Kh1 Qxc5 24. Rc1 Qd4 25. Rc4 Qe5 { With definite compensation }) (18... f4 { Later grandmaster Niclas Huscenbeth tweeted a photo which displayed this move in his notes. } { [%cal Gc8f5] } 19. c4 (19. Be4 Bg4 { and now there is no Qc2 } { [%cal Gd1c2] }) 19... Bf6 20. Be4 (20. Nxc8 Rxc8 21. Bxf4 Nxf3+ 22. Qxf3 Bxb2) (20. Bxf4 Nxf3+ 21. Qxf3 Bd4+ 22. Kh1 Bxb2 23. Rae1 Be5 { Is fine for Black }) 20... Bg4 21. Qc2 { [%cal Gc2h7,Gh7h6] } 21... Ng6 22. Bxg6) 19. c4 f4 (19... g4 { The problem is this doesn't really work. After } 20. Be2 Bg5 { [%cal Ge7g5] } 21. g3 { Black's counterplay is too slow and he will get anihilated on the other wing } { [%cal Gf5f4,Gb2b4,Gc4c6,Gc4c5,Gd8f6,Gf6h6] }) 20. Bc3 { With the strong threat of c5 against almost anything } { [%cal Gc4c5] } 20... Bf5 (20... Bf6 21. c5 dxc5 22. d6 { Is almost winning }) (20... Qc7 { [%cal Gc4c5] } 21. b4 { [%cal Gc4c5] } 21... Bf6 (21... Bf5 22. Rc1 g4 23. Be2 { [%cal Gf4f3] }) (21... Nxc4 22. Rc1 (22. Nxc8 Rbxc8 23. Bg4 Rce8 (23... Ne5 24. Bxe5 dxe5 25. Bxc8 Rxc8 26. Rc1))) 22. Rc1 { Is obviously something Black wants to avoid - he is passive here. }) 21. c5! { A strong blow, putting Black on the verge of defeat } 21... Nxf3+ 22. Qxf3 dxc5 { At least Black has a pawn for his troubles. } 23. Rad1 { A logical move, putting the rook behind the pawn and aiming to put another rook on e1. But this is the first move that can perhaps be criticized, although it does not yet ruin White's advantage } { [%csl Gd5][%cal Ga1d1,Gd1d5,Gf1e1,Ge1e6] } (23. Rae1 { Controling the e5 square was stronger, but you need to find a brilliant follow up after } 23... Bf6 (23... Bd6 { [%cal Gd6f4,Gg5g4] } 24. Qh5 (24. Nc4 { With the threat of Nxd6 followed by Be5 } { [%cal Ga1e1,Gc4d6,Gc3e5] } 24... Rc8 (24... g4 25. Qf2 { [%csl Gc5,Gf4] }) 25. Qh5 { Is pretty horrible for Black } 25... Bg6 (25... Be7 26. d6 Bxd6 (26... Bf6 27. h4) 27. Qh6) 26. Qh6) 24... Rf7 25. Nc4 Bf8 26. d6) 24. h4 { Everyone was exclaiming Black is winning, but you need to find this move to make it clear-cut. } (24. Qh5) 24... gxh4 (24... Rf7 25. hxg5 Bxc3 26. Qxc3 Qxg5 27. d6 { And once again the knight on b6 dominates }) (24... h6 25. Qh5 { [%csl Gb8,Gb6] }) (24... Bxc3 25. Qxc3 (25. bxc3 g4 (25... h6 26. g4 fxg3 27. Qxg3 { [%csl Gb6,Gb8][%cal Gf1f7,Ge1e7,Gb6c8,Gb6a8,Gb6d7] }) 26. Qxf4 Qxh4 27. Qh2 Qxh2+ 28. Kxh2 { And in this endgame White is close to winning. }) 25... Qd6) 25. Qxf4 Bxc3 26. bxc3 Bg6 27. Qh2) 23... Bd6 { [%cal Gg5g4] } 24. h3? { But this is the real howler, which lets Black back into the game } (24. Qh5 { For better or for worse, this had to be played. After } { [%cal Gc3g7,Gh5h6] } 24... Bg6 (24... Qe8 { Is perhaps the best. } 25. Qxg5+ Qg6 26. Qxg6+ hxg6 27. Nc4 Rbd8 { And Black can hope he can survive this endgame where he will be a pawn down after } 28. Nxd6 Rxd6 29. Be5 Rd7 30. Bxf4 { [%csl Gb7,Ga6,Gc5] }) (24... Rf7 25. Nc4 Bf8 26. d6 (26. Ne5 { Black is in trouble } { [%csl Gb8] })) 25. Qh3 { [%csl Ge6] } 25... Rf7 26. Nc4 Qf8 27. Rfe1 { And Black is in trouble } { [%cal Gf1e1,Ge1e6] } 27... Bf5 28. Qh5 Be7 29. d6 { [%csl Gb8] }) 24... Qe8 { Played instantly by Magnus. Now Black is out of the woods - Qh5 is prevented and the Queen is coming to g6, } { [%csl Gg5,Gd6,Gg6][%cal Ge8g6,Gb6c4] } 25. Nc4 Qg6 { [%cal Gg5g4] } 26. Nxd6 Qxd6 { Now White is even a pawn down and has to do something. } { [%cal Gc3e5] } 27. h4! { Without this, White could even end up significantly worse } 27... gxh4 (27... g4 28. Qxf4) (27... h6 28. Qh5 { [%csl Gh6] }) 28. Qxf4 Qxf4 29. Rxf4 h5! { Precise defence by Magnus, preparing Bg4. Now the game quickly peters to a draw. } 30. Re1 (30. Rxh4 Bg4) (30. Rc4 Bg4 31. Re1 Rbe8 32. Rxe8 Rxe8 33. Rxc5 Rc8 { [%cal Gc5c8] }) 30... Bg4 31. Rf6 Rxf6 32. Bxf6 Kf7 33. Bxh4 Re8 34. Rf1+ Kg8 { [%csl Gb7] } 35. Rf6 Re2 36. Rg6+ Kf8 37. d6 Rd2 38. Rg5 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } { The very first game in which White achieved something out of the opening. Unfortunately for Caruana fans, he missed the strongest continuation and Magnus can be satisfied with the outcome of the opening. } 38... Rxd6 39. Rxc5 1/2-1/2


