[UTCTime "14:47:22"]

1. c4 { We have entered in a last third of match (at least for classical portion) it's expected players won't be taking huge risks in games to come. My trainer used to say 1.c4 positions are always better for white with small and long lasting advantage. It's well known Carlsen likes that type of position and has win them countless number of times. } 1... e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Bg2 Bc5 { Same as in game 4, we have entered in this variation. In moves to come, Carlsen showed better preparation for the first time in match } { [%csl Gc5,Gf8][%cal Gf8c5] } 7. O-O (7. Nxe5 Nxc3 8. Nxc6 { Just doesn't work. } 8... Qf6 $19) 7... O-O 8. d3 (8. Nxe5 Nxc3 9. Nxc6 { Doesn't work again. } 9... Bxf2+ 10. Rxf2 Nxd1 11. Nxd8 Nxf2 12. Nxb7 Nh3+ 13. Kf1 Bg4 $17) 8... Re8 9. Bd2 (9. Bg5 { In game 4 Carlsen went for more peaceful Bd2. } { [%cal Gg5d8] } 9... Nxc3 { Nc3 is the most natural continuation, extremely common in this type of postions. } (9... f6 10. Qb3 Be6 (10... fxg5 11. Qxd5+) 11. Qxb7 Qd7 { [%cal Ga8b8] } 12. Qb5 { [%csl Gc5][%cal Gb5c5] } 12... Bxf2+ 13. Rxf2 fxg5 14. Nxg5) (9... Nde7) 10. bxc3 { [%csl Gc3,Gd4][%cal Ga1b1,Gb1b7,Gc6d4,Gg5c1] } (10. Bxd8 Nxd1 11. Bxc7 Nxb2 { And black would be a piece up }) 10... f6 (10... Qd6 { Black could have played without weakening his king side structure but that would result in his pieces being very awkwardly placed. } 11. Bc1 { [%cal Gd6d8,Gc1b2] } 11... Bb6 12. Qc2 Bf5 13. Nd2 Qe6 14. e4 Bh3 15. Nc4 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Rad8 $13 { Engine likes blacks position but from a practical stand point, white has much easier position to play. Black has to play precisely and not let white to consolidate and fully develop otherwise pawn force in the center will bring white advantage. }) 11. Bc1 { White spent 2 tempos to make a weakness on f6. a2-g8 diagonal and weaker king will be a motiv for white until the end of the game. Also it's important to notice that Carlsen will focus his play in center rather than on queen side like he did in game 4. } { [%csl Gc1,Gb2][%cal Gc1b2,Gd3d4] } 11... Be6 12. Bb2 Bb6 { [%cal Gb6d4] } (12... Bf8 13. d4 Bf7 { Black could have played this type of fortress. Engine likes it, but in practical play black will have hard time playing due to the lack of space. } 14. e4 exd4 15. cxd4 Rxe4 { [%cal Gf3e2] }) (12... Qe7 13. d4 Rad8) 13. d4 Bd5 { Caruana spent a lot of time here. There are many good options here but Bd5 is probably the most natural one. The idea of the move is to stop e4, weaken white's light square bishop and maybe push e4 your self. } (13... e4 14. Nd2 f5 15. Qc2 Na5 16. Rfd1 { Was also possible, leading into a double edged position. Caruana probably wanted to simplify as much as possible since Carlsen was better prepared. If Caruana wanted to enter this type of position he's bishop would be better on f8 rather than on b6. } 16... Nc4 17. Nxc4 Bxc4 18. e3 $14 { [%csl Gb6][%cal Gf2f3,Ga2a4] }) 14. Qc2 { [%cal Ge2e4] } 14... exd4 (14... e4 { Wouldn't be so good for black because of not so obvious maneuver with knight. } 15. Nh4 Na5 16. Nf5 Nc4 (16... c5 17. Ne3 Bf7 18. dxc5 Bxc5 19. Rfd1) 17. Ne3 Nxe3 18. fxe3 { [%cal Gc3c4] } 18... c6 19. c4 Bf7 $16) 15. cxd4 Be4 16. Qb3+ (16. Qd1 Qd5 { [%cal Gd5g2] }) 16... Bd5 (16... Qd5 17. Qxd5+ Bxd5 18. e3) 17. Qd1 Bxf3?! { This is the first critical position in the game. Objectively speaking, Caruana had better options. He knowingly decided to enter in a weaker position in hope ( or confidence ) he will be able to hold it. It should be mentioned till this point Carlsen blitzed out all of his moves and Caruana had only about 50 minutes left on clock. } (17... Qd7 18. e3 Na5 19. Nd2 Bxg2 20. Kxg2 $14) (17... Na5) 18. Qb3+ (18. Bxf3 Nxd4 19. Bxd4 Qxd4 20. Qb3+) 18... Kh8 19. Bxf3 Nxd4 20. Bxd4 Qxd4 (20... Bxd4 21. Rad1 $18) 21. e3 Qe5 22. Bxb7 Rad8 (22... Rab8 23. Qa4 { [%cal Ga4a6] } (23. Bc6 { Black doesn't have any good bishop discoveries. } 23... Bxe3 24. Qxe3 Qxe3 25. fxe3)) 23. Rad1 { [%cal Gd1d8] } 23... Qe7 { At first this move can seem weird. The idea of it is to cover f7 square and to start with the plan g6 Kg7. } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Gb3f7] } (23... g6 24. Qf7 Rf8 25. Rxd8 Rxd8 26. Rc1 { [%cal Gc1c6] } 26... Qd6 27. Rc6 Qf8 28. Rxf6 Qxf7 29. Rxf7 $16 Rd1+ 30. Kg2 Rd2 31. Kf3 Rxa2 32. g4 { [%cal Gb7d5,Gg4g5,Gf7f8] }) 24. h4 { With idea h5 and h6 to weaken blacks structure. } { [%cal Gh4h5,Gh5h6,Gg1g2,Gf1h1,Gh1h6] } (24. Kg2 g6 25. Bc6 (25. h4 h5 (25... Kg7 26. h5 gxh5 27. Rh1 { [%cal Gh1h5] })) 25... Rf8 26. Qc4 Kg7) 24... g6 { Second critical moment in game. Carlsen went for immediate h5 what wasn't really the best plan. Engine suggest to let black push h5 and enter in not so dynamic position where white is better and can try to make slow proress. } 25. h5 (25. Bc6 Rf8 26. Kg2 h5 27. Qc2 f5 28. Bf3 Kg7 29. Qc6 Rxd1 30. Rxd1 Rd8 31. Rd5 Rxd5 32. Bxd5 $16 { Carlsen believed that he won't be able to win this against Caruana. While white is undoubtedly better, black can draw with good play. }) (25. Kg2 { [%cal Gf1h1] } 25... h5 26. Bc6 Rf8 27. Bf3 f5 { [%csl Gb6,Gc7,Ga7][%cal Gg3g4,Gf2f3,Ge3e4] }) 25... gxh5 { Players entered in almost forced sequence of moves. } { [%csl Gh4,Gg2,Gg1][%cal Gh5h4] } 26. Qc4 (26. Kg2 h4) 26... f5 { [%cal Gh5h4] } 27. Bf3 h4 28. Rxd8 Rxd8 29. gxh4 Rg8+ 30. Kh1 Qf6 { [%csl Gf5] } 31. Qf4 Bc5 32. Rg1 (32. Qxc7 Qxh4+) (32. e4 Bd6 33. Qxf5 Qxf5 (33... Qxh4+) 34. exf5 { [%csl Gf5][%cal Gh8f6] }) 32... Rxg1+ 33. Kxg1 Bd6 34. Qa4 { [%cal Ga4a7,Gd6c5] } 34... f4 { [%csl Gh4] } 35. Qxa7 fxe3 36. Qxe3 Qxh4 { The position is objectively equal but Caruana is close to time trouble and has a weaker king so Carlsen tried to push for a win. } 37. a4 { Very tricky move. Black can safely take on a4 but has to see a lot of moves forward and play precisely. } 37... Qf6 { The idea is if white plays a5 now, black can play Qa1 and take on a5 without white having a check on c3. } { [%cal Gf6a1] } (37... Qxa4 38. Qc3+ Kg8 39. Bd5+ Kf8 40. Qh8+ Ke7 41. Qxh7+ Kf6 42. Qf7+ Kg5 (42... Ke5 { Would lose a game. } 43. Qe6+ Kd4 (43... Kf4 44. Qe3+ (44. Qf6+ Kg4 45. Be6+ Kh5 46. Bf7+ Kg4 47. Kg2 { [%cal Gf2f3] })) 44. Qe4+ (44. Qg4+ { [%cal Gg4a4] }))) 38. Bd1 Qe5 39. Qxe5+ Bxe5 { [%csl Gc2,Gf5,Ga6,Gh5][%cal Gd1c2] } 40. a5 Kg7 41. a6 Bd4 42. Kg2 Kf6 43. f4 Bb6 44. Kf3 h6 45. Ke4 Ba7 46. Bg4 Bg1 47. Kd5 Bb6 48. Kc6 Be3 (48... Bf2 49. Kxc7) 49. Kb7 (49. Kxc7 Bxf4+ { [%cal Gf4e3] } 50. Kb7 Be3 51. a7 Bxa7 52. Kxa7 h5 53. Bxh5) 49... Bb6 50. Bh3 (50. a7 Bxa7 51. Kxa7 c5 { [%csl Gg4,Gf5] } 52. Kb6 c4 53. Kc5 c3 54. Bd1 Kf5) 50... Be3 51. Kc6 (51. a7 Bxa7 52. Kxa7 c5 53. Kb6 c4 54. Bf1 Kf5 $10 (54... c3 55. Bd3 h5 56. Kb5 h4 57. Kc4 h3 58. Kxc3 h2 59. Be4 h1=Q 60. Bxh1 Kf5 $10)) 51... Bb6 52. Kd5 Ba7 53. Ke4 Bb6 54. Bf1 Ke6 55. Bc4+ Kf6 56. Bd3 { [%cal Ge4d5,Gd5c6,Ge4b7,Gh6h1] } 56... Ke6 { The easiest way to draw. If black let's white king to go back to b7 he can be in a trouble since white's bishop is better positioned right now. } (56... Ba7 57. Kd5 Bb6 58. Kc6 Be3 (58... h5 { Black can still save a game by pushing h4 pawn now. } 59. Kd5 h4 60. Ke4 h3 61. Kf3 Bg1 62. Be4 h2) 59. Be4 Bb6 60. Kb7 Be3 61. a7 Bxa7 62. Kxa7 $18 { And white is winning ! } 62... c5 63. Kb6 c4 64. Kc5 c3 65. Kd4 c2 66. Bxc2 { [%cal Gd4h4] })) 1/2 - 1/2


[Event "World Chess Championship 2018: Game 10"]
[Date "2018.11.23"]
[Result "1/2 - 1/2"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B33"]
[Opening "Sicilian Defense: Lasker-Pelikan Variation"]
[StudyName "World Chess Championship 2018"]
[ChapterName "Game 10"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/xV6OiytA/MxfiuGJN"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/chessentialsBLOG"]
[UTCDate "2018.11.23"]
[UTCTime "14:36:16"]

1. e4 c5 { Both players continued with their standard openings for this match. } 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { Same as in game 8, Caruana went for open Sicilian rather than Rossolimo, Carlsen refuted in games 2, 4 and 6. } (3. Bb5) 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 { Carlsen went for Lakser (Sveshnikov) variation. We have already seen all of this already in game 8. } { [%cal Ge7e5] } 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Nd5 { Much less common than the main line 7.Bg5. } (7. Bg5) 7... Nxd5 8. exd5 Nb8 { 20 years ago they would call you crazy and throw you out of club for making a move likes this. Today this is the main theory. } (8... Ne7 9. c4 Nf5 (9... a6 10. Qa4 Bd7 11. Nxd6#) 10. Bd3 Be7 11. O-O O-O 12. f4 a6 13. Nc3) 9. a4 { The idea of 9.a4 is to leave c4 square for the knight with Na3, Nc4 maneuver, also white will try to take advantage of b6 square after a6 is played by black. } (9. c4 { Was more popular back in the day. } 9... a6 10. Qa4 Nd7 { [%csl Gd6][%cal Gf8d6] }) 9... Be7 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O Nd7 12. b4 { Team Caruana prepared idea never seen before. In post game interview Carlsen said he didn't see this line before but that he wasn't too uncomfortable. The idea behind 12. b4 is that if black plays in same way as Carlsen did in game 8, white will be a tempi up. } { [%cal Ga4a5,Ga7a5] } (12. Bd2 { [%cal Gd2a5] }) 12... a6 (12... f5 13. a5 a6 14. Na3 { We would have reached same position as in game 8 except white would has pawn on b4 rather than bishop on d2. That's better for white since bishop on d2 is even weaker than on c1 and white would have to spent another tempo to get him on more active square. } { [%csl Gb4][%cal Gc1d2,Gc1e3,Ge3b6] }) (12... a5 { Black now has the option of playing a5 right away. It's arguable is the knight better on b5 or a3. } 13. c3 (13. bxa5 Rxa5 14. Ba3 { Black would be in weird spot. His d6 pawn is hanging and there is no good square for knight. If you go with knight on f6, you wont be able to play f5 for a long time. } { [%csl Gd6][%cal Ga3b4] })) 13. Na3 { [%csl Ga3][%cal Gc1a3] } 13... a5 14. bxa5 { Fabiano instantly played this move showing that he's still in his preparation and that his game plan is different than the one in game 8. Playing this move white won't be able to play c2-c4-c5 in future to make past pawn on d file. } { [%csl Ga4,Gc2][%cal Gb4a5,Gc2c4] } (14. c3 f5 15. Nc4 b6 $13 16. f4 Ba6 { The position we get is double edged but more peaceful than the one we got in game. }) 14... Rxa5 (14... Qxa5 { Was also possible but after Nc4 black would have to go back to d8 with queen. } 15. Nc4 Qd8 (15... Qc7 16. a5 b5 { b6 or b5 is not really good for black. } (16... f5 17. Be3 f4 18. Bb6 Nxb6 19. Nxb6 { Black's queen is wrongly placed on queen side but she'd rather be on g file to attack whites king. } { [%csl Gc7][%cal Gd8h4] }) 17. Nb6 Nxb6 18. axb6 { [%csl Ga1,Gc7][%cal Ga8a1] } 18... Qb7 19. Rxa8 Qxa8 { [%csl Gb5,Gb6] } 20. Qd3 $16 { White would be much better. } { [%cal Gd3b5] })) 15. Nc4 Ra8 16. Be3 (16. a5 { Would be met with now possible b6. } 16... b6) 16... f5 { 16. f5 is most human and best practical move for black. He has clear ideas of attack white on king side as fast as possible. } { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gf5f4] } (16... b6 { Black has the option of playing b6 now, but his pawn will be attack very quickly by white pieces. } 17. Rb1 Rb8 (17... Rxa4 18. Nxb6 Ra3 19. Qc1 Rc3 20. Qd2 Rc7 21. Nxd7 Qxd7 22. c4 { Black's attack didn't even start and white has clear ideas of pushing c5 in near future. }) 18. Qd2 Ba6 19. Nxe5 { [%csl Ga6][%cal Ge2a6] } 19... Bxe2 20. Nc6 { [%cal Gc6d8,Gd2e2] } 20... Qe8 21. Qxe2) 17. a5 f4 18. Bb6 Qe8 { Again best practical decision. } (18... Nxb6 19. Nxb6 Rb8 20. Bg4 { White would be very happy to play this position. He has significant advantage on light squares after forcing the exchange. } { [%csl Gb6,Ge7,Gb7,Ga5][%cal Ge2g4,Gc8g4,Ge6e3,Gf6f3] } 20... Bxg4 21. Qxg4 $16) 19. Ra3 { This position is so complicated that even with strong engines on high depth it's not really clear what is the best move. What is for sure is that 19.Ra3 is not the best move. While not being the best move it is an understandable move and human move. White wants to activate his rook mostly in defensive tasks on 3rd rank. } { [%cal Ga3h3,Ge5e4,Gf4f3,Gb7b5] } (19. Bh5 { Idea of the move is pretty simple. Force black to play g6 and take 6th rank from black pieces. } 19... g6 20. Be2 (20. Bf3 { [%cal Gf3e4] } 20... Nf6 21. Bc7 Ra6 $13 { [%csl Gd6,Ge2][%cal Ga6d6,Ge2a6] }) 20... Nf6 { Would work in this line. } (20... Nxb6 21. Nxb6 Ra7 22. Bg4 Bf5 { In difference from other lines, if white changes light square bishops, black will opened g file and strong attack. } { [%csl Gg6] } 23. Bxf5 gxf5 { [%csl Gf5,Ge4,Gd1][%cal Gg8g2,Ge7d8] }) 21. Bc7 Ra6 (21... Qd7 22. Nb6 Qxc7 23. Nxa8 Qc5 { And the machine says }) 22. Nb6 { [%cal Ge2a6] } 22... Ra7 23. Bb8 $18) (19. Re1 { Was pointed out by chat in chess24. This is incredibly strong - e4 is prevented and White prepares to get the bishop to e4 } { [%csl Ge4] } 19... Nxb6 (19... Qg6 20. Bc7 (20. Bd3 { [%cal Ge5e4] } 20... Qg5 21. f3 Rf6 22. Bf2 Rh6 23. Rb1 Qh5 24. h3) 20... Rf6 21. Bf3) 20. Nxb6 Ra7 21. Bg4 Bxg4 22. Qxg4 Bd8 { [%csl Gb6][%cal Ge7d8] }) (19. Kh1 Qg6 20. Bc7 Rf6) (19. Bc7 { [%csl Gd6][%cal Gc7d6] } 19... Rf6 { Important thing now is that f8 square is free for queen. } { [%cal Ge8f8] } (19... Nf6) (19... Qg6 20. Bh5 (20. Kh1 e4) (20. Re1 e4 (20... Qh6) (20... Rf6 21. Bh5 Qh6) 21. Bh5 { [%csl Ge4,Gd6] }) 20... Qh6) 20. Bh5 { [%cal Gg7g6,Gf6h6] } 20... Qf8 { Black would play Rh6 and Qf6 in moves to come to attack white. } (20... g6 { 20...g6 would be bad for black in this position. White's dark square bishop has moved to c7 and can't be taken anymore. Black pieces are very awkwardly placed and it's not obvious how he will untangle. } 21. Bf3 Qf8 { [%cal Gf8h6] } 22. Qe2 Nc5 23. Nb6 Ra6 24. Nxc8 Qxc8 25. Bb6 $16 { White has bishop pair and would be better in this position. })) 19... Qg6 20. Bc7 { [%cal Gd7f6] } (20. Re1 { Now comes a bit too late } 20... Nf6 21. Bc7 e4 22. Nb6 (22. Bxd6 Bxd6 23. Nxd6 f3 (23... Bh3) 24. Bf1 Bh3 25. g3 Bxf1 26. Rxf1 Qg4 { [%cal Gg4h3,Gf6g4] }) (22. Nxd6 f3 23. Bf1 Ng4 { [%csl Gg6][%cal Gg6h5] }) 22... Ra7) (20. Kh1 Nf6 21. Bc7 e4) 20... e4 21. Kh1 { [%cal Gf4f3] } (21. f3 e3 { [%csl Gf4,Ge3][%cal Gg6g5,Gf8f6,Gd7e5,Gd7f6,Gf6h5,Ga3h3] }) (21. g3 f3 { [%csl Ge2] }) 21... b5! { The idea is to get rid of the rook on a3 that defends the third rank } { [%csl Gc4] } (21... Qh6 { Was suggested by the engine, but it is not something a human wants to play } { [%csl Gh2,Gf5][%cal Gg6h6,Gf8h5,Gh5g5] } 22. Rg1 (22. Re1 f3 23. gxf3 b5 24. Nb6 Bg5) (22. Rh3 Qf6 { [%csl Gf6][%cal Gd7e5] } 23. Ra3 { [%cal Gf6h6] } 23... Ne5 { [%cal Gc8g4] }) (22. c3 Rf5 { [%cal Gf4f3,Gf5h5] })) 22. Nb6 { The only move } (22. axb6 { Leads to trouble } 22... Rxa3 23. Nxa3 f3 24. gxf3 Ne5 { [%csl Ge5,Ge7,Gc8,Gf8,Gc7,Ga3] } 25. Rg1 Qh6 { [%csl Gf2][%cal Ge4f3] }) 22... Nxb6 23. Bxb6 Qg5 { The only clear "mistake" of this game } { [%cal Gf8f6,Gf6h6] } (23... b4 { Was the way to hold } { [%cal Ge2b5] } 24. Rb3 Bf6 { [%cal Gf6c3] } 25. Rxb4 Bc3 26. Ra4 Be5 { [%cal Gf4f3,Ga4a3,Ga3h3] } (26... Bd7) 27. Ra3 (27. Re1 f3) (27. Bb5 Rf6 (27... f3 28. g3 { [%cal Gf1e1] })) 27... f3 28. gxf3 exf3 29. Bxf3 Qh6) 24. g3 (24. Bxb5 { Caruana couldn't evaluate the consequences of this pawn grab. And indeed, it is difficult to defend as White, but the machine does it without a problem } 24... Rf6 25. Re1 Rg6 { [%csl Gg2] } 26. Bf1 Bf5 { [%csl Ge4] } 27. f3 (27. g3 Rh6 (27... Bf6) 28. gxf4 Qxf4 29. Rg3) (27. Ra4 { [%cal Ga4e4] } 27... Bg4 28. f3 exf3 29. gxf3 Bd7 { [%csl Gh2,Gf3][%cal Gb6g1] }) 27... e3) 24... b4 (24... f3 25. Bxb5 Qg4 26. Re1 { [%csl Ge4] } 26... Rf6 27. Rxe4 Qxe4 28. Re3 Qb4 29. c4 Bf8 30. Rb3 { [%csl Gb4] }) 25. Rb3 (25. gxf4 Qxf4 26. Rb3 Bf6 { [%cal Gf6e5] } 27. Rg1 Be5 28. Rg2 { [%csl Gb3][%cal Gc8h3] }) 25... Bh3 26. Rg1 (26. Re1 { Is almost losing } 26... Bf6 { [%csl Ge1][%cal Gf6c3] } 27. Rxb4 Bc3 28. Rxe4 Bxe1 29. Qxe1 Rae8 30. Bf3) 26... f3 27. Bf1 { [%csl Gh3] } (27. Bb5 { Would be losing } 27... Rf6 { [%cal Gf6h6,Gg5h5] } (27... Bg2+ { This version of the exchange sack is actually quite decend for White } 28. Rxg2 fxg2+ 29. Kxg2 { [%csl Gb4,Ge7] }) 28. Be3 Qh5 29. Rxb4 (29. Qd2 Rxa5 30. Qxb4 Ra8 { [%csl Ga5] }) 29... Bg2+ 30. Rxg2 fxg2+ { [%csl Gd1] }) 27... Bxf1 28. Qxf1 { [%cal Gf1h3,Gb3b4] } (28. Rxf1 { Would be losing } 28... Qg4 29. Rxb4 Rf5 (29... Rf6 30. Be3 (30. Rxe4 Qh3 (30... Qxe4 31. Re1) 31. Rg1 Rh6) 30... Rf5 31. a6 Qh3) 30. Rg1 Rh5 31. Qf1 { [%csl Gf1,Gg1][%cal Gf1h3] } 31... Bg5 { [%cal Gb6e3,Gh5h6,Gg4h5] } (31... Rh6 32. Be3 g5) 32. c3) 28... Qxd5 (28... Qg4 { Is now bad - you can never play Qh3 } 29. Rxb4 Rf6 (29... Rf5 30. a6 Rh5 31. a7 { [%cal Gg4h3] } 31... Rxh2+ 32. Kxh2 Qh5+ 33. Qh3) 30. Be3 g5 (30... Rf5 31. a6)) 29. Rxb4 Qe6 { Objectively speaking, this should now be an equal endgame. On the first glance, the pawn on h3 guarantees Black advantage. But the computer never leaves out of "dynamic equilibrium" } { [%csl Gf3,Ge4,Gd5] } 30. Rb5 { [%cal Ge7b4,Gd6d5] } (30. Qb5 d5 31. Rd4 Rf5 32. c4 { Leads to an immediate draw, but you have to find a very nice finesse } 32... Rh5 { [%csl Gh2] } 33. Rxd5 g5 { [%cal Ge6h3] } 34. Rgd1 { The point } 34... Qh3 35. Rd8+! Rxd8 36. Rxd8+ Bxd8 37. Qe8+ Kg7 38. Bd4+ Bf6 (38... Kh6 39. Qf8+) 39. Qe7+ Kg8 40. Qe8+ { With perpetual check, lol }) 30... Bd8 { People were rather critical of this move, but it is not so bad. The idea is to take on b6 and play e3 } (30... Rfc8 31. Qb1 Bd8 { [%csl Gc8][%cal Gd8b6,Ge4e3] } 32. Qb2 Bxb6 33. axb6 e3 34. b7 { [%cal Gb7c8,Gb7a8] }) 31. Qe1 { Preventing e3 } { [%cal Ge1e3] } 31... Bxb6 32. axb6 Rab8 33. Qe3 (33. Qd2 { Defending c2. After } { [%csl Gc2] } 33... d5 34. Qxd5 Qxd5 (34... Rxb6 35. Qxe6+ Rxe6 { Is probably also draw }) 35. Rxd5 Rxb6) 33... Qc4 34. Rb2 (34. Rgb1 { [%csl Gc2] } 34... Qxc2 35. b7 d5 36. h4 (36. Qd4 Rfd8 37. h4) 36... Rfd8 37. Qd4 { And the machine says Black can't make progress here }) 34... Rb7 { [%csl Gb6] } 35. Rd1 { [%csl Gd6] } (35. h4 { Making luft for the king was more precise. } { [%cal Gh1h2] }) 35... Qe2!? { The tricky move and the only chance for playing for a win } (35... d5) 36. Re1 (36. Qxe2 fxe2 37. Re1 Rxf2 38. Kg1 Rbf7 { Is beautiful. After } 39. Rbb1 { [%csl Gf1] } (39. b7 Rf1+ 40. Kg2 Rxb7) 39... d5 40. b7 Rf1+ 41. Rxf1 exf1=Q+ 42. Rxf1 Rxb7 { Black is close to winning }) (36. Qb3+ Kh8 37. c4 { Loses due to } { [%csl Ge2] } 37... Rxb6 38. Rxe2 fxe2 { [%csl Ge2] } 39. Qa4 exd1=Q+ 40. Qxd1 Rxf2) 36... Qxe3 37. Rxe3 d5 { This seemed a bit unpleasant for White at first, but he is actually fine. } { [%csl Gb6] } 38. h4 { [%cal Gh1h2] } 38... Rc8 39. Ra3 { [%csl Ga6][%cal Ga3a7] } 39... Kf7 40. Kh2 (40. Ra7 { Would draw immediately } 40... Rb8 41. c4 dxc4 42. Rb4 Kg8 43. Rxc4 Rxb6 44. Rxe4) 40... Ke6 { [%csl Gh2,Ge6] } 41. g4 Rc6 42. Ra6 Ke5 43. Kg3 h6 { [%csl Gg3][%cal Gg7g5] } 44. h5 { White can't allow g5. There aren't any ohter moves anyway } 44... Kd4?! { An attempt to play for the win which leads to problems... for Black } { [%cal Gd4c3] } (44... g5 45. hxg6 Rxg6 46. Rb5 { [%csl Gd5][%cal Gb5d5,Gb5e5] } 46... h5 47. Raa5 { Leads to a draw } 47... Rxg4+ 48. Kh3 Kf6 49. Rxd5 Rxb6 50. Rxh5 Rg6) 45. Rb5 { Missed/underestimated by Magnus } { [%cal Ga6a5,Ga5d5] } 45... Rd6 { A practical way of making a draw. Magnus admits his mistake and goes for a rook endgame 3v2 on the kingside } (45... Rc5 46. Ra4+ { Loses } 46... Rc4 47. Ra7 (47. Raa5)) (45... Kc4 46. Raa5 Rbxb6 47. Rxd5 Rb1 48. Re5 Rg1+ 49. Kf4 { And Black has to fight for a draw }) (45... Rxc2 46. Raa5 { Is also horrible } { [%csl Gd5,Ge4,Gf3][%cal Ga5a7] }) 46. Ra4+ Ke5 47. Rab4 { C4 is coming } { [%cal Gc2c4] } 47... Ke6 { [%cal Ge6f7,Gf7g8] } 48. c4 { [%cal Gd5c4] } 48... dxc4 (48... d4 49. c5 Rc6 50. Rxd4 { [%csl Ge4,Gf3] }) 49. Rxc4 Rdxb6 50. Rxe4+ Kf7 51. Rf5+ Rf6 52. Rxf6+ Kxf6 53. Kxf3 Kf7 54. Kg3 { And the players shook hands here, because this is a theoretical draw. What a fascinating encounter, one of the best games we have ever seen in the World Chess Championship. } 1/2 - 1/2


