1. e4 { So, in his last White game, Carlsen decided to go with 1 e4 and face the Petroff. } 1... e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 { The main line } (4. Nd3 { Was played in game 6, without particular success }) 4... Nxe4 5. Nc3 { The main line against the Petroff nowadays } (5. d4 { Is still probably the main line, but it has been supplemented with 5 Nc3 at the top level instead }) 5... Nxc3 6. dxc3 { This looks like a beginner mistake - why would White allow the doubling of his c-pawns?
There are two main benefits:
- the diagonal of the dark-squared bishop is open
- pawn on c3 controls d4
- the pawns act as bullwarks against Black's queenside attack } 6... Be7 7. Be3 O-O { Caruana goes for a different set-up this time } (7... Nc6 { Was played by Caruana in the game between these opponents in Saint Louis. Hints at the queenside castling } 8. Qd2 Be6 9. O-O-O Qd7 { For instance } 10. a3 h6 11. Nd4 { [%cal Gc3d4] } 11... Nxd4 12. Bxd4 { [%cal Gd4g7] } 12... Rg8 13. Be2 c5 14. Be3 d5 15. f4 O-O-O 16. Bf3 Bg4 17. Bxd5 Bxd1 18. Rxd1 { Karjakin, Sergey - Caruana, F., 1-0, FIDE Candidates 2018, https://lichess.org/MJrl1AMY } { As in this famous game, which brought Karjakin an important victory in the 2018 Candidates }) 8. Qd2 Nd7 { In the leaked Caruana video, Nd7-Nf6 idea was featured, so it shouldn't have come as a surprise for Carlsen. } { [%cal Gc7c5,Gd8a5] } (8... Nc6 { In this position is less common. It doesn't guarantee Black immediate equality } 9. O-O-O Bf5 (9... Ne5 10. Nxe5 (10. Kb1) (10. h4 { [%csl Ge5] } 10... Nxf3 11. gxf3 { [%csl Gf2,Gf3,Gh4,Gc3,Gc2][%cal Gh1g1,Gg1g7] }) 10... dxe5 11. Qxd8) 10. Bd3 Qd7 11. Rhe1 Ne5 12. Bxf5 Qxf5 13. Nxe5 dxe5) (8... Bf5) 9. O-O-O Nf6 10. Bd3 (10. h3 { Is also logical here, but it might be a bit too slow } { [%cal Gf6g4] } 10... Be6 11. Kb1 c5 12. c4 Qb6 (12... d5 { And Black has equalized } { [%cal Gd7f6] })) 10... c5 { Somewhat surprising, but thematic nevertheless. Black opens the path for his queen to queenside and controls the d4 square } { [%csl Gd6][%cal Gc3c4,Gc5d4,Gf3d4,Gd8a5,Gc5c4] } (10... Be6 11. Kb1 c6 12. Nd4) (10... c6 11. c4 { Is not worse } 11... d5 12. cxd5 (12. Rhe1 { [%csl Gc5,Gd4] }) 12... Nxd5) 11. Rhe1 Be6 12. Kb1 { The novelty of this game } (12. Bg5 { Was played by several strong players, like Karjakin and Giri and in both instances their opponents replied poorly. } { Karjakin, Sergey - Harikrishna, P., 1-0, Vugar Gashimov Mem 2016, https://lichess.org/RxOfakrN } { Giri, A. - Motylev, A., 1/2-1/2, FIDE World Cup 2017, https://lichess.org/EdtFKo2U } 12... d5 { Is probably most logical } (12... Qa5 { Was played by Motylev Alexander and he ran into trouble } 13. a3 c4 14. Bxc4 Bxc4 15. Rxe7) (12... Re8 { Is also sensible }) (12... h6 { Was played by Harikrishna, but after } 13. Bxh6 { He was almost immediately losing }) 13. Qf4 Re8) 12... Qa5 { Another point of c5 is revealed. Black intends to follow things up with d5 } { [%cal Ga5a2] } 13. c4 { White has to play this, but after the exchange of queens, Black's game is eased. It is curious why team Carlsen allowed this. Did they judge this might be advantageous for them or were they already aiming for tiebreaks? } { [%cal Gd2a5] } (13. a3 c4 { [%csl Ga3][%cal Ge3g5,Gg5f6] } 14. Bxc4 Bxc4 { Now doesn't work - the rook is not attacking on e7 }) 13... Qxd2 { [%csl Gg5] } 14. Bxd2 h6 { [%cal Gf3g5] } 15. Nh4 { This allows Black to equalize almost on the spot } (15. h3 { Preventing Ng4 was more circumspect, but even then it is debatable whether White has any advantage } { [%cal Gf6g4] } 15... Rfe8 16. Nh4 Ng4 { Is actually still possible } 17. Ng6) 15... Rfe8 (15... Ng4 { Was possible immediately } 16. Nf5 (16. Ng6 fxg6 17. Rxe6 Nxf2 18. Rde1 Nxd3 19. cxd3 Bf6 20. Rxd6 { With equality } 20... Rae8) 16... Rfe8 17. Nxe7+ Rxe7 18. Re2 Ne5 { Is still good enough probably } { [%csl Gd3] }) 16. Ng6 { [%csl Ge6][%cal Gf7e6] } (16. h3 Ng4 { Was already mentioned as an equalizer }) 16... Ng4 { [%csl Gf2,Gh2][%cal Gg4e5] } (16... fxg6 17. Rxe6 { [%csl Gg6,Gd6] }) 17. Nxe7+ Rxe7 18. Re2 { [%csl Gf2] } 18... Ne5 { [%csl Gc4,Gd3] } (18... Nxh2 { Would be pretty stupid way of losing a World Championship match } 19. f3 { And Rh1 is coming } { [%csl Gh2,Gh1][%cal Gd1h1] }) 19. Bf4 { [%csl Gd6][%cal Gf4d6] } 19... Nxd3 20. Rxd3 Rd7 { And the game was practically over even before it began. White doesn't have any chances in the resulting opposite coloured bishops endgame } { [%csl Gd6][%cal Gf4d6,Ge6c4] } 21. Rxd6 (21. Bxd6 Bxc4) (21. b3 d5 { Is immediate equalizer } 22. Red2 d4 23. c3 Bf5) 21... Rxd6 22. Bxd6 Rd8 { [%csl Gc4][%cal Gd6d1] } (22... Rc8 23. b3) 23. Rd2 Bxc4 24. Kc1 { [%csl Gd2,Gd6] } (24. b3 Bf1) (24. Bxc5 Rxd2) 24... b6 { [%csl Gc5] } 25. Bf4 Rxd2 26. Kxd2 a6 { [%csl Gb6,Gc5,Gf7,Gg7,Gh6] } (26... Bxa2 27. b3 c4 28. Kc3 cxb3 29. Kb2 { [%csl Ga2] } 29... bxc2 30. Kxa2 { [%csl Gc1,Gc2,Gb6,Ga7][%cal Gf4c1,Ga2b2] }) 27. a3 { Black will lose a pawn on the queenside, but just one extra pawn is not enough for White in this position } 27... Kf8 28. Bc7 b5 29. Bd6+ Ke8 30. Bxc5 h5 (30... Kd7 31. Bf8 { [%cal Gf8h6] }) 31. Ke3 Kd7 32. Kd4 g6 33. g3 Be2 34. Bf8 Kc6 35. b3 Bd1 36. Kd3 Bg4 37. c4 Be6 38. Kd4 bxc4 39. bxc4 { [%csl Ge6,Ga6,Gf1,Ge2][%cal Gc4c5,Ge6h3] } 39... Bg4 40. c5 Be6 41. Bh6 Bd5 42. Be3 Be6 43. Ke5 Bd5 44. Kf4 Be6 45. Kg5 Bd5 46. g4 hxg4 47. Kxg4 Ba2 48. Kg5 Bb3 49. Kf6 { [%cal Gf2f5,Gg6f5,Gh2h8] } 49... Ba2 50. h4 Bb3 51. f4 { White's idea is to create a passer on the h-file, but he is unable to do so: } 51... Ba2 (51... Be6 52. f5 { Is the only mistake Black can make } { [%cal Gg6f5] } 52... gxf5 (52... Bxf5 53. h5 { And wins } 53... gxh5 { [%csl Gf5] } (53... Bb1 54. h6 g5 55. Bxg5 { [%cal Gf6g7] } (55. Kxg5 { [%cal Gg5f6,Gf6g7] })) 54. Kxf5) 53. h5 { [%cal Gh5h8] }) 52. Ke7 (52. f5 { [%cal Gg6f5,Gh4h8] } 52... Bb1 { And all is good } 53. Kxf7 (53. fxg6 fxg6 { [%cal Gh4h8] }) 53... Bxf5) 52... Bb3 53. Kf6 Ba2 54. f5 Bb1 55. Bf2 Bc2 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } { And this rather uninspiring encounter ended in a draw. It is a bit surprising to see Magnus playing like this, considering he has to undergo a serious test in game 12. But perhaps he is confident in his abilities and his preparation with the Black pieces } (55... Bxf5 56. h5) 1/2-1/2


