1. e4 { Of course - there is no reason to deviate from this move and face the unknown } 1... c5 { There was an argument for 1....e5, but it would be risky to test Caruana's pre-match preparation } (1... e5) 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { Of course - no Rossolimo. The Open Sicilian landed Carlsen in some problems } { [%cal Gf1b5] } 3... cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Ndb5 d6 7. Nd5 Nxd5 8. exd5 { So far everything as in games 8 and 10 } 8... Ne7 { A wise choice by Magnus - he is the first to deviate. This move was employed several times by Kramnik ... back in 1994 } (8... Nb8) 9. c4 Ng6 { Black has to move the knight and uncover the defence of the d6 pawn } { [%csl Gd6][%cal Gf8d6,Ge8e7] } (9... Nf5 10. Bd3 Be7 11. O-O { Is regarded as better for White }) (9... a6 10. Qa4 { Is losing } { [%cal Ga4e8] } 10... Bd7 (10... Qd7 11. Nxd6+ Kd8 12. Nxf7+) 11. Nxd6# { [%cal Gd6e7] }) 10. Qa4 Bd7 { Now d6 is defended } { [%csl Gd6][%cal Gf8d6] } 11. Qb4 { [%csl Gd6] } 11... Bf5 12. h4 { [%cal Gf7f4] } 12... h5 { A real surprise. This was played by top engines in the TCEC competition. Grischuk once again was harsh and called Caruana's preparation bad. It is Grischuk being Grischuk, but the things is - you can't afford to avoid looking at correspondence and engine games these days } { [%csl Gg5][%cal Gf7f5] } (12... Be7) (12... a6 13. h5 axb5 14. hxg6 bxc4 15. Rxh7 (15. gxf7+ { Was Grischuk's recommendation } 15... Kxf7 16. Qxb7+ Be7 17. Bxc4 h5 { But in both positions only White can be better }) 15... Rxh7 16. gxh7 Bxh7 17. Qxb7 Be7 18. Bxc4 { Was mentioned in chess24 stream as defensible for BLack }) 13. Qa4 { Caruana was in deep thinking and hinted at the move repetition. Considering the situation and the position he obtained in the game, going for the draw wasn't the worst idea ever. } 13... Bd7 (13... Qd7 14. Nc7+) 14. Qb4 Bf5 15. Be3 { Displaying his fighting spirit... and risking it a bit } (15. Bg5 { IS more sensible, since Black doesn't really want to play f6 } { [%csl Gg5][%cal Gf7f6] } 15... f6 (15... Qb8 16. g3 a6 17. Nc3 Be7 18. Be2 { And White is somewhat better } (18. Be3)) (15... Be7 16. Bxe7 Kxe7 { Is also bad due to } 17. c5 dxc5 18. Qxc5+ Kf6 { And White should be close to winning here }) 16. Be3 { Is better for White }) 15... a6 16. Nc3 Qc7 { [%csl Gb7][%cal Gb4b7] } 17. g3 { The problem with this position is that it is incredibly hard to play it with White. There are a lot of possibilities. On the other hand, Black has a very clear plan } { [%csl Gh4,Gg6][%cal Gg6f4] } 17... Be7 18. f3 { [%cal Gc3e4,Gf1d3] } (18. Be2 Nf8 19. Rc1 Bg6 20. O-O { [%cal Gf7f5] } 20... Nd7 21. Na4 O-O { Something along these lines is perhaps safer }) (18. O-O-O Bg4 { Is a bit uncomfortable } 19. Re1 f5 { [%cal Gf5f4] }) 18... Nf8 { Magnus played this quickly, indicating he was still within his preparation } 19. Ne4 Nd7 20. Bd3 O-O 21. Rh2?! { Probably the source of all White's issues. Caruana wants to transfer his rook to c2 and castle long, but this is highly artificial } { [%cal Gh2c2,Gb7b5] } (21. O-O { The most sensible plan, greatly reducing the effect of f5-e4 break. } 21... Bg6 22. Qd2 f5 23. Ng5 { [%cal Gf5f4,Ge5e4] } 23... Bxg5 24. Bxg5 e4 25. Be2 Ne5 { And White is slightly better }) (21. Qd2 b5 (21... Bg6 22. O-O f5 23. Ng5 Bxg5 24. Bxg5 f4 (24... e4) 25. Bxg6) 22. O-O bxc4 23. Rac1 Nb6 24. b3 { [%csl Gc4][%cal Gc4d3,Gc1c7] }) (21. O-O-O { Svidler said this is stronger } 21... b5 22. Kb1 { And here he said things are unclear, but I think it can quickly get ugly for White, e.g. } 22... Rfb8 (22... bxc4 23. Rc1 Rfb8 24. Qxc4 Qb7) 23. Rc1 bxc4 24. Qxc4 Qb7 { [%cal Gb7b2] } 25. Rc2 { [%cal Gc2b2] } 25... Nb6 { And I believe Black's attack is faster. More importantly, it is easier to play } { [%cal Gb8b2,Gg3g4] }) 21... Rac8 22. O-O-O Bg6 { [%cal Gf7f5] } 23. Rc2 { An interesting concept, but Black is not forced to play b5 and now f5-e4 plan gains in strength } (23. Kb1 f5 { Is also strong } { [%cal Ge4g5] } 24. Nd2 e4 25. Bc2 b5) 23... f5 24. Nf2 (24. Ng5 Bxg5 25. hxg5 (25. Bxg5 Nc5 { [%cal Gc5d3] } 26. f4 (26. Bf1 f4 { And wins } { [%cal Gg6c2] }) 26... b5 { And Black is crushing }) 25... e4 { Is highly unpleasant now } (25... Nc5 26. f4) 26. Bf1 f4 27. Bxf4 Nc5 28. fxe4 Bxe4 { And it is clear Black has fantastic compensation }) 24... Nc5 25. f4? { The losing move } { [%csl Gb7][%cal Gb7b5,Gf3f4] } (25. Bxc5 dxc5 26. Qd2 { Is recommended by the computer which hopes to hold }) (25. Qa3 { Also seems more resilient } 25... Nxd3+ 26. Qxd3 { Although it is clear only Black can win }) 25... a5? { Indicating Magnus' mood } (25... b5 { Was very strong } 26. Qd2 (26. Bxc5 dxc5 27. Qd2 e4 28. Be2 { And this is a dream for Black } { [%csl Gf4,Gb5][%cal Ge5e4,Gb5b4,Ga6a5] }) (26. cxb5 Nxd3+ { You obviously can't take } 27. Rxd3 Qxc2#) 26... exf4 27. Bxf4 (27. gxf4 { [%cal Gd1g1,Gg1g7] } 27... Bxh4 (27... Bf6)) 27... Bf6) (25... exf4 26. Bxf4 b5 27. Qd2 { Is probably even more precise, to reduce White's options }) 26. Qd2 e4 { Magnus played this in order to reduce White's options and to play on one goal. It proves how nervous how he lacked confidence perhaps in critical moments } { [%csl Gf5,Gh5,Ge4][%cal Gb7b5] } 27. Be2 Be8 { [%cal Ge8a4] } 28. Kb1 (28. Nh3 Ba4 { Wins on the spot } 29. b3 Bxb3 30. axb3 Nxb3+ { [%cal Gb3c1,Gb3d2] }) 28... Bf6 (28... Ba4 { Even without the bishop on f6, this move is dangerous } 29. b3 Bxb3 30. axb3 Nxb3 31. Qe1 { [%cal Ge1a5] } 31... Bf6 32. Bxh5 Na1 33. Ra2 (33. Rcc1) 33... Qxc4) 29. Re1? { Another losing move } { [%cal Gd2e1] } (29. Nh3 { Was the best move } 29... Ba4 (29... g6) 30. b3 Bxb3 31. axb3 Nxb3 32. Qe1 { [%cal Ge1a5] } 32... b5 33. c5 Nxc5 34. Rdc1 { And here once again the engine shows 0.0 evaluation }) 29... a4? { Another mistake } { [%csl Ga4,Gb4][%cal Ge8a4] } (29... Ba4 { Was very strong. After } 30. b3 (30. Rcc1 { [%cal Gb7b5] } 30... b5 (30... g6 { [%csl Gh5] } 31. Nh3 b5 (31... Rb8)) 31. cxb5 Qb6 32. Bd4 Bxd4 33. Qxd4 Bxb5 34. Bxh5 { It is true that White has some counterplay, but Black should be significatnyl better here }) 30... Bxb3 31. axb3 Nxb3 32. Qd1 a4 { Black has a very primitive threat of bringing the queen to a3 via dark squares } { [%cal Gc7a5,Ga5b4,Gb4a3] } 33. Nh3 Qa5 34. Nf2 Qb4) 30. Qb4 g6 31. Rd1 Ra8 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } { And here Magnus made a very shocking decision - he offered a draw. His position is still way more pleasant } 1/2-1/2


