1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 { [%cal Ge2e3,Gd2d4,Gg1e2] } (3. Nf3 { In classical games Carlsen went for 4 Knights position after 1.c4. He decided to switch and surprise Caruana in not so well known position. } { [%csl Gc5][%cal Gf8c5] } 3... Nc6) 3... Bb4 { We've entered in reversed Rossolimo where white is move up. } { [%cal Gb4c3] } 4. e4 { Surprisingly extremely rare move. Carlen is trying to play the same structure as in games 1 and 3. } { [%csl Ge2][%cal Ge2e4] } 4... O-O { Bg2 can seem like a no-thinker but Nge2 is much more precise. Any exchanges on c3 will be taken with night without ruining the structure. } (4... Bxc3 5. dxc3 Nxe4 6. Qd5 Ng5 7. Qxe5+ Ne6 8. Bg2 { [%csl Gc3,Gc4][%cal Gg2c6,Gc1g5] } 8... O-O { White would be slightly better. }) 5. Nge2 { [%cal Gb4c3,Ge2c3,Ge7b4] } 5... c6 (5... d6 { [%cal Gb8c6] }) 6. Bg2 a6 { [%cal Gb7b5] } (6... d5 { Was more critical line. } 7. exd5 cxd5 8. cxd5 Bf5 9. d4 (9. O-O Bd3 { Playing imprecisely would allow black to equalize and play this double-edged position. }) 9... exd4 10. Qxd4 { White is better. }) 7. O-O b5 8. d4 d6 { [%cal Gd6e5] } (8... exd4 { Would just activate white pieces. } 9. Nxd4 { [%csl Gc6,Gb5,Ga6,Gd6,Ge5][%cal Gb7b5,Ga7a5,Gc7c5] } 9... Re8 { [%cal Gc4b5] } 10. e5 Rxe5 11. Bf4 Re8 12. cxb5 axb5 13. Ndxb5 $16 { [%cal Gf4c7,Gg2c6,Gc3b5] }) 9. a3 Bxc3 { [%cal Gb5c4] } (9... Ba5 10. b4 Bc7 $16 { Was also possible but Caruana didn't want to play passively. } { [%csl Ga3,Gb4,Gc4,Gd4,Ge4] }) 10. Nxc3 bxc4 { [%csl Gc4,Gc1,Gg2,Ga6,Gc6,Gd6,Ge5] } 11. dxe5 dxe5 { [%csl Ge5,Gc4,Gc6,Ga6] } 12. Na4 { Keeping queens on board was also possible, but it's well known Magnus prefers positions where he can play on one goal without any risks. } { [%csl Gb6,Gc5][%cal Ga4b6,Gc1e3] } (12. Be3) 12... Be6 13. Qxd8 (13. f4 { Is engines suggestion, a player should see a ton of lines to play it. Also it's really risky. exchanging queens was better practical decision. } { [%csl Gg4] }) 13... Rxd8 14. Be3 { [%csl Gc4][%cal Ga1c1,Gf1d1,Gg2f1] } 14... Nbd7 15. f3 { Preventing Ng4 and defending an e4 pawn. } { [%csl Gg4,Ge4][%cal Gf6g4,Gf6e4,Gf3e4,Gg2f1] } 15... Rab8 { [%cal Gb8b2] } 16. Rac1 Rb3 17. Rfe1 (17. Kf2 Rdb8 18. Rfd1 c3 19. Nxc3 Rxb2+ $15 { If someone played this most logical line he'd quickly find himself in some truble. }) 17... Ne8 { [%csl Gb5,Gd4][%cal Ge8d6] } (17... Rdb8 18. Bf1 c3 19. Rxc3 Rxc3 20. bxc3 a5 { [%csl Ga3,Gc3][%cal Gb8b3] }) 18. Bf1 Nd6 { [%csl Gc4][%cal Gd6b5] } 19. Rcd1 { [%cal Gc1c4,Gd1d8] } 19... Nb5? { Crucial mistake. After this point Carlsen didn't let advantage out of his hand. In Caruana's defense it was second best move in the position. } (19... Nb7 20. Rd2 Kf8 21. Kf2 Ke8 22. Red1 { [%csl Gc4,Ga6,Gc6][%cal Gd2d8] } 22... Rb8 23. Rc2 Na5 $14 { White is slightly better but there is no clear way how he will improve. } { [%cal Ga5c4,Ga5c6] }) 20. Nc5 { [%csl Gb5,Gb7][%cal Gd1d8,Gb5d8,Gb7d8] } 20... Rxb2 (20... Nxc5 21. Rxd8#) 21. Nxe6 fxe6 22. Bxc4 { [%cal Gc4e6] } (22. Bg5 { Wouldn't be possible. } 22... Nd4 { With Nf3 checkmate threat. } { [%csl Gf3][%cal Gd4f3] } 23. Rxd4 (23. Bxd8 Nxf3+ 24. Kh1 Rxh2#) 23... exd4 24. Bxd8 Ne5 { Again the same threat. } { [%csl Gd8][%cal Ge5f3,Gd4d3,Gc4c3] } 25. Be2 d3 $19 { 2 past pawns and mate threat are simply too strong. Black is winning. } 26. Bd1 (26. Bc7 Rxe2 27. Rxe2 Nxf3+ 28. Kf2 dxe2 29. Kxe2 Nxh2) 26... c3) 22... Nd4 23. Bxd4 exd4 { Carlsen felt this was critical moment spent about 6 minutes to find the best move. Unfortunately it's not easy to see most important move. } 24. Bxe6+ (24. Rxd4 Kf7 { Black's position is falling apart. Only threat he has is Ne5 with perpetual. } { [%cal Ge1d1] } 25. Kh1 { Counter intuitive since in the endgame you want your king to be closer to center. } { [%cal Ge5f3] } (25. Red1?? Ne5 $10 { And white would have to draw a game. } { [%csl Gf3][%cal Ge5f3] } 26. Rxd8 Nxf3+ 27. Kh1 (27. Kf1 Nxh2+ 28. Ke1 Nf3+ 29. Kf1 Nh2+) 27... Rxh2#) 25... c5 (25... Ke7 26. Red1 Rb6 27. Rd6) 26. Rd6 Rb6 27. Red1 Ke7 28. e5 $16) 24... Kf8 25. Rxd4 Ke7 26. Rxd7+ Rxd7 27. Bxd7 Kxd7 { White is a pawn up but the endgame is not the easiest one to win since there is no easy way for white to activate his king. } { [%cal Gb2h2,Gc6c2] } 28. Rd1+ Ke6 29. f4 { [%cal Ge6e5,Gd1d8] } 29... c5 30. Rd5 (30. Rc1 Kd6 { [%csl Gc5] }) 30... Rc2 31. h4 c4 32. f5+ (32. Rd4 { [%csl Gg3][%cal Gh2h4] } 32... Rc3 { [%cal Gc3a3,Ga3g3] } (32... h5)) 32... Kf6 33. Rc5 h5 { [%cal Gg3g4] } 34. Kf1 Rc3 35. Kg2 { [%csl Gg3] } 35... Rxa3 36. Rxc4 Ke5 { [%cal Gf6e5,Gf4f5] } 37. Rc7 { Last mistake Caruana did. At this point he could have saved the game. Although this was rapid Caruana him self said he didn't play even close to his best. } 37... Kxe4 { [%csl Gg7,Ga2] } (37... Ra2+ 38. Kf3 Ra3+ 39. Kg2 Ra2+ { [%cal Gg2h1,Ge5e4,Ge5f3] } 40. Kh3 Kxe4 41. Rxg7 Rf2 (41... Kf3 42. f6 (42. Rb7 Ra1 43. Rb3+ Ke4 44. f6 Rf1 45. Rb6 Kf3) 42... Ra1 { [%cal Ga1h1] } 43. Kh2 Ra2+ 44. Kh3 Ra1) 42. Ra7 Rxf5 43. Rxa6 $10 { White is a pawn up but the position is easily holdable even on faster time controls. } 43... Ke5 44. Ra5+ Kf6 45. Rxf5+ Kxf5 46. g4+ hxg4+ 47. Kg3 Kg6 48. Kxg4 Kh7) 38. Re7+ { An important move. White has to stop black from protecting his h5 pawn. } { [%csl Ge4][%cal Gc7e7,Ge7e4] } (38. Rxg7 Ra2+ { [%cal Ge4f3] } 39. Kh3 Kf3) 38... Kxf5 { [%cal Gf5f3] } 39. Rxg7 { [%csl Gh5] } 39... Kf6 40. Rg5 a5 41. Rxh5 a4 42. Ra5 Ra1 43. Kf3 a3 44. Ra6+ Kg7 45. Kg2 Ra2+ 46. Kh3 Ra1 47. h5 (47. Kg4 { A possible mistake many players would have made resulting in a draw. The point is white cannot push his g-pawn any more. } 47... a2 48. h5 Kh7 { [%cal Gg4f4,Ga1f1,Ga2a1] } 49. h6 (49. Kg5 Rg1 { [%csl Gg3,Gg2] } 50. Ra7+ (50. Rxa2 Rxg3+) 50... Kg8 51. Rxa2 Rxg3+ $10) 49... Rh1 50. Rxa2 Rxh6) 47... Kh7 48. g4 { [%cal Gg4h5] } 48... Kg7 (48... a2 49. Kg2 Kg7 50. Kh2 { It's important to free g2 square for rook. } 50... Kh7 51. g5 { [%csl Gh2] } 51... Rb1 (51... Kg7 52. h6+ Kh7 53. Ra7+ Kg6 (53... Kh8 54. g6 { Passive resist can't save black either. }) 54. h7) 52. Rxa2 Rb5 { [%cal Gb5g5] } 53. Rg2) 49. Kh4 { [%cal Gh4g5] } 49... a2 50. Kg5 { [%cal Gh4g5] } 50... Kf7 (50... Kh7 51. Ra7+ Kg8 52. h6 Kf8 (52... Kh8 53. Kg6 Rg1 54. Ra8#) 53. h7 { [%cal Gh7h8] }) 51. h6 Rb1 52. Ra7+ Kg8 53. Rxa2 Rb5+ 54. Kg6 Rb6+ 55. Kh5 { Impressive endgame precision by Carlsen. } *


