1. e4 { Unusual choice to go 1.e4 when opponent is in a must win situation but here it makes sense. Caruana only prepared Petrov in which Carlsen can quickly change queens and simplify position. This forces Caruana to go for opening he doesn't know as well as Carlsen. } 1... c5 2. Nf3 e6 (2... g6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d6 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 { [%csl Gd6,Ge4,Gc4] }) 3. c4 { [%cal Gc2c4,Ge2e4] } 3... Nc6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 { [%csl Ge4,Gc4] } 5... Bc5 { Trying to go for something complicated } (5... Nf6 { [%cal Gf6e4] } 6. Nc3 Bb4 { [%cal Gd4c6] } 7. Nxc6 bxc6 (7... dxc6 { [%cal Gd1d8] }) 8. Bd3 e5 { [%cal Gb4c5,Gc5d4] }) 6. Nc2 { In move 6 we are already out of the book. } (6. Nb3 { [%csl Gb3][%cal Gc5e7] } 6... Bb4+ 7. Bd2 a5 8. Nc3) 6... Nf6 (6... Qb6 { Was an interasting option. White would have to play unnaturally. } 7. Qd2 Nf6 8. Nc3 Ng4 9. Nd1 (9. Na4 Bxf2+) 9... O-O 10. h3 Nge5 11. f4 Ng6 12. Nc3 $13 { White has slight advantage but position is extremely double-edged. }) 7. Nc3 O-O (7... Qb6 { [%cal Gb6f2] } 8. Ne3 O-O 9. Bd3 { [%csl Gd5] }) 8. Be3 { Black's dark squares are weak. White goal should be to exchange dark color bishops and attack d-pawn. } { [%csl Ge6,Gd7,Gd6,Ge7,Gc2][%cal Gc2e3,Gf2e3] } 8... b6 { [%csl Gb4,Gd4][%cal Ge3c5] } 9. Be2 Bb7 10. O-O Qe7 11. Qd2 Rfd8 12. Rfd1 Ne5 (12... d6 { [%cal Ga7a6] }) 13. Bxc5 bxc5 (13... Qxc5 { Was also possible to put pressure on white's c and e pawns. } 14. Qd4 d6 15. f3 Rac8 16. b3 { White has enough resources to defend pawns and simplify position without too much trouble. } 16... d5 17. Qxc5 bxc5 18. cxd5 exd5 19. exd5 c4 20. Rab1 cxb3 21. Rxb3 Nxd5 22. Rxb7 Nxc3 23. Rxd8+ Rxd8 24. Bf1 Nxa2 25. Rxa7 $10) 14. f4 { Courageous decision. f4 is the best move in position but f3 is also good move, making it harder for him to push d5. } (14. f3 d6 (14... d5 15. Qg5 Qc7 16. cxd5 exd5 17. exd5 Nxd5 18. Nxd5 Bxd5 19. Ne3 $14 { Position is equal, but white is slightly more comfortable. }) 15. b3 Rac8 16. Qe3 Nc6 17. Rd2 $10 { Keeping the tension in air, forcing black to find a good way to break through with d5. }) 14... Ng6 15. Qe3 (15. e5 Ne8 { [%csl Gf4][%cal Gd7d5] }) 15... d6 { [%csl Gf4,Ge4,Gc4][%cal Gd6d5] } (15... d5 { Would just lead to simplification. Black wouldn't be able to get any advantage. } 16. exd5 exd5 17. Qxe7 Nxe7 18. cxd5 Nexd5 19. Nxd5 Bxd5 20. Ne3 $14) 16. Rd2 a6 { Caruana is trying to improve his position as much as possible before pushing d5. Unfortunately for him, there are not too many moves that will make a significant improvment. } 17. Rad1 Qc7 { [%cal Gd8d7] } 18. b3 h6 19. g3 Rd7 20. Bf3 { [%csl Gd5] } 20... Re8 21. Qf2 { [%cal Gg6e7,Ge7c6,Gc6d4,Ge6e5,Gf4f5,Gg3g4,Gh2h4] } 21... Ne7 22. h3 Red8 23. Bg2 Nc6 24. g4 Qa5 (24... e5 25. g5 hxg5 26. fxg5 Nh7 27. Nd5 { [%csl Gd7,Gd8][%cal Gc2e3,Ge3f5,Gh3h4,Gc6d4,Gc2d4] }) 25. Na4 { [%csl Gc5][%cal Ga4c5,Gg4g5,Gd2d7] } (25. Qe3 e5 { [%cal Ge5f4,Gg4g5] } 26. g5 exf4 { [%csl Gg5] } 27. Qd3 Ne5 { [%csl Gd3] }) 25... Qc7 { [%cal Gc7d7] } (25... Kh8 26. g5) (25... Ba8 26. g5 hxg5 27. fxg5 { [%cal Gf6d7] } 27... Nh7 28. Nxc5 Qxc5 29. Qxc5 { [%cal Gd6c5] } 29... dxc5 30. Rxd7 { [%csl Gd7][%cal Gd1d8] }) 26. e5 { Carlsen saw the chance to change rooks and went for it. There were options for him to play for advantage, but he would be satisfied with a draw. } (26. g5 hxg5 27. fxg5 Nh5 { [%csl Gd7][%cal Ga4c5,Gc7d7] } 28. Nb2 { After knight left f6 square, black can't play d5 any more. } { [%csl Gh5,Gf6][%cal Gd6d5] } 28... Ne7 { With an idea of d5. } (28... Re7 29. Nd3 e5 30. Ne3 Nd4 31. Rf1) 29. Qh4 g6 30. Ne3 d5 { Doesn't work. } 31. exd5 exd5 32. cxd5) 26... dxe5 27. Nxc5 { [%cal Gd2d7] } 27... Rxd2 28. Rxd2 Rxd2 29. Qxd2 { [%csl Gb7] } 29... Ba8 { [%csl Gd8,Gc8,Gb8,Ga8][%cal Ga8g8] } (29... exf4 30. Nxb7 Qxb7 31. Qxf4) 30. fxe5 Qxe5 31. Nd7 (31. Nxa6 { Is also possible but white's goal was to draw in simplest manner. } 31... Qb2) 31... Qb2 32. Qd6 { Forcing further exchanges. } { [%csl Gc2] } 32... Nxd7 (32... Qxc2 33. Qf8+ Kh7 34. Nxf6+ gxf6 (34... Kg6 35. Qxa8) 35. Qxf7+ Kh8 36. Qf8+ Kh7 { [%csl Ga8][%cal Gf8a8] } 37. Qf7+) 33. Qxd7 Qxc2 34. Qe8+ Kh7 35. Qxa8 Qd1+ 36. Kh2 Qd6+ 37. Kh1 Nd4 (37... Qd1+ { Is a draw, but Caruana was having none of it }) 38. Qe4+ f5 39. gxf5 exf5 40. Qe3 Ne6 { Objectively this position is a draw but win is only what works for Caruana. From this point on he started to despertly try and trick Carlsen } 41. b4 { [%cal Gc4c7] } 41... Ng5 (41... Nf4 42. c5 Qd1+ 43. Kh2 Nxg2 44. Kxg2 Qd5+) (41... Qxb4 42. Qxe6) 42. c5 Qf6 43. c6 Ne6 44. a4 Nc7 45. Qf4 Ne6 46. Qd6 Qa1+ 47. Kh2 Nd4 48. c7 { [%cal Gc7c8,Gd4e2] } 48... Qc3 (48... Ne2 { [%cal Ga1g1] } 49. Qc5 { [%cal Gc5g1,Gc7c8] }) 49. Qc5 Qe3 50. c8=Q f4 51. Qg4 *


